<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-1S     03-20 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOLS.') 
CALIFORNIA GUARANTEES SOME A PLACE IN UNIVERSITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS lede to change `top 4 percent of the state's high school
students' to `TOP 4 PERCENT OF THE STUDENTS IN EACH OF THE STATE'S(mk) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The University of California's board of regents
decided Friday to guarantee a place in the prestigious public
university system for the top 4 percent of the students in each of
the state's high schools.
</P>
<P>
   The rule, which will take effect in the fall of 2001, was one of
the most frequent promises that Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, made
in his campaign last year. It was seen by some people as an effort
to get around the affirmative action prohibitions that voters
approved in 1996 and to reverse the decline in the number of black
and Hispanic students being admitted to the system.
</P>
<P>
   But the rule is expected to result in only a tiny increase in
black and Hispanic students, officials at the University of
California said Friday. The rule will add about 3,600 students of
all ethnic backgrounds to the pool of eligible applicants, but less
than half of them are expected to enroll. About 43,000 freshmen
enrolled in the system last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a decent but not significant number of minorities''
in the expanded pool, said William Bagley, a regent and lawyer from
San Francisco who voted for the new rules. ``But it will be helpful
for those of us who think diversity is important.''
</P>
<P>
   The percent of black students who meet the university's
eligibility requirements will increase by just eight-tenths of 1
percent, to 3.6 percent from 2.8 percent. That would be an increase
of 161 students, half of whom would be expected to enroll. The
eligibility rate for Hispanic students will go to 4.7 percent from
3.8 percent, an increase of 716 students. The eligibility for Asian
students will go to 31.5 percent from 30 percent, and for white
students it will go to 14.4 percent from 12.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will probably help disadvantaged white children more than
any other group,'' said another regent, Howard Leach. ``It is
totally unrelated to affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagley, the regent from San Francisco, said there were more than
800 high schools in California and that some of them ``supply
literally zero students to our campuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The board approved the new rules Friday after a subcommittee
recommended the change in a 13-1 vote on Thursday. The sole
dissenter was Meredith Khachigian, a regent from San Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to hold the schools accountable for providing the
courses and teaching to make students eligible for the
university,'' Ms. Khachigian said Friday. ``I felt this gave them a
pass. I'm concerned about students coming to the university and
competing with students who have a higher level of preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward Connerly, the regent who led the fight against affirmative
action, voted for the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought this 4-percent plan was a Trojan horse to
resurrect racial preferences,'' he said. ``But the more I looked at
it, the more I thought it was based on merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Bebitch Jaffe, a political scientist at the Claremont
Graduate University, said the new admission rule was ``by and large
a symbolic gesture'' without the remedial and financial aid
programs to make sure students from poor, inner-city high schools
and their rural cousins can compete with their more advantaged
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jaffe said a student in the top 4 percent from a big urban
school, where the books and buildings are old and the history
teacher has to teach biology, is not the same as a student ranked
in the top 4 percent at a suburban school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any bridge programs to help the 4 percent who
qualify from poor, impoverished families and school districts,''
she said. ``The bridges have all been burned. If you really want to
bring these students up to speed, it will take will and money _
quite a bit of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Genethia Hayes, the executive director of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference in Los Angeles, said much more money must be
spent to improve education in the lower grades. Otherwise, she
added, ``we are preparing these kids to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this plan allows people to do,'' Ms. Hayes said, ``is to
get off the hook of really having to do something about inequitable
sharing of educational resources, both human and capital.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the policy ``a silver bullet kind of thing.'' Still,
she said, it is a positive step.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jaffe agreed, adding that as modest as the 4-percent policy
is, it would never have passed under former Gov. Pete Wilson, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new rule does send a message, and it's a positive
message,'' Ms. Jaffe said. ``It's a message of opportunity and that
there is a concern that the university be somewhat representative
of the diversity of the state. But I worry that it will raise false
hopes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
