<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-BACKGROUND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI TO REQUIRE BACKGROUND CHECKS FOR TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Certified teachers moving to Missouri will
have to submit to an FBI background check that includes
fingerprinting before they can work in a public classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Board of Education approved the fingerprinting
requirement Thursday as part of an emergency rule change, which has
other provisions aimed at making it easier to hire out-of-state
teachers. It marks the first time the state will require teachers
to be fingerprinted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is to ensure that we have done everything possible to
make sure these individuals are not coming into our classrooms with
criminal histories that we're not aware of,'' said John Miller,
director of teacher certification.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas does not require mandatory fingerprinting of teachers.
Instead the state relies on county attorneys to report certain
crimes to the state Department of Education. In addition, some
local districts require fingerprinting.
</P>
<P>
   Fingerprinting is the latest weapon the state has introduced in
its battle to prevent or remove felons from teaching in the state's
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the state conducted the first criminal records check
of Missouri teachers by comparing the list of certified teachers
against a state criminal database maintained by the Missouri
Highway Patrol. The search turned up 520 matches, including at
least 65 felony convictions for crimes such as rape, sodomy and
deviate sexual assault. The state has since moved to revoke many of
those certifications.
</P>
<P>
   That check did not require fingerprints and the search was
limited to crimes committed in Missouri. Even so, Miller said the
state had no plans to seek fingerprints from teachers who already
hold Missouri certification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any movement at this time in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan vowed in December 1997 to make stronger
teacher certification legislation a priority. That followed stories
in The Kansas City Star detailing how the Kansas City School
District imposed little if any discipline on several staff members
accused of sexual misconduct with students, including some staff
members who had criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule will become effective 10 days after being filed
with the secretary of state's office. Miller said he expected the
rule to be filed next week.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman for the state's largest teacher organization said
the group has consistently supported state-funded background
checks, but has not taken a position on fingerprinting. The new
rule will require applicants to pay for the background check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people would resist the idea of fingerprinting _
but we have not as an association debated that issue _ but support
keeping felons out of the classroom,'' said Bruce Moe, of the
42,000-member Missouri State Teachers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision of the rule change granted reciprocity to
teachers certified by other states. Officials say the move is aimed
in part at addressing a pending teacher shortage.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, teachers moving to Missouri were granted
certification only after the state conducted a rigorous analysis of
the applicant's college transcript.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no way to recognize their experience or capacity to
teach,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new rule, such applicants would be required
only to pass the state assessment test in their subject area before
being granted a Missouri license.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more reflective of an accountable system,'' Miller said.
``It's `Can you do this?' not `Did you have the course work?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
