<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET HELPS KEEP BIG BROTHER IN CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The Internet may prove as much a boost for economic
freedom as it is for commercial activity.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the gratifying conclusion to be drawn from the
recent revelation that regulators seem set to abandon an Orwellian
scheme to transform your banker into your Big Brother.
</P>
<P>
   When the public-comment period ended for the proposed
know-your-customer rules, the head of the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. signaled her intent to shelve the proposal. She was
responding to a deluge of criticism of the initiative, most of
which seemingly came by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   By the final day allowed for public feedback, the number of
e-mail responses was estimated to be 225,000, and it was
overwhelmingly negative. Meantime, the political fallout spread to
Capitol Hill, where resistance was said to be mounting. At the end
of the comment period, the FDIC chief said she would urge her
regulatory colleagues to drop the bid, which could happen at a
meeting scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting aspects of this development is that
the overwhelming outcry developed in what was mostly a media
vacuum. During the early phase of the proposal's rollout, newspaper
and television coverage of the issue was exceedingly scarce, even
though it posed a serious threat to the basic economic freedoms of
most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this vacuum was filled by the Internet, where word of
the regulatory proposal's onerous nature was spread. The Internet
also provided a convenient and expeditious way for concerned
bankers and their customers to communicate their objections to the
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Though the regulation has been offered in the spirit of catching
drug traffickers and money launderers, it threatens an egregious
assault on the first principles on which the nation was founded. As
such, it ignored that the current regulations designed to monitor
big money deals for wrongdoing should be more than sufficient to
catch the real bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good argument to be made, in fact, that more such
regulation would make catching actual criminals more difficult
because paperwork generated by existing rules overwhelms the
process.
</P>
<P>
   CIA turncoat Aldrich Ames, for example, went undetected even
though his spymasters were providing him huge sums through normal
banking channels. His payoffs were probably missed because they
were obscured by the mountains of minutia already confronting those
who police these matters.
</P>
<P>
   Without putting too fine a point on it, the proposal would turn
bankers into snoops and snitches. As such, they would be required
to make highly subjective judgments about what constitutes
``unusual and inconsistent'' transactions for even their most
average law-abiding customers. Far from protecting society from
criminals, this would be Big Brotherism at its worst, with life in
America imitating George Orwell's literary art in his 1984 novel.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposal gets the funeral it deserves, it will happen to
a significant degree because the Internet's democratizing potential
filled a role historically served by media watchdogs fulfilling
their check-and-balance responsibility as the unofficial fourth
branch of government.
</P>
<P>
   Nature, it would seem, still abhors a vacuum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
