A7692 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOTEL-FIRE-KAN &LR;      03-20 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-FIRE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CHECKING INTO A HOTEL, CHECK OUT THE SAFETY FEATURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Jerry Ingram knows there's more to a good
hotel than a workout room and a concierge. Since the Overland Park
man survived a Las Vegas hotel fire that killed eight persons in
1981, he won't stay in any place that wasn't built with fire safety
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Ingram and Overland Park Fire Battalion
Chief Ted McIntosh used the Overland Park Marriott's 11th floor to
demonstrate to the media ways to safely escape a hotel fire.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram always looks for fire alarms, sprinklers and at least two
fire exits, and he won't sleep higher than the second floor. He
learned the importance of fire safety 18 years ago when a hotel
busboy set fire to the eighth floor of the Las Vegas Hilton. Ingram
was in his ninth-floor room when he heard windows breaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Las Vegas. I thought it was drunks breaking glass,''
Ingram said.
</P>
<P>
   He rushed out of his room when he realized fire was shattering
the hotel windows, but before he could reach a stairway, someone in
a hotel uniform told him to get into an elevator, he said. The
elevator stopped on the eighth floor, which had filled with black
smoke. He dropped to his hands and knees just before another man in
the elevator succumbed to the smoke. Ingram crawled blindly through
the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was deathly quiet,'' he said. ``I thought everyone in the
hotel was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   By staying low, Ingram managed to bump his way down the hall
until he reached a room where a woman was stuffing wet towels at
the bottom of her door. Ingram and the woman stayed in the room for
about 90 minutes until firefighters rescued them.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to survive a hotel fire is to prepare for disaster.
McIntosh recommends that travelers pack a flashlight, medical
information, a first-aid kit, a notebook for recording escape
routes and duct tape for sealing vents and doors from smoke. As
soon as you check into a hotel, walk the two nearest escape routes
to make sure you can get out quickly without any surprises.
</P>
<P>
   If an alarm sounds, grab your key in case you have to retreat to
your room, and then check the door. If it's cool, stay close to the
floor and crawl to a stairway. Never use an elevator in a fire.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to stay in your room, use duct tape or wet towels at
the bottom of the door and around vents to keep smoke out. Dial 911
to let someone know where you are. Fill the bathtub with water and
use the ice bucket to splash water on hot walls and floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want to do is break a window,'' McIntosh
said. ``That's just another avenue for smoke to come into your
room.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time to break the window is if too much smoke is
pouring into your room for you to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinklers will control or extinguish fires 97 percent of the
time, McIntosh said, but they're not required in all hotels.
Travelers should always ask about sprinklers when they make
reservations, Ingram said.
Hotel fire safety tips
</P>
<P>
   - When you reserve a room, ask whether the hotel has sprinklers
and smoke detectors.
</P>
<P>
   - Take along duct tape and a first-aid kit.
</P>
<P>
   - Walk the two closest fire-escape routes as soon as you check
in.
</P>
<P>
   - If an alarm sounds, check the door. If the door isn't too hot
to open, crawl toward an exit. Otherwise, seal the door and vents
with wet towels or duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   - Remember that firefighters probably can't rescue you from the
outside if you're above the sixth floor. Anyone staying higher than
that will have to depend heavily on the building's safety features
and escape routes.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Overland Park Fire Department
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
