<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK AND SABRES BEAT RANGERS IN OVERTIME, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is not easy to beat Dominik Hasek, especially for
the New York Rangers. Even in a mediocre season by Hasek's high
standards, the league's premier goalie returned from an injury
Friday night with a record of 5-0-2 in his previous seven
appearances against the Blue Shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Playing for the first time in a month, Hasek stopped 27 of 29
Rangers shots, some of them with the creative contortions for which
he is known. His Buffalo Sabres teammates supported him by coming
back from a one-goal deficit late in the third period to win it in
overtime, 3-2, on the second goal of the night by Miroslav Satan at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Satan scored at 1 minute 18 seconds of overtime by whipping the
puck past Rangers goalie Mike Richter high on the glove side from
the right-wing circle while on the power play. The manpower
advantage was created in the final minute of regulation when the
Rangers' Mathieu Schneider slashed Buffalo's Mike Peca when Peca
was on a breakaway while killing a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The result left the Rangers three points behind the Boston
Bruins in the race for the eighth and final playoff berth in the
Eastern Conference. However, they have played two more games than
the Bruins and have only 13 games remaining. The Rangers went 0-3-1
against the Sabres this season.
</P>
<P>
   With both teams rested and the crowd in a festive, Friday mood,
the game had a brisk pace and a nasty edge. Until late in the third
period, the Rangers led by 2-1 on power-play goals by Schneider and
Petr Nedved. But the Sabres tied it at 2-2 on the power play at
11:40 on a slap shot by Michal Grosek. The Rangers' Scott Fraser
was in the penalty box for slashing.
</P>
<P>
   Also playing well was Richter, who stopped 21 of 24 shots. One
of his best saves came with less than two minutes left in
regulation, when he came out from his crease to stop Peca on a
breakaway after a Fraser turnover. Peca, the Buffalo captain, was
one of the best players on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek was back in the Buffalo net for the first time since Feb.
17, when he suffered a groin strain during a 3-2 loss to Toronto.
During his absence, the Sabres went 5-4-3 and had won their
previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres went to the Eastern Conference finals last spring and
lost to Washington. They think they can advance at least that far
this year and could be active before the trade deadline on Tuesday.
They recently sent Matthew Barnaby to the Pittsburgh Penguins for
Stu Barnes, an exchange of forwards. They entered the game with a
record of 31-23-13, third in the Northeast Division and seventh in
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres scored the first goal, Satan beating Richter on a
breakaway with a backhander at 10:21 of the first period after a
turnover by Brian Leetch at the Rangers' blue line. But the Rangers
scored the next two goals, both on the power play and both set up
in part by Leetch.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers tied it at 12:47 of the first period when Schneider
scored his eighth goal of the season with a slap shot from just
above the left-wing circle. With a two-man advantage, they went up
by 2-1 at 5:44 of the second period on Nedved's 18th goal of the
season, a high wrist shot that was aided by a John MacLean screen
in front of Hasek's crease after Nedved won the face-off in the
left-wing circle.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not figure in the scoring in the first 40
minutes, the rookie Manny Malhotra of the Rangers stood out on
several exciting plays. Twice in the second period, he was stopped
by Hasek on excellent scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   On the first, Malhotra sailed in clear on Hasek, who has won
both the Vezina and the Hart trophies in the last two seasons as
best goalie and most valuable player in the league. Malhotra faked
Hasek onto his back and tried to flip the puck over him, but Hasek
blocked it with his leg extended upward.
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra's next chance, also a clear shot, was low and stopped
by the goalie standing up.
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra also seemed to be a target of the Sabres. In the first
period, his helmeted head snapped back when rammed against the
glass by Richard Smehlik. In the second period, Darryl Shannon
seemed to hurt him when he caught Malhotra's left thigh with his
hip in an open-ice hit that resulted in a Buffalo penalty. Later,
Malhotra was cut over his upper lip in another collision near the
glass.
</P>
</TEXT>
