<SLUG> BC-DRAG-RACING-CAMP-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATORNATIONALS CAMPGROUND IS A SHOW IN ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.H., Texas, Calif., Ga., Canada, Germany, U.K.)  (js) 
 By BOB ARNDORFER   The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Last year at what might be called the
Gatornationals garden of good and evil, Darrell Hampton of Atlanta
was chatting with a woman who was sitting naked in a pickup truck.
When the woman's husband came over and said to him, ``It's time to
go,'' Hampton left.
</P>
<P>
   No offense intended, none taken.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it is here, say Hampton and other denizens of the
garden, also known as the Gainesville Jaycees' campground, which is
a mile from Gainesville Raceway where the National Hot Rod
Association is staging the Mac Tools Gatornationals through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The campground is where during the 30-year-old Gatornationals,
the party never ends and conflict rarely begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are here just to have a good time,'' Hampton, a
31-year-old construction worker, said Thursday inside the
``Gatornationals Party Animals Compound'' at the camp. ``They don't
come here to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   They do, however, come to drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come to get toasted,'' said Gene Sweeney of Melbourne,
relaxing with a straight Coke _ he gave up demon rum when he turned
50 _ behind the wheel of his $720,000 Bluebird Wanderlodge motor
home. ``It's a sideshow all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, 55, is a retired computer salesman who has stayed at
the camp about 15 years. Sharing his luxury digs in what they
jokingly call the ``respectable'' section of the campground are his
wife, Jan, and brother-in-law, Herb Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always the drags, that's the big thing,'' said Lucas, an
independent sales representative from Bedford, N.H., who flies in
each year to join the Sweeneys at the campground. ``But out here
it's a lot of fun just walking around and watching all the
crazies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always clean fun,'' Gene Sweeney added. ``In 15 years,
I've never seen a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaycees have run the county-owned, 40-acre campground for
some 25 years, said Ed Olowin, a pharmacist who takes a week's
vacation every year to help run the camp. By Saturday, he said,
they will have filled 500 of their $20 campsites with everything
from upscale RVs to pup tents. At its peak, party town will number
some 2,500 residents, including some regulars from Germany, England
and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Gatornationals is expected to attract 130,000 to
Gainesville, including an audience of 60,000 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Through the pine trees from the ``respectable'' district is
rowdy central, where the biggest of the camp's parties are held.
It's home to the Party Animals Compound, a complex hosted by
Hampton and half a dozen bleary eyed buddies whose posted mottoes
include: ``When you're stupid, you gotta be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The buddies come from Texas, California, Georgia and Florida,
meeting each other at the campground every year. They welcome all
FUBARs _ it means, loosely, Fouled Up Beyond All Recognition, a
reference to a person's state of intoxication _ to their
high-decibel campsite. Their supreme achievement last year was
getting the Budweiser Girls to join their party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice getaway,'' said Larry Buitron, 45, a meat cutter
from Miami who said he first came to the races 24 years ago with a
friend and seven cases of beer. ``It's a guys' thing. You need to
do things you can look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Smith, 46, an almanac of drag racing facts, is generally
credited with organizing the doings at the compound. He owns some
Arby's restaurants in Okeechobee, but his chief job, he said, is
``I have fun.'' In 25 years of camping at the Gatornationals, he
said, he too has never seen a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple,'' Smith said. ``We're too old to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie and Jerry Ash, a white-haired couple from Stuart, have
been coming to what they call the ``mud, blood and beer'' fest for
10 years. As they stretched out the awning on their camper trailer
a short hike from rowdyville, they said they belong to a Ferrari
club, attend NASCAR races and drag races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports car people stay in a hotel,'' said Jerry Ash, retired
from the mini-storage business his wife still runs. ``NASCAR people
stay in motor homes. And drag racers sleep in tents beside
bonfires.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no fun to go to a race and sit in a hotel room,'' Bonnie
Ash said. She said nothing she's ever seen in a decade of attending
the Gatornationals' wildest party has bothered her.
</P>
<P>
   At the campground, she added, she can do something she'd never
do if she stayed at a motel in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine and I wander around here at midnight,'' she
said. ``A woman can feel perfectly safe here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bob Arndorfer writes for The Gainesville Sun.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
