<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-2TAKES-     03-20 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMPS OR NO BUMPS, MERRILL LYNCH'S STEAMROLLER ROLLS ON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan)   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juggernaut. Steamroller. Mother Merrill. Those are the nicknames
most commonly associated with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., a brokerage firm
that long ago decided that it wanted to be No. 1, or very close to
it, in everything Wall Street does.
</P>
<P>
   The names were never more valid than last year, when Merrill
simultaneously pursued three huge international acquisitions, set
records in its giant worldwide bond business, and took in hundreds
of millions of dollars each day from investors seeking to ride the
bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, that image has been tarnished. Like many
rivals, Merrill was hit hard by a slump in financial markets last
fall. Unlike many, it did not snap back quickly, some current and
former employees say. Many of them contend that an aura of
invincibility has given way to a crisis of confidence in some
crucial businesses.
</P>
<P>
   All this has led to renewed speculation about Merrill's allying
itself with a bigger partner, including Chase Manhattan Corp. Such
talk has caused Merrill's stock price to rise in recent days. Some
people close to the firm say that if Merrill enters a merger now _
and some at Merrill say that the chances of merging with a bank are
higher now than at any time in recent years _ it will probably be
on weaker terms than the firm could have commanded a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Merrill faces losses that ballooned beyond
expectations in Japan, where it bought a failed securities company
last year but has found the cost of building a new operation there
staggering. Merrill's world-leading business of issuing and trading
debt for companies and governments is also in upheaval, people
involved in that business said. The firm is facing defections of
important staff members and slippage in areas where it long
smothered the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Either of those troubles by themselves might not amount to much
for Merrill, which prides itself on having diversified its earnings
to prevent downturns in one area from hurting overall profits. But
Merrill is putting out fires all over the place these days. It is
scrambling to catch up with online trading companies that threaten
its retail brokers, revamping its weak-performing mutual funds, and
trying to inject a shot of adrenaline into Mercury Asset
Management, the big London-based fund manager it bought recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, this company was going to take over the world,''
said Sallie Krawcheck, who follows Merrill for Sanford C.
Bernstein. ``Now people are talking about it as a potential
turnaround story.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Krawcheck recommends that investors buy stock in the firm's
archrival, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, rather than Merrill. But she
sees great potential for the future if Merrill figures out the
Internet and its international expansion bears fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill officials acknowledge that the firm has undertaken a
``wrenching'' overhaul of its debt business. They also say that it
faces larger-than-expected losses in Japan. But they strongly
dispute that all this amounts to trouble for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that somehow a large part of our business is in
disarray is fallacious,'' Jim Wiggins, a Merrill spokesman, said.
``There's no question that we have moved quickly to redeploy
resources to areas that have the greatest future promise. But we
are running record revenues in every category that we do business
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's earnings fell to $1.3 billion last year from almost $2
billion in 1997, largely because it suffered an $850 million loss
in its bond business. But Wiggins emphasized that other areas,
including investment banking, asset management and brokerage
commissions, were earning record profits.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Merrill has been criticized in the past for spending
heavily abroad, but has often proved critics wrong. It took a
beating after it paid top dollar for the British brokerage house
Smith Newcourt in 1995; most analysts now consider that purchase a
runaway success.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, troubles in Merrill's debt business have proved
trickier to resolve than most people had expected. Some Merrill
bankers, including several who remain at the firm and many who have
left, said David H. Komansky, Merrill's chairman, and his No. 2,
Herbert M. Allison Jr., overreacted to the bond market downturn
last fall by cutting too deeply. They are now struggling to rebuild
morale and performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They panicked, plain old palpable panic,'' said one former
Merrill executive who left the firm voluntarily. ``They were
shooting guys who bleed Merrill colors because they needed someone
to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill dismissed some 3,500 people from its fixed-income
division in the fall, far more than any other Wall Street firm. It
also reduced the amount of capital devoted to its debt business,
especially corporate debt and foreign government debt. Capital
devoted to corporate debt, for example, fell to $21.6 billion from
$35.5 billion, according to Merrill's annual report.
</P>
<P>
   The staff reductions and reallocation of capital represent a sea
change in what had been seen as an almost sacred part of its
franchise, people at the firm said. Komansky long mandated that
Merrill occupy the No. 1 spot across the board in debt. The firm
promised to serve customers anywhere, anytime. To fulfill that
edict, Merrill often used its own capital to buy bonds that
customers wanted to sell, even if there was no immediate buyer.
</P>
<P>
   All that seemed to change in the fall, when Merrill nearly shut
down its bond operation for weeks, Merrill executives and
institutional clients said. The business is up and running again,
but many say its future shape remains a question mark.
</P>
<P>
   Continued losses of important Merrill executives are adding to
the uncertainty. Recent defections include David Webb, director of
the Merrill unit that raises money for leveraged buyouts; Thomas
Gahan, global leader of leveraged finance; Seth Waugh, the former
top executive of the global debt business; David Tory, in charge of
corporate bonds in Europe, and Nabeel Nabulsi, director of bond
sales in Europe. All were longtime Merrill executives whom Komansky
and Allison sought to keep, people close to the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Rethinking how best to manage the debt business was inevitable
after last fall's losses, Merrill officials said. They said the new
leaders in most debt operations had acted fast to reshape the units
and reduce the capital at risk. But they insisted that this would
not diminish Merrill's commitment to customers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, Merrill's purchase of the defunct Yamaichi Securities
was greeted as a master stroke, positioning it to build a United
States-style brokerage operation just as Japan climbed out of its
long recession. But Japan's slump has proved stubborn, and costs
have bloated. Merrill lost $230 million on the retail operation
there last year, considerably more than it had predicted. This
year's losses will probably hit $300 million, with some people
close to the operation saying the results could be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese middle-class investors have not been as quick to open
brokerage accounts as Merrill had hoped, and the amount of assets
the firm has gathered there has proved disappointing, people close
to the operation said. In part, they said, that is because the
firm's American-style approach has met resistance in Japan. For
example, Merrill asks clients to fill out a long questionnaire
about their income and their families, information many Japanese
are not eager to disclose to a broker.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill does not dispute that losses in Japan are heavy. But
Wiggins said the firm always expected that it would take three
years for the operation to break even. The losses are also pretax,
Wiggins noted, meaning that the impact on Merrill's bottom line is
less severe than the numbers suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Whether setbacks like this mean that Merrill is more receptive
to overtures from banks is a hot topic of discussion at the firm,
fueled most recently by reports of a coming article in Forbes
magazine that explores a potential link with Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between Chase and Merrill last year produced no deal, in
part because Merrill demanded big concessions in running the
combined banking behemoth, and also asked that Chase pay a hefty
premium over Merrill's stock price at the time, people close to
those talks said. Adding to doubts is word that Chase, which has
sought a merger partner for months, is at the moment exploring ties
with J.P. Morgan, not Merrill, people close to the two banks said.
</P>
<P>
   But insiders do not rule out the prospect of Komansky's
considering a deal that would dispel the gloom at the firm. As one
person close to the firm put it, ``That's one way to be alpha dog
again.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
