<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CURRENCY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CURRENCY SPROUTS IN MENDOCINO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW LaMAR Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENDOCINO, Calif. _ The independence of this tiny coastal
village known for its striking ocean vistas and vibrant artistic
community has never been in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   But for many who make their home in this isolated region, the
next paycheck is sometimes very much in question.
</P>
<P>
   It's partly for that reason, activists say, that they launched a
local currency. The Mendocino coast joined the ranks of more than
65 other communities across the country when it began issuing its
own bills three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   SEED, which stands for Self-Sufficient Ecological Economic
Development, can be purchased for between $5 and $5,000 and used to
supplement U.S. dollars for the purchase of local goods and
services. The SEED organizing committee uses the money raised by
selling the bills to pay for printing costs and for a newsletter
that lists the businesses and people who accept the local currency.
</P>
<P>
   One SEED is the equivalent of roughly $10 U.S. dollars, or one
hour of work, whether you're a lawyer or a ditch digger. People
with the new currency are encouraged to use it to buy services or
goods from someone else in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seemed like it would be fun,'' said Susan Hofberg, who
began discussing the idea with a dozen fellow organizers over a
year ago. ``It's really the right thing to do, to have a barter
network facilitated by a currency that works for our community.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a home-grown currency was prompted by fear that
modern commerce is siphoning cash away from the Mendocino coast.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say the rise of inland malls and Internet shopping
has added to the economic woes of the region, which has watched
timber and fishing jobs dwindle over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The key, according to Hofberg, is where the money goes. SEED
remains in the community forever, whereas money spent at chain
stores goes to the corporate headquarters and is used in the
corporations' interests.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 200 people have signed up for the new currency, which
is to be exchanged in coastal communities between Elk and Westport.
The money is legal because it is backed by a nonprofit agency and
has a value greater than $1. SEED also comes in one-half,
one-quarter and one-eighth denominations, and all four SEED notes
are adorned with the work of coastal artists.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Miklose, who has run the Down Home Foods health food
store in Fort Bragg for 24 years, jumped on board after hearing
about it. The store accepts SEED to supplement any purchase of more
than $15.
</P>
<P>
   Along with strengthening the community's reliance upon itself,
the new bills will add to the Mendocino coast's allure as a tourist
destination, Miklose said.
</P>
<P>
   One beauty of the new currency is that it has attracted support
from all coastal political persuasions, which run the gamut from
ultraliberals in Mendocino to working-class conservatives in Fort
Bragg, said organizer Margaret Howe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone believes it's a good idea to keep the money here,''
Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of local currency cite many reasons for the
popularity of the movement. The barter-like exchange of community
bills requires interaction that heightens people's awareness of
their community and counteracts forces, such as computers and
automobiles, that can serve to drive communities apart, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now part of a nationwide movement,'' the SEED Exchange
newsletter proclaimed, ``that emphasizes trust, cooperation, and
regionalism _ qualities that can be very uplifting in this era of
corporate control and environmental worries.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it may take several years to build the circulation of
the bills. Advocates of local currency who started the trend eight
years ago in Ithaca, N.Y., advise building money slowly to avoid
inflationary problems.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Hofberg said, people must become accustomed to the bills
and how to use them. The health food cooperative Hofberg helps
manage in Mendocino is already struggling with how to distribute
the new bills to employees.
</P>
<P>
   Another critical element is enlisting people with a diversity of
skills so the money can be used for more than a massage or a vase
made by a local artisan. Initial members include one lawyer and a
community health clinic, and Hofberg would like to see the
professional services expand.
</P>
<P>
   The new money couldn't be better for Bernie MacDonald, a former
computer instructor who is working to develop an electric vehicle
at his home in Mendocino, he said. He can earn SEED by assisting
people with their computers and then use the SEED for everyday
living.
</P>
<P>
   Recently he purchased 20 gallons of organic compost for his
greenhouse for 10 SEED.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the day-to-day economics more obvious,'' MacDonald
said. ``My personal belief is community activity is local economic
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
