<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEANIE-BABY-BANDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEANIE BABY BANDIT ARRESTED ; GIGI, JAKE AND JABBER STILL MISSING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ The Beanie Baby Bandit is safely behind
bars, the Suffolk County police said Friday. But the litter that
was stolen from a Centerport stationery shop last month _ 200
floppy creatures with names like Gigi, Jake and Jabber _ appears to
have been lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days ago, the case, investigated by detectives from the
2nd Precinct, had grown cold. But a March 11 press release from
Crime Stoppers of Suffolk County drew a blitz of news coverage, and
television news programs broadcast videotape taken by a security
camera at the shop that showed the burglar in a Syracuse University
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Watching at home, detectives from the 7th Precinct recognized
the man as Douglas Gibbs, 57, of Ronkonkoma, whom they had arrested
five days earlier and charged with a gas station burglary in Rocky
Point. Gibbs' mother-in-law told detectives that she, too, had seen
the tape, and agreed that he was the burglar, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   With Gibbs behind bars, the police searched his home last
Saturday and found the Syracuse jacket, and the cash register and
lottery ticket dispenser stolen from Hope's Stationery, officials
said. The cash-and-scratch tickets were gone and so were the Beanie
Babies. The police did find about 20 of the pellet-packed
playthings at Gibbs' home, but they apparently were no relation to
the missing Babies. ``The store owner can't ID the ones we
recovered,'' said Lt. Frank Stallone.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Scicutella, the shopkeeper, said he had moved from anger
to acceptance. ``I want to just move on,'' he said. ``I didn't even
want to press charges. But with the coverage the police gave me, I
didn't really have a choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
