<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-BALANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL BUDGET COMMITTEE LOOKS TO GET $500 MILLION FOR GOVERNORS
ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal budget is chock-full of them every
year: sources of revenue based more on wishful thinking than
hard-headed analysis. They help balance the budget on paper, though
they may not produce a dime. One of them happens to be a historic
island in New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Since enacting the budget of 1997, Congress has presumed that
the federal government would earn $500 million by auctioning off
Governors Island in 2002. Real estate developers and city officials
consider the price hilariously high because the cost of developing
and maintaining the 173-acre island is expected to be immense,
potentially requiring government assistance. But removing the item
from the government's long-term budget plan would require finding
another $500 million to replace it, a daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Senate Budget Committee has approved legislation
sponsored by a bipartisan group of Midwestern senators that would
move up the sale of Governors Island to next year, so the money
could be used to expand federal crop insurance for farmers. The
full Senate is expected to take up the bill next week.
</P>
<P>
   New York officials are reacting with a mixture of amusement and
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take this seriously,'' Deputy Mayor Randy L. Levine
said. ``If they can sell it for $500 million, they should do it.
We'd be thrilled. Because whoever could pay $500 million for it
could really do something incredible with the island.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn B. Maloney, a Manhattan Democrat, said: ``They are
trying to plug a hole in the budget. But this is a fraudulent way
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But other officials said the committee's actions were troubling
because they signaled an unwillingness among many members of
Congress to give the island to New York City. In 1995, President
Clinton told New York Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan that he would be
willing to help in an effort to transfer the island to the city for
$1, provided state and city officials could come up with an
acceptable plan for it.
</P>
<P>
   A commission appointed by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is expected to
release a plan for the island, a former Coast Guard station, in the
coming months. Ideas include a mixture of park land, university
housing and commercial space. Any plan would have to preserve the
historic buildings and fortifications on the island, which is just
off the southern tip of Manhattan. The island was an Army post from
the 1790s to the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bullock, chief of staff for Moynihan, said the senator
would try to kill the measure on the Senate floor. If that effort
fails, the bill could also be blocked in the House or removed
during budget negotiations between the two chambers later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Levine said the Budget Committee's move provided evidence that
New York state needs a Republican senator, asserting that a member
of the Senate majority could have blocked the bill. Giuliani, a
Republican, is considering running for the Senate next year. The
state's two Senators, Moynihan and Charles E. Schumer, are
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But Bullock scoffed at that assertion. ``This stuff goes on all
the time here,'' he said. ``The island is a big 180-acre target
floating out there in the harbor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 0047EST &QL; 
