A7713 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     03-20 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURIOUS LAKERS FALL FLAT IN PHILLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ One piece away from championship contention a
week ago, in pieces today, the Lakers near the end of their road
trip with nothing but losses and question marks to show for 3,500
miles of travel.
</P>
<P>
   Nine straight wins have given way to two straight losses, three
in four games, the latest a 105-90 pounding by the Philadelphia
76ers on Friday. So infuriating was the defeat, it sent the Lakers'
coach into a near-confrontation with a mouthy fan, and sent players
into a frenzy of self-blame.
</P>
<P>
   And now the questions burn: Where did their defense go? Why the
inconsistent offense? Who's to blame? Did Dennis Rodman really mean
that much to their winning streak? In short, what the heck
happened?
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to the man known as ``The Answer'' to provide one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they need Rodman,'' Allen Iverson volunteered, after
torching the Lakers for 41 points. ``I see some chaos in their
team. I won't elaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, even The Answer has to keep a few in reserve. Or maybe he
was just too tired to keep giving answers after answering the
challenge for four quarters against the Lakers. In a simply
spectacular display of his skills, Iverson shot the ball a
career-high 36 times and converted 17 of them for a sizzling 47.2
percent success rate.
</P>
<P>
   He scored off screens and on pick-and-rolls, in traffic and in
the open court, from short range and long distance, on drives and
spot-up jumpers, crossing over Kobe Bryant, Derek Harper and
whoever else was in his path.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's new a.k.a. should be MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave the ball to Allen Iverson,'' said coach Kurt Rambis,
asked what the Sixers did to take over the game. ``He was just
drilling everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers, as per usual on this six-game road trip, were
unable to respond. Rambis said their erratic defense had improved,
yet for the second straight night the Lakers gave up 100 points and
allowed 49.4 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Harper blamed himself. Bryant volunteered, too. Others should
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the point guard, I take a lot of responsibility for those
two losses (to Cleveland and Philadelphia),'' Harper said. ``We got
stagnant on offense and I just didn't get what we needed to get
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, there was just no stopping Iverson. Bryant failed
that test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew how I wanted to guard him,'' Bryant said, ``but I just
wasn't prepared for pick-and-roll situations. That's it. It was
just my fault for not being prepared. It won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having the league's best shooter (Glen Rice) and
field-goal percentage leader (Shaquille O'Neal), the Lakers shot
40.8 percent _ 27.8 percent in the second half. Worse, the
Rodman-less Lakers were killed on the boards 46-34, and O'Neal
grabbed just four.
</P>
<P>
   And while O'Neal and Bryant scored 23 points each, they also
coughed up five turnovers apiece to account for half of the Lakers'
20 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played well,'' O'Neal said of the Sixers. ``I don't think
they really beat us. We pretty much beat ourselves . . . taking
ill-advised shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The collapse came in phases, first in a second-quarter collapse
in which the Lakers squandered a 10-point lead, then in a
third-quarter meltdown in which the Sixers used an 18-6 run to take
a double-digit lead that effectively put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis found it tough to take. He stomped. He paced to halfcourt
and back. He crumpled up stat sheets.
</P>
<P>
   And in the waning seconds, he nearly lost his cool, exchanging
words with a heckler, who he heatedly told, ``Say something
intelligent. Say something intelligent.'' The fan kept at it,
Rambis walked behind the bench and took a step toward him, stopping
when assistant coach Chris Bodaken intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a competitive person. I don't like to lose,'' Rambis said
of his frustration. But of the incident with the fan, he said only,
``We'll leave that one alone.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not alone in his fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss. Without a doubt,'' Harper said. ``But you
gotta keep going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 0050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
