<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-POLITICS-NOTEBO     03-20 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-POLITICS-NOTEBOOK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO-WHITE GROUP PUTS REPUBLICANS ON HOT SEAT  
 POLITICAL MUSIC MAN  
 TAKING AIM AT NATIONAL SECURITY  
 COMPENSATING LANDOWNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Fla., Miss., Ga., N.C., Ohio, Ala., La.)  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A self-described ``pro-white'' group with roots in
the South is generating a fuss on Capitol Hill, where some
lawmakers, mostly Democrats, want to condemn it as racist.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that several Republican lawmakers have ties to
the Council of Conservative Citizens and the GOP leadership doesn't
seem particularly enthusiastic about a congressional
tongue-lashing. In fact, they seem to wish the whole matter would
simply disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 138 House members, including just 11 Republicans, have
endorsed a resolution condemning the council. Critics cite the
writings of some CCC members, who deride the intelligence of blacks
and warn against marriage between the races, as evidence of the
group's bigoted views.
</P>
<P>
   But only one Southern Republican, Rep. Jay Dickey of Arkansas,
has joined the condemnation effort.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., a chief sponsor of the resolution,
hopes more lawmakers will sign on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress and the American people must not remain silent,''
Wexler said.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans are embarrassed by the fact that lawmakers such
as Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Rep. Bob Barr,
R-Ga., spoke before state chapters of the council. Pressed about
their appearances, both men said they did not agree with all of the
views of the council members.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders won't say if they will bring the resolution to the
floor for a vote. And a spokesman for Lott said it would be unfair
to condemn the entire group for the opinions of a few. A competing
resolution making the rounds of Republican offices would condemn
all racism, without citing the CCC.
</P>
<P>
   But one prominent conservative activist, Arianna Huffington,
called on Republicans to take a stronger public stand against such
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing more immoral ... than playing footsie with
racists,'' Huffington said. ``This is at the heart of the
caricature about the Republican Party, that it does not care about
minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC MAN
</P>
<P>
   There they were, some of America's top music stars from the
1950s and 1960s _Mary Wilson of the Supremes, Bowzer of Sha Na Na,
Sam Moore of Sam and Dave _ and Rep. Howard Coble, the rumpled
Republican of North Carolina?
</P>
<P>
   The musical artists descended on Capitol Hill to lobby for a
bill that would grant them new performing rights and stronger
trademark protection from competing copycat groups.
</P>
<P>
   Coble can't sing, but he presides over the House subcommittee
with jurisdiction over copyright law, so he provided back-up of
sorts at the press conference, promising to help get the bill
passed. The ``Truth in Rock Act'' is sponsored by Dennis Kucinich,
D-Ohio, whose Cleveland district includes the Rock 'n' Roll Hall of
Fame, and Charlie Norwood, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Coble recalled that he did sing last year in his office when
some artists came to his office asking for help. ``No agents
knocked on my door,'' Coble said of his rendition of ``Charlie
Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Burned by their failed drive to oust President Clinton from
office over the Monica Lewinsky scandal, Republicans are zeroing in
on what many consider a far bigger problem with this White House _
national security.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners, who have long prided themselves on their emphasis
on national defense matters, are in the front lines. Many,
including some Democrats, are blasting the Clinton administration
for its handling of a possible espionage case at Los Alamos
National Laboratory, suggesting it indicates a lax attitude about
security matters. Critics say the FBI took too long to investigate
a scientist suspected of passing warhead design secrets to the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``an institutional disregard for security at our national
labs,' Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Select
Committee on Intelligence, called on the administration to halt
visits to American nuclear research labs by scientists from
sensitive countries.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENTAL CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the Endangered Species Act, opponents of the
federal law say what is good for the goose should be good for the
gander.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that a federal agency was recently paid $26 million to
absorb some impacts on threatened wildlife from a Minneapolis
airport expansion, they likewise want private landowners
financially compensated when they are forced to make accommodations
for wildlife deemed in danger of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Positive incentives always work better than a gun-to-the-head
approach,'' said Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., a longtime foe of the
Clinton administration's approach to species issues.
</P>
<P>
   Private landowners are not now compensated if the government
places restrictions on the use of their land to protect endangered
species, a fact that galls property rights groups. But the new
proposal is likely to draw considerable fire from conservation
groups that want even tighter restrictions on private property that
is home to rare plants and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
