<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SENATORS-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS TIP OVER STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A tip of the goal last night gave the Stars their worst
slump of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But looking at the play on the ice, you'd never be able to tell.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had a third-period Tony Hrkac goal disallowed because
the net had tipped off of its base, and lost a 2-1 game to the
Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   The loss meant the Stars had strung together two consecutive
defeats for only the third time this season and it created their
longest winless drought at four games (0-2-2). Even so, the Stars
outshot the Senators, 32-14, including 13-1 in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the game lived up to its billing,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said of the high-speed affair that between the teams with
the NHL's best records.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars fall to 42-14-12 (96 points) but remain nine points
ahead of the Eastern Conference-leading Senators (39-20-9) in the
quest for the Presidents' Trophy, given to the team with the best
regular-season record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to see where we're at, so it was a big game from
that standpoint,'' Senators coach Jacques Martin said. ``Dallas has
a lot more experience than us, but we're learning as we go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars felt they had worked hard enough for at least a tie,
but were denied when Hrkac had a goal taken away at the 11:44 mark
of the third period because the net had tilted forward and was off
its base when the puck went in. Stars winger Grant Marshall worked
hard to get a puck from Rhodes behind the net and fed Hrkac in the
right circle for an easy shot into an open net. In his haste to
return to the front of the net, Rhodes ran into his own defenseman
Lance Pitlick and fell down, pulling the net forward for a second.
</P>
<P>
   NHL rules state a goal cannot be scored if the net is not in
place, unless a player from the defending team ``intenionally''
knocks the net from its moorings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it deliberate? No, I don't think it was,'' referee Paul
Devorski said. ``If it was deliberate, yeah, we could have awarded
a goal. But in that case, the net wasn't sitting down when the puck
went across the line, so we can't allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, it was bad luck for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They caught a break,'' Hitchcock said. ``That's the fine line
when you've got two good teams going at it. They needed that break
at that time, because we were pretty well all over them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars rolled onto the ice in the first period with the
intention of getting their forecheck in hard and pushing their
defensemen up into the play. They did just that, swarming the
Senators, getting two power-play chances and scoring on one when
Darryl Sydor deflected in a Mike Modano shot at the 7:16 mark of
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process of pushing so hard to the Senators' net, the
Stars left themselves uncovered defensively. The speedy Senators
took advantage for several outmanned rushes and strong scoring
chances on Stars goalie Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   The key chance came in the final 30 seconds of the first period
with the line of Joe Nieuwendyk, Pat Verbeek and Jamie
Langenbrunner on the ice. Sergei Zubov got caught in a scrum along
the right boards and no forward rotated back to help cover. That
left the Stars facing a 2-on-1 and Andreas Dackell bounced in a
crossing pass off Sydor with 19.8 seconds remaining in the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators grabbed that momentum and capitalized in the second
period, again outhustling the line of Nieuwendyk, Langenbrunner and
Verbeek. This time, winger Steve Martins carried the turnover up
ice and behind the Stars net, feeding out to Marian Hossa in the
slot, who had beat the check of Nieuwendyk to the net and flicked
in his 11th goal.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be the game-winner when Hrkac's goal was
disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We battled hard, we worked hard, we had lots of scoring
chances,'' Hitchcock said. ``But you know what, we have to finish
those chances.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
