<HEADLINE>
MIAMI,SZCZERBIAK CAN'T SLOW KENTUCKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST LOUIS _ In a Midwest Regional engagement between Miami and
Kentucky on Friday night, a familiar sociological struggle
re-emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Man against machine, with the usual results.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Wally Szczerbiak concluded his amazing experience in the
NCAA Tournament, leaving little doubt among 42,440 patrons at the
Trans World Dome that he is among the nation's finest players.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Kentucky (28-8) left little doubt that it is among
the finest teams, rolling methodically to a 58-43 victory and a
date with Michigan State in Sunday's regional final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally is a great player, but we had a great team performance
today,'' said Kentucky coach Tubby Smith. ``The bench really came
through for us _ we got help from a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could kind of see it when they hit the wall in the second
half. I think we kind of wore Wally down finally.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak finished with 23 points _ giving him 90 for three
tournament games. But for Miami (24-8), he was almost the whole
show. His supporting cast was overwhelmed by Kentucky's depth and
towering front line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a great run,'' Miami coach Charlie Coles said. ``But
when Scott Padgett started hitting threes in the second half, it
was a little too much for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Padgett, who finished with 17 points, capped a 10-0 run midway
through the second half that finished the RedHawks, who fell
behind, 45-28, with little hope of recovery. The Wildcats' lead
eventually reached 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats finished with a 37-18 advantage on the boards.
Excluding Szczerbiak, the RedHawks were 6-of-28 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   If third-seeded Kentucky can win again Sunday against a
top-seeded Michigan State team that has thus far been victorious
but unimpressive, the Wildcats will secure their fourth consecutive
trip to the Final Four. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
