<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-ADVANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S-OHIO STATE IS BATTLE OF BACKCOURTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ St. John's coach Mike Jarvis is not queasy
about his wishes regarding what he would like to see happen to Ohio
State's guards before they face his team tonight in the South
Regional championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish \RScoonie Penn and Michael Redd\S would go to the same
restaurant \RRon Artest\S went to the other night and that they
would fall over ``both'' beds in their rooms,'' Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm coach was referring to the sequence of events of
earlier in the week when his star guard-forward slightly injured
his ankle while attempting to get to the bathroom in the middle of
the night after eating what Artest termed, ``some nasty food.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was only one of the ways Jarvis expressed his
appreciation _ backhanded though it may have been _ for the Buckeye
counterparts to the Red Storm's Erick Barkley and Bootsy Thornton.
And Jarvis did not mince words when it comes to the long-held
theory that teams with the best guards usually advance in the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is guard time, when the guards step up,'' Jarvis said.
``Ohio State has as good a backcourt as there is in all the United
States of America. It's going to be a great matchup. Our guys who
play against them are going to have their work cut out for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley and Thornton combined for 41 points in St. John's 76-62
semifinal victory over Maryland. Penn and Redd connected for 48 in
Ohio State's 72-64 win over top-seeded Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Barkley and Thornton are very good scorers who can get to
the bucket,'' Buckeyes' coach Jim O'Brien said. ``Barkley has
tremendous quickness and is good \Ron the dribble\S with either
hand. Thornton can put points on the board. Didn't he get 40
against Duke?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to do a really good job of knowing where
they are and not giving them a lot of space. But the thing I like
is the way they pass the ball. They have a lot of players who are
good with the ball and are unselfish players.''
</P>
<P>
   The focal matchup will be between Penn and Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither team would be here without them,'' Jarvis said. ``In
Scoonie and Erick, you have two of the best in the country. And you
cannot get to the point we're at without a great point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the main thing that makes them great is, team and winning
come first. They believe they can win every game they play.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn, a 5-foot-10 scooter, has 142 assists to 94 turnovers. He
set a school record with 83 successful 3-point shots while
averaging 16.9 points a game. The 6-1 Barkley passed out 168
assists against 76 turnovers, made 56 3-pointers and averaged 13.5
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a chance to watch Erick several times this season on
TV,'' Penn said. ``He does a great job of running their team. He's
the leader, the guy who gets them going. It's going to be a good
matchup, one that should be fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Redd, who averages a team-leading 19.6 points and has 77
assists, said it's not unusual for the Buckeyes to face this kind
of challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played against great guards all year long in the Big 10,
so this is nothing new,'' he said. ``But St. John's does have great
guards and this will be a challenge to us.''
</P>
<P>
   There is always the possibility that other things will determine
which team advances to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those combinations neutralize each other,'' Jarvis noted.
``It may go to which team has the best frontcourt. And that's how
the game may unfold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
