<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     03-20 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A CHATTY EL-AMIN BACKING IT UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Jim Calhoun is built like one of those enforcers who
used to protect Bob Cousy in the old days. His speech is
unadulterated Boston corner boy. But he looks at Khalid El-Amin, an
Orthodox Muslim point guard from Minneapolis, with body by
Teletubbies, and he sees a kindred soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can relate to Khalid more than almost any other player I've
ever had,'' Calhoun said. ``Even down to getting the hungry
horrors.''
</P>
<P>
   The hungry horrors?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you know, when you're starving at 11 o'clock at night,''
Calhoun explained.
</P>
<P>
   They share another hunger _ the desire to verbalize, to explain,
to put their stamp on everything around them. They are so much
alike that Calhoun must sometimes tell El-Amin to just button it
up, leave it alone. Quiet!
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun and his roly-poly henchman must beat Gonzaga Saturday to
send Connecticut to the Final Four for the first time in school
history.
</P>
<P>
   There is a decade of frustration, which Calhoun sought to end by
recruiting El-Amin, even though Connecticut already had point
guards galore. The coach also had to come to grips with El-Amin's
buttery 5-foot-10-inch, 203-pound body, which was no more likely to
shape up than his penchant for verbosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were not going to allow me to play my game,
but he took a chance on me,'' El-Amin said Thursday night, after
leading Connecticut to a bruising 78-68 victory over Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin, a sophomore, seems fearless, projecting his
human-bowling-ball body into the air at oblique angles and tossing
up soft shots off the backboard. He often leads with his lip,
yapping and gesticulating, as he did Thursday, when he nearly
touched off a melee.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the half ended, he watched Jess Settles, a truculent
sixth-year senior for Iowa, burrow his forehead into the forehead
of Connecticut's Edmund Saunders, the two of them trading baleful
Sonny Liston-type scowls.
</P>
<P>
   This struck El-Amin as hilarious. As Iowa went to shoot a free
throw, El-Amin made running commentary, acting like the
prototypical schoolyard agitator, his expressive face ranging from
chortles to smirks, as if to say, ``I can't believe that your guy
thinks he can beat up on my guy.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin's remarks annoyed Joey Range of Iowa. A few seconds
later, as the teams headed for their respective locker rooms, Range
stuck out his arm _ reached down, actually, being seven inches
taller than El-Amin _ and clotheslined him by his stubby little
neck. Needless to say, more words were exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I didn't appreciate that,'' El-Amin said.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun did not appreciate El-Amin's stoking Iowa, which was
already setting a tone with flying-Wallenda rebounds, elbows
flailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, anybody who talks is going to have a seat next to
me,'' Calhoun said later. ``I told them to shut up. Just shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   This is hard for Calhoun to do, he admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khalid and I are both nonstop personalities,'' Calhoun said.
``I am 63-7 with him. We are in the NCAA's with him. He's one of
the great ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has felt this way about El-Amin since his recruiting
visit to Minneapolis, where El-Amin was already something of a
celebrity. He was married with child, had the state map tattooed on
his left bicep, and was not necessarily the perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun took him to Connecticut for a visit, and El-Amin found
his way to the gym for a workout with incumbent players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this guy screaming and yelling,'' recalled the
senior Ricky Moore, the starting point guard at the time. ``Guys
were saying, `Who is this kid?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Given El-Amin's shape and his mouth and his aspirations, Moore
said: ``I could easily have said, `This isn't the place for you.'
But we have a lot of guys who are competitive, and we want the best
team possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, in the meantime, uttered the magic words, ``start as a
freshman,'' to El-Amin. This has forced Moore to play the off guard
position, but the players quickly accepted El-Amin, and laughed at
his adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a game at Virginia when we were taking layups and
this guy asked me if I was hungry,'' El-Amin recalled. ``I said I
wasn't, but he held out a pizza box and said I'd be hungry by
halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this season, the fans in Pittsburgh were getting quite
personal, and when El-Amin's late shot beat the home team, he
jumped on a press table and crowed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, fans were calling him ``Idi Amin,'' but he laughed
that off, too. He has that glow of a man on a hot streak, the way
Keith Smart did before firing the winning jumper for Indiana in
1987 and Rumeal Robinson did before making the two epic free throws
for Michigan in 1989. They were both bright guys who had been
around, and were not in awe of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is an exciting game,'' El-Amin said. ``You've got
to have fun playing it. You give 110 percent, sure, but it's got to
be fun. The crowd calls me `fat boy,' that gives me motivation. I
just laugh it off.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes the incoming fire. At news conferences, the Connecticut
players defer to their chubby teammate. They know he wants the
microphone _ and the basketball.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
