<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-KENTUCKY-MIAMI-NY     03-20 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KENTUCKY-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY AGAINST SZCZERBIAK IS NO CONTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Wally Szczerbiak could not rescue Miami of Ohio one
more time. He could not keep his and Miami's magical journey
through March alive, not by himself. That is really what it
amounted to Friday night as Szczerbiak and four sometimes-invisible
teammates fought Kentucky and lost, 58-43. The matchup was a
mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak was the premier player on the court, but Scott
Padgett was almost his equal, and the third-seeded Wildcats proved
that they were the premier team with just enough defense and more
than enough depth to outlast the one-dimensional RedHawks. It was
an awful experience for 10th-seeded Miami, which could have made
the game much more interesting if someone not named Szczerbiak
occasionally slashed to the hoop or drilled a jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to do whatever it took to keep us in the
game,'' Szczerbiak said. ``Unfortunately, it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to do whatever it took to win. The zone they
played, it seemed like no one had an answer for it. There was
nothing tactical we could do. When they stick those long arms out,
it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was the team with the best players, not the team with the
best player, that marched through the semifinals of the West
Regional to oppose Michigan State on Sunday. Padgett had 17 points
for the Wildcats, including 14 in the second half and 12 during one
stretch that broke Miami's back.
</P>
<P>
   If the defending national champions beat the Spartans, the
Wildcats (28-8) will reach the hallowed Final Four for the fourth
straight season and will be trying to win their third title in that
time. Szczerbiak finished his college career with 23 points, but
only 8 after intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Wally was going to get his points,'' Padgett said.
``We wanted to play good team defense and make other people make
plays for them. I know this is crazy to say, but he only got 16
shots. I guess we limited him a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Padgett and Jamaal Magloire defended him physically, and the
Wildcats were more willing to let him shoot jumpers than to let him
drive. Szczerbiak, who did not force shots even as it became
apparent that he was Miami's only option, went 8 for 16 from the
field. The other players on Miami (24-8) were an unsightly 6 for
28, and that included two irrelevant field goals in the last 90
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After Damon Frierson, Szczerbiak's sidekick, finally drilled a
3-pointer to chop the deficit to 35-28 with his first points,
Kentucky got serious. Padgett made four free throws, stole the ball
from Szcerbiak, hit two 3-pointers and another jumper. When the
slaughter had finally ended for Miami, Padgett had 12 points during
a 14-4 streak and the Wildcats led, 49-32.
</P>
<P>
   ``Padgett got those threes in,'' said Miami Coach Charlie Coles.
``I thought he hit some key shots. Once he did that, they did a
marvelous job on defense. ''
</P>
<P>
   Padgett pumped his fist against his chest after the game-turning
run. No one could save Miami anymore, not even Szczerbiak. As
Padgett celebrated, Szczerbiak's eyes were on his sneakers. He knew
his season and his college career were over. The best player had
lost. The best team had won.
</P>
<P>
   Other than being rather low-scoring, the first half played out
as expected. Kentucky led Miami, 26-19, and Szczerbiak led Miami
with 15 points. It was the one-man team against the team with 10
men, and the Wildcats could not stop Wally, but that did not stop
them from scooting to the lead. Saul Smith climaxed the first half
with a double pump 3-pointer at the buzzer for Kentucky and then
inadvertently knocked over Miami's red hawk mascot as he rumbled to
the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wanted to see Szczerbiak. Even Kentucky's players were
intrigued and determined about playing the sweet shooter known as
Wally World. The Wildcats surged to a 4-0 lead on Scott Padgett's
dunk and Wayne Turner's jumper, but Szczerbiak buried a 3-pointer
the first time he touched the ball. After Heshimu Evans converted a
layup, Szczerbiak drilled an 18-footer to make it 6-5. It was the
second time he had touched the ball. There was electricity in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   But then it disappeared, along with Miami. Kentucky methodically
reeled off 10 straight points. In 11 consecutive possessions the
RedHawks went 0 for 9 from the field and had two turnovers.
Szczerbiak was 0 for 3 with 1 turnover during the eight and a half
minute drought. The Kentucky fans, who were boisterous and
outfitted in blue, derisively chanted, ``Wall-eee, Wall-eee,'' as
the lead expanded to 16-5.
</P>
<P>
   With 8:55 left in the half and Miami standing still against
Kentucky's man to man defense, Szczerbiak finally ended the lengthy
drought by taking a step back and swishing another 3-pointer. It
was 16-8 and Szczerbiak had all of Miami's points. It was looking
more and more obvious that Miami needed Szczerbiak to have an
awesome game to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Miami sputtered and did not receive points from
someone other than Szczerbiak until Anthony Taylor's two free
throws with 6:22 remaining, the Wildcats did not pin the RedHawks.
Kentucky's largest advantage was 19-10 and that immediately shrunk
when Szczerbiak scored 5 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   The RedHawks trimmed the deficit to 21-17 on Rob Mestas' basket
with 2:50 left in the half, the first field goal by a player other
than Szczerbiak. But Kentucky did not allow Szczerbiak University
to get any closer than that. While Szczerbiak was 5 for 9 from the
field, his vanishing teammates were a gory 1 for 12. Damon
Frierson, who averages 13.1 points a game, and John Estick, who
scores 8.5, were a combined 0 for 6 from the field with no points.
The RedHawks had Wally and almost nothing else, which is why the
Wildcats had the edge. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
