<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MEDIA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TV PLANTED SEEDS OF MADNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television's influential role in sport past, present and future
is the underlying theme of HBO's latest episode of ``Real Sports
With Bryant Gumbel'', which airs at 9 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The first three segments of the hourlong program focus on a
college basketball game played in Houston 31 years ago, the raging
economic disparity among Major League Baseball franchises and the
mystery that is Dick Vitale.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Dicky V, the connection between the subjects and the
television industry seems tenuous. But as the program shows,
neither college basketball nor baseball's financial ills would be
what they are without television. Neither, of course, would Vitale.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball game profiled is what a lot of observers regard
as the greatest ever played, the Houston-UCLA matchup on Jan. 20,
1968. That night the No. 2 Cougars, led by Elvin Hayes, upset Lew
Alcindor's top-ranked Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   The game was the first ever in college basketball to be
broadcast live nationally to a prime-time viewing audience.
Previously, even college basketball's national championship game
was aired on a tape-delayed basis. But unexpected interest in the
game helped an independent TV producer named Eddie Einhorn sell the
contest to 150 stations in 49 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the night that pushed college basketball from the
independent producer into the eyes of the networks,'' Einhorn said.
``And the big sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the next year NBC bought TV rights to college
basketball. Neither the game nor TV has looked back since. So was
born the mania that eventually became March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years, it's probably the most important
telecast of my career,'' recalls Dick Enberg, who that night called
his first national broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Considering how their sport has grown in popularity, NCAA
basketball advocates could say the same today.
</P>
<P>
   Television's influence on baseball's growing economic gap
between big market and small market clubs also is examined by HBO.
Kevin McClatchy, owner of the Pittsburgh Pirates, succinctly
identifies the problem by stating that the New York Yankees will
reap $55 million to $60 million this year in local cable TV rights
money while his club will earn closer to $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference right there,'' McClatchy states.
</P>
<P>
   One remedy that is offered: Don't allow rich clubs to televise
their road games played against poor franchises. That would
significantly cut into the rich clubs' revenue, perhaps forcing
them to accept greater revenue sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Rangers owner Tom Hicks to pump his fist at that
suggestion, however. In an interview from Port Charlotte, Fla.,
Hicks tells HBO that revenue sharing isn't likely as long as rich
clubs like the Rangers have to pay for their own oversized
payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to share the good stuff and keep all the bad
stuff,'' Hicks states.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks does estimate that when his forthcoming regional sports
network is up and operating the club could generate about one-half
the Yankees' local TV haul, enough, presumably, to keep the Rangers
among the big boys of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the power of television.
</P>
<P>
   Vitale, of course, would be nothing (at least not a celebrity)
without TV other than another fired coach. It's a piece of fortune
he clearly recognizes and for which he is obviously grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stealing money, baby, doing something I love,'' he tells
his interviewer, sympathizing with those who daily trudge to their
daily drudge. ``Please don't take it away from me.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 0125EST &QL; 
