r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SOUTHNOTES-TEX     03-20 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S PLAYERS FIND `ZONE' AFTER SWITCHING DEFENSES
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is unusual for a coach to turn away from proven strategies
late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in effect, that's what St. John's coach Mike Jarvis has
done. After playing a zone defense only sparingly while forging a
28-8 record and an NCAA Tournament first-round victory over
Samford, Jarvis has switched to the mainstay of a zone defense.
</P>
<P>
   The zone debuted in the stunning 86-61 victory over Indiana that
got the Red Storm to the Sweet 16. It was most effective in
Thursday's victory over Maryland that got St. John's to tonight's
South championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things work differently than you think,'' Jarvis
said. ``I remember before the Duke game (a 92-88 overtime loss Jan.
24), I said we're going to play some zone and if looks could kill,
they all would have killed me. I said, `Remember the first time we
met, I asked you to have faith and trust me.' They began to trust
me a little more as the year went along and began to understand why
I asked them to go to the zone. They're very intelligent players.
And it helps to have a positive experience. They're asking me to
play it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, however, discounts strategies at this stage of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about fresh minds and fresh legs,'' he said. COACHING
OVERRATED?
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien is one of many who thinks
television commentators and national basketball writers make too
much of coaching at this point of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about it,'' he said. ``And I've talked to our guys
about this. I really and truly believe we've lost sight of what
this is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone who has played this game a little bit (Boston
College, the ABA), I never remember thinking about a coach having
any impact on games. In the age of all this exposure, a little too
much is made of coaches. You can lose sight that this is for the
guys who are playing and getting it done.'' MILESTONES
</P>
<P>
   Two St. John's players are likely to set school records tonight
against Ohio State. Guard Erick Barkley is 11 points short of tying
the mark for most points by a freshman (498), held jointly by Chris
Mullin and Felipe Lopez. Winger Ron Artest is one steal away from
Malik Sealy's school-record 75 steals in a season. As a team, the
Red Storm with 358 steals, breaking the mark of 310 set in 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State has also set a school record for steals at 287.
PORTER PLANS TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's 6-foot-7 forward Chris Porter reiterated after Thursday
night's loss to St. John's that he would not opt to enter this
year's NBA draft and would return for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I said before still holds,'' the Southeastern Conference
player of the year said. ``We accomplished a lot this year, but
there are still some things we want to accomplish next year. This
is a young team (with two seniors) but we're going to play our best
and do what we can.'' SPOTLIGHT
</P>
<P>
   James ``Scoonie'' Penn School Pos. Ht. Wt. Yr. St. John's G 5-10
185 Jr. Did you know? Penn was the Big East Conference rookie of
the year in 1996 while playing for Boston College. As a sophomore,
he led the Eagles to the Big East tournament championship and was
selected the tourney's MVP. He followed coach Jim O'Brien when
O'Brien left BC to take the Ohio State job. After sitting out last
season, Penn has helped the Buckeyes turn things around this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Why should you care? Because transfers aren't always malcontents
and sometimes do have success at a second school. ``The decision
took quite awhile,'' Penn said. ``I wasn't sure if wanted to leave
home (Salem, Mass.) I had two good years at BC. But I also knew
which way the program was headed, but I didn't know if I wanted be
part of it anymore. I just felt it was best for me to leave.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
