A7734 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROTATION-     03-20 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROTATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LIKELY TO STAND PAT ON ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ The Rangers appear set to begin this season
with a rotation built from their existing roster.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's performance by right-hander Esteban Loaiza may leave
those in the organization uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza surrendered four runs (three earned) on four hits and two
walks during his three-inning appearance against the Philadelphia
Phillies, leaving him with a 7.04 earned-run average through 7 2/3
innings this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, I haven't had a club call and tell me that it
has pitching available,'' general manager Doug Melvin said before
yesterday's game at Jack Russell Stadium. ``There are probably 22
to 24 clubs looking to upgrade their pitching, and there's just not
that many pitchers available.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Melvin with two alternatives _ Cleveland's Orel
Hershiser and Kansas City's Kevin Appier _ from outside the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Neither thrills the Rangers, Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser can become a free agent tomorrow if the Indians do not
place the 40-year-old right-hander on their 40-man roster.
Hershiser pitched four scoreless innings Wednesday to improve his
ERA to 2.70 through 10 innings this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like `The Bulldog' of old,'' Indians pitching coach
Phil Regan told reporters after a Hershiser appearance this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers don't appear to be so convinced of `The Bulldog's'
bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't made that final decision,'' Melvin said of
Hershiser. ``We'll talk to our people who have seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   Appier, whom the Royals want to trade to reduce their payroll,
appears to be less of a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old right-hander, who this season will earn $4.9
million, pitched only 15 innings for the Royals last season after
undergoing arthroscopic surgery on his right shoulder a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Appier's contract also presents potential difficulties. His
salary will increase by $500,000 if he is traded this season, and
the contract also includes an option for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   That means it could become a multiyear contract if an
organization exercises the option. As a player with five or more
years of major-league experience, Appier could demand to be traded
after being traded in the midst of a multiyear contract. Therefore,
an organization could part with prospects in a trade and retain
Appier only for the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Mike Morgan, the leading candidate to become the
Rangers' long reliever, could become a possibility for the
rotation. Morgan owns a 0.79 ERA and has limited opponents to a
.231 batting average (9-for-39) through 11 1/3 innings this spring.
However, Morgan averaged only 5 1/3 innings per start last season.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, 27, remains an enigma because his talent often exceeds
the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like he has all spring to me,'' manager Johnny Oates
said. ``He makes some quality pitches, and he makes some pitches
that aren't so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza will remain in the rotation until those results alter the
manager's decision, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Morgan is not going to change my mind,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers likely would be interested in Oakland's Kenny
Rogers, Philadelphia's Curt Schilling and Minnesota's Brad Radke
should any of the three become available, but that will not be the
case before Opening Day, their respective general managers have
said repeatedly this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things can change,'' Melvin said. ``It's still a little
early.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
