<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO EYES START ON OPENING DAY
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ First baseman Rafael Palmeiro will be in the
Opening Day lineup if he appears in at least one exhibition game
before the Rangers return to Texas, manager Johnny Oates said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' exhibition schedule also includes games April 2-3
with the Houston Astros and New York Mets at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would give him at least three games, and that would be
plenty for me'' barring any setbacks, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers trainer Danny Wheat told Oates on Thursday that Palmeiro
could return by next week. Palmeiro, who underwent arthroscopic
surgery March 7 to remove torn cartilage from his right knee,
continues to show significant progress from his rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Conway, the Rangers' orthopedic consultant, plans to
return to Port Charlotte, Fla., next week to examine Palmeiro,
Oates said. PATTERSON ON TARGET
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Danny Patterson required only 11 pitches for his
one-inning appearance Friday against the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   That is significant, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, whom Oates prefers to limit to one-inning
appearances, can pitch effectively on consecutive days when the
reliever does not extend himself beyond 20 pitches during an
appearance. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Outfielder Milt Cuyler, who departed camp after Wednesday's
game to attend his grandfather's funeral, rejoined the Rangers for
Friday's game and delivered a ninth-inning single as a pinch
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Minor-league catcher Jason Torres joined the travel squad and
was used as an 11th-inning pinch hitter for right-hander Al Levine.
Phillies left-hander Billy Brewer retired Torres on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only several hundred tickets remain for the Rangers' Opening
Day game April 5 against Detroit at The Ballpark in Arlington.
Tickets can be purchased at The Ballpark or Dillard's ticket
outlets, at the Rangers' internet site (www.texasrangers.com),
through area electronic ticket machines or by calling the Rangers'
ticket office at (817) 273-5100. GAME RECAP RANGERS 6, PHILLIES 6
(12)
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-hander Al Levine could not protect a ninth-inning
lead, and the two clubs agreed to halt the game after Rangers
left-hander Mike Venafro was hit on the right wrist by a
12th-inning line drive off the bat of Philadelphia's David Miller.
The Rangers lacked another available pitcher to complete the game.
John Blake, the Rangers' vice president of media relations, said
Venafro's wrist was bruised.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate: Center fielder Ruben Mateo went 1 for 3 to extend
his hitting streak to eight games and is hitting .474 with two home
runs and six runs batted in. Blake said Mateo slammed into an
outfield wall late in the game and bruised his right hand. He and
Venafro are listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound: Left-hander Tony Fossas, who allowed two hits and
one walk during his two-inning appearance, has pitched 3 2/3
consecutive scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the field: Shortstop Royce Clayton committed his fourth error
since Monday by failing to field a bad-hop ground ball off the bat
of Phillies left fielder Ron Gant.
