<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ IS MONEY, SO GIVE HIM A BIG CHECK, NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ The crack of Juan Gonzalez's bat had the
ear-popping timbre of a rifle shot, and the baseball arched into
the blue Florida sky, climbing high and far beyond the fence in the
left-field power alley at Jack Russell Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said as we
watched the ball becoming smaller and smaller until it disappeared
beyond a stand of palm trees behind the fence. ``That ball didn't
go through the palm trees, it went over them!''
</P>
<P>
   His play-by-play was punctuated by another ``Crack!'' and
another ball flying into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's got a car in the parking lot,'' Oates rattled. ``I
wouldn't park out there today, I don't care how much insurance I
had. That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who has averaged 144 runs batted in over the past
three seasons, was putting on another of his frequent batting
practice power-hitting shows before the Rangers' exhibition game
with the Phillies yesterday, and no matter how often he has seen
them, Oates never tires of watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the best pure hitter I've ever seen, or the best
power hitter I've ever seen,'' Oates said, ``but I've never seen
anyone better at driving in runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played, managed or coached with five different 500-plus
home run hitters _ Hank Aaron, Eddie Mathews, Frank Robinson, Mike
Schmidt and Reggie Jackson _ but none of them was better than Juan
with men on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, those five all have a common address _ the
National Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y. Gonzalez will
be there one day, too, which is why the Rangers must do the smart
thing and sign him to another long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
   Now.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner the better.
</P>
<P>
   They were ahead of their time when they signed him to a
seven-year, $45.45 million contract (including the two options)
after the '93 season. Now they must be just as clever this time,
before Gonzalez becomes a free agent after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   No rush, you say? I beg to differ. The closer Gonzalez gets to
free agency, the more his agents and the players' union will push
him in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to find out how much you're worth on the market
is go try it,'' Oates said. ``Some of our players have gone that
route and regretted it later.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is just about money, if becoming wealthy to the point of
absurdity is all that matters to Gonzalez, then there's probably
not much the Rangers, who at least have opened negotiations, can do
to get this done. Gonzalez and Ken Griffey Jr., who also becomes a
free agent after the 2000 season, can take turns setting new
records for greed and avarice.
</P>
<P>
   But Juan has never been that kind of person.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business game,'' Gonzalez conceded, ``but Texas has
provided me security and the fans like me there. It's a great place
to play. Sometimes you maybe can make more money some other place,
but you don't feel as comfortable playing there.''
</P>
<P>
   How much is enough? That's the question Gonzalez must ponder.
How much does he need to assuage his pride and make him feel
wanted? Those who know him say he will feel insulted if the Rangers
offer him Mo Vaughn money _ $13.33 million a year _ and that he'd
like to see them do something about the two option years (this year
and next) on his contract. He will make about $16 million over the
next two years, and yes, that's well under market value.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is Gonzalez, who hit his 301st career home run before
celebrating his 29th birthday last October, worth?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he can get,'' second baseman Mark McLemore said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who are uncomfortable with the idea of
renegotiating Gonzalez's contract, must hope that Gonzalez will
maintain control of his contract situation and not leave it
strictly with agent Jim Bronner. Bronner preferred to take
Colorado's Larry Walker to free agency, but Walker pushed to
re-sign with the Rockies and got $75 million for six years.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers must get Gonzalez's attention and keep him
interested. They can do that by offering him a hefty signing bonus,
say something in the $10 million range, which allows them to deal
with the next two years without actually re-negotiating. Then they
extend him with a five-year deal for $15 million a year. That would
give Gonzalez a seven-year total of $91 million.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Pentagon and Kevin Brown could get insulted at that
kind of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If \Rthe Rangers\S continue to be smart,'' McLemore said,
``they'll do it now, before he throws another MVP award on 'em.
He's got that look in his eye like, `Let's go, let's get this
season started.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, it's the classic, pay-him-now or
pay-him-a-lot-more-later dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably a little more complicated than that, of course,
but how smart do you have to be to figure that one out?
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
