<SLUG> BC-BBN-WOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD NEEDED MORE MUSCLE, HOUSE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood was too strong and talented for
his own body, a problem all-star reliever Robb Nen had when he was
with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   That's the opinion of former Rangers pitching coach Dr. Tom
House, now a consultant with the San Diego Padres and a nationally
known expert on pitching injuries and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generated arm strength, and the muscle mass and the muscle
stamina didn't match up,'' House said. ``That's why he broke. He
was not strong enough or mature enough or hard-working enough for
what his gene pool produced.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs announced Tuesday that Wood, a former Grand Prairie
High School star, has a torn ligament in his right elbow and will
require surgery. He is expected to miss the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way those kids who throw hard enough can support it
is if they have to find enough strength to make it all hold
together,'' House said. ``The support systems _ primary muscles,
secondary muscles and connective tissue _ weren't functionally
strong enough with Kerry to balance the 100 mile per hour arm
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   House said the Rangers went through that with Nen and eventually
decided to move him to the bullpen. Nen also went on a massive
weightlifting program and, after the Rangers traded him, became a
front-line closer with the Florida Marlins and the San Francisco
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is Robb Nen worked his tail off,'' House said.
``If Kerry wants to be a starter, he's got to go hard; he's got to
become Roger Clemens or Nolan Ryan in the weight room to give
himself the strength base for what he creates.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood told a news conference in Arizona on Wednesday, ``It's safe
to say it was inevitable. From the time my velocity picked up and I
started to throw harder, I felt it could happen on any given day.''
</P>
<P>
   House said he did not believe Wood's mechanics or his workload
contributed to the injuries, and others agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year he's pitched since high school, he's missed time
because of his elbow,'' said Phil Regan, the Cubs' pitching coach
last year and now with the Cleveland Indians. ``All through his
career he has missed time because of his elbow. The other thing is,
last year was the first time he has pitched more than 150
innings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs kept Wood on a strict 110-pitch count through his
minor-league development, and his 20-strikeout performance against
the Houston Astros last May is the only complete game of his
professional career. Only nine of his 28 starts last year went
longer than seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wood complained of a tired arm last August. He threw more than
120 pitches just once in his last nine starts before being shut
down in September. He made one start against the Atlanta Braves in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals manager Tony La Russa was among those who praised Cubs
manager Jim Riggleman for the way he used Wood last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't going to put his own situation above the kid's
future, which would have been very easy for anyone to do,'' La
Russa told reporters in Florida. ``There are right ways to do
things and that's the way Jim Riggleman does them. He would rather
sacrifice his own career rather than do the wrong thing and hurt
the kid. He has too much integrity for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said House, ``The Cubs did everything they were supposed to do.
His mechanics were 94 percent correct, and they were very concerned
about his pitch totals. The piece of the puzzle they missed was
functional strength.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
