<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE ROLLS TO EAST REGIONAL FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There's a reason that one of Mike
Krzyzewski's prized Labradors is named ``Defense.'' Forget the 93
points a game and the 26-point winning margins. The name of the
Blue Devils' game is defense.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's ability to put the clamps on an opponent came in handy
Friday night. The top-seeded Blue Devils (35-1) won their 30th
consecutive game, ``struggling' to a 78-61 victory over 12th-seeded
Southwest Missouri State (22-11) in the East Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between Charlotte and here, the Blue Devils lost their
take-no-prisoners intensity that produced two 41-point victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing unusually great basketball,'' Duke coach
Mike Krzyzewski said. ``In the first half, we wouldn't get a loose
ball that would have been two points for us and they'd pick it up
and score.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the first half, Krzyzewski yelled ``You're
playing soft.'' The Blue Devils, for once, were passive. Southwest
Missouri State beat them to loose balls and rebounds. Twice the
Bears scored baskets after winning ``up-for-grab'' situations.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their effort and good fortune, the Bears still found
themselves looking up at a 39-30 halftime deficit. And they had to
believe that a Blue Devil blast was forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   And it did come. Duke closed down the Bears' offense,
particularly over the last 15 minutes. As the Blue Devils
inexorably pulled away, their defense made the difference. The
Bears shot just 37 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils swarmed Southwest Missouri State center Danny
Moore with double and triple teams, limiting him to 15 hard-earned
points on 5-of-15 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got beat by a better team,'' said Southwest Missouri State
coach Steve Alford, noting Duke's 50 percent shooting. ``We knew we
had to shoot a pretty high percentage and we needed them to miss
some shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's offensive spark came from senior guard Trajan Langdon,
who had 24 and a career-high eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give credit to SMS, they matched our intensity,'' said
Langdon, who made 4-of-6 3-point shots. ``They controlled the
tempo. But we didn't come ready to play like we've done all year.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 0127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7740 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-JOURNAL-TEX     03-20 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-JOURNAL-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
WEST: ROLLING TO SUCCESS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Khalid El-Amin has a shape more fitting for a right guard on the
Connecticut football team than a point guard on the basketball
team. At 5-foot-10, 220 pounds, El-Amin is about as wide as he is
tall.
</P>
<P>
   Before and during games, opposing fans make sure to remind
El-Amin of his portly physique. They call him, ``Fat Boy,'' and
``Pillsbury Doughboy.'' Sometimes the heckling is so intense that
El-Amin just laughs at himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in Virginia last year,'' El-Amin said, ``during
pregame warmups, and when I was going through the layup drills and
a guy shows me a Domino's Pizza box. He asks me if I'm hungry. I
said no. He said that he'd just keep the box and offer me some at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuff that people say about me does not bother me,'' said
El-Amin, who had 21 points, and five assists in the Huskies' 78-68
victory against Iowa in the West regional semifinals Thursday. ``It
actually motivates me, inspires me, and makes me want to do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin's ample posterior might be the butt of many jokes, but
he usually gets the last laugh. He is the one who lightens up the
mood by making jokes in the locker room. He can impersonate most of
his teammates, and each of the coaches. He likes being the center
of attention, The media spectacle that is March Madness is made for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best time of year for me personally,'' El-Amin
said. ``I like the media attention and I want to play well when it
is like that. Careers are made in the NCAA Tournament. This is
where the big-time players make their name.'' _ Kevin Lyons
MIDWEST: EXPLAINING UPSETS
</P>
<P>
   Although Oklahoma came in still bristling at being a No. 13
seed, the Sooners are perfectly in step with the prevailing trend
of the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the day of the underdog, and Sooners coach Kelvin
Sampson thinks he knows why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can trace a lot of it to the drop in scholarships
from 15 to 13.'' he said. ``The big teams just aren't as dominant
as they once were.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to see teams that not only had five truly outstanding
players out on the floor, they had five more sitting on the bench
waiting their turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That depth has thinned out, and another factor is the number
of kids turning pro after their junior year. A lot of kids will go
where they can get that chance; they're not interested in sitting
on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been suggested to Sampson that he has developed a unique
method of giving the Sooners an edge _ filling spots on the squad
with talented players from Mexico such as Eduardo Najera and Victor
Avila.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I hope we've cornered the market for the moment,''
Sampson said. ``But there's a problem you run into: how many of
those guys are both great players and bilingual? Najera had to
learn English before coming here, and that was harder than anything
he's faced on the court. But I would like to see more players
coming in from those countries.'' _ Whit Canning
</P>
<P>
   EAST: SIGN OF THE TIMES
</P>
<P>
   Some people have business cards; Marty Prather does. But he also
has signs. Big, view-blocking signs. One sums up his support of
Southwest Missouri State's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans Go To Games; Fantatics Help Win Them.''
</P>
<P>
   Prather, a Springfield, Mo., native, is familiar to baseball
fans in St. Louis as ``commander-in-chief'' of the MacAttackPack, a
Mark McGwire fan club. Prather holds up pre-printed signs during
Cardinals games in Busch Stadium and he does similar work for the
Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a maroon hard hat, Prather was on hand in East
Rutherford, N.J. last night for the Bears' loss to top-seeded Duke
in the East Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   One of his signs had an optimistic tone. It had the scores of
the Villanova-Georgetown and North Carolina State-Houston games.
There were blanks next to ``SMS'' and ``Duke.'' Unfortunately for
Prather and other Bears fans, those blanks were filled in with 78
for Duke and 61 for Southwest Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   It is an expensive hobby. Prather's signs cost $80 (printing on
both sides). For Southwest Missouri State's East Regional game
Friday, Prather had about 20 signs or $1,600 worth of signage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a friend who makes them for me,'' Prather said. ``I'm
putting his son through college.'' _ Wendell Barnhouse
SOUTH: A MASCOT'S STORY
</P>
<P>
   One should not jump to conclusions based solely on appearance,
Ohio State mascot Brutus the Buckeye says.
</P>
<P>
   So don't think Brutus is prejudiced toward football just because
he wears shoulder pads, what appears to be football pants and a
quarterback's towel hanging down from his waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when you don't hit the weight room,''
Brutus said, explaining the shoulder-pad look.
</P>
<P>
   Brutus' alter-ego is actually business-marketing major Jamie
Cleverly, a native of Columbus, Ohio, and a longtime Ohio State fan
who has been inside Brutus' head for three years now. And no,
neither Brutus nor Jamie prefer the gridiron over the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love basketball,'' Cleverly said. ``Especially this season
with the big turnaround \Rfrom 8-22\S. This has been a great
season. But I like football, too. And hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamie and Brutus are both diplomats as well. _ Mike Jones
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
