<SLUG> BC-SOC-DALLAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURN BANKS ON OLD FACES, NEW GOAL-ORIENTED ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 BURN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Major League Soccer season begins Saturday, but
already the Dallas Burn is concerned about finishing.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing, of course, in soccer parlance means scoring goals.
And last season, the Burn mustered a league-low 1.3 goals per game
on the way to losing nine games by one-goal margins, including the
season-ending 3-2 defeat against
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dave Dir ``is really stressing to us that he wants goals
scored this year,'' midfielder Jason Kreis said. ``He wants to
score goals right away. We've played more direct (in the
preseason). The midfielders are getting the ball to the forwards
much quicker. We're going to go at teams more than we have in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn lost two key players from last season's squad that
finished 15-17. Swiss international star Alain Sutter was hampered
by a hip injury most of last year and hasn't returned to MLS.
Often-injured Gerrell Elliott is also gone.
</P>
<P>
   However, the familiar faces that have formed the backbone of the
team the past three seasons have returned. Leonel Alvarez, Dante
Washington, Chad Deering, Oscar Pareja, Mark Dodd, Kreis and Jorge
Rodriguez _ all established names within MLS and international
soccer _ should continue as the core of the squad.
</P>
<P>
   Dir's vision is for those mainstays to renew on-the-field
chemistry for a more efficient offense this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten younger, but not so young we don't have a good
base group here that could compete right away, without having to
start with scratch,'' Dir said. ``We could have gutted it and taken
away the core of a team that took us to the finals of the West (in
1997) and the Open Cup title (in 1997). We don't want to destroy
that either.''
</P>
<P>
   What destroyed the team last year _ and what Dir says is often
overlooked when considering the team's subpar finish _ was a rash
of injuries. Ten starters combined to miss a total of 82 games
because of injuries, not counting additional time that didn't add
up to full games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion I think (last year) was a success,'' Kreis said.
``We played through extremely large adversity and made through it
by getting to the playoffs. I don't think too many other MLS teams
could have done that. It shows a lot of depth and character from
guys that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of boosting offensive firepower, the team is still in
the hunt for a proven forward to play alongside Washington up
front. The Burn has another foreign-player slot to fill, and
forward is the likely spot for such an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The other question mark _ acquiring a sweeper _ has been
answered, but not with a new face. After playing midfield last
year, Richard Farrer has secured the starting spot with impressive
play during the preseason. With the help of Rodriguez in the back
line, the Burn's defense could emerge as one of this season's
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Dir was pleased with how all those facets clicked during the
preseason. The Burn finished its usual tour through Mexico and its
first overseas trip _ to southern France _ with a 9-3-1 record
against upper- and middle-division teams.
</P>
<P>
   How the squad will fare in the MLS season is another question,
though. Players and coaches aren't promising a trip to the MLS Cup,
but they're predicting different _ and better _ results from
essentially the same team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where it comes into play about getting the most of
players,'' goalkeeper Mark Dodd said. ``I said it last year and
I'll say it again. If every player is able to up their level of
performance by 10 or 20 percent, I think collectively as a team
(we're) going to have far superior outcome. Obviously, with team
chemistry and getting things together, you can get different things
with the same core.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
