<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GONZAGA-FEVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAGA OVER GONZAGA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The alumni include late actor and crooner Bing Crosby,
former Speaker of the House Thomas Foley, and NBA basketball star
John Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   But until this month, much of the nation never knew the three
had any connections. Yet that is the beauty of sports. A no-name
team comes into the NCAA basketball tournament, unexpectedly wins a
few games, and everyone wants to know: ``Where did these guys come
from?''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga University.
</P>
<P>
   Pronounced Gone-Zag-Uh, this Jesuit Catholic school with an
enrollment of about 4,500 is nestled in Spokane, Wash.
Hewlett-Packard is one of the city's major employers. People think
more about computers than college basketball in this town of
450,000 that was ranked as the eighth-best place to raise a family
in the April 1997 issue of ``Reader's Digest''.
</P>
<P>
   Gone-Zag-uh.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, for the first time, there is something else to boast
about this time of year. Like the folks in, say, Storrs, Conn., or
Durham, N.C., the people in Spokane are watching their college
basketball team have quite a season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a lineup that features just two players taller than
6-foot-8, the Gonzaga Bulldogs won the West Coast Conference
tournament to earn a No. 10 seed in the NCAA tournament. Led by
junior guard Richie Frahm, the Bulldogs have shot 50.8 percent from
the three-point line to defeat seventh-seed Minnesota, second-seed
Stanford and sixth-seed Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as the first No. 10 seed to make it to a regional
championship game in eight years, Gonzaga will wear the glass
slipper again in hopes that the clock doesn't strike midnight. The
opponent: Top-seeded Connecticut in the West Regional championship
game at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to play UConn 10 times, we'd be in trouble,''
second-year coach Dan Monson said. ``But we don't have to play them
10 times. We just have to play them once, for 40 minutes. And
that's the beauty of the tournament. Anything can happen at any
time in one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone-Zag-uh.
</P>
<P>
   How did the stars and the moon align just so for the Bulldogs?
</P>
<P>
   Monson, who was born in Spokane, wanted a career in football.
But a knee injury at Vanderbilt cut short his career and he turned
to coaching, where he first landed a job as a high school boys
basketball coach in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Quentin Hall said Gonzaga was the only school to
offer him a scholarship, so he left his family and the warm beaches
of the Bahamas to play in the chilly Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Frahm's list of recruiters thinned after he suffered a broken
ankle in his junior year of high school. He picked Gonzaga over
Baylor, although UCLA and Arizona State showed interest after he
signed early.
</P>
<P>
   A few friends talked Gonzaga up to senior center Jeremy Eaton,
who was at first wary of the school because, ``I didn't always want
to have my nose in a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore forward Casey Calvary, whose last-second tip-in
Thursday vaulted the Bulldogs over Florida, wanted to hang out with
some of his friends who were already there. So did junior guard
Matt Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   The players keep a close relationship. Jokes, and light-hearted
kidding keep everybody light. When asked how the team would come
off on say, ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno'', Santangelo said,
``We'd do better on \RJerry\S Springer than the late night talk
shows the way this team interacts with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone-Zag-Uh.
</P>
<P>
   Only the 10 Bulldogs players, Monson, and his three assistants
knew they could play this well. They had gone 1-4 against ranked
teams during the regular season (including a 90-87 loss at TCU).
``We played well,'' Monson said. They are not afraid. Cinderella?
In the eyes of Monson, that tag doesn't fit this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinderella is one of those tags that happens in the first or
second round _ not at this level,'' Monson said. ``These kids
believe that they belong. If our jerseys didn't say, `Gonzaga,' on
the back, but a state name instead, we wouldn't be a Cinderella
team. We would just be a good team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
