<HEADLINE>
JUST WHAT DUKE NEEDS: HEALTHY LANGDON IS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Just in time for its national
championship hunt, Duke has regained its heart and soul.
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Trajan Langdon, who missed three games with a
sprained foot, returned to the lineup in the Blue Devils'
second-round victory over Tulsa. Last night in the East Regional
semifinal victory over Southwest Missouri State, Langdon scored a
team-high 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to practice all week and my foot feels really
good,'' said Langdon, Duke's second-leading scorer. ``I just wanted
to stay aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke needed that aggression. The Bears stayed within striking
distance until midway through the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Langdon is a great scorer and shooter, he was the
difference,'' Southwest Missouri State coach Steve Alford said.
FINDING FLAWS
</P>
<P>
   Duke has won its past 12 games by the average margin of 29
points. The closest game over that span was an 83-68 victory over
North Carolina State in the semifinals of the Atlantic Coast
Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coaching staff showed us that Duke does have some
faults,'' Southwest Missouri State point guard William Fontelroy
said. ``There wasn't a whole bunch. We tried to drive and kick to
our shooters, go inside to \Rcenter Danny Moore\S. We saw that on
the press, if we could break it, we'd get easy shots. And if we
pushed the ball in transition, they couldn't be able set up their
defense.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Duke is 14-1 in East Rutherford. The Blue Devils' only loss came
to Arizona, 77-75, on Feb. 26, 1989. In NCAA Tournament East
Regional games, Duke is 9-0 here.
</P>
<P>
   Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski needs one more victory to tie former
UCLA coach John Wooden on the NCAA Tournament coaching victory
list. Krzyzewski has 46. Former North Carolina coach Dean Smith is
No. 1 on the list with 65.
</P>
<P>
   Superior depth? Against Southwest Missouri State, Duke's bench
provided 14 points and 10 rebounds. The Bears' reserves had 30
points and 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Temple, which finished third in the 1956 and 1958 Final Fours,
has lost three regional finals in the past 11 years. In 1988, the
top-seeded Owls lost to second-seeded Duke. In 1991, they lost to
top-seeded North Carolina. In 1993, they lost to top-seeded
Michigan.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
