<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA'S RUN REMINISCENT OF PROVIDENCE TEAM OF '87
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way Gonzaga is making its 3-point shots reminds Connecticut
coach Jim Calhoun of the way the 1987 Providence team, coached by
Rick Pitino, made the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga has made 50.8 percent of its 3-pointers, including 12 of
22 in the one-point victory over Florida on Thursday, and just 43.8
percent of its 2-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we faced a team like (Gonzaga) it was Billy
Donovan's team,'' Calhoun said of Donovan, the Florida coach who
was a player on that team. ``At that time, (current Connecticut
guard) Khalid El-Amin was 7. Gonzaga right now has great
confidence. It isn't a case of if the shot will go in, it's when.
We don't want to overextend ourselves and allow penetration from
their guards, or post-ups by their big men.'' CLIMATE DIDN'T SUIT
HIS CLOTHES
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga guard Quentin Hall is out of his element. He grew up on
the warm beaches of the Bahamas. Yet the only school to offer him a
scholarship was Gonzaga, which is located in chilly Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's biggest adjustment?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to buy more clothes,'' he said. ``I only had one jacket
and it was for rain.'' FINALLY FOUR?
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun is 331-122 in 13 seasons at Connecticut, and 581-259 in
27 years overall as a college coach. But he has never been to a
Final Four. He has taken Connecticut to the Elite Eight three times
this decade, only to lose each time.
</P>
<P>
   All week, Calhoun has had to answer questions about his failures
to reach the Final Four. He said if he loses Saturday, that he
should not be considered a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has made so much of us getting to the Final Four,''
Calhoun said. ``I know I will not change. I won't be a better coach
if we get there. I know I won't be a worse coach if we don't. When
your career is 830, 840 games and you get judged on two or three,
it's not entirely (fair). In the next 10 years, if we average 26
wins a year and we don't get to the Final Four, I'll be a happy
coach. I won't be a satisfied coach, but I will be a happy coach.''
CASEY'S DAY
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, his tip-in with 4.4 seconds remaining gave
the Bulldogs a one-point victory over Florida. He partied with his
teammates, coaches and friends. But he couldn't sleep late.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of being a hero, Casey Calvary.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 6:30 a.m., radio stations were calling my room asking me
about the shot,'' the Gonzaga forward said. ``I'd be on the air,
just sleeping. Some of the stations called and asked, `Why did I go
over that guy's back. (Florida's Brent Wright).' I was just
sleepy.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
