<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHIGAN-STATE-OKLAHOMA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP-SEEDED SPARTANS ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The prevailing line about Oklahoma and Michigan
State was that it figured to be a great football game.
</P>
<P>
   Living up to its advance billing, it produced a 54-46 Michigan
State victory and a bloody collision that both sides identified as
the key moment of the battle.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred with 9 minutes, 34 seconds remaining and left two
players _ Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves and Oklahoma's Eduardo
Najera out cold on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say that if we had had Ed we would have won,
because Michigan State won this game,'' OU coach Kelvin Sampson
said. ``But it hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Spartans coach Tom Izzo was somewhat more emphatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That helped us a lot, truth be known,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the moment of impact, the top-seeded Spartans
(32-4) went on a brief run that doubled a five-point lead, and
Oklahoma (22-11) never caught up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very physical game,'' Izzo said. ``And it kind of
typifies our season, I guess. It's hard to define exactly why we
won, but we did.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the larger reasons was the disappearance of Oklahoma's
vaunted 3-point game in the face of a withering Michigan State
perimeter defense. The Sooners, a team that averages 22 3-point
shots per game, had their worst outing of the season _ 4-of-15 _
from beyond the arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot of emphasis on stopping that part of their game,
and I guess we did a pretty good job,'' said Izzo, whose team won
its 21st consecutive game and 28th of the past 29.
</P>
<P>
   As for the collision, both players eventually returned to the
game _ but Cleaves, whose head had collided with Najera's chin on a
pick, was better off.
</P>
<P>
   Najera, OU's leading scorer, suffered a concussion and lacerated
chin and was unable to play effectively after his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of used to this sort of thing, because we see it a
lot in the Big 10,'' said the Spartans' Antonio Smith. ``We'll take
a win any old way, on a fast break or beating the crap out of each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Cleaves said he felt pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never saw him,'' he said. ``I've got a bump on my head.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a pretty ugly game, but to tell you the truth, it's
been a pretty ugly tournament. We're just glad we're still in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners cut the Spartans lead to 47-43 on Ryan Humphrey's
free throw with 1:41 left, but never got closer. Michigan State
made five free throws to stretch it back to 52-43 with 21 seconds
left, and Sampson sent Najera off to be X-rayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fistfight, and we lost,'' Sampson said. ``It was
tough going out there and seeing my best player lying in a pool of
blood with his chin laid open. But I was proud of the way we
played. We did the things we wanted _ stopping their transition and
keeping them off the boards, but they stopped us on the
perimeter.''  &LR; tagtop:Whit Canning, (817) 390-7760
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
