r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEMPLE-TEX     03-20 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEMPLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE WALLOPS PURDUE WITH TECHNICAL KNOCKOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Combine 52 percent shooting with
Temple's sticky matchup zone defense and the Owls become a
dangerous team. Purdue discovered that fact.
</P>
<P>
   Going against the bricklaying trend of this NCAA Tournament,
Temple shot 52.7 percent to swamp 10th-seeded Purdue, 77-55, in
Friday night's East Regional semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very surprised,'' Temple coach John Chaney said. ``Maybe
I've seen them shoot this well one other time. Maybe one surprise
begets another.''
</P>
<P>
   The sixth-seeded Owls (24-10) will play top-seeded Duke, a 78-61
winner over Southwest Missouri State, in Sunday's regional final.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue was its own worse enemy. The Boilermakers (21-13) held an
11-7 lead when they imploded. Two technical fouls _ one on Jaraan
Cornell, the other on the Purdue bench _ helped the Owls score 10
consecutive points without the Boilermakers touching the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Quincy Wadley) pushed me and I kind of nudged him back and I
guess the official felt he needed to make a statement,'' Cornell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Temple completed a three-point play, then made both technical
free throws, then two more technical free throws, a free throw on a
foul and finally a basket _ all without Purdue getting a
possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gave us the momentum, got us in the flow of the game,''
said Temple's Mark Karcher, who finished with 21 points and made
5-of-12 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, after Purdue closed to within 24-18, Temple
broke the Boilermakers' spirit with a 13-0 run. Karcher hit a pair
of 3-pointers. After the second _ set up by two jab steps that
froze Purdue's Brian Cardinal _ Karcher headed to the defensive end
shaking his head as if to say, ``He can't check me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Boilermakers shot 55 percent from the
field and 80 percent from 3-point range _ and trailed, 47-32.
Temple scored an astounding 25 points from 11 Purdue turnovers and
turned 10 offensive rebounds into 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't contain them,'' Purdue coach Gene Keady said.
``Sanchez is the best point guard we've played and we didn't have
an answer for Karcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22-point defeat was Purdue's worst in 41 NCAA Tournament
games.
</P>
<P>
   Temple closed it out with another run. After an Alan Eldridge
3-pointer made it 47-35 with 18:12 remaining, the Owls went on a
14-1 run. Karcher and Sanchez hit 3-pointers and Quincy Wadley
converted a three-point play.
</P>
<P>
   With 13 minutes remaining, Temple's fans began the prerequisite
``We Want Duke'' chant. Request granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those fans don't know what they're talking about,'' Chaney
said. ``I don't want to see 'em, but I gotta see 'em. Who wants to
see Duke?'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
