</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA SWAGGER ONLY GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A little less than 24 hours after their thrilling
Sweet 16 victory on a tip-in, who would have blamed the Gonzaga
Bulldogs if reality had set in and, surprise, no one especially
liked what they saw?
</P>
<P>
   Up now, the Connecticut Huskies, the No. 1 seed in the West with
a Duke-like 31-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   Up now, a bruiser of a point guard named Khalid El-Amin, a
devastating forward named Richard Hamilton and a UConn portfolio so
thick with NCAA tournament wins it could knock you out cold.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, ever since August, have been focused on winning a
national championship. Their mission continues, and they wear the
steely look of executives with unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags, ever since last March, when they were not included in
the 64-team field, have been eagerly awaiting the opportunity to
embarrass the selection committee for not giving them a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags, playing like a creme de la creme Pac-10 team, have
certainly accomplished their primary goal. They find themselves one
victory away from a trip to next week's Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   So under that scenario, who would have blamed the Zags if they
just plain got up Friday and freaked out? Who would have blamed
them if they realized they finally hit their heads on college
basketball's glass ceiling?
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. And it doesn't look like it's going to happen
_ not the way the Zags are taking their 15 minutes of fame and
sharing it with a national audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been crazy, taking chartered flights, getting police
escorts like we did to the game (Thursday),'' point guard Matt
Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw the flashing lights, we thought we were getting
pulled over for something. We were like, `What did we do?' But
we've been able to stay loose through it all. We've been loose all
year _ a lot of times at each other's expense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the national sporting media, Santangelo said that if
the Zags could pick one TV show to appear on, should they do the
improbable and win a national championship, they wouldn't take Jay
Leno or David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd do better on the `Jerry Springer Show,' the way
we fight and claw with each other,'' Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   The deeper they get in this NCAA tournament, the looser and
goosier and more confident they become. This could mean one of two
things:
</P>
<P>
   1. The Zags are willing to go down laughing; or,
</P>
<P>
   2. They are hellbent on having the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at 6:30 a.m. Friday, Casey Calvary's phone started
ringing. Radio stations from Washington to New England were dialing
up the hot new star of the NCAA tournament, the blond bruiser whose
two-handed tip gave Gonzaga the 73-72 win over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Now, under normal circumstances, the Gonzaga forward likes his
beauty rest. Noon is about the time Calvary usually rouses his
6-foot-8 frame from bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe even 1 p.m.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But these crazy days of March are anything but normal
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I figure instead of being mad because people are
calling me, and I'm trying to talk even though I'm asleep and have
no idea what I'm saying, I might as well enjoy this,'' Calvary
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, two years from now, I'm going to be some bum on the
street corner in Spokane, and no one is going to remember any of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   While this flirtation with celebrity is grand, the Zags are
flying higher on the intense level of basketball they have been
playing all season and especially the last four games, including
their resounding West Coast Conference championship victory that
kicked off this barn-burning roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags will not for one second agree with analysts who said
unlike their tournament wins over Minnesota, Stanford and Florida,
the Zags' day of reckoning is now truly upon them, since UConn is
in another class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Dick Vitale said about us after we beat Minnesota: `Now
they get Stanford and the dream is over,''' said Calvary, who
politely disagreed with that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't thinking (that since) we're a small school, it's
time for us to go get stomped by a bigger school.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zags still believe this is their best chance to prove their
one, emphatic point. Never mind the soothsayers, who give them no
chance against the Huskies _ who, if you recall, almost fell to the
Washington Huskies last March in the Sweet 16, save for that
Hamilton buzzer-beater.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags might believe they can do what their cross-state rivals
from the Pac-10 could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've watched UConn and other teams on ESPN all year long, and
of course you want a chance to go out and play against them to
prove you're good, too,'' Jeremy Eaton said. ``Now it's time to put
up or shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose and tough, the Zags are ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
