<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHNER STEALS THE THUNDER ON YOUNT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARYVALE, Ariz. _ On Robin Yount Day at Maryvale Baseball Park,
the Milwaukee Brewers saluted their newly elected Hall of Famer
with a poster giveaway and encouraged fans to applaud him.
</P>
<P>
   Yount, however, was a no-show. A local resident, he begged off,
citing a prior commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Just as well. Five batters into the Brewers' game against the
Mariners Friday, this clearly was the Jay Buhner Hour. Two hours,
actually.
</P>
<P>
   Playing 6{ innings, the Mariners' surgically repaired right
fielder socked a three-run home run, drove in a fourth run with a
sacrifice fly and doubled to carry his club to an 11-7 victory. All
of this comes just seven months after having elbow surgery and 11
months after a knee operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine. Everything's great,'' Buhner said as he walked to
the Mariners' charter bus. ``I've got things to do still. I'm not
out of the dark yet. It's OK as long as I take it slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Slow?
</P>
<P>
   His first time up, Buhner stepped into an 0-1 pitch from
left-hander Bill Pulsipher and sent it over the left-field fence.
In the fifth, he launched a sacrifice fly deep to right off Cal
Eldred. In the seventh, Buhner lined a double into the left-field
corner off Eric Plunk.
</P>
<P>
   All hard hits, all coming off veteran pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels nice to be able to contribute at the plate,'' said
Buhner, who is 8-for-23 (.348) with three homers and 10 RBIs this
spring. ``I know I'm going to contribute defensively once the
season starts.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't exactly a liability in right Friday. Buhner didn't
have to test his arm, but he appeared as nimble as ever running
down a couple fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay really looked good out there with the bat and the glove,''
manager Lou Piniella said. ``He's coming along great. He's running
better than ever. I might even let him steal.''
</P>
<P>
   MOUND UPDATE: While Buhner forged ahead, rotation candidate John
Halama might have killed his chances to start the season in
Seattle. The 27-year-old left-hander lasted just three innings
against the Brewers, serving up five runs (two earned) and four
walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't throw the ball all that well,'' Piniella said. ``His
rhythm was not good, he threw a lot of pitches and he was up in the
count. It wasn't one of his better performances. (Butch) Henry has
the edge on him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners Friday outrighted right-hander Maximo De La Rosa to
Tacoma and optioned left-hander Jordan Zimmerman to Class AA New
Haven, reducing their pitching corps to 18. By Tuesday, Piniella
will have pared the list to 14.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't offer a confirmation, but his rotation is shaping up
like this: Jeff Fassero, Jamie Moyer, Ken Cloude, Mark Leiter and
Henry, which leaves out rookie Freddie Garcia and veteran Billy
Swift.
</P>
<P>
   HERE TODAY, GONE ...: Even with Bobby Ayala's surprisingly good
camp, Mariner decision-makers privately say they still prefer to
move the veteran reliever rather than keep him. Way too many scars.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the front-office execs looking on Friday, Ayala
threw two innings and let two runs cross in the seventh, personally
getting charged for one.
</P>
<P>
   RELAY THROWS: Alex Rodriguez and Butch Huskey also slugged long
homers against Milwaukee. Huskey's landed near a walkway in left
field, some 430 feet away. ... Neck news: Edgar Martinez returned
to action after suffering neck spasms, but as a first baseman, not
designated hitter. David Segui missed Friday's game and has been
ruled out of Saturday's contest with the same ailment. ... Against
the Brewers, third baseman John Mabry let his frustration show,
winding up and firing his glove into the dugout as the third inning
ended. He had booted a ball, though he was able to recover and
throw the runner out. In the first, he failed to make a play on a
two-out, bases-loaded grounder, his fielding error leading to three
runs. ... Knitted mitt: Last season's embattled third baseman, Russ
Davis, idle Friday, has not been charged with an error in 11 games
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   NAME THAT ROOK: Veterans have given first-year pitcher Freddie
Garcia the nickname ``Chief'' for his resemblance to the character
in the Jack Nicholson movie ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.''
Both lean to the strong, silent type. Garcia, 22, seems to enjoy
the newfound label and says he has seen the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who came to the Mariners in the Randy Johnson trade,
might find himself answering to ``Boz'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``From behind he walks like Chris Bosio,'' pitcher Jamie Moyer
said. ``He has that bow-legged walk.''
</P>
<P>
   LAST WORD: A clubhouse visitor this week was Alvin Davis, the
former Mariner first baseman. Now 38, Davis works for Pro Athletes
Outreach, a league-wide ministry. He noted how only a handful of
his Seattle teammates remain active, but says he follows the club
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mariners are in my blood,'' Davis said. ``I've got blue
blood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
