<SLUG> BC-BKC-GONZAGA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDESPREAD ROOTS MAKE ZAGS APPLE OF WASHINGTON EYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the last two weeks, Gonzaga has ruined Minnesota,
Stanford, Florida and office pools everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs are overachievers, embraced across the country by
college basketball fans who hope Gonzaga can advance to the Final
Four with a victory over Connecticut Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere is there more support than here, in Washington,
where no one much cared about the Zags before the NCAA tournament
began. Now you can feel statewide excitement, the passion building
with each Gonzaga win.
</P>
<P>
   For Washingtonians, there is more than a Cinderella connection
with the Bulldogs. Ten of the players are home-grown, nine
graduating from in-state high schools and another who was a junior
college star in Yakima.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every part of the state is represented _ from Mark Spink
(Sehome) in Bellingham to Richie Frahm in Battle Ground, from Ryan
Floyd in Sprague to Mike Nilson (Shorecrest) in Seattle. There's a
Tacoma-area twosome in Casey Calvary of Bellarmine Prep and Mike
Leasure of Spanaway Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The starting center, Jeremy Eaton, is from Benton City, a
Richland High and Walla Walla CC graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Even the deep reserves _ freshmen Zach Gourde (Prairie) and Eric
Chilton (Kelso) _ have Washington ties.
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzaga catalyst is point guard Quentin Hall, who arrived in
Washington via North Idaho Community College and the Bahamas, an
unusual hoops odyssey that has taken him to the national stage in
Phoenix this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Most were overlooked and underestimated. But the Bulldogs are
lovable mutts, pedigree or no. Here are some of their stories:
</P>
<P>
   SEND IN (THE) CALVARY
</P>
<P>
   When Gonzaga beat Florida on a tip-in by one of their own, the
Bellarmine Prep coaches erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bernie Salazar and his assistants, Jenny Phillips and
Randy Gause, watched Thursday's game from Prep's basketball office,
where Casey Calvary first walked in as a ``string-bean'' freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was skinny,'' Salazar said. ``I told him, `If you want to
be an impact player, you're going to have to find the weight room.'
I only had to tell him once.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga's 6-foot-8 sophomore forward was in Friday's headlines;
six years ago, he was in the local YMCA at 5 o'clock every morning,
building muscles and a promising basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar remembers Calvary as a reserved teenager but highly
competitive. Like all of his Gonzaga teammates, Calvary was a
workaholic, making the most of his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't the most talented, but he set the standard for how
hard we were going to work,'' Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Huskies were interested in Calvary but had a
greater need for perimeter players. That was all right. Calvary
felt that Gonzaga was a perfect fit anyway, even if others did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he picked Gonzaga, a lot of people in the area would say,
`Gonzaga, why Gonzaga? He's not going to a very good place.' Look
who's laughing now,'' Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday in the gym where Calvary played, a spring sports pep
assembly was held. The mention of Calvary's name elicited cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the kids know who Casey is,'' Salazar said, ``so they
were all excited.''
</P>
<P>
   As is the coach. ``He's living a dream for us,'' Salazar said.
``That's what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE GROUND TESTED
</P>
<P>
   Richie Frahm was the player who made five 3-pointers against
Florida the other night. Seven years ago, he was just like Calvary,
scrawny and raw but loaded with upside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a team with no one who wanted to shoot,'' said Battle
Ground coach Butch Blue. ``Richie was a skinny little freshman kid.
I needed a shooter. I told him that was his job. I didn't have time
to wait for him to develop. I needed him right then.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhood waited as the adolescent produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some games where he would flat-out light it up,'' Blue
said. ``He had the kind of body that knew it was going to be a stud
someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Frahm might have been a nothing-but-net kind of player, but no
one seemed to know anything about him during the recruiting
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have coaches come up to me and say, `What's the story? Why
haven't we seen him or heard of him before?''' Blue said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Blue said that Frahm played baseball in the
summertime while most other recruits were showcasing their
basketball skills in all-star games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some schools shied away because they didn't know his
background,'' Blue said.
</P>
<P>
   Now here he is, one game from the Final Four. ``It's fun to see
one of the hometown boys on national TV, Chevrolet player of the
game, hitting game-winning shots,'' Blue said.
</P>
<P>
   THE CLASS B KID
</P>
<P>
   When you're on I-90 and 38 miles from Spokane, take the Sprague
exit and head north for 24 miles. That's where you'll find
Harrington, Wash., and Ryan Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sprague High and Harrington High have around 60 students
each in grades 9-12, the two schools combine for sports. Floyd
commuted to Sprague to play basketball. He has energized the entire
area.
</P>
<P>
   If the folks here weren't ga-ga for Gonzaga before, they are
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are totally, absolutely going crazy,'' said Dee Pearson,
secretary at Sprague High. ``The whole region is crazy about the
Gonzaga Bulldogs. This doesn't happen to (Class) B schools. We're
the little boys.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CITY SLICKER
</P>
<P>
   Mike Nilson was the same kind of player at Shorecrest High _
unselfish and disciplined. If Gonzaga coach Dan Monson wants him to
come off the bench, it's not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is such a team-oriented person,'' said Shorecrest coach
Greg Tacon. ``Mike fit in so well he could have easily scored 20 to
30 points a game. But he never complained.''
</P>
<P>
   Nilson averaged around 13 points his senior season, leading
Shore-crest to its fourth straight state tournament appearance.
</P>
<P>
   If Gonzaga wins Saturday, the camera likely will pan to Nilson
at some point. He might be the one in tears.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour before Shorecrest's state championship game against
Mount Vernon in 1992, then-coach Marv Morris delivered an
inspirational speech in the locker room. Pumped-up, the players
raced onto the floor. Except for Nilson. He was in the shower room,
breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a special feeling,'' Tacon said. ``I know it's special
for him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   LEASURE WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Walk into the main entrance at Spanaway Lake High School and
take a look at the door to nurse Jeanette Perry's office. There's a
big picture of Mike Leasure, the old alum himself, slapping fans'
hands after beating Stanford at KeyArena last week.
</P>
<P>
   They are reveling in Leasure's success at Spanaway Lake.
Basketball coach Karl Hoseth wore a Gonzaga T-shirt and embroidered
Gonzaga socks to school Friday. Wrestling coach Paul Greeley and
history teacher Amanda Allen also wore T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   When he was at Spanaway, Gonzaga's 6-7 senior forward displayed
his quickness and ball-handling ability. He was also Spanaway
Lake's best shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Leasure could have been playing at Nevada-Reno for former Cougar
coach Len Stevens. But when Stevens was fired, Leasure was released
from his letter of intent and opted for Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have worked out any better for him,'' said Russ
Leslie, who coached Leasure at Spanaway Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ISLAND MAGIC
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Hall provides the quickness in Gonzaga's lineup. He
buzzes from one spot on the floor to another. You never know where
he will end up.
</P>
<P>
   It's like his journey to Gonzaga. As a high schooler, Hall
played in Las Vegas with a touring team from his native Bahamas.
Gonzaga assistant coach Mark Few saw him and was impressed. He
suggested that Hall play at Northern Idaho CC before transferring
to Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Hall went to Northern Idaho for a year. Then a coaching change
resulted in a different coaching philosophy. Hall was not wanted at
Northern Idaho anymore and assumed he was going back to the
Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left, Hall went to Gonzaga assistant coach Bill
Greer's wedding in Spokane. Leon Rice was also there. The head
coach at Yakima Valley CC lost his starting point guard to a
four-year school and needed another. There were two matches made in
heaven that day.
</P>
<P>
   During his one season in Yakima, Hall led his team to a 26-4
record while being named Eastern Region MVP. Rice's wife, Robin,
helped Hall with his academics. Hall went to Gonzaga this year, and
the acclimation to the state is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fearless,'' Rice said. ``He leads them into places where
they shouldn't be. It's surreal. They're in the Final 8 in the
nation. It can't be. It can't happen in this day and age.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
