<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, March 20.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ Preparing the American public for
military action in the Balkans, President Clinton said Friday that
Serbian atrocities have crossed the ``threshold'' of acceptable
behavior and invited military action to prevent further bloodshed
in the province of Kosovo. By John M. Broder. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ International monitors were ordered
Friday to pull out of Kosovo, and Western embassies ordered their
nonessential staff to leave Yugoslavia after peace talks here
collapsed and NATO renewed threats to bomb unless President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia accepted a peace plan for Kosovo.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ NATO's plans for attacking Yugoslavia
include missile and air strikes that would begin with attacks
against air defenses and would widen to more sustained strikes on
tanks and other heavy weapons, NATO and Clinton administration
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Srbica, Yugoslavia) _ There are thousands of
refugees on the move in Kosovo. A spokesman for the U.N. High
Commission for Refugees estimated that 20,000 have been displaced
since Sunday, the bulk of them in the mountain range just northwest
of the capital, Pristina. By Carlotta Gall. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI-FAHD (Riyadh, Saudi Arabia) _ King Fahd said Saudi Arabia
will issue visas and he will pay the expenses of 18,000 Iraqis who
were waiting at the Saudi border to enter the country for their
annual pilgrimage. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI-RECESSION (Jidda, Saudi Arabia) _ Faced with a recession,
soaring unemployment and declining incomes, Saudi Arabia is
undergoing a transformation, and what once seemed inconceivable is
slowly becoming the order of the day. The government, famous for
free health and education programs and lavish military spending,
and for never collecting a nickel's worth of taxes, has announced
deep spending cuts concentrated in defense and security. By Douglas
Jehl. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA-MANDELA (United Nations) _ Nelson Mandela, in Libya, says
the Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi has promised in a letter to the
United Nations to hand over the suspects accused of the bombing
over Lockerbie, Scotland, by April 6. By Paul Lewis. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMB (Moscow) _ In one of the most devastating acts of
violence in the volatile North Caucasus region, a powerful bomb
ripped through the central market in the city of Vladikavkaz,
killing 62 people and injuring 100. By Celestine Bohlen. With map.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-EDUCATION (Paris) _ Foreign Journal: Trying to change the
education system in a country that fears any sort of change is a
thankless job, says Claude Allegre, the feisty French minister of
education who has become one of the most vilified politicians in
France. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN-PROSECUTE (Detroit) _ Four times, prosecutors have
tried to prove that Dr. Jack Kevorkian, the man who says he has
presided over more than 130 suicides, committed a crime when he
helped seriously ill people die. Four times, they have failed. On
Monday, prosecutors will try again. It is a trial that people on
both sides of the debate over euthanasia and assisted suicide see
as a potentially defining showdown over whether such acts should be
considered criminal or whether they are the entitlement of the
terminally ill. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (Los Angeles) _ The University of
California's board of regents decided Friday to guarantee a place
in the prestigious public university system for the top 4 percent
of the students in each of the state's high schools. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   TRAIN-WRECK (Chicago) _ As they wound down their investigation
at the scene of Monday's deadly crash of an Amtrak train and a
truck loaded with steel, federal investigators said Friday that a
language barrier might have caused them to misunderstand the
description of the accident by their first witness. By Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGSTEEN (Asbury Park, N.J) _ For a small resort city that
has had very little to smile about for decades, the fleeting
reappearance of Bruce Springsteen and his E Street Band, in
rehearsals for a world tour, has generated a frenzy reminiscent of
the days when Billie Holiday, the Marx Brothers and Frank Sinatra
came here to play, followed generations later by The Doors, The Who
and the Rolling Stones. By Jacque Steinberg. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ At his first full-dress news conference
in nearly a year, held in the formal East Room of the White House,
Clinton ranged over an array of foreign and domestic issues for an
hour. Clinton said Friday that when the final word was written on
his legacy, he would have one strike against him _ for lying _ but
``hundreds and hundreds and hundreds'' of pluses for the times that
he was truthful. By Katharine Q. Seelye. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MONEY (Washington) _ President Clinton's impeachment
appears to have a silver lining _ or at least a green one. Campaign
donations to Democratic coffers have soared, with much of the
giving inspired by the president himself as he crisscrosses the
country, blaming Republicans for trying to bring him down and
thanking his supporters for sticking by him. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAFETERIA (Washington) _ Washington Journal: For home-style
cooking, reasonable prices and a friendly atmosphere, there is
nothing else in the nation's capital quite like Sholl's Colonial
Cafeteria. As an old-fashioned
slide-your-tray-along-and-keep-the-line-moving kind of place, there
may be few like it anywhere. Trouble is, the last of the Sholl
chain of cafeterias might soon follow the automat and tailfins into
cultural oblivion. By Michael Janofsky. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI-LVMH (Rome) _ ROME _ A battle for the famed Italian
fashion house Gucci Group NV erupted Friday when a wealthy French
takeover investor agreed to pay $3 billion for a 40 percent stake
to rescue it from a hostile bid for control by French luxury goods
maker LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton SA. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG (Hong Kong) _ Confirming a dismal earlier prognosis,
Hong Kong's government said the economy shrank an estimated 5.7
percent in the fourth quarter and 5.1 percent in the full year. It
is the first full-year decline in economic output since Hong Kong
began keeping records in 1961. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-LYNCH _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. was hit hard by a slump in
financial markets last fall. It did not snap back quickly, some
current and former employees say, adding that its aura of
invincibility has given way to a crisis of confidence. All this has
led to renewed speculation about Merrill allying itself with a
bigger partner, including Chase Manhattan Bank. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   BASS-PRO-SHOPS (Springfield, Mo.) _ Last year, more than 4
million people passed through the turnstiles of Bass Pro Shops
Outdoor World. Now the privately owned company is branching out,
betting that the store's success as a shrine to America's dreams of
the outdoors can be cloned. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   LILLY-MIGRAINE (Undated) _ Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. announced Friday that
it would not develop an experimental migraine drug that had been
billed as a promising new method to treat the monster headaches. By
David J. Morrow.
