<SLUG> BC-UNITED-TRAINING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUMBO JETLINER LOST POWER, NARROWLY MISSED SAN FRANCISCO HILLSIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 AND PAUL SHUKOVSKY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Last June, a Boeing 747-400 lifting off from San
Francisco International Airport with 307 people aboard came within
100 feet of crashing into a hillside thick with houses and
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The jumbo jet lost power in one engine. And the co-pilot _
apparently with little recent experience at the controls on takeoff
_ nearly flew the plane into what could have been one of the worst
aviation disasters in history.
</P>
<P>
   Sources at the Federal Aviation Administration and United
Airlines Friday confirmed an account published in The Wall Street
Journal. The incident, just now being publicly disclosed, has
spurred the FAA to require United to increase training of pilots on
the 747-400, the industry's longest-range airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 400 is a spectacular airplane,'' says Clay Foushee, vice
president for regulatory affairs at Northwest Airlines. ``But ...
it's the airplane that's never on the ground.'' In flights of more
than 12 hours, it is required to have four certified pilots on
board. A pilot therefore may get few turns performing takeoffs and
landings.
</P>
<P>
   That's what may have been the problem with Flight 863. The
flight departed at 11:30 p.m. on June 27 bound for Sydney,
Australia. As the heavily laden jet climbed into the fog,
retracting its landing gear, one of its four engines conked out,
according to an FAA report. ``They were losing speed and the plane
started to literally shake,'' said an FAA official who asked not to
be identified.
</P>
<P>
   A co-pilot was at the controls, with two other officers sitting
behind him, shouting advice. He cut fuel to the malfunctioning
engine, according to The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Because there were two engines functioning on the left wing and
just one on the right, the plane veered to the right. To
compensate, the pilot turned the control wheel left instead of
using the rudder. Wing ailerons extended, slowing the air speed and
threatening a stall. By the time the error was corrected, the plane
was off course, low and headed for San Bruno Mountain, crowded at
its base with houses and apartments. The 747 cleared the mountain
by just 100 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA official said the pilot was so focused on the engine
problem that he almost neglected to take the steps necessary to
keep the aircraft aloft.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal reported that the pilot at the controls was out of
practice on the 747-400, having made one takeoff and landing in the
previous week and no others for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   United confirmed the engine failure, but spokesman Joe Hopkins
refused to comment on the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Walton, spokesman for the Air Line Pilots' Association's
United unit, said the union and the carrier have each appointed
five pilots to a committee to study the incident and make
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just disregard incidents like this,'' he said. ``We
take them seriously and address them in depth.''
</P>
<P>
   United produced a safety videotape analyzing the crew's actions
and has required its 9,500 pilots to watch it. It has also required
that pilots of the 747-400 return to its Denver training center for
a three-day proficiency check twice a year rather than once a year,
as do pilots of its other airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA also reacted. The agency initially ordered United to
make sure its 747-400 pilots had at least three takeoffs and
landings in the plane every 90 days. When United said it would have
to cancel flights, the agency cut its demand to one real takeoff
and landing and two on the simulator, said Allison Duquette, an FAA
spokeswoman. The renegotiated FAA requirement is an interim
measure, Walton said, and may be strengthened in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
