<HEADLINE>
FAITHFUL TURN OUT FOR OSCAR VIEWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They come with tents and ice chests and sleeping
bags. They come with buckets for, er, emergency relief. And, of
course, they come with cameras.
</P>
<P>
   They come to scream at heartthrobs like Tom Cruise, Kurt Russell
and Goldie Hawn.
</P>
<P>
   They come from as far away as Jupiter, Fla., St. Louis and even
Frankfurt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The line of campers waiting for seats in the bleachers outside
the Academy Awards is well known to Glenice ``Babe'' Churchill and
Sandi Stratton, who have come every year for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   It says so on the sign they put up by their first-in-line tent
on Hope Street downtown by the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Christmas is over, we start planning to come,''
Churchill, 68, a Chino resident, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   How early do you have to set up camp to be the first in line?
``We came on Sunday,'' said Stratton, 56, of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But they'd already guarded their spot Saturday by marking it off
with broad green tape on the sidewalk, she said, sitting on an
inflatable deep blue sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Their group is 13 strong. All take turns holding down the fort
during the day and night, with most of the group sleeping in
motels.
</P>
<P>
   Come Sunday morning, they'll pack everything back into their
cars before they are let into the bleachers wearing their lime
green Bleacher Creature T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Next to them on the sidewalk was the ``Oscar Chatter Club,''
which revolves around a 2-year-old newsletter put out by 16-year
Oscars veteran Tina Hernandez of Huntington Beach, who was
expecting 30 fans in her group.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get together with friends,'' she said, standing by a table
holding four or five little plastic Oscar statuettes and
movie-related books. ``It's a reunion.''
</P>
<P>
   She was looking forward to seeing Roberto Benigni of ``Life Is
Beautiful. ``He's going to brighten up the whole show.''
</P>
<P>
   Her group included Kathy and Bill Franks of Jupiter, Fla. ``My
big favorite is Tom Cruise,'' said Kathy Franks, 39. Two years ago
in the bleachers she screamed his name so loudly he finally turned
and acknowledged her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the most exciting moments,'' said Franks.
</P>
<P>
   Susanne Wolf and Silvia Farag may win the prize for longest
distance traveled by fans. They came from Frankfurt, Germany _ Wolf
for the fifth time and Farag for the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole year I count off the days,'' said Wolf, a huge Jodie
Foster fan who was wearing a Melissa Etheridge T-shirt. ``I think,
280 days, 279 days. My colleagues at work ask me how many days.''
</P>
<P>
   Farag said she actually prefers the camping out to the cavalcade
of stars on Sunday. ``It's a party, and you meet a lot of nice
people,'' she said as they headed back to the youth hostel in Santa
Monica to shower and change clothes.
</P>
<P>
   By 1 p.m. Friday, about 10 tents stretched from Stratton and
Churchill's site east on Hope, then around the corner onto Temple.
But some sites marked off with tape weren't yet occupied.
</P>
<P>
   Television crews and print reporters from around the world
interviewed the fans. The fans relaxed, ate and showed off
photographs from last year's Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell,'' said Jill
Cornelli of St. Louis. ``They're such a cute couple.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
