   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-TRIBUNAL-YUGO (Washington) _ Investigators at the
international war crimes tribunal in The Hague have concluded that
the Croatian Army carried out summary executions, indiscriminate
shelling of civilian populations and ``ethnic cleansing'' during a
1995 assault that was a turning point in the Balkan wars, according
to tribunal documents. The investigators have recommended that
three Croatian generals be indicted, and an American official said
this week that the indictments could come within a few weeks. By
Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   WITH:
</P>
<P>
   MILOSEVIC (Washington) _ Profile of Slobodan Milosevic. By
Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOONISTS (GENEVA, Switzerland) _ Dr. Bertrand Piccard and
Brian Jones sailed into history Saturday when their Breitling
Orbiter 3 completed the first nonstop balloon trip around the world
_ a goal many had sought but never achieved. By Malcolm W. Browne.
With art.
</P>
<P>
   WITH:
</P>
<P>
   PICCARD-PROFILE (Undated) _ Profile of Dr. Bertrand Piccard, the
41-year-old Swiss captain of the Breitling Orbiter 3 balloon who
has been an aviation enthusiast since childhood. By Malcolm W.
Browne.
</P>
<P>
   JONES-PROFILE (London) _ Profile of Brian Jones, the co-pilot on
the Breitling mission, who would have remained a quiet but crucial
part of his team's ballooning effort if it had not been for a
series of lucky breaks. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMAKOV-PROFILE (Moscow) _ In his long and somewhat mysterious
political career, Yevgeny M. Primakov has dealt with the United
States in many guises: reform Communist, intelligence chief and an
occasionally quarrelsome foreign minister. But now, as prime
minister and effective leader of the Russian government under an
erratic, ailing and jealous President Boris N. Yeltsin, Primakov is
facing one of his most important challenges. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Dateline to come) _ Developments. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-CHIRAC (Paris) _ A French prosecutor has ruled that
President Jacques Chirac cannot be prosecuted while in office on
political corruption charges stemming from his years as mayor of
Paris and leader of his conservative Gaullist party. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-POLITICS (Quito, Ecudaor) _ Where did the smooth,
apparently efficient president go wrong? How Ecuador got into its
worst crisis since the Great Depression. By Larry Rohter. With art.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI-U.S. (Riyadh) _ Three months of American bombing of Iraq
are generating new tensions with Saudi Arabia. By Douglas Jehl.
With art.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ARMED-POLICE (Beijing) _ The People's Liberation Army may
be shrinking, but another more secretive branch dedicated to
internal security is expanding. A look at the little known People's
Armed Police. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CHINA-RIGHTS (Geneva) _ Even before the start of this
year's meetings of the U.N Human Rights Commission, which begins a
six-week session on Monday, China has begun a vigorous campaign to
head off possible censure of its human rights record. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-WILDLIFE (Toronto) _ American environmental groups are
pressuring Canada, through threat of economic sanctions, to enact
an endangered species law. By Anthony DePalma. With art.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-TAXES (Milwaukee) _ The first tax season since Wisconsin
finished its radical paring of the welfare rolls is a showcase of
the competing dynamics involved in the makings of a new working
class: low pay and large government subsidies; old habits and new
starts; streetwise versions of the white lies that accompany tax
season everywhere and a few outright scams. By Jason DeParle. With
art.
</P>
<P>
   TEXTBOOKS-ADS (Undated) _ When his 11-year-old son asked Joe
Stein for help with his homework last fall, Stein got a big
surprise. There on the page of his son's sixth-grade math textbook
was ``what looked like an ad for a chain electronics store,'' he
said. Going through the rest of the book, Stein discovered
references to a wide array of brand-name consumer products, from
Nike and Gatorade to Disneyland and Topps baseball cards, many of
which appeared in illustrations as well. And that made him angry.
By Constance Hays. With art.
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN-TRIAL (Detroit) _ Jack Kevorkian goes on trial for
murder on Monday, and prosecutors have raised the stakes by
dropping an assisted-suicide charge. That means the dead man's
family will not be allowed to testify as to how sick he was, and
that could improve the chances for a conviction. (This was the
death that was shown on ``60 Minutes.'' In the videotape, Kevorkian
is shown injecting drugs into the man after he talks about how he
is ready to die.) By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-HOLIDAY (Los Angeles) _ For the creme de la few in this
company town, the day of the Academy Awards has long been the
unofficial holiday of Hollywood, that moment each year when the
movie business stops worshiping the golden calf just long enough to
bow down before a 13-and-a-half-inch gold-plated idol named Oscar.
By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   TATTOO-CHRISTIANS (Los Angeles) _ Inside a born-again Christian
tattoo parlor in Los Angeles. By Gustav Niebuhr. With art.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-LAWYER (Marlborough, Conn.) _ The frequent requests for
fees in advance, the secretiveness, the blithe disregard for phone
messages, all made Dennis B. Messenger wonder about the lawyer
representing his brother on a murder charge. But then the lawyer,
F. Mac Buckley, turned on the charm that had made him one of
Connecticut's best-known criminal defense attorneys. Messenger now
believes he was being snowed. Buckley vanished on March 1, leaving
behind several clients _ including Messenger's brother, David _ who
now accuse him of absconding with hundreds of thousands of dollars
that he held in trust for them. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LABOR (New York) _ Energized by new leaders at some of the
city's largest unions, the labor movement in New York is becoming
more vigorous _ and more combative _ than it has been in decades,
labor experts and union officials say. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CIVILITY (Hershey, Pa.) _ Congress travels to the home
of the Hershey Kiss this weekend to learn about civility from an
Irish Nobel laureate and an Abe Lincoln impersonator. By Frank
Bruni. (Coded `a') With art.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-TOBACCO (Washington) _ Taking a cue from the tobacco
industry, the gun manufacturers have banded together to fight
lawsuits and promote favorable legislation. A look at the other
similarities and the many differences between the gun and tobacco
issues. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   COHEN-PROFILE (Washington) _ Along a Pentagon corridor, defense
secretaries of the last half-century appear on magazine covers. The
latest has William S. Cohen sharing a cover of Parade Magazine with
his wife, Janet Langhart Cohen, under the headline ``Two For
America.'' That portrait is not just an example of Cohen's famous
sentimentality _ he has written an ode to the F-15 jet fighter _
but a fairly apt description of a campaign by this newest husband
and wife team to bridge the gap and ``reconnect`` civilians with
the military. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (New York) _ Behind the plummeting crime
statistics, behind the incessant trumpeting of New York as a city
reined in and refashioned by a tough-as-nails mayor, lies the
fearful reality of police misconduct so widespread and at times so
insanely violent that it has brought a new kind of terror to the
streets of New York.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ Commentary by Maureen Dowd; dateline and subject
to come.
</P>
