   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (GORNJA KLINA, Yugoslavia) _ The town of Srbica, home to
thousands of civilians and swollen with some 5,000 refugees from
outlying villages, was under attack Saturday. Shell fire resounded
in the hills and three houses in the town were in flames. Hundreds
of panicked refugees were reported to be swarming out of the town.
It was just hours after some 1,300 foreign monitors had pulled out,
under orders to evacuate to neighboring Macedonia, after peace
talks collapsed in Paris this week and NATO stepped up its threat
of punitive air strikes against Serbia for refusing to negotiate
peace. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CIVILITY (Hershey, Pa.) _ Congress travels to the home
of the Hershey Kiss this weekend to learn about civility from an
Irish Nobel laureate and an Abe Lincoln impersonator. By Frank
Bruni. (Coded `a') With art.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LABOR (New York) _ Energized by new leaders at some of the
city's largest unions, the labor movement in New York is becoming
more vigorous _ and more combative _ than it has been in decades,
labor experts and union officials say. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
