<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7814 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-REVIE     03-20 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSILE DEFENSES LEAVE FANTASY BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's a far cry from the space-based, rocket-zapping
shield that President Ronald Reagan envisioned 16 years ago in the
depths of the Cold War. But the country is suddenly jettisoning its
qualms about forging a national missile defense and is moving fast
toward building one.
</P>
<P>
   The threat is not an all-out strike from thousands of Soviet
missiles, which prompted Reagan to propose the anti-missile program
popularly known as ``Star Wars'' in 1983. The fear now is that
rogue nations like North Korea or Iran, with little or no warning,
could lob a devastating missile or two into Los Angeles or Seattle.
This anxiety has been heightened by suspicions that China stole
U.S. nuclear secrets in the 1980s to enhance its small nuclear
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Such developments helped prompt the Senate and House last week
to vote overwhelmingly in favor of anti-missile defenses as a
matter of national policy, while stopping short of actually
appropriating money for construction. Even the White House has
reversed its opposition to the legislation, lending conditional
support and pledging $10.5 billion in preliminary funding over the
next six years. Clearly, pressure is mounting on President Clinton
to actually build a system, once proven feasible, and he says he
will decide by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There are two surprises here. One is that anti-missile defenses,
once strongly opposed and even ridiculed by Democrats and others,
seem to be almost magically melting away as a domestic political
issue. The second is that anti-missile defenses are more
contentious than ever as an international political issue _ even
with Russia, America's main nuclear rival, in eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow is now threatening to stop reducing its 7,000-warhead
arsenal if the United States breaks out of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty, which bars national defensive systems. China,
meanwhile, says fielding missile defenses in Asia could seriously
escalate tensions over Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov arriving in
Washington on Tuesday for talks, and Chinese Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji due in Washington in early April, Clinton's foreign policy
aides are bracing for a rough few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But first, why are things growing quiet on the domestic front?
</P>
<P>
   For years, Republicans from Reagan onward tried to make missile
defenses a national priority _ in an era when the threat of attack
was arguably much bigger than it is now _ and for years they were
opposed and even scoffed at by less hawkish opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, a string of startling events prompted a sea
change. A bipartisan commission headed by former Defense Secretary
Donald Rumsfeld, a Republican, warned in July that within five
years, North Korea and Iran could have the potential to hit the
United States with a ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, as if on cue, North Korea stunned U.S.
intelligence analysts by test-launching a three-stage missile with
conceivably enough range to hit North America.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans claimed vindication, and those claims
have been enhanced lately by opinion polls showing that the public
trusts Republicans over Democrats in matters of national security.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken by the developments, many Democrats have been rethinking
their opposition to missile defenses. And the ambitious plans for
such defenses have been scaled back _ brought, literally, down to
earth _ beginning with plans for about 20 interceptors that could
shoot down a handful of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial, recent convert is Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, the
ranking Democrat on the Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Aug. 31 launch was a watershed moment,'' Kerrey said.
``There is a growing recognition that there's a real danger of
proliferation that produces either an accidental launching or an
attack by a rogue nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey pulled along other centrist Democrats in support of the
Republican-sponsored bill that passed in the Senate last week.
Fearing that the votes weren't there to sustain a presidential
veto, the White House and Senate Democratic leaders settled for two
face-saving amendments that seek to control the cost of any system
and to insure arms control talks with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a change in Democratic ideology,'' said Frank Luntz, a
Republican pollster. ``The old-fashioned Democratic doves of the
1970s are giving way to centrists who are less hostile to
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that all Democrats have bought into missile
defenses. In fact, half the House Democrats opposed such a move
last week. After $55 billion invested in developing a national
system since the early 1980s (when the Reagan administration
creatively interpreted the ABM treaty to allow research), the
technology is still unproven. Moreover, detractors say, terrorists
and despots could thwart a sophisticated missile defense with other
weapons of terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be bypassed with suitcase bombs, pickup trucks and
sea-launched missiles,'' said Rep. Rush Holt, D-N.J., who is a
physicist. ``It would be billions of dollars down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon brass dismiss the naysayers, arguing that military
contractors and engineers will work out the technical kinks and, by
2005, field a limited system of radars and missile-killing
interceptors _ perhaps in Alaska, North Dakota or on ships at sea _
if Clinton gives the go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3172 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-REVIE     03-20 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSILE DEFENSES LEAVE FANTASY BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's a far cry from the space-based, rocket-zapping
shield that President Ronald Reagan envisioned 16 years ago in the
depths of the Cold War. But the country is suddenly jettisoning its
qualms about forging a national missile defense and is moving fast
toward building one.
</P>
<P>
   The threat is not an all-out strike from thousands of Soviet
missiles, which prompted Reagan to propose the anti-missile program
popularly known as ``Star Wars'' in 1983. The fear now is that
rogue nations like North Korea or Iran, with little or no warning,
could lob a devastating missile or two into Los Angeles or Seattle.
This anxiety has been heightened by suspicions that China stole
U.S. nuclear secrets in the 1980s to enhance its small nuclear
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Such developments helped prompt the Senate and House last week
to vote overwhelmingly in favor of anti-missile defenses as a
matter of national policy, while stopping short of actually
appropriating money for construction. Even the White House has
reversed its opposition to the legislation, lending conditional
support and pledging $10.5 billion in preliminary funding over the
next six years. Clearly, pressure is mounting on President Clinton
to actually build a system, once proven feasible, and he says he
will decide by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There are two surprises here. One is that anti-missile defenses,
once strongly opposed and even ridiculed by Democrats and others,
seem to be almost magically melting away as a domestic political
issue. The second is that anti-missile defenses are more
contentious than ever as an international political issue _ even
with Russia, America's main nuclear rival, in eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow is now threatening to stop reducing its 7,000-warhead
arsenal if the United States breaks out of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty, which bars national defensive systems. China,
meanwhile, says fielding missile defenses in Asia could seriously
escalate tensions over Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov arriving in
Washington on Tuesday for talks, and Chinese Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji due in Washington in early April, Clinton's foreign policy
aides are bracing for a rough few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But first, why are things growing quiet on the domestic front?
</P>
<P>
   For years, Republicans from Reagan onward tried to make missile
defenses a national priority _ in an era when the threat of attack
was arguably much bigger than it is now _ and for years they were
opposed and even scoffed at by less hawkish opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, a string of startling events prompted a sea
change. A bipartisan commission headed by former Defense Secretary
Donald Rumsfeld, a Republican, warned in July that within five
years, North Korea and Iran could have the potential to hit the
United States with a ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, as if on cue, North Korea stunned U.S.
intelligence analysts by test-launching a three-stage missile with
conceivably enough range to hit North America.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans claimed vindication, and those claims
have been enhanced lately by opinion polls showing that the public
trusts Republicans over Democrats in matters of national security.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken by the developments, many Democrats have been rethinking
their opposition to missile defenses. And the ambitious plans for
such defenses have been scaled back _ brought, literally, down to
earth _ beginning with plans for about 20 interceptors that could
shoot down a handful of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial, recent convert is Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, the
ranking Democrat on the Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Aug. 31 launch was a watershed moment,'' Kerrey said.
``There is a growing recognition that there's a real danger of
proliferation that produces either an accidental launching or an
attack by a rogue nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey pulled along other centrist Democrats in support of the
Republican-sponsored bill that passed in the Senate last week.
Fearing that the votes weren't there to sustain a presidential
veto, the White House and Senate Democratic leaders settled for two
face-saving amendments that seek to control the cost of any system
and to insure arms control talks with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a change in Democratic ideology,'' said Frank Luntz, a
Republican pollster. ``The old-fashioned Democratic doves of the
1970s are giving way to centrists who are less hostile to
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that all Democrats have bought into missile
defenses. In fact, half the House Democrats opposed such a move
last week. After $55 billion invested in developing a national
system since the early 1980s (when the Reagan administration
creatively interpreted the ABM treaty to allow research), the
technology is still unproven. Moreover, detractors say, terrorists
and despots could thwart a sophisticated missile defense with other
weapons of terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be bypassed with suitcase bombs, pickup trucks and
sea-launched missiles,'' said Rep. Rush Holt, D-N.J., who is a
physicist. ``It would be billions of dollars down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon brass dismiss the naysayers, arguing that military
contractors and engineers will work out the technical kinks and, by
2005, field a limited system of radars and missile-killing
interceptors _ perhaps in Alaska, North Dakota or on ships at sea _
if Clinton gives the go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fast-emerging consensus for missile defenses at home,
however, collides with growing anxiety abroad, particularly in
Beijing and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has long opposed a U.S. missile defense system, fearing
that Washington would use it as an excuse to reprise the much
grander Star Wars, which would be dauntingly expensive to match.
</P>
<P>
   While the anti-missile issue is of little concern to ordinary
Russians struggling with dire economic conditions, it is core
national security for Russian politicians, and a matter of
considerable national self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   With the United States moving ahead on such a system, Russian
nationalists could use the argument that Russia was losing its
nuclear deterrent _ since an anti-missile defense could encourage a
nation with one (that is, the United States) to risk a nuclear
exchange. That argument could undercut, for example, efforts by the
Russian Parliament to ratify the second strategic arms reduction
treaty between the two countries, or Start 2.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Foreign Ministry warned after last week's U.S. Senate
vote that building even a limited system ``poses a serious threat
to the whole process of nuclear arms control, as well as strategic
stability.''
</P>
<P>
   And for this reason, arms control advocates are nervous about
doing anything to upset further nuclear arms reductions with
Russia. After all, they say, North Korea may threaten America with
one to five missiles, but instability in Russia is a much greater
risk. ``Our overwhelming and sustained concern has to be Russia,''
said Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who voted reluctantly for the
Senate measure. ``They got the most, they got the biggest, and they
got the most accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans and a growing number of Democrats say that
building an anti-missile system is just as necessary to insure a
safer world as reducing Moscow's nuclear stockpile, which is
declining with or without a treaty because Russia no longer can
afford to maintain it at Cold War levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delicate balance with Russia,'' said Paul Wolfowitz, a
senior Pentagon official under President George Bush and a member
of the Rumsfeld panel. ``We don't want to alienate the Russians,
but on the other hand we can't let them bully us.''
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, U.S.-Japanese plans to develop a missile system to
defend Japan, South Korea, Taiwan and the U.S. troops in the region
got under way about a decade ago, in anticipation of the possible
missile threat from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   As that threat has become more real, the plans to defend against
it have encountered growing criticism from China _ and even from
key allies. Two weeks ago, South Korea's defense minister said a
joint U.S.-Japanese missile defense would be ineffective against
North Korean missiles, and added that his government would not help
pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the possibility that such an anti-missile system
might not be ready for years, when there is at least a chance that
there won't be a North Korea left to worry about. This is a point
not lost on China, which views the proposed missile umbrella
primarily as a threat to its plans to reunify Taiwan with the
Chinese mainland. Since the early 1990s, China has more or less
doubled, to several hundred, the number of missiles on the Chinese
coast pointed at Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The fear among many national security analysts in Asia is that
missile defenses could do to China what the creation of NATO did to
the Soviet Union: help to trigger a new escalation of arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are for the development of advanced missile defense
systems, we are going to touch off new rounds of an arms race,''
said He Yafei, a senior Chinese diplomat in Washington who has long
experience in arms control.
</P>
<P>
   And the idea of including Taiwan under any missile umbrella ``is
an obstruction on our course of unification of our motherland,'' he
added. ``Taiwan is part of China. Politically, that is an
interference, a very serious interference in our internal
affairs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
