<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7820 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-ISSUES-REVIEW-N     03-20 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-ISSUES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING BABY-SIZE ISSUES INTO VOTERS' HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First he decried the evils of traffic congestion.
Then he vowed to do something about cow manure that pollutes
streams. Then he called for larger print on over-the-counter drug
labels.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the mayor of Los Angeles or a county agriculture
commissioner or a pharmacist in Sarasota, Fla. This was the vice
president of the United States, Al Gore, unveiling his latest
initiatives recently as he competes for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   If President Clinton transformed the presidency (some say shrank
it) from a wellspring of grand ideas to one of itsy-bitsy
proposals, his vice president has gone further. Forget the
bite-size morsels like school uniforms that Clinton doled out four
years ago. To some, Gore is serving up crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Well beyond Gore, the smaller-is-better movement threatens to
infiltrate American political discourse. A favorite line of
Republican presidential aspirant Elizabeth Dole is her boast about
how, as transportation secretary, she championed emergency aisle
safety lights on airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   These appeals to everyday life may reflect a radical change in
what people expect from their president. They may also be spurred
by an inward-looking culture in which Americans are relatively
content and more preoccupied with challenges of their daily lives
than with the less tangible state of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But that some leading politicians are as eager to talk about
tiny things as they are about grand matters of war and taxes may
also reflect an era of caution. Humbled, for example, by the
spectacular collapse of Clinton's huge health care overhaul,
politicians these days may be more inclined to propose sure-fire
initiatives than more ambitious or imaginative ones that may be
difficult to enact. These candidates may also be encouraging voters
to hold low expectations about what government can actually
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Even in areas like health care, where there is general agreement
that the system needs an overhaul, political polarization stands in
the way of any meaningful changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more risk in proposing big changes _ it's harder to
get it done,'' said Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. ``And there is in life
a general and very understandable tendency to make an assessment of
what can be done and work on that. I've been working on
entitlements since 1993. I think we're making progress. But it's
not something we can put on a press release.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., who is thus far Gore's only
rival for the nomination, derides the concept of baby proposals,
asserting that as president his priority would be ``to cultivate 10
strong oaks rather than sprinkling water on a thousand house
plants.'' Bradley speaks ambitiously of rescuing the quarter of
American children living in poverty and tackling the deepening
crises in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, to be sure, talks about big things. But he risks becoming
known as parochial _ as Mayor Al _ when he dwells on matters that
his predecessors would never have raised.
</P>
<P>
   He produced titters for proposing an ``Airline Passenger Bill of
Rights,'' that calls for such things as increasing the compensation
for lost baggage. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a prospect for the
Republican presidential nomination, actually came up with the idea
first.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Kerrey said, he did a radio show in Omaha, Neb., and
the announcers started laughing when the subject of the Airline
Passenger Bill of Rights came up. ``Jesus! I'm sure there's a need
there somewhere,'' Kerrey said. ``But it makes me a little
uncomfortable as an American.'' Mocking the measure, he said, ``All
of a sudden, I'm going to pass a law saying, `Give me sparkling
water instead of plain water!'''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore may be practicing smart politics. A common frustration
of elected officials is that they cannot break through and explain
to voters how what they do touches people's daily lives. So when
Clinton in 1996 made small-bore ideas a centerpiece of his
campaign, voters rewarded him. Pollsters have also found that there
is a surge in potential voters who are part of an upper middle
class; these proposals are designed to appeal to them.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is particularly well placed to promote these
ideas because he and Clinton can dream up _ and announce _ all
sorts of executive decrees that do not require congressional
approval. (Democrats are generally more eager than Republicans to
want to impose new government regulations.)
</P>
<P>
   But Gore and his loyalists warn that matters that to some appear
trivial may, in the eyes of others actually loom large. ``There
seems to be a difference of perspective between politicians and
journalistic elites on the one hand and the American people on the
other as to what counts as an idea that's large enough to be
meaningful,'' said William Galston, a professor of public affairs
at the University of Maryland who was a domestic policy official in
the early days of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Galston, a longtime adviser to Gore, added that politicians need
to adjust to the changing times. ``There is no reason to believe
that Bill Clinton was harmed in any way in 1995 and 1996 by
addressing issues that during the cold war might not have been seen
as presidential,'' he said. ``Obviously, you can go too far down
that road. These are questions of judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Castellanos, a Republican consultant, said, ``Our next
president is not going to be Gore or small-minded Republicans. It's
going to be the candidate with one big idea. That's what America is
hungry for.''
</P>
<P>
   But just what constitutes a big idea these days? Gore asserted
that the next president will understand ``how tired working parents
are'' and that they do not want to be ``caught in traffic jams.''
For frazzled working parents with interminable commutes _ many of
whom are important swing voters _ that may be as big an idea as
they get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3178 &Cx1f; var-z
