<HEADER>
A3179 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-HANGERS-ON-     03-20 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-HANGERS-ON-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE POLITICIAN CAN'T TAKE A HINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In New Jersey, former Gov. Jim Florio wants to run
for the U.S. Senate. In California, former Rep. Robert Dornan is
threatening to challenge a fellow Republican congressman. And in
New York, former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato keeps floating his name as a
candidate for his old job.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every state has them, defeated politicians trying to
reclaim old glory. Like ghosts of elections past, they rattle their
platforms and demand attention from voters, local officials and the
media. But the people they often end up scaring the most are
members of their own parties.
</P>
<P>
   In Florio's case, many of his fellow Democrats are worried that
he will end up in a replay of his loss in the 1993 gubernatorial
race to Christie Whitman, who Republicans say is leaning toward
running for the Senate next year. Voters are still angry with
Florio for raising taxes, those Democrats say, and are sure to
punish him and possibly other Democratic candidates if he runs
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was someone prominent the Democrats could push
forward against Florio, someone with statewide name recognition,
they would do it,'' said Russ Baker, a professor of political
science at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan, a combative conservative Republican from Orange County,
was unseated in 1996 by Loretta Sanchez, a Democrat. Dornan
disputed the results, failed, tried to get the House of
Representatives to overturn them, failed again, and then challenged
Ms. Sanchez in 1998, failing for a third time.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Dornan now says he may challenge Ms. Sanchez again
next year, or possibly take on a fellow Republican, Rep. Dana
Rohrabacher, who Dornan says failed to help him in the 1998 race.
</P>
<P>
   To many Republican leaders in California, Dornan is a divisive
candidate whose attacks on immigration have hampered the party's
efforts to attract Hispanic and Asian voters. But their efforts to
block him in 1998 failed when Dornan won the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear the groans from Republicans when he said he
might run next year,'' said Amy Walter, an editor of the Cook
Report, a nonpartisan newsletter that tracks congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   When D'Amato was ousted by Charles Schumer last year, many
political analysts chalked it up in part to voter exhaustion with
the brash three-term Republican. So when D'Amato started saying on
national television recently that running next year was ``very
tempting,'' not every New York Republican cheered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bulk would be mortified'' if he ran again, said Norman
Adler, a political consultant who works for both Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   What makes people like Dornan, Florio and D'Amato hard to ignore
is their ability to move blocs of loyal voters, even small blocs.
And since only a small percentage of the electorate votes in
primaries, those loyalists can carry the day, particularly in
crowded fields.
</P>
<P>
   But why would politicians subject themselves to the rigors of a
campaign after voters had rejected them before? Political analysts
say the comeback personality usually falls into one of two
categories (and sometimes both): the vindication seeker and the
egoist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vindication seekers are the people who lost by just a few
hundred votes, which is a very tough pill to swallow,'' said Ms.
Walter. ``They can't help thinking, `If only 200 people changed
their minds, I would win.'''
</P>
<P>
   The egoist thrives on public attention, seeming unfocused,
unfulfilled and disoriented without it. ``A lot of guys need to
reaffirm their importance,'' said Adler. ``And one way to do it is
to say, `I'm running for something.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing seems to inspire not-ready-for-retirement
politicians: the examples of comeback kids who succeeded. Michael
Dukakis in Massachusetts and Bill Clinton in Arkansas were both
defeated after their first terms as governor, then won their jobs
back in the next election. And Richard M. Nixon lost the 1960
presidential campaign and 1962 California gubernatorial race before
winning sweet vindication in the 1968 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the defeated candidates expressed contrition for
being prideful, aloof or hard-charging, and claimed to have become
more in tune with voters' concerns, Baker said. He calls it the
``politics of epiphany.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a basic forgiveness among Americans,'' he said,
``this idea of a second chance, particularly if someone is willing
to humble himself and say they've made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The politics of epiphany seems to be at the heart of Florio's
current pitch for becoming a Senate candidate. Criticized as an
intense, unemotional man who failed to sympathize with middle-class
voters' worries in 1993, Florio now says that five years as a
lawyer in private practice, battling traffic jams and navigating
government bureaucracy, has made him more empathetic to the gripes
of regular folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a better understanding of the frantic pace of life,''
he said in a recent interview, ``the stresses and strains that real
people go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said Florio will have to battle suspicions that his new
image is ``packaging over substance.'' And Adler said Florio may
have a hard time convincing major contributors that he can win
again, a potentially towering obstacle given the high cost of
statewide campaigns today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most big contributors give not for ideological reasons, but to
people they think will be winners,'' he said. ``And it's very hard
to resuscitate a dead politician.''
</P>
