<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7824 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-AUSTERITY-REVI     03-20 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-AUSTERITY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'M THE FISCAL PURIST. NO, I AM. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal budget deficit is history, and the
strong economy is generating surpluses that could last for decades.
But in Washington, pledges of budgetary austerity are emanating
from both parties in a way they never did when the outlook was
bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Republicans are still fixated on a big tax cut, and
Democrats still tend to want to throw money at problems. But both
parties have built their agendas this year around the goals of
reducing the national debt and keeping spending in check.
</P>
<P>
   There are certainly great economic benefits to be gained from
keeping the country's financial house in order and using any
windfall wisely. Still, given that Washington's commitment to
fiscal discipline was notably absent during the 1980s and early
1990s when it was arguably needed most, it seems fair to wonder
whether this bipartisan outbreak of responsibility will prove more
than a passing political fad.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that by the end of the year Congress and President
Clinton will have broken the strict spending caps at the heart of
the current budget law. As the $20 billion burst of last-minute
spending outside the caps last year proved, it's hard to hold the
line when faced with pleas for aid to hard-pressed farmers, or pay
increases for the military, or more money for Head Start.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even with the country as flush as it is, there is
little evidence that the two parties will be able to turn their
good intentions into agreements on shoring up the twin pillars of
the social welfare system: Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Implicit in the whole austerity effort, however transitory, is
the broader question of whether it requires a crisis to take tough
action or whether, as Clinton likes to say, the best time to fix
the roof is while the sun is shining.
</P>
<P>
   If political positioning were the standard, the answer would be
clear. For now at least, Democrats and Republicans alike are
determined to portray themselves as not just fiscally pure but
purer than the other party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton started the bidding by proposing that three-quarters of
projected surpluses be set aside, effectively through debt
reduction, to deal with the looming problems in Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans countered last week with a plan to stop the
longstanding practice by both parties of using Social Security's
reserves to pay for spending and tax cuts. Then, in votes in the
House and Senate Budget Committees, Democrats tried to up the ante
by proposing to bar any tax cuts until the long-range solvency of
both Social Security and Medicare has been assured (the Republicans
defeated the effort).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Democrats on the Senate Budget Committee voted with
Republicans to reject Clinton's budget proposal because it dipped
into Social Security money for a few years to pay for spending
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Behind much of the maneuvering is an attempt by each party to
define itself for the new politics of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the reality that the deficit exploded on
President Ronald Reagan's watch in the 1980s as they cut taxes,
pumped up the Pentagon budget and did little to restrain domestic
spending, Republicans have long laid claim to being the party of
fiscal responsibility. Having seen the Democrats under Clinton
co-opt them on so many issues, Republicans are eager to reassert
themselves on this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not recognized as the party that wants to restrain
spending and cut taxes, what's the purpose?'' said Rep. John
Kasich, R-Ohio, chairman of the House Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, the situation is more complicated. On one level,
many Democrats, even some liberals, now seem convinced that the
nation cannot afford to spend with abandon, and that keeping the
federal budget under control yields big benefits to working
families by keeping interest rates, inflation and unemployment
down.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats also believe that using the bulk of anticipated
surpluses in a way that helps Social Security and Medicare works
for them on both political and policy grounds. If they prevail this
year, it will be because Clinton managed to link the idea of debt
repayment to strengthening the two most popular social welfare
programs.
</P>
<P>
   From the Democratic perspective, the argument is simple: A
sweeping tax cut now, before the expected surpluses materialize,
risks squandering the best chance to deal with Social Security and
Medicare while requiring painful and unjustified cuts in a wide
array of popular programs. If they can block Republican tax cuts
and in the process erase the tax-and-spend stigma they have been
stuck with for years, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   The professed commitment to austerity within both parties
appears to be driven in part by a palpable sense of skepticism
among voters _ evident in polls and in meetings between elected
officials and constituents _ that the promised surpluses will ever
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration and Democrats more generally have
discovered that the best route to achieving liberal ends may be
conservative means, especially when those ends are defined as
preserving the social welfare programs most highly regarded by the
citizenry,'' said Thomas Mann, director of governmental studies at
the Brookings Institution. ``That approach has the great benefit of
matching the priority of the public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0079 </DOCNO>
