u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-N     03-20 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, March 21, move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scheduled for the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE-REVIEW (Washington) _ The nation is fast moving
toward developing a national missile defense. When viewed as a
domestic political issue, it seems surprising that the former
divisiveness over the question seems to be suddenly, magically
melting away. But don't be fooled. As an international political
and diplomatic issue, the surprise is that it's more contentious
than ever. By Eric Schmitt. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-JITTERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Dow floats near 10,000. Jobs
are plentiful. Wages are rising. Spending is everywhere. The
economy booms, month after month. And nothing seems to shake the
public sense of prosperity. So why are the oracles of the economy
talking like Nervous Nellies? Because this is not only the biggest
economic expansion in history but also the most atypical. By Louis
Uchitelle. (`a' category). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-ISSUES-REVIEW (Washington) _ If Bill Clinton shrunk the
presidency from a wellspring of grand ideas to a trickle of
itsy-bitsy proposals, then Al Gore, Elizabeth Dole and other
would-be successors are going further by addressing seemingly
unpresidential issues like traffic congestion and lights in
airplane passenger aisles. These appeals to everyday life may
reflect a radical change in what people expect from a president.
Talking about small issues may be a way of avoiding larger ones
that are more difficult, perhaps impossible, to deal with. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-HANGERS-ON-REVIEW (Washington) _ Former New Jersey
Gov. Jim Florio wants to run for the Senate. Former Rep. Bob Dornan
of California and former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato of New York signal
that they may want to run again for their old jobs. Like ghosts of
elections past, defeated politicians trying to reclaim old glory
demand attention from voters and the media. But the people they
often end up scaring the most are members of their own parties. By
James Dao. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-AUSTERITY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Pledges of budgetary
austerity are emanating from both parties in a way they never did
when the outlook was bleak. Given that Washington's commitment to
fiscal discipline was notably absent during the 1980s and early
1990s when it was needed most, it seems fair to wonder whether this
bipartisan outbreak of responsibility will prove more than a
passing political fad. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   PORN-PALACE-REVIEW (West Hollywood, Calif.) _ Hustler Hollywood
is a 9,000-square-foot up-market sex emporium. With its
floor-to-ceiling windows and coffee bar, it unashamedly pitches
erotica. Opened last December, its sleek design, aromatic candles
and Kama Sutra massage oils are intended to appeal to women. It is
the flagship of what owner Larry Flynt hopes will be a nationwide
Hustler chain. By Frances Anderton. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-MANUAL-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ In 1969, Dr. David Reuben
published the groundbreaking book `Everything You Always Wanted to
Know About Sex But Were Afraid to Ask.' Now, 30 years later, comes
an updated edition. An idea of the revisions can be gleaned by
comparing some of the tamer passages of his book's two editions.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-PRISON-REVIEW (Undated) _ The most exclusive Oscar party
of all will take place in the Louisiana State Penitentiary at
Angola, the setting for `The Farm,' which was nominated for best
feature documentary. The guest of honor will be Wilbert Rideau,
convicted of murder 38 years ago, who co-directed `The Farm' with
New York filmmakers Liz Garbus and Jonathan Stack. He is not named
on the nomination because an Academy Awards rule permits only two
names per documentary. By Elin Schoen Brockman.
</P>
<P>
   BRAND-DIVERSIFICATION-REVIEW (Undated) _ Retailers and makers of
products from T-shirts to watering cans are broadening their pitch,
selling their wares by marketing an entire way of living. Once
people get to know a brand's most famous product, the thinking
goes, they will trust that brand to deliver any number of items,
even if the original product has no relationship to the subsequent
stuff the company markets. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-SNAFU-REVIEW (Undated) _ In a form letter from Arizona
State University, a prospective student's Social Security number
was inadvertently substituted for his name. The university says
only a handful of such faulty letters were mailed _ out of
thousands sent out recently by the college's parents association _
and the glitch has been corrected. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   SADDAM-MILOSEVIC-REVIEW (Undated) _ Iraq's Saddam Hussein and
Serbia's Slobodan Milosevic are similar in that both have become
experts at cornering the world's only superpower, frustrating its
diplomatic strategists, tying down its military and daring the
United States to use force to get its way. Each has laid bare the
lack of a Western strategy to deal with dictators who, simply by
continuing in power, further weaken the ability of their peoples to
resist. By Alison Smale.
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-TAXES-REVIEW (Quito, Ecuador) _ With governments all over
Latin America coming under pressure from the IMF and other lenders
to cut yawning budget deficits, there is a growing recognition that
the region's historical and deeply ingrained aversion to paying
taxes is crippling development and poisoning citizens' attitudes
about their societies and governments. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: &LR;
