researchers in Seattle say, treat children with respect, encourage
them to cooperate with one another and their teachers, reward their
accomplishments, give them a quiet place to do their homework and
teach them how to say no without losing friends and status.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. J. David Hawkins and a team of social scientists at the
University of Washington instituted a test program in first grade
in Seattle's toughest schools and continued it through sixth grade.
At the end, students in the program were significantly less likely
to have committed violent acts, indulged in heavy drinking, engaged
in sexual intercourse or caused a pregnancy or become pregnant than
students at comparable schools with no special intervention.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE E. BRODY
</P>
<P>
   Prison Nation  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite seven straight years of falling crime, the number of
inmates in the nation's jails and prisons climbed again last year,
to a record 1.8 million, the Justice Department reported. The rise
in the prison population is not the result of more effective police
department policies. It is but largely the outcome of the
get-tough-on-crime movement in this country: politicians
legislating mandatory sentences, prosecutors pushing to make sure
more offenders are locked up, judges giving longer sentences and
parole boards less willing to let convicts out early.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FOX BUTTERFIELD
</P>
<P>
   Not Quite Becoming  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A retired two-star general who served as the Army's deputy
inspector general pleaded guilty to eight counts of misconduct
stemming from affairs he had with the wives of his subordinates.
The Army hopes the court martial of Maj. Gen. David Hale will put
to rest criticism that senior officers are treated more leniently
than junior personnel.
</P>
<P>
   But the sentence _ a $22,000 fine _ was not as severe as that
given to the Army's top soldier, Sgt. Maj. Gene McKinney, who was
convicted last year of one count of obstructing justice during an
investigation into sexual harassment. He was reprimanded and
demoted, which resulted in a cut in his pension that over 40 years
will cost him $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
<P>
   Grandmaster First  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amassing the necessary number of points in the necessary number
of games, Maurice Ashley of New York became a grandmaster of chess,
the loftiest level of the game, and a status conferred by the
International Chess Federation.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Jamaican immigrant not only attained his own
lifelong dream but also became the first black ever admitted to the
elite group of 470 of the world's most brilliant players. ``It's
not significant to be the best black chess player in the world,''
Ashley said. ``But it is sweet to be the first.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA STEWART
</P>
<P>
   South African Found Guilty  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom was packed as former anti-apartheid activist Allan
Boesak was found guilty of stealing hundreds of thousands of
dollars earmarked for helping children and educating black voters
before South Africa's 1994 elections.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments, Judge John Foxcroft made clear that the fiery
former cleric's behavior had repeatedly betrayed the trust donors
put in him, spending the money on two luxury houses, vacations for
his family and a radio studio for his wife, Elna, among other
items. The sentencing process is scheduled to begin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SUZANNE DALEY
</P>
<P>
   A Bookish Trend  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pocket book revolution that trumpeted itself as bringing
``good reading for the millions'' is losing its revolutionary zeal.
Since 1995, the number of mass market paperbacks sold declined by
almost 9 percent, falling to 484 million copies last year.
Discounted hard covers are eroding the market, but other
entertainment forms like video rentals may also be diverting
readers. Publishers suspect that their most dependable customers _
affluent, aging baby boomers _ are shifting away from paperbacks
because they can afford hard covers and the larger print is easier
on fading eyesight.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   Candidacy on the Net
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire publisher Steve Forbes formally announced his
candidacy for the presidency, becoming the first contender to
announce on the Internet. In his second campaign for the Republican
nomination, Forbes cast himself as the unconventional choice,
telling visitors to his Web site, ``You and I are entering the
information age _ and the Washington politicians are stuck in the
Stone Age.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Forbes made his mark hawking the flat tax, which he
still wants, but he devoted his opening speech to positioning
himself as anti-abortion and as a supporter of religious
conservatives. Although Forbes sank $36 million of his personal
wealth into a lost cause last time, he is expected to be a force in
shaping the political dialogue, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep and Aging
</P>
<P>
   Novelist Mary Gordon once described her erotic fantasy: Getting
a good night's sleep. Aging boomers will understand soon enough.
Sleep grows lighter with age, and almost a third will suffer from
chronic insomnia. Sleeping pills can treat symptoms, but side
effects in the elderly are linked to falls and car accidents. A
more durable solution, researchers reported, is behavioral therapy
to instill better sleep habits.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERICA GOODE
</P>
<P>
   Replay the Replay  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Often, the most intense sports dramas in this sports-mad nation
involve heated disputes among mature adults about whether some ball
or body part landed a smidgen this or that side of the line. Who
can forget the touchdown-that-wasn't in the December Jets-Seahawks
game?
</P>
<P>
   Well, once again, technology will try to dispense perfect
justice. The much-quibbled-over instant replay, banished in 1992,
partly because it slowed games so much, is back _ for a one-year
trial. This time, coaches must call for it sparingly _ just twice a
game, and only if the team has timeouts left. If a call is
overruled, the team keeps its replay credit. And if it's overtime
or the last two minutes of a half, a referee assistant glued to a
monitor can step in.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   North Korean Assent
</P>
<P>
   Last year U.S. spy satellites found a giant hole in the ground
in North Korea, dug by thousands of military troops. Problem was,
it looked a lot like a future home for a nuclear reprocessing
plant, a place for the North Koreans to revive their frozen nuclear
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiations, the North Koreans have finally
agreed to allow American inspectors to visit the site regularly. In
return they got what they need the most: a promise of continuing
food aid, and an agreement to help teach the country how to plant
potatoes. It may be the first ever spuds-for-nukes deal.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
