<SLUG> BC-PICCARD-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PSYCHIATRIST USES HYPNOTISM TO HELP HIS FLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BALLOONIST, JONES-PROFILE)  
(DW) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By profession, Bertrand Piccard is a Swiss psychiatrist. By
avocation, he is a pioneer, from a family of noted scientific
adventurers.
</P>
<P>
   Piccard, 41, the Swiss captain of the Breitling Orbiter 3
balloon, has been an aviation enthusiast since childhood. An expert
hang-gliding pilot while he was a schoolboy, he became the European
aerobatic hang-gliding champion and established a hang-gliding
altitude record by age 16.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to become a pilot of ultralight airplanes and hot-air
balloons while earning a degree in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Piccard, who is married and has three daughters, comes from a
family famous for daring, inventiveness and breaking altitude
records in the air and depth records at sea.
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather, Dr. Auguste Piccard, also a medical doctor,
invented the pressurized balloon crew gondola, allowing flights to
very high altitudes. In 1931, flying such a balloon, he became the
first human being to ascend into the stratosphere, at more than
50,000 feet. Dr. Auguste Piccard also invented a deep diving
submersible called the Bathyscaphe.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Jacques Piccard, Bertrand's father, used the
Bathyscaphe to descend to the deepest place on earth _ the Marianas
Trench, 35,815 feet below the surface of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Breitling captain, who spent much of his time in recent
years explaining the fine points of ballooning to journalists,
worked closely with the British balloon-maker Don Cameron in
perfecting improvements in balloon design of the kind that brought
the Breitling Orbiter 3 to victory Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the dream of all balloonists, the ultimate flight,''
Piccard said as he entered the capsule on March 1 _ 20 days ago _
with Jones at Chateau-d'Oex, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   To honor his grandfather, Bertrand Piccard set off on his second
attempt at the global record last year on the 114th birthday of the
eldest Piccard. This year, he launched his latest test of personal
endurance on his own 41st birthday, watched by his wife, Michele,
and their three young daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Piccard used his medical knowledge on the grueling trip. At
his Lausanne-based practice, Piccard became an advocate of using
hypnosis to help patients. He used self-hypnosis techniques to
overcome stress and to sleep better. When he felt dispirited last
week, he picked up his satellite telephone to call a medical
colleague, who reportedly perked up Piccard through hypnosis.
</P>
<P>
   In a satellite phone hookup on Friday, Piccard burst into tears
when the control center directors told him there would be
sufficient fuel and good enough weather to land in Egypt, bringing
him full circle to his goal.
</P>
<P>
   Success has not come easily. Piccard and his then-flying
partner, Wim Verstraeten, became the first balloonists to cross the
Atlantic in 1992. Then the pair failed twice to circle the globe,
first in 1997 when the toxic fumes in the cabin from a fuel leak
forced their flight down over the Mediterranean, and again in 1998,
when the Breitling Orbiter 2 landed in a rice paddy in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   In planning his epic flight, Piccard adapted some of the lessons
learned by his grandfather, including the idea of partially
inflating the balloon at takeoff, instead of a full inflation, to
allow for gas expansion at higher altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   He also tapped into experiences of his father, now 76, who once
worked for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on Jacques' data from travels on the ocean's Gulf
Stream, the younger Piccard calculated the jet stream currents that
would help the balloon travel faster.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
