<HEADLINE>
LATIN AMERICA'S CONTAGION: WHERE TAXES AREN'T SO CERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ As the year began, the Ecuadorean government
was nearing bankruptcy, unable to pay teachers, doctors and other
public employees or to repair $2.6 billion in damage inflicted by
El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of global economic contagion? Not directly. It
reflected a much older, if related, problem in Latin America _ tax
evasion. Here it had become so bad that the Ecuadorean Congress
took a truly unorthodox step: It abolished the income tax
altogether in favor of a 1 percent tax on financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador's move was ``an act of extraordinary desperation and an
admission of defeat,'' as one U.S. aid official put it last week.
In effect, it wrote off the 60 percent or more of taxpayers here
who are thought to be dodging their obligations, in hopes that the
new tax would be easier to collect.
</P>
<P>
   Americans grumbling over their 1040 returns this month might be
envious. But there is a sobering context: Governments all over
Latin America are coming under pressure from the International
Monetary Fund and other lenders to cut their yawning budget
deficits and open their economies to the outside world to prevent
the spread of the financial slump that has humbled Southeast Asia
and crippled Russia (a country with severe tax collection problems
of its own).
</P>
<P>
   Latin America may yet prove particularly vulnerable to this
contagion because development and growth are already crippled by
the inability to collect taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any more vital issue in Latin America
right now,'' said Michael Shifter, a senior fellow at the
Washington-based policy analysis group Inter-American Dialogue.
``It's a vicious cycle that is very, very hard to break. People
