<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION GROWS AS MONITORS LEAVE KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORNJA KLINA, Yugoslavia _ Thickset policemen in dark blue
camouflage uniforms blocked the road. They wore outsized flak
jackets and pistols at their belts and swung automatic weapons in
their black-gloved hands.
</P>
<P>
   They waved through a convoy of armored jeeps, and police
personnel carriers and a water truck, clad with crude metal sheets
of armor, machine guns poking out of small slit windows. There was
no other traffic on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the police lay the town of Srbica, home to thousands of
civilians and swollen with some 5,000 refugees from outlying
villages. On Saturday, it was under attack.
</P>
<P>
   Shell fire resounded in the hills and three houses in the town
were in flames. Hundreds of panicked refugees were reported to be
swarming out of the town.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists who gained access described groups of gunmen, in
white snow-camouflage and black masks, driving around the town, and
tanks and armored vehicles ranged in positions through the town.
</P>
<P>
   It was just hours after some 1,300 foreign monitors with the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe had pulled out,
under orders to evacuate to neighboring Macedonia, after peace
talks collapsed in Paris last week and NATO stepped up its threat
of punitive air strikes against Serbia for refusing to negotiate
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the people originally sent in to monitor such movements
left the country, in a coordinated motorcade of bright orange
vehicles to the border, they watched large numbers of Yugoslav army
soldiers on the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made signs, they blew kisses. They are pleased to see us
go,'' said one monitor, speaking of the soldiers on condition of
anonymity. He had driven out from Pec, in western Kosovo, and
passed a large column of armor headed the other way. There was also
heavy military activity around the main army base outside Kosovo's
capital, Pristina, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are glad to see the back of us so they can finish the
job,'' the monitor said. ``They have a window of opportunity with
the weather and they are going to put the squeeze on.'' Kosovo lay
coated in snow and beneath low clouds, and the roads were thick
with ice Saturday _ not good weather for NATO to bomb, the monitor
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as the peace talks shut down in Paris and President
Clinton warned the Serbs that they had crossed the threshold of
acceptable behavior, nonessential foreign diplomats and their
families began to leave Belgrade, the capital of Yugoslavia, which
consists of Serbia and Montenegro. NATO's secretary-general, Javier
Solana, and other foreign leaders warned the Serbs that air strikes
could come within days.
</P>
<P>
   But neither those warnings nor the weather deterred the Serbian
security forces _ heavily armed police and the army _ apparently
intent on pressing their offensive against soldiers of the Kosovo
Liberation Army in the Drenica region. This hilly region lies
northwest of Pristina and is the stronghold of the ethnic Albanian
rebels who began fighting the Serbs just over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Their Kosovo Liberation Army _ financed by the Albanian diaspora
and backed by the heavily ethnic Albanian population of this
southern Serbian province _ has grown in that year from a ragtag
force equipped with World War II-era guns to a far more uniformed
and disciplined group increasingly equipped with sophisticated
weapons, as well as the standard Kalashnikov rifle.
</P>
<P>
   But those weapons are still no match for the heavy armor of the
Serbs. On Saturday, tanks were ranged in firing position and
mortars set up along the road looking south over the villages in
the Cicavica mountain range.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Police manned a new position, and aimed their guns out from
newly constructed sandbagged defenses. Columns of troop trucks and
army artillery guns were drawn up in organized groups beside the
road.
</P>
<P>
   In Srbica itself, foreign journalists who gained access found a
very heavy military presence in the small town. Tanks were blasting
away at villages in the hills, these journalists said, while bands
of armed men in black masks were driving around, piled into and
even riding on top of civilian cars.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, the main road to Belgrade was cut by fighting.
Police said the rebels had attacked a police station at Luzane
Friday evening. That could not be independently confirmed, but
shooting and shelling continued much of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, the 1,300 foreign monitors who left Saturday have
kept a check on army and police movements, trailing military
convoys and watching their exercises and operations. While they
were not able to force them to keep to barracks, the presence of
the monitors appeared to have a restraining effect. They had some
success, especially in negotiating local cease-fires.
</P>
<P>
   As the foreigners left, many ethnic Albanians said they feared
that Serbian forces would unleash the full might of their
firepower. A woman who gave her name only as Sofi was walking back
to her house on the outskirts of Gornja Klina, to bring food to her
husband and sons.
</P>
<P>
   She had fled the village when shells landed in the area Monday.
She had heard that the monitors were leaving and said she now
wanted to persuade her husband to abandon the house and follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of fear, everyone feels it,'' she said. ``When
we fled the OSCE was there, they helped us. But now I do not know
what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the monitors expressed unhappiness at leaving, even
though their job as unarmed monitors had been increasingly
frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   William Walker, the American head of the verification mission in
Kosovo, acknowledged the problem. ``None of us are happy,'' he
said. ``All of us would want to stay.'' He added that the mission
was now redundant, and that he hoped the monitors' withdrawal would
help break the current deadlock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
