<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-CHIRAC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING SAYS CHIRAC CAN'T BE PROSECUTED ON CORRUPTION CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A French prosecutor has ruled that President Jacques
Chirac cannot be prosecuted while in office on political corruption
charges stemming from his years as mayor of Paris and leader of his
conservative Gaullist party.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Yves Bot, told investigating judges who are
probing illegal party financing that article 68 of the French
Constitution, written for Gen. Charles de Gaulle in 1958, appeared
to put French presidents beyond reach of normal justice as long as
they held office. Chirac's current term runs until the spring of
2002.
</P>
<P>
   French news media have reported that investigating magistrate
Patrick Desmure had turned up a handwritten letter from Chirac when
he was mayor of Paris, in December 1993, recommending a promotion
for a city employee because she had done good work for nine years
for his party adviser on agricultural affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the letter, published in the daily Liberation last
Wednesday, did not say the employee had been illegally transferred
to work for Chirac's party, the Rally for the Republic. But all
French newspapers said that what it meant was that the employee
worked at taxpayers' expense in the party's headquarters on the
other side of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Even the daily Le Figaro, usually fiercely loyal to Chirac and
his party, reported Saturday morning, ``Judge Desmure is believed
to be persuaded that the person concerned never actually occupied
an office in City Hall, being instead almost entirely in the
service of the Rally for the Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   In France, criminal investigations are carried out by special
judges who report their findings to prosecutors. Desmure asked his
prosecutor, Bot, for a ruling on whether the judge could proceed
with an investigation of Chirac, who was mayor of Paris from 1977
to 1995 and the leader of his party for most of that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave Desmure a ruling tending to confirm lack of
jurisdiction,'' was all the prosecutor would say to reporters late
Friday night, denying an earlier report by Agence France-Presse
that said he had made exactly the opposite ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The French news agency retracted the erroneous report Friday
night, and Chirac's office publicly demanded an official inquiry
into all the leaks of what was supposed to be privileged court
information.
</P>
<P>
   A French president can be impeached for high treason, but only
by something called the High Court of Justice, a court never yet
convened in the 41-year history of the Fifth Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that Chirac might be called to account in one of
the myriad corruption investigations that have shaken up standard
party business in France since the late 1980s had all political
Paris holding its breath for most of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Until judges like Desmure got the bit between their teeth early
in this decade, every political party, right or left, conservative
or liberal, apparently financed itself with kickbacks, padded
payrolls, sweetheart contracts and all the other devices that have
tended to accompany corrupt politics around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   French politicians, when asked how this could have gone on for
so long, tend to reply that, earlier, there was no law on party
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac's longtime right-hand man, former Prime Minister Alain
Juppe, is under investigation as part of the inquiry into the way
their party financed itself under Chirac's leadership. Chirac's
successor as mayor, Jean Tiberi, is under investigation, too.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac's immunity while in office was confirmed on Jan. 22 by a
ruling of the Constitutional Council, the country's supreme
administrative tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   The council's president is Roland Dumas, a former foreign
minister who figures in a long-running scandal about a former
mistress who says that a state-owned oil company, Elf Aquitaine,
paid her millions of dollars to keep Dumas favorable to Elf's
interests. Dumas, under investigation by another set of
magistrates, has not been formally charged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
