<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CHINA-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TRIES TO FEND OFF U.N. CENSURE OVER RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also U.N.-Women-Treaty)  
(DW) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Even before the start of this year's meetings of the
U.N. Human Rights Commission, which begins a six-week session on
Monday, China has begun a vigorous campaign to head off possible
censure of its human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has yet to indicate whether it will
sponsor such a resolution, but it is under increased pressure to do
so, as both houses of Congress voted unanimously last month to
condemn China at this year's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   China's agreement to engage in dialogue on human rights averted
an anti-Beijing resolution from the 53-member commission last year.
But China has drawn renewed disapproval recently by rounding up
members of outlawed opposition parties and religious dissidents,
torturing prisoners, discriminating against its Christian minority
and imposing restrictions on the press.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent trip to China, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright warned Chinese officials about their human rights record,
although the Clinton administration generally has sought to
separate the issue from other aspects of U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Chinese Foreign Ministry warned that criticizing
China's record in ``protecting and promoting human rights'' would
be an attempt to ``interfere in China's affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the U.N. human rights chief, Mary Robinson, noted
in a televised interview on Thursday that ``we will, no doubt, be
discussing China'' at the meetings this year.
</P>
<P>
   Along with China, a number of other countries including Cuba,
Iran, Iraq, Congo, Cambodia, Rwanda, Yugoslavia and Afghanistan are
also likely to come under scrutiny by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The body has no enforcement powers. Its strength lies in casting
a moral spotlight on countries that are not living up to
commitments made under international treaties that recognize a
broad array of political, economic, social and cultural rights.
</P>
<P>
   China escaped formal censure for the past seven years, with the
last resolution in 1997 being defeated by a strong margin. The
margin reflected traditional divisions in voting between Western
countries, led by the United States, and Asian and African nations,
which reject such criticism as undue domestic interference.
</P>
<P>
   Such political divides will be seen in another key battle that
is shaping up this year over whether to condemn Cuba's rights
violations. Cuba's recent trial and sentencing of four
``unpatriotic citizens'' has fueled efforts to examine its
treatment of dissenters. Last year, a condemnatory resolution,
fielded by the United States, missed adoption by three votes.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's record is likely to be on the docket again this year. An
anti-Havana resolution may be sponsored by an Eastern European
country, according to officials who asked not to be named, because
the U.S. effort has been steadily losing support. Last year, Italy
and France, which co-sponsored the resolution condemning Cuba in
1997, refused to sign on again.
</P>
<P>
   While many nations perceive the condemnations, usually of
developing countries, as unfair interference by the West, not all
Western states escape censure. In each of the past two years, the
commission overrode United States objections and voted for a
worldwide moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's censure came on the heels of a U.N. investigator's
report that the United States engages in unfair, arbitrary and
racist use of capital punishment. A new report, issued this month,
calls on the United States and other countries to abolish the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups are seeking to have the European Union
sponsor another anti-death-penalty resolution this year, which the
United States, although it will not be listed by name, will do its
best to fend off in order to avoid the political embarrassment of
having other countries point to the resolution as proof the United
States, too, breaches international human rights norms.
</P>
<P>
   As the commission opens its 55th session, the United Nations is
undertaking a restructuring of its human rights bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring has been motivated in part by the more visible
role by Mrs. Robinson, who took over as rights chief in September
1997 after seven years as Ireland's president.
</P>
<P>
   She is widely credited with turning around the lackluster
Geneva-based human rights center and with launching the idea that
human rights should be ``mainstreamed'' into all U. N. work,
instead of being regarded as a separate task.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, she has attracted enough new funding to
increase the number of field operations, in which staff members
monitor compliance with human rights norms, to 22 countries,
including Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
