<HEADER>
A7882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-WOMEN-TREATY-NYT     03-20 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-WOMEN-TREATY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. ADDS ENFORCEMENT MECHANISM TO TREATY FOR WOMEN 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Twenty years after it first adopted an
international convention banning all forms of discrimination
against women, the United Nations finally has put some teeth into
it by agreeing on a way to offer abused women independent redress
against violations of their rights.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights and women's groups working for the reform generally
have welcomed it, despite reservations about the need to secure the
consent of individual women before an appeal can be brought before
a new 23-member committee of experts that will rule on claims of
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have preferred a free hand in acting for women who
may be detained, have disappeared or be afraid of reprisals if they
complain,'' said Florence Martin, of Amnesty International. ``But
we will be able to work with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new mechanism, which ran into considerable opposition from a
number of governments, mainly in the developing world, takes the
form of an optional protocol to the Convention on the Elimination
of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women. That convention was
adopted in December 1979 and has been ratified by 163 countries so
far. The 22 countries that have not ratified the convention so far
include the United States and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The new protocol, approved unanimously by the Commission on the
Status of Women at its regular half-yearly meeting here last week,
allows a woman suffering any form of discrimination banned by the
convention to appeal to the experts' committee once she has
exhausted all means of redress in her own country.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals also may be made to the committee by women's
organizations or other bodies acting on behalf of victims. But a
victim must first give consent unless the author of the appeal can
justify acting without it.
</P>
<P>
   The committee may launch its own investigation into a member
state's conduct if it receives ``reliable information indicating
grave or systematic violations'' of the rights afforded women.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has no power to compel a government to change its
behavior. But if it finds a complaint justified, it must inform the
country in question and make recommendations for correcting rights
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the committee to be flexible about the need for
victims' consent,'' said Donna Sullivan, a New York University law
professor working with human rights groups pressing for the new
protocol. ``Many persecuted women lack the education and the money
to complain themselves about human rights abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Widney Brown of Human Rights Watch called the protocol an
important step forward. ``Governments talk a lot about women's
rights but don't do anything concrete to enforce them,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan hailed the new protocol as ``a
major step forward in realizing governments' commitments to women's
human rights'' and urged states to ratify it.
</P>
<P>
   The convention banning discrimination against women guarantees
women's rights across many fields including employment, education,
voting, nationality, marriage and divorce, health care and equality
before the law.
</P>
<P>
   However, the convention on women has lacked enforcement
mechanism. The fact that it has taken 20 years to create one is
seen by activists as proof of governments' indifference or
hostility toward ending discrimination against women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private pressure groups put enforcement on the agenda, not
governments,'' Sullivan said. Along with Ms. Martin of Amnesty
International, she identified China, Algeria, Egypt, India and Cuba
as among the governments most hostile towards the new protocol.
</P>
<P>
   A big U.N. human rights conference in Vienna in 1993 first
called for a way to put teeth into the convention on discrimination
against women. The call was repeated at the 1995 U.N. conference on
women held in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The new protocol will be opened for signature at the next U.N.
General Assembly later this year, and only needs ratification by 10
countries to come into force.
</P>
<P>
   Although President Carter signed the convention on eliminating
discrimination against women, the Senate never ratified it. But the
city of San Francisco recently did so and has started adjusting
rules and regulations to comply with its provisions. Los Angeles
has promised to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Many Muslim countries also have ratified the convention on
discrimination against women, including Pakistan, Morocco, Jordan
and Tunisia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
