<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: OBLIVIOUS AT THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Perkins, a city councilman from Harlem, was
among those arrested at police headquarters with David Dinkins and
Charles Rangel last week. It was not his idea of a good time. Even
if you have chosen to offer yourself up for arrest, being in the
custody of police with your hands cuffed behind your back is not
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd all prefer to be doing something else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the plummeting crime statistics, behind the incessant
trumpeting of New York as a city reined in and refashioned by a
tough-as-nails mayor, lies the fearful reality of police misconduct
so widespread and at times so insanely violent that it has brought
a new kind of terror to the streets of New York.
</P>
<P>
   A black newspaper reporter remarked last week: ``I am afraid to
use my cell phone. All a cop has to say, to justify shooting you,
is, `I thought he was reaching for a gun.' It's too late, after
you're dead, to say, `I was just reaching for my phone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins is among the growing number of New Yorkers who believe
that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir
have shown insufficient concern about the nature and the extent of
the misconduct, and a callous attitude toward the fear and the
anger it has provoked.
</P>
<P>
   I agree. They are something to see, this mayor and this
commissioner. They exude contempt. There is no evidence that either
man really cares about the tragic crumbling of relations between
police and the communities they serve. And they are publicly
scornful of the opposition growing all around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership,'' said Safir, ``is about standing up to media
hype, demagogues and political agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins has a different view. ``We have a very serious problem
with police brutality,'' he said. ``But the leadership that should
be provided by the mayor and the police commissioner is just not
there. They seem to be hostile to the fact that people are outraged
and upset about this unfortunate situation _ the Diallo shooting _
and other situations before that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not think that most New Yorkers were anti-cop,
but that a tremendous amount of frustration has built up over
excessive use of force by police, and that people are anxious for
that to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``History has taught us that one way to get change is through
protest and civil disobedience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the plastic flex-cuffs were attached to his wrists on
Monday, Perkins became one of scores of people, many of them
high-profile public officials, who have been arrested at the daily
protests outside police headquarters arranged by the Rev. Al
Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has dismissed the protests as ``silly.'' But while he
may not be listening to the cries of genuine anguish from New
Yorkers concerned about police abuse, plenty of others are. Both
the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, Mary Jo White, and the U.S.
attorney in Brooklyn, Zachary Carter, are investigating the Police
Department. The U.S. Civil Rights Commission voted this month to
hold a public hearing as part of its investigation into allegations
of abuse by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the state attorney general, Eliot Spitzer, announced
that his office would investigate charges that police officers have
routinely been stopping people on the street, especially
African-Americans and Latinos, and frisking them without
justification. ``There is a tidal wave of concern about this
issue,'' said Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   He described the relationship between police and residents in
ethnic minority neighborhoods as ``frayed.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Mark Green, the public advocate and a political rival
of the mayor, said in a prepared statement that ``the Giuliani
administration's failure to address the problem of police
misconduct has eroded the mutual respect between community and
police that is vital to effective law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on Safir to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the arrests outside police headquarters continue.
</P>
<P>
   More and more New Yorkers are acknowledging that police
misconduct is a serious problem. They see what Giuliani apparently
can't see _ that unless the problem is honestly engaged the
consequences for the city will be dire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
