<HEADER>
A7887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-CIVILITY-ART     03-20 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CIVILITY-ART-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass., N.Y., Wash., Mich., Texas)  
 LAWMAKERS GET AWAY FROM CAPITAL FOR LESSON IN BEING NICE  (ART ADV:
Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERSHEY, Pa. _ During fights on the House floor, they have
plenty of opportunity to snipe. During committee hearings, they
have ample occasion to seethe.
</P>
<P>
   But in this candy-coated realm of chocolate kisses, members of
Congress had a rare chance this weekend to do something different.
They got to share.
</P>
<P>
   Descending on a rambling lodge and conference center for what
was billed as a three-day course in civility, nearly 200
Republicans and Democrats, some with their spouses and children in
tow, came together to exercise their diplomacy and exorcize their
demons, primarily in small discussion groups that were meant,
according to organizers, to provide ``safe environments'' for the
venting of feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers listened on Friday afternoon to a keynote speech by
John Hume, the Nobel-winning architect of peace in Northern
Ireland, on the theory that anyone who could soothe the tensions
there might be able to do as much for Ways and Means.
</P>
<P>
   They were scheduled for line dancing Saturday night at a Family
Country Hoedown, on the theory that if they could kick up their
heels together, then maybe _ just maybe _ they could break the
impasse over Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   These were lofty goals indeed, but not, participants insisted,
beyond all reach.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on Hume's address, Rep. Richard Neal, D-Mass., said,
``The odds that he faced getting the Good Friday agreement were
clearly more difficult than the odds we face here.''
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan retreat, from Friday to Sunday, was a reprise of
a similar gathering here two years ago, but lawmakers conceded that
this one came at an even more difficult moment, on the heels of the
impeachment ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence here seemed to signal both a genuine desire for
some degree of reconciliation and a genuine concern about their
everyday estrangement from one another.
</P>
<P>
   As they boarded a chartered train leaving Union Station in
Washington on Friday morning and as they took breaks from their
scheduled activities here Friday and Saturday, they spoke ruefully
of the frenetic pace in Congress these days and the impersonal
atmosphere around Washington, where they said fewer and fewer
lawmakers were anchoring their family and social lives.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Quinn, R-N.Y., said between events that there was an
incalculable benefit to ``getting to know someone over a tuna fish
sandwich and a Pepsi instead of a minimum wage agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But the failure of a majority of House members to come to
Hershey, the self-christened ``sweetest place on earth,''
underlined a feeling among many that all they would get here were
empty calories. Several of them said the event was a futile
charade, more useful for public relations than political harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the point,'' said Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., who
stayed away. In a telephone interview on the eve of the retreat,
McDermott said that if Republicans were really interested in warmer
relations, they would have been more generous in awarding committee
assignments to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in some place in the Bible, it says that by your deeds
you shall be known,'' McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, as the House retreat loomed, some Republican
aides suggested that their party would field about 150 of 200
participants, which prompted Democrats to grumble privately that
Republicans were releasing inflated numbers to make their opponents
look bad. Democrats and even Republican leaders of the retreat
insisted the attendance split was 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   But they declined, even as the train pulled out of Union
Station, to provide a detailed list of participants or even an
overall attendance figure. They simply said the retreat had proved
nearly as potent a draw as it was two years ago, when 197 members
showed up.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The weekend was suffused in secrecy and heavy security, with
reporters relegated to the periphery of the conference center. A
text of Hume's speech was unavailable and details of the schedule
were kept under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   But, this being Congress, there were any number of leaks,
revealing an itinerary rife with items that had an ambiguous
connection to civility and healing.
</P>
<P>
   After a Friday night event at which the actor Sam Waterston
performed his imitation of Abraham Lincoln, early risers could
attend an aerobics workout at 6:45 Saturday morning led by Sandie
Knollenberg, the wife of Rep. Joe Knollenberg, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon was set aside for diversion and relaxation,
with lawmakers and their families choosing among such options as a
journey to Gettysburg, a trip to the chocolate museum, high tea at
the Hotel Hershey and a skating exhibition known as World on Ice.
That was all leading up to the hoedown, where the kind of
fluorescent necklaces popular at circuses would be scattered around
the tables as festive icebreakers. (Two years ago, it was hula
hoops.)
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said none of this strayed from the retreat's purpose
of fostering greater civility in Congress. A common refrain was
that once a lawmaker had seen a colleague across the aisle changing
a toddler's diaper or had broken bread with someone from the enemy
camp, it would be harder for him or her to summarily demonize the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there was something to that. Susan Lampson, who attended
the retreat with her husband, Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Texas, said that
ever since she happened to meet and befriend Rep. Kevin Brady,
R-Texas, and his wife a while ago, ``I've told my husband that
during the next campaign, he can't go out and talk ugly about
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers at the retreat also said Waterston's commentary on the
Civil War and Hume's remarks about the quest for peace in Northern
Ireland had helped them put their own quarrels in perspective, and
even inspired them.
</P>
<P>
   That boded well for a wish that Rep. Joe Crowley, D-N.Y.,
expressed at the start of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that at the end of this weekend,'' he said with a
smile, ``I can lay a big Hershey's kiss on a Republican, preferably
female.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
