<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-DATA-$ADV21-COX     03-20 1819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-DATA-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: First in a two-day series.
 &HT;    Embargoed For Use Sun., March 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    CHART INFORMATION ON HAITI
 &HT;    With HAITI-FAILURE-$ADV21.
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: A Cox News Service chart-graphic using this data is
also available.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAITI: AT-A-GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Population: 7.8 million
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Port-au-Prince, population 2 million
</P>
<P>
   Location: Haiti occupies the western third of the Caribbean
island of Hispaniola, an island it shares with the Dominican
Republic. Haiti is about the size of Maryland, and is located 600
miles southeast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Languages: Creole; French
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy: 54.5 years
</P>
<P>
   Adult Literacy Rate: 40 percent
</P>
<P>
   Currency: the gourde; exchange rate about 17:1
</P>
<P>
   Religion: About 80 percent are Catholic, but voodoo is widely
practiced.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment/underemployment: 70 percent
</P>
<P>
   Percentage of people with access to doctor/clinic: 60 percent
</P>
<P>
   Average annual per-capita income: $225
</P>
<P>
   Fertility rate: 4.8 children per woman
</P>
<P>
   President: Rene Preval
</P>
<P>
   Political situation: Haiti's government has been virtually
paralyzed since June 1997, when then-Prime Minister Rosny Smarth
resigned. Parliament then rejected President Preval's first three
nominees to replace Smarth, creating a crisis that has blocked
government programs and held up nearly $1 billion in international
aid. The crisis came to a head on Jan. 11, when Preval announced
that the terms of most legislators, as well as the mayors, had
ended.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. involvement: Haitians have long been suspicious of the
United States, which occupied Haiti from 1915 to 1934. The United
States funneled millions of dollars to the Duvaliers -- father,
``Papa Doc,'' and son, ``Baby Doc'' -- who ruled Haiti with an iron
fist. During their 30-year reign, which ended in 1986, thousands of
people were massacred or tortured to death. Jean-Bertrand Aristide,
a populist priest, was elected president in 1990, but was removed
by a military coup only nine months after taking office. He spent
three years in exile in the United States. Then, in September 1994,
President Clinton ordered 20,000 troops to Haiti to remove the
military regime and restore Aristide to power.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: U.S. and Haitian governments.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI TIMELINE: FROM THE DUVALIERS TO U.S. INVASION . . .
</P>
<P>
   1986: The oppressive 30-year dictatorship of the Duvaliers comes
to an end when son, Jean-Claude ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier flees to
France in February.
</P>
<P>
   1987: Gen. Henri Namphy, the head of the interim military
government, promises presidential elections, but they are called
off after Duvalierists massacre at least 34 voters on polling day.
</P>
<P>
   1988: New, but fraudulent elections were held in January and
Professor Leslie Manigat is handed the presidency. He is ousted in
June, however, when he tries to remove Namphy as army commander.
After only four months, Namphy himself is ousted by a coup that
brings Gen. Prosper Avril to power.
</P>
<P>
   1989: Several unsuccessful coup attempts are then staged against
leader Gen. Prosper Avril.
</P>
<P>
   1990: Avril flees the country amid violent protests, and
democratic elections are held. Father Jean-Bertrand Aristide is
elected president.
</P>
<P>
   1991: Aristide is overthrown by the military. He flees to the
the United States, where he heads a Haitian government-in-exile for
three years. The Organization of American States, led by the United
States, imposes a crippling economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
   1992: Haiti is under brutal military dictatorship of Army
commander Gen. Raoul Cedras. In July, Aristide and army sign accord
to return him to power but Cedras and other military leaders fail
to resign.
</P>
<P>
   1993: Further United Nations pressure comes in the form of an
oil embargo. Cedras agrees to the deployment of U.N. human rights
monitors in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   1994: U.S.-led forces invade Haiti, and restore Aristide to
power.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Cox Newspapers Archives.
</P>
<P>
   THE NIGHTMARE SCENARIO: AFTER DROPPING OFF DRAMATICALLY IN 1995,
THE NUMBER OF HAITIAN REFUGEES IS CLIMBING AGAIN:
</P>
