<P>
   U.S. TAXPAYERS: SO MUCH MONEY ... SO LITTLE TO SHOW FOR IT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $30 million on election support ... three sets of elections
plagued by fraud and low turnout
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $30 million on justice reform ... among other things, programs
have provided legal services to 18,710 poor Haitians who didn't
have access before; but the justice system is still weak and mostly
corrupt
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $400,000 a year on a Special Investigations Unit ... it was
set up to investigate 26 politically-motivated murders but has yet
to crack a case
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $34 million on agriculture and environment ... millions of
trees planted; more than 140,000 hillside farmers are learning to
produce more tree crops such as coffee, mangos, cocoa and citrus
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $17 million on education ... 960 teachers trained and books
distributed to a million students
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $60 million on health ... health services provided to 4.7
million people
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $5.3 million to sell off nine state-owned enterprises; flour
mill, cement plant, the seaport, airport, phone company, electric
company, water company and two banks. ... only one -- the flour
mill -- has been sold
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CONGRESS IS SAYING:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  U.S. Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla.: ``There's a trend in Haiti back
toward authoritarian rule. We've been ripped off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we've gotten for our money. The justice
system doesn't exist. The roads are falling apart. There's cover-up
and denial on the drug issue. There's so much corruption that the
only way to make sure aid gets to the people is to fly down there
yourself with some food, hand it to a Haitian, and watch him eat it
in your presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That place is hanging on by a thread. All indicators show the
country is going backwards, not forwards.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rep. Carrie Meek, D-Fla.: ``I don't think that U.S. policy
toward Haiti should be changed. There has been a political crisis,
but that's to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political turmoil is no reason to take aid away from the
people. I think some members of Congress would just as soon see
Haiti go away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.: ``Clinton has shown a lot of
political courage in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very disappointed with the government of Haiti. But we
can't penalize the people just because there are political
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rep. James E. Clyburn, D-S.C.: ``I'm disappointed more
progress hasn't been made in Haiti. I'm disappointed with the
government of Haiti. We're watching the situation there closely.
One problem is that they have too many political parties in Haiti.
The country's too fragmented.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio.: ``Our aid has had success. The
problem is that the success stories haven't been as big as we'd
like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central government doesn't function. I think the elite in
Haiti hasn't decided that it's in their best interest for the
government to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certainly open to trying to find ways to leverage aid to
get the changes that need to be made in Haiti. I think it's going
to be tougher and tougher to sustain our level of assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  U.S. Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala.: ``If we'd give the
administration total discretion, they'd spend every penny they have
on Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haiti is not a success story. I chastised Warren Christopher
for calling Haiti a success story. The place is getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even on President Preval's part, he shows no enthusiasm to
make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   FOLLOWING THE FLOW OF AID MONEY, FROM U.S. TAXPAYERS TO HAITI
POOR . . .
</P>
<P>
   According to USAID, here's how an aid program gets funded:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The idea for a program, like feeding the hungry, is hatched by
the USAID office in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The program, including the budget, is sent to USAID in
Washington and also to the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Both have to review it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Then it is sent to the White House for its review.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The White House makes changes and sends it back to USAID in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Then it goes to Capitol Hill. USAID makes a presentation
before Congress. Then Congress decides whether or not to
appropriate the money.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Then the final plan and budget goes back to State Department
for one more review, and then back to USAID in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Then the money is sent to USAID in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  They give money to one of 30 non-governmental organizations
which will then implement the program. For example, with food aid,
much of the money would go to Atlanta-based C.A.R.E.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  C.A.R.E. would in turn set up a feeding center at a school,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
