<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-FAILURE-$ADV21-     03-20 2511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-FAILURE-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: First in a two-day series.
 &HT;    Embargoed For Use Sun., March 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    HAITI: A FOREIGN POLICY NIGHTMARE -- WAITING TO HAPPEN?
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    With HAITI-FLOPS-$ADV21; HAITI-DATA-$ADV21.
 &HT;    With Photos; Graphic.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ In the fall of 1994, President Clinton
confounded his critics by successfully using 20,000 U.S.-led forces
to overthrow a brutal military regime here and give democracy a
second chance.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no blood was shed. A triumph in foreign policy was
declared.
</P>
<P>
   But today, after nearly five years of pouring more than $2.2
billion of American taxpayers' money into Haiti, there is little to
feel triumphant about.
</P>
<P>
   The daily killings have indeed ceased. But instead of bringing
lasting democracy and economic development to this poor Caribbean
nation, impatient members of Congress -- and even some Haiti
experts within the administration -- say the United States is on
the brink of a foreign policy disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could slip back to chaos (at any moment), and that is a
great concern,'' said one State Department official who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A foreboding came in January when Haitian President Rene Preval
dissolved the parliament, effectively implementing one-man rule.
Preceding government gridlock over much-needed economic reforms had
already frozen nearly $1 billion in aid pledged by international
financial institutions -- partly underwritten by the United States
-- that might have resulted in real progress toward systemic
development.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of the Clinton administration's aid program here by
Cox Newspapers showed instead that despite U.S. efforts roads are
crumbling, electricity and clean water are scarce, and many
children still go hungry as per-capita income has fallen from $260
in 1994 to $225 today.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis, which also included World Bank and Inter-American
Development Bank (IADB) documents, showed some successes. But they
also revealed glaring weaknesses in a sometimes-misguided policy.
In some cases, it appears that money was simply misdirected.
</P>
<P>
   For example, no money disbursed by the U.S. Agency for
International Development (USAID) here has been spent on adult
literacy, although two-thirds of Haitian adults can't read or
write. In addition, USAID has only spent 15 percent of aid money on
agricultural programs when two-thirds of the people live off the
land in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nearly $30 million has been spent to support a panoply of
elections marred by fraud, inefficiency and low voter turnout.
Another nearly $30 million has been spent on reforming a justice
system the U.S. State Department recently called ``nearly
moribund.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the United States gives billions more in total aid
to Russia and more per capita to Israel, but critics find the
Clinton administration's inability to show much for taxpayers'
money in Haiti is particularly grating given that Haiti offers so
comparatively little by way of economic or security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   What Haiti does have, if things fall apart there, is nearly 8
million potential refugees sitting 600 miles off the South Florida
coast. It is this potential nightmare -- and the numbers have
increased sharply over the past year -- that keeps U.S. foreign
policymakers awake at night.
</P>
<P>
   Enough so, that the administration is attempting to obtain
another $105 million for Haiti this year. That has drawn the
attention of critics like U.S. Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., who
introduced a resolution earlier this month calling for the
Organization of American States to consider actions to bring about
a return to democracy in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been ripped off in Haiti and I don't see why we should
put any more money into it,'' said Goss, who chairs the House
Intelligence Committee. ``There's so much corruption that the only
way to make sure aid gets to the people is to fly down there
yourself with some food, hand it to a Haitian, and watch him eat it
in your presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Haiti's people stagger on.
</P>
<P>
   In the seaside slum of Cite Soleil, a 2 1/2-square-mile tin
encampment that houses 200,000 of this city's poorest, citizens say
they're fed up with democracy and long for the days of
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were jobs when (Jean Claude) Duvalier was around . . .
there were even tourists in this country, can you believe that?''
says Alexi Charles, 38, grousing that everything is worse.
</P>
<P>
   Even when U.S. programs have been well-designed, efforts are
often stymied by a paralyzed Haitian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe both the Haitian government and the Haitian private
sector are corrupt,'' said Michael Azefor(CQ), the World Bank
representative here, in a recent interview with the Cox News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   He said the World Bank, which recently suspended about half of a
$50 million loan to Haiti for road construction because officials
failed to report how they used the money, has determined that it is
no longer ``responsible'' to negotiate new projects with Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   USAID has reduced the amount of money it funnels through the
Haitian central government to 10 percent, choosing instead to work
with 30 non-governmental organizations -- much as it did in the
days of dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   But USAID officials warn that development can't be expected to
occur overnight in a country trying to recover from nearly two
centuries of oppressive rule capped by a three-year economic
embargo imposed in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes couldn't have been higher in 1994 when Haiti won the
equivalent of the international lottery for foreign aid. After the
U.S. invasion, donors from all corners of the globe pledged $3.5
billion to help prop up this embryonic democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the country still ekes along largely on foreign support,
with aid accounting for a whopping 37.3 percent of the gross
domestic product, or GDP.
</P>
<P>
   The United States alone, has spent some $750 million in
non-military aid since 1994 trying to meet the basic needs of
Haiti's poor by planting trees, renovating clinics and distributing
food to hundreds of thousands of Haitians a day. Another $22
million or so a year has gone to maintain a U.S. ``support team''
here of nearly 500 troops.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of U.S. forces in Latin America and the Caribbean
recommended last month the withdrawal of American troops from
Haiti, saying the country's growing political turmoil is placing
them in danger. But State Department officials have vowed to keep
troops in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, it appears that donors, including the United
States, may have miscalculated in pressuring the Haitian government
to adopt economic reforms designed to jumpstart the economy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, USAID spent $5.3 million to help Haiti sell off
nine state-owned enterprises -- only one has been sold.
</P>
<P>
   According to a confidential World Bank study, the pressure
divided a pro-reform president and an anti-reform parliament that
is behind much of today's current gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Still, USAID officials point to a laundry list of achievements
while helping to build a country from scratch, most notably more
credit for small businesses and less malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   It not only feeds 500,000 school children a day, but has spent
$7.3 million on a project to improve Haiti's coffee bean crop and
market it to U.S. roasters. About 20,000 farmers participate, and
they enthusiastically report that their incomes have increased
four-fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aid is having specific, measurable results,'' said Mark
Schneider, USAID's assistant director for Latin America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   But a close look at USAID programs in Haiti reveals at best, a
mixed bag of results.
</P>
<P>
   For example, USAID has supported three sets of elections, all
fraught with fraud and waste -- from inadequate attempts to
register voters to $600,000 paid to an AFL-CIO affiliate for
pollwatching and other duties that were apparently never performed.
The affiliate responded in a Government Accounting Office report,
however, that it did help register 800,000 people to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pastor, who, at the time, was director of Latin American
and Caribbean Programs at the Carter Center in Atlanta, observed
the June 1995 elections -- the first following the invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor, who's observed 20 elections, called them the worst he'd
ever seen. ``I observed more instances of fraud in that election
than I had ever seen before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Seiger of the Washington, D.C.-based International
Foundation for Election Systems (IFES), which USAID hired for
election-related support, blamed the election's troubles on the
Haitian government's own inexperience at overseeing elections.
</P>
<P>
   Even Haiti's most recent election, in April 1997, attracted a
derisory 5 percent of the electorate and was never validated due to
charges of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The attempts at justice reform have not fared much better.
</P>
<P>
   USAID officials say they've provided education for more than
34,000 Haitians, making them more aware of their rights in the
judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   But a report by Creative Associates International Inc., a
consulting firm hired by USAID to evaluate the justice program,
said that ``even with long-term donor support, it is not likely
that a well-functioning judiciary will ever be built on such a weak
foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the justice system's biggest problems is one
USAID can do little about. Haiti's judges are woefully underpaid
and many of them don't show up for work. They resent U.S. attention
showered on the police force, and the relationship between judges
and police is notoriously poor.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins.)
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, among it greatest successes, U.S. officials count
the training of the Haitian National Police force -- even though it
still falls short, both numerically and professionally, of being
able to effectively police the country.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the United States has helped disband the military
and quickly train more than 6,600 police officers at a cost of some
$95 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to the State Department, the police have been a
stabilizing force -- and admirably a neutral one -- although it
still grapples with corruption and human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The force today totals about 5,500, compared with nearly 40,000
police officers in New York City which has a population of roughly
the same size -- about 8 million. Hundreds of police officers have
been dismissed for various reasons, including drug trafficking,
according to U.S. officials. It has no forensics laboratory, which
has sorely curtailed efforts conduct investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also spends $400,000 a year to support a
Special Investigations Unit, a 28-member team of Haitians working
under the direction of an American adviser. The team was formed in
1995 to investigate 26 high-profile, politically motivated murders
that had drawn the attention of Republicans in the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
   It has yet to crack a case.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends).
</P>
<P>
   At the crux of all of these problems, according to aid
officials, is a Haitian government that has been crippled since
June 1997, when the last prime minister resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian President Preval's announcement in January -- citing a
1995 electoral law --that the terms of most legislators and mayors
had ended has sparked fears of a return to dictatorship. Preval's
decision threw into question $6.5 million in aid allocated to
support Haiti's fledgling local governments since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Preval says he intends to organize quick elections to resolve
the crisis. But the gridlock is keeping Haiti from using about $200
million sitting in a Washington, D.C. bank account, said Ericq
Pierre(CQ), who represents Haiti at the IADB, which promotes
development in Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   In all, he said Haiti's lost out on nearly $600 million from the
IADB alone.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Clinton administration has budgeted $105 million
for Haiti this year, despite a November internal memo by James
Dobbins, the top Latin America and Caribbean specialist on the
National Security Council staff, acknowledging that the poor
situation in Haiti ``has (unfortunately) not changed in any
significant way'' over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a growing chorus of criticism from members of
Congress convinced U.S. resources have been squandered.
</P>
<P>
   They include Republican North Carolina Sen. Jesse Helms, the
powerful chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. A
letter from Helms to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright halted a
U.S.-funded program in Haiti last month that used voodoo ceremonies
to promote contraceptive use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big failure's been the lack of political will inside Haiti
to do the things that need doing,'' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio,
who co-signed Rep. Goss' resolution denouncing the Haitian
government. ``We simply haven't been able to have the impact on
Haiti we would have liked.''
</P>
<P>
   A major complaint is that the money's failed to buy the U.S.
government a lot of influence.
</P>
<P>
   Even a parade of high-level emissaries to Haiti that include
Albright and First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton have not been able
to break the political impasse here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're funding a huge part of the government's budget, and
you still don't have any leverage, how do you explain that?'' the
Carter Center's Pastor asked.
</P>
<P>
   With about 20 percent of all U.S. foreign aid for Latin America
and the Caribbean going to this country with less than 2 percent of
the region's population, a lot of congressmen -- especially
Republicans -- are asking the same question.
</P>
<P>
   Goss, House International Relations Committee chairman Benjamin
Gilman and others say U.S. policy toward Haiti should be completely
re-evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   But for Republicans, who opposed the deployment of troops here,
aid to Haiti has never been popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some members of Congress would just as soon see Haiti
go away,'' said Rep. Carrie Meek, D-Fla. ``But I don't think that
U.S. policy toward Haiti should be changed. There has been a
political crisis ... (but) political turmoil is no reason to take
aid away from the people.''
</P>
<P>
   USAID's Schneider said aid must continue not only for reasons of
compassion, but to keep U.S.-bound Haitians from fleeing the
country.
</P>
<P>
   A flood of Haitian boat people that reached nearly 25,000 in
1994 has been reduced to a mere trickle, albeit one that threatens
to grow as the situation here appears all the more hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   And because the United States has no repatriation agreement with
Haiti, as it does with Cuba, it cannot automatically send back
Haitians intercepted in international waters.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next in Haiti is the great unknown.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, however, one State Department official may
have summed it up best: ``Haiti has cost a lot and it will cost a
lot and it will continue to cost a lot for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
