<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0320-C     03-20 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON: SERBS HAVE CROSSED 'THRESHOLD,' WARNS OF 'RISKS' WITH
NATO STRIKES
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    Moving in both the International and Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Serbs in Kosovo have already crossed the
''threshold'' that would trigger NATO air strikes, President
Clinton said Friday, warning that the alliance is united and poised
to attack to prevent further civilian deaths and a widening Balkan
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stressed, however, that Serbs may still avoid military
action by agreeing to a U.S.-brokered peace plan that would place
28,000 NATO peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to put a single American pilot into the air. I
do not want anyone else to die in the Balkans. I do not want a
conflict,'' Clinton told reporters at a White House news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Clinton, with some 40,000 Serb troops and police
backed by hundreds of tanks already massing in or near Kosovo, NATO
has all the justification it needs to strike. The alliance will not
wait for further atrocities to be committed before it acts to avert
a widening humanitarian disaster there, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that whatever threshold they need to cross has been
crossed,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have massed their troops, they have continued to take
aggressive action, they have already leveled one village in the
recent past and killed a lot of innocent people,'' Clinton said.
``I do not believe that we ought to have to have thousands more
people slaughtered and buried in open soccer fields before we do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing the nation for possible casualties, Clinton conceded
that American pilots could face formidable Serb defenses and a
hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unquestionably, there are risks in military action, if that
becomes necessary,'' Clinton said. ``U.S. and other NATO pilots
will be in harm's way. The Serbs have a strong air-defense
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Those threats, Clinton said, must be weighed against the risks
of inaction in a region that has already provided stark lessons to
those who would hope to avert military action with endless
diplomacy and appeasement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake: if we and our allies do not have the will to
act, there will be more massacres,'' Clinton said. ``In dealing
with aggressors in the Balkans, hesitation is a license to kill.
But action and resolve can stop armies and save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned further that allowing the Kosovo crisis to simmer
could set off related conflicts in neighboring countries. He
mentioned Macedonia, Albania, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced we'll be dragged into this thing under worse
circumstances, at greater cost,'' he said, ''if we don't act.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks -- part of his first solo White House
news conference since last April -- as Kosovo peace talks in Paris
collapsed in the face of Serb intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, as the State Department ordered non-essential
personnel to evacuate the U.S. Embassy in Belgrade and some 1,400
international monitors began making their way out of Kosovo as a
precaution against military strikes, Clinton briefed congressional
leaders on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the brink of a very grave situation,'' House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., told reporters after the two-hour White
House meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be going to bombing pretty soon,'' said Sen. Joe
Biden, D-Del.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va.,
said he expected a full debate on U.S. action in Kosovo early next
week, a further suggestion that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic may have a few more days to consider the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the meeting added momentum towards the Senate
supporting the president and NATO in this action,'' said Warner.
``Credibility of NATO is on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Warner, ``It is my expectation we will have a strong debate
next week and, hopefully, come to a consensus as how best we can
support our president.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The only hope for averting NATO action, Clinton said, is for
Milosevic to sign on to the peace agreement signed Thursday by
Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to be working on this all weekend,'' Clinton said,
without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a southern province of 2.2 million people -- 90
percent ethnic Albanians and the other 10 percent Serb -- in
Serbia, one of two remaining states that make up Yugoslavia. For
the past year, rebels with the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) have
challenged the authority of Serb forces, which have retaliated
against villages and civilians in fighting that has left more than
2,000 dead and some 230,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, warned in October
that it would not tolerate continuing Serb military activity in
Kosovo. Clinton authorized, at that time, the use of U.S. forces as
part of any NATO air strikes initiated against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has since said, and reiterated Friday, that he was
prepared to strike Serbs if they rejected the peace agreement, as
they did on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO planners have provided target sets for more than 350
warplanes -- half of them American -- standing by to strike Serb
military and communications positions if ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton avoided any discussion of the timing of possible air
strikes. He is scheduled to meet next Wednesday with Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have speculated that he might prefer to defer strikes
until after that meeting, out of consideration to Russia, which
opposes military action against the Serbs, which have close
historic links to the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   White House security officials, however, said NATO action would
be dictated by conditions on the ground, not by political
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can prevent the use of force, that's the preferred
course,'' said one such official, speaking on background. But, this
source stressed, ``NATO's response will be driven by (Serb)
intransigence and the reality of conditions on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also made clear that he has no deadline in mind for
removing NATO peacekeepers from Kosovo -- should they ever be
deployed there. Such a force would include roughly 4,000 Americans,
under current plans, and Clinton declined to specify a time limit
on their deployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just tell you that I think that we have tried to limit
our involvement, we have tried to limit our mission, and we will
conclude it as quickly as we can,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get in the position in Kosovo that I was in in
Bosnia where the Pentagon came to me with a very honest estimate of
when they thought we could finish, and we turned out to be wrong
about that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent U.S. peacekeepers to Bosnia in December 1995,
vowing that their mission would be over a year later. While the
numbers are down sharply, U.S. peacekeepers remain in Bosnia, where
they help other NATO troops police an uneasy peace. There is no
indication that the mission would end anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
