<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-FUTURE-$ADV22-C     03-20 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-FUTURE-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: Second in a two-day series.
 &HT;    Embargoed For Use Mon., March 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    HAITI'S FUTURE MAY DEPEND ON LACK OF DEPENDENCE ON FOREIGN AID
 &HT;    With Photos; Graphics.
 &HT;    With HAITI-HANDICAPPED-$ADV22.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ Five years from now, U.S. aid officials
envision a very different Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   It is a place where elections draw a majority of voters, and the
average woman bears only four children. A place where mayors
provide garbage pick-up, and tourists swarm seaside cities.
</P>
<P>
   They've had these kinds of visions before, however. Five years
go, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   But a U.S. led invasion and a massive infusion of non-military
aid later -- $669 million from the United States alone -- and
unyielding hopes have slammed up against an unshakable reality:
International assistance is no substitute for the Haitian
government's will to reform.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some key members of Congress are saying -- in
louder and louder voices -- that it is time for the United States
to rethink an aid policy that hasn't always accomplished its goals.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton administration officials, there is an added sense of
urgency in that the number of Haitian boat people coming to the
United States is steadily increasing. The White House is seeking
another $105 million in aid money for Haiti this year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the U.S. Agency for International Development, the
State Department's foreign aid arm, also know they have reached a
critical juncture.
</P>
<P>
   Either show more results, or Congress is likely to get its way
-- sharply reducing aid and exacerbating an already miserable
situation.
</P>
<P>
   USAID officials insist that a new five-year plan will help make
this poor Caribbean country an exemplar of economic prosperity and
democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of ideas from outside the administration,
as well:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Putting more money into rural areas, and farming programs;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Training seminars on how to resolve differences -- peacefully;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And expanding U.S. trade with Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no scheme will work. But aid officials agree they must
keep trying.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tom Friedeberg, director here for C.A.R.E., the
Atlanta-based relief organization: ``I am disappointed we haven't
made more progress . . . but if we pulled out now, it would be a
disaster for the country,''
</P>
<P>
   A microcosm of the future can be glimpsed inside a third-grade
classroom at the Immaculate Conception School, an all-girls' school
of about 500 students.
</P>
<P>
   Here, all eyes are fixed on a radio that's prominently displayed
on the teacher's desk.
</P>
<P>
   From that radio, the day's lesson is broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have two baskets, and there are five avocados in each
one, then how many avocados do you have?'' asks the voice on the
radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten,'' the students shout in unison. Their teacher nods her
head in approval.
</P>
<P>
   Although a fifth of the class is absent, the 40 or so students
present -- all neatly dressed in blue socks and blue dresses --
seem genuinely enthusiastic about their studies.
</P>
<P>
   USAID officials hope they stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   After spending nearly $20 million to train teachers in a country
where some educators can barely read and write, officials now plan
to spend nearly $20 million more on this form of distance education
known as interactive radio instruction, which allows a radio to
deliver lessons designed by Haiti's best teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 6,200 third-graders in 118 schools are being reached.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to improve the quality of education while increasing
attendance at schools in a country where only half of all children
aged 6 years to 12 years attend classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is moving away from emergency assistance and
focusing more on programs that can have a long-term impact on
Haiti,'' said Mark Schneider, USAID's assistant director for Latin
America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly education is an area that can have a real long-term
impact,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   That's a different approach from the one taken five years ago,
when aid officials were confronted with the challenges of
rebuilding from scratch the hemisphere's poorest nation, where
everything from jobs to clean water was absent.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they set up 2,500 feeding centers and started a short-term
jobs program. They trained a police force to defend citizens rather
than oppress them.
</P>
<P>
   While those efforts will continue, USAID officials will focus
more over the next five years on working directly with local
governments provide services Americans take for granted, such as
garbage pick-up.
</P>
<P>
   USAID also plans to help develop Haiti's tourism industry,
particularly in the picturesque seaside town of Jacmel, located
just 55 miles southwest of Port-au-Prince.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a $1.3 million project to restore Jacmel's wharf
will allow docking for cruise ships bringing up to 2,000 visitors a
day.
</P>
<P>
   For critics of USAID's programs, though, the focus should also
turn to Haiti's long-overlooked countryside.
</P>
<P>
   USAID spends 15 percent of its money on agricultural programs in
rural areas, although two-thirds of the population lives outside
the big cities.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of spending in rural areas -- where three million
people subsist on less than $160 a year -- has caused residents to
migrate, swelling already overcrowded cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rural areas must be brought more fully into aid programs since
this is where most people live and work,'' said Rachel Neild, a
Haiti expert at the Washington Office on Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   But the challenge of rural development is an intimidating one
because half of Haiti's land is on inclined slopes, rendering
mechanical farming difficult, if not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neild says these harsh conditions argue strongly for a
strategy of development in rural areas, if only to keep poverty
from getting any worse.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that farmers should be encouraged to grow food for
their own tables, rather than products for export -- such as
gourmet coffee -- as has been the focus of many USAID programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have nothing against exports, helping people grow
food for themselves and for the local market is the real way to
foment long-term development,'' said Kevin Murray, executive
director of Grassroots International, a Boston, Mass.-based
independent aid organization.
</P>
<P>
   He said more farm loans and training programs could spark
small-scale agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Some, also take issue with the roughly $30 million that has been
spent on justice reform without giving consideration to human
rights or conflict resolution -- a must in a society as fragmented
as Haiti's.
</P>
<P>
   Even representatives of the Haitian government say justice
programs should be oriented to ensuring that military officers
responsible for human rights abuses during the coup of 1991 against
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide are brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would bring the population together and give people some
real confidence in the justice system, which they don't have now,''
said Ira Kurzban, the Haitian government's Miami-based legal
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Haitians say more seminars on training their politicians to
resolve differences must be organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Haiti, everyone always has to win,'' said Micha Gaillard, a
leader of the socialist National Congress of Democratic Movements
in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how to compromise or how to play the game of
give and take with one another, and that's created political
problems which have really hurt this country,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it is the trade battle is brewing in the U.S.
Congress that could have the biggest long-term impact on Haiti's
future development -- and go along way toward reducing dependence
on foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the Haitian government's budget now comes from
foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Various proposals have been introduced in recent months that
would, if passed, expand the Caribbean Basin Initiative, or CBI,
granting exporters from the Caribbean the same preferential
treatment enjoyed by Mexico under the North American Free Trade
Agreement, or NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Caribbean countries, including Haiti, have argued
that they can't compete with Mexico for foreign investment --
particularly in assembly industries -- which their economies need
to reduce unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in Haiti tops 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States shouldn't maintain trade barriers against
the poor,'' said Merrill Smith, director of Haiti Advocacy Inc., a
Washington, D.C.-based lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   But even USAID officials admit privately that economic growth
here will have to average 8 percent to 10 percent -- for several
years in a row -- before real widespread development can occur.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few seem willing to give up on Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to continue to show great concern over Haiti,'' said
Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio. ``The place is in our own backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
