<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-HANDICAPPED-$AD     03-20 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-HANDICAPPED-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: Second in a two-day series.
 &HT;    Embargoed For Use Mon., March 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    DISABLED BUT HARDLY HANDICAPPED: PRIVATELY FUNDED SCHOOL MAKES A
DIFFERENCE FOR CHILDREN IN HAITI
 &HT;    With Photos; Graphics.
 &HT;    With HAITI-FUTURE-$ADV22.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ Painfully shy, Maderges Vincent is the
type of child who greets strangers by running to hide.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, the nine-year-old is so bright, energetic and
giggly with girlfriends she's usually able to fool the casual
observer. But only for a little while.
</P>
<P>
   Then it becomes apparent. She has no arms.
</P>
<P>
   Born here, in the hemisphere's poorest country, where many
handicapped children are effectively written off at birth, Maderges
was abandoned by her parents when she was a mere three months old.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for her, she was deposited on the front stoop of the
Ecole Saint Vincent Pour Enfants Handicapes, creole for St.
Vincent's School for Handicapped Children.
</P>
<P>
   It's the only place in Haiti designed to care for disabled young
people, be they blind, deaf or, like Maderges, missing limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1945 by the Episcopal church, St. Vincent's receives
little money from either the Haitian or American governments.
Rather almost all of the center's money comes from private
donations, mostly from the United States. Its success is proof of
what can be accomplished in Haiti when individuals take matters
into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   With a relatively meager budget, St. Vincent's has a staff of
130 -- including scores of volunteer doctors and teachers from the
United States, Haiti, and Canada -- that serve nearly 400 kids that
attend the school. About 248 children live there.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent are blind. Another 20 percent are deaf. Many of
the rest are missing limbs.
</P>
<P>
   It houses Haiti's only shop for the design and manufacture of
prosthetics, which is staffed by deaf workers, and fashions some
15-20 plastic arms and legs a month -- which helps support the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Little Maderges seems to get along just fine without such
things.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime, the dexterous child props her feet up on the
table, just like she would elbows. She gestures with her feet when
she talks. She eats with a fork that dangles, incongruously,
between her toes. She also uses her feet to write and brush her
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   When she's bored, she rests her chin on the bottom of her foot
as if it were the palm of her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Her lack of arms would seem to be an almost-paralyzing
challenge, yet she seems strangely competent.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, she has friends who understand her disability
because they, too, are disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maderges has no parents, so we're her family now and we've
taken good care of her, because who else was going to do it?'' said
Frantz Casseus(CQ), the school's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach these children to eat by themselves and dress by
themselves,'' he said. ``We stress that they can live normal lives
despite their disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   By stressing self-reliance, the center gets results in a country
where almost nothing else seems to work.
</P>
<P>
   Here, there is no money for ``social services,'' and prejudice
against the physically disabled runs rampant -- so much so that the
handicapped are generally left to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Haiti are so poor, and they have their own
overwhelming problems to deal with, so they don't have a lot of
time or compassion for handicapped people,'' said Joseph Jean Paul,
40, who helps care for the children at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Born with no limbs, he came to live at the center when he was
three.
</P>
<P>
   St. Vincent's is located in the middle of a noisy downtown
street just a short walk from Haitian President Rene Preval's
gleaming white palace.
</P>
<P>
   The three-story motel-like structure is a nondescript one, built
around a tiny pool that hasn't seen water in three years and a
concrete play area where only a metal teeter-totter sits rusting.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity is available for only four to six hours a day. The
dormitory rooms are lined with simple bunk beds, and contain few
toys or decorations. The physical therapy room is equally sparse,
although volunteers make due exercising the students with giant
rubber balls and old metal tricycles.
</P>
<P>
   What the center lacks in material resources, however, it makes
up for in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   A cacophony of music swells in the air daily here, as learning
to play a musical instrument is perhaps the biggest part of a
child's education here.
</P>
<P>
   In one dimly lit room, a group of blind children sitting around
a table can be heard practicing ``Top of the World,'' by The
Carpenters on handbells, accompanied by an out-of-tune piano. In
another, St. Vincent's 30-member orchestra may be tuning up for
practice, in preparation for a planned fund-raising concert in the
United States next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music gives these kids real confidence in themselves,''
Casseus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we did our first concert here in Haiti and people
were stunned,'' he added. ``They had no idea handicapped children
could perform so beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
