<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-HOLIDAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACADEMY BELLS SUMMON MOGULS AND MAVENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the creme de la few in this company town, the
day of the Academy Awards has long been the unofficial holiday of
Hollywood, that moment each year when the movie business bows
before a 13-and-a-half-inch gold-plated idol named Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise has all the rituals of a spiritual quest, from the
ceremonial procession of stretch limousines to the gnashing of
teeth and rending of designer garments.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hope, the broadcast's longtime host and perennial
non-nominee, once began his monologue by cracking, ``Welcome to the
Academy Awards, or, as it's known at my house, Passover.''
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
has made the holiday official.
</P>
<P>
   It is holding the ceremony for the first time in its 71-year
history on what the bold red-and-blue banners outside the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion on Hope Street proclaim as ``Oscar Sunday,'' in a
bid to win even bigger television viewership for the industry's
single biggest self-advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   The academy's full logo for this year's broadcast on ABC,
plastered at bus stops around town, is ``SUNDAY AT THE OSCARS,''
with each capital ``A'' shaped like a ringing bell, and the Oscar
statuette swinging inside it like a clapper.
</P>
<P>
   Its British-born graphic designer, Arnold Schwartzman, insisted
that no religious overtone was intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not the first person to ask me this,'' Schwartzman said
the other day. ``And I have to tell you that when I first came up
with the concept, I worried that it perhaps had religious
connotations, it being a Sunday. I suppose maybe it's a very
British thing, and maybe that's my excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born within the sound of Bow Bells,'' in London, he
said, ``and in Europe, bells are used an enormous amount to
announce things, and in celebration. It was sort of a shorthand.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman did not have to look far to draw his Oscar-clapper.
Only as far as the inside of his unlit fireplace, where he keeps
his own Oscar for producing and directing ``Genocide,'' a 1981
documentary about the Holocaust that he made with Rabbi Marvin Hier
of the Simon Wiesenthal Center here.
</P>
<P>
   For 32 of the last 40 years, the awards have been held on
Monday, long considered a slow night for the movie business, while
Sunday attendance was seen as a vital chunk of the weekend grosses.
But in recent years, the academy and the network came to believe
that by broadcasting the ceremony on Sunday, they could start a
half-hour earlier, at 5:30 p.m., and not risk losing precious East
Coast viewers when the show drags past the midnight hour _ and also
avoid weekday traffic headaches through downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The change has pushed back the round of Saturday and Sunday
parties that traditionally kick off a three-day weekend, and means
that win or lose, many nominees will now be expected to show up on
Monday morning for a full week's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscars on Monday was always a snow day in Hollywood,'' said
Sean Daniel, a producer and former studio executive, recalling how
little got done on a nominal workday when stars and moguls had to
be in black tie and ball gowns by midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it can be a holiday for the rest of America and not just
Los Angeles,'' said Bruce Vilanch, the comedy writer who is
contributing to his 10th Oscar show this year. ``Except for
hairdressers. If you go down Rodeo Drive on Sunday, you'll just see
`The Sound of Blow-Dryers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the hype and hoopla that always attends the show seems
bigger than ever this year. A single studio, Miramax, has spent
something approaching $15 million, a record, to promote its dark
horse nominees, principally ``Shakespeare in Love'' _ more than it
costs to run a typical race for governor and more than many
presidential contenders will raise this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is called show business,'' said Army Archerd, the Variety
columnist who has presided over the red-carpet arrival ceremonies
for 41 years. ``They're all trying to make a buck out of whatever
they can do. There's no question that it's now almost a full week
celebration. It starts a good 72 hours in advance with the various
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   One past nominee who is sitting out this year's festivities
said, on the condition of anonymity: ``I've never seen it so
overblown. I think that the half-life of sensation in this country
has gotten shorter and shorter and the size of sensation needed to
fill the beast has gotten bigger and bigger. This is the fuel, and
it's no different than O.J. or Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, Sunday is easier for the scores of support
industries that serve Oscar. Joey Henriques, manager of West Coast
operations for Dav El Chauffeured Transportation Network, a
limousine company that calls in reinforcements for this weekend
like a fire department borrowing trucks from neighboring towns,
said the lack of Sunday traffic would ``make a huge difference in
just getting people in and out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Marks, director of special projects for Vanity Fair, which
holds perhaps the evening's hottest party, at Morton's restaurant
in West Hollywood, said empty parking lots in the neighborhood
would make it easier to set up satellite television trucks and
other equipment needed for ``what is really sort of a military
operation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   OPTIONAL CUT. STORY CAN END HERE
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sandi Stratton, who lives in Escondido, and her sister Glenice
Churchill, a beautician from Chino, have come to watch celebrity
arrivals from the Oscar bleachers for 30 straight years. They
staked out their spot on the sidewalk last Saturday, so they would
be first in line when the bleachers open at 7 a.m. Sunday, when
other family members will join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to see all those people up close, it's worth
it,'' Ms. Stratton said as she sat in a lawn chair, surrounded by a
cooler, cell phone and a two-person tent, perusing a scrapbook of
snapshots of Shirley Temple Black and Claire Trevor from last year.
``My husband just shakes his head and lets me come. But I think
he's kind of proud of us, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
