<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TATTOO-CHRISTIANS-ART     03-20 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TATTOO-CHRISTIANS-ART-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN MINISTRIES FLOURISHING IN A WORLD OF TATTOOING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ANA, Calif. _ Late one evening in his tattoo shop, Sid
Stankovits bent over the outstretched leg of Jeff Houston, who had
his shoe off and sock turned down. To the buzz of his electric
needle, Stankovits drew a picture on Houston's calf: a kneeling
angel, followed by a cross and Easter lilies.
</P>
<P>
   Tattoos tend to be on the secular side, featuring exotic flowers
or the odd flaming skull. But in Stankovits' shop, and on his own
skin, there are designs with a difference. Yes, he has one tattoo
that says ``Sid'' and another of a crouching panther. But there is
also a portrait of Jesus, a cross and a pair of praying hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a job, but our lives are a ministry,'' said
Stankovits, 27, proprietor of Sid's Tattoo Parlor, a tidy, brightly
lighted space in a modest strip mall in this city south of Los
Angeles. ``We're totally blessed that we can bring our ministries
into our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The three men who work at Sid's are born-again Christians. So
too are many of their young customers, who include Christian rock
musicians, as well as others like 20-year-old Nick Crocker, whose
left arm is marked by a banner proclaiming, ``1 Thess. 5:17,'' the
biblical verse in which the Apostle Paul says, ``Pray without
ceasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Three academic researchers who have studied Sid's have discerned
a trend emerging, at least on the West Coast. They wrote a
scholarly paper titled, ``Marked for Jesus: Sacred Tattooing Among
a `New Generation' of Evangelicals.''
</P>
<P>
   In it the three _ Donald E. Miller, a professor of religion at
the University of Southern California, Richard W. Flory, an
associate professor of sociology at Biola University, and Lori
Jensen, a doctoral student at Southern California _ say that ``for
a small but growing subculture within evangelical Christianity,
religious tattooing is becoming an increasingly legitimate
expression of individuality, identity and faith.''
</P>
<P>
   No one claims to know how widespread the practice is, although
Ms. Jensen said she knew people who had been tattooists, became
born-again Christians and then ``stayed in the profession.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ms. Jensen, 24, displayed a photograph of a
tattoo on her back, and said her tattoos included a cross, floral
design and the phrases ``Approved unto God'' and ``II Tim. 2:15.''
The phrases were references to a verse in St. Paul's Second Letter
to Timothy: ``Do your best to present yourself to God as one
approved by him, a worker who has no need to be ashamed, rightly
explaining the word of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like studying the Bible a lot,'' Ms. Jensen said, ``so that
verse has a lot of significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Stankovits, who opened his shop in 1996, became born again by
accepting Jesus as his personal savior before he became a
tattooist. He is related to an important figure in evangelical
Protestantism, having married a granddaughter of the Rev. Chuck
Smith, pastor of Calvary Chapel in nearby Costa Mesa. By reaching
out to hippies around 1970, Smith became a leading figure in what
many called the ``Jesus Movement.'' Calvary Chapel grew into a
church with thousands of members and spawned a movement with
hundreds of congregations.
</P>
<P>
   Until she went back to school, Stankovits' wife, Jennifer, 21,
also worked at Sid's. On a visit, she displayed a tattoo on her
forearm of a cross rising above ocean waves beneath the motto,
``Rock of Ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, 27, who got the angel tattoo, goes with his wife to
Smith's church. He chose his tattoo design, he said, because it
also adorned his father's headstone.
</P>
<P>
   Several people at Sid's said a tattoo allowed its bearer to
``witness,'' or share a message of faith.
</P>
<P>
   That is how Rob Silva, 32, became born again. A professional
tattooist, he became curious when a friend showed him a religious
tattoo. Nowadays, Silva works with Stankovits at Sid's, where his
work station has a sticker that says, ``I'm the Christian that
Satan warned you about.'' On the wall behind him are photos of
Christian rock bands, many of them autographed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tattoo a lot of Christian bands,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   One customer on a recent afternoon was Robert Goodwin, the
29-year-old bass player with Headnoise, a Christian punk band, on
whose arm Silva drew a portrait of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious reason is Christ is my savior and my body is a
testimony of him,'' Goodwin said. ``A lot of people will ask
questions about the tattoos, and I'll get an opportunity to share
my faith.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Goodwin has found Sid's to be an oasis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before a shop like this,'' he said, ``we had to go to shops
where people were cussing, smoking, doing drugs. A whole lot of bad
things were going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Stankovits, who leads a Friday evening Bible study in a
storefront close by, said a few customers had been converted as a
result of conversations in the shop. But he, Silva and the shop's
other tattooist, 20-year-old Eric Jones, said they did not try to
talk about religious faith to anyone who did not want to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, about 40 percent of the tattoos they do are purely
secular designs, like people's names, animals and the sort of
modest pinup girls that one might have seen in an earlier era. One
recent evening, Stankovits worked on a full ``sleeve,'' an
arm-length tattoo, of a Japanese dragon, on a young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what so cool about tattooing,'' Stankovits said. ``It's
so individualized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
