<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, March 21, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Susan Leh at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-BEE-MAN (Los Angeles) _ John Hurley is on the front line of
Los Angeles County's war on killer bees, a war that just this past
week extended to Calabasas, north of Los Angeles. Hurley was suited
up in his white protective coveralls, rubber boots, gloves that
reach to the elbow, and a sort of pith helmet with a fine mesh veil
hanging all around from the brim. His mission: to find out if yet
another Los Angeles County neighborhood has been colonized by
dangerous Africanized honey bees. By Douglas Haberman. (Will move
in the ``n'' California news file and ``a'' national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-MONEY (Los Angeles) _ A lot is at stake on Oscar night.
Winning an Academy Award, for one. But one winner is assured every
year: the economy of Los Angeles. The Oscars are a yearly bonanza
for the proprietors of restaurants, limousine services and floral
shops. By Marla Matzer. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file and ``a'' national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
