</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-TOBACCO-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECHOES OF TOBACCO BATTLE IN GUN LAWSUITS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill., Fla., La., Conn., S.D.)   (jw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The battle lines look familiar. On one side are
public officials who are frustrated because they have been unable
to get laws passed regulating an industry that makes a dangerous
product. Egged on by trial lawyers, the officials have sued the
industry to try to win in court what they cannot win in the
political arena.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the companies in the besieged industry have
banded together and pooled their money to fight the lawsuits and
pay for extensive lobbying and advertising campaigns that they hope
will protect their political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   For years, these were the competing forces in the tobacco wars.
That issue is more or less settled. Now it is the gun manufacturers
who are being attacked in court and who are mobilizing to defend
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Five cities _ Atlanta, Chicago, Miami, New Orleans and
Bridgeport, Conn. _ have sued gun manufacturers and their trade
associations seeking reimbursement for what they say are the
millions of dollars they must spend each year in their police
departments and hospitals because of gun violence. Many other
cities are considering similar lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The suits are similar to the ones brought by more than 40 state
attorneys general against the tobacco companies, for the money the
states said they spent to treat people with smoking-related
illnesses. After several years of fighting, the tobacco companies
agreed this year to pay the states $246 billion over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the cigarette makers, the companies that make firearms _
including such familiar names as Colt's Manufacturing Co., the
Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp. and Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Co. _ had no experience
working together for common causes. But now they have formed an
umbrella group called the Hunting and Shooting Sports Heritage Fund
to fight the legal attack. They have been joined by many companies
that make products like camping equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Each member has vowed to contribute 1 percent of its sales.
Robert Delfay, the director of the fund, said he hoped to raise an
annual budget as large as $20 million for litigation expenses,
lobbying and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   If all 1,400 companies that had exhibits at the industry's
annual Shot Show in Atlanta last month joined, Delfay said, the
budget could be as large as $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the National Rifle Association, with its 3 million
dues-paying members, has often gone a separate way from the
manufacturers. But it, too, feels threatened by the lawsuits, and
the association has committed its formidable lobbying strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their customers are our members,'' said James Baker, the NRA's
chief lobbyist. ``If they are driven out of business, it certainly
limits the sources and affects the prices of products our
membership buys.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the NRA's lobbying, a law was enacted in
Georgia this winter outlawing suits by the cities against the gun
makers. A similar measure has been approved by the South Dakota
Legislature and is expected to be signed by Republican Gov. William
Janklow next week. Baker said there was a good chance that bills
along these lines would become law this year in more than a dozen
other states, mostly in the South and West.
</P>
<P>
   A bill prohibiting the suits has also been introduced in
Congress by Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., who is on the NRA board. This
bill stands little chance.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce and other business organizations
are also backing the gun makers, just as they did the cigarette
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started with tobacco,'' said Jim Wootton, director of the
chamber's Institute for Legal Reform, an organization formed to
combat trial lawyers. ``Now it's guns. This can be used against any
industry.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert Ricker, the new executive director of the American
Shooting Sports Council, a trade association that represents gun
dealers and distributors, said the firearms industry had learned
from the tobacco industry that ``the surest way to win these kinds
of battles is to form coalitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same trial lawyers who brought suits against tobacco
companies are involved in the lawsuits against the gun
manufacturers. Most of them are part of the Castano Group, a
coalition of 65 law firms formed in 1994 to finance the case of
Peter Castano, a lawyer who died of lung cancer, and to fashion a
nationwide class-action lawsuit against the cigarette industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers from this group are representing New Orleans in its suit
and are consulting with other cities.
</P>
<P>
   The cities' arguments in their lawsuits are similar to those the
attorneys general made against the tobacco industry: The gun makers
failed to make safe products and, just as the tobacco companies
were accused of marketing cigarettes to minors, the gun industry
markets its product to criminals.
</P>
<P>
   But the cities face hurdles that did not exist in the tobacco
cases. Unlike cigarettes, which can be deadly when used as the
manufacturers intended, guns have safe and proper uses like hunting
and target shooting. Moreover, there is scant evidence of corporate
deception the way there was with the cigarette makers, and no
whistle-blower has emerged in the arms industry.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the gun makers, with annual sales in this
country of about $1.5 billion, do not have the deep pockets of the
cigarette companies, which have sales of $45 billion. This could
discourage trial lawyers who make their money from a percentage of
the damages they win.
</P>
<P>
   The suits are not likely to go to trial anytime soon. First, the
question of whether the states have the constitutional authority to
block lawsuits by the cities may need to be answered, and it could
take the Supreme Court to resolve the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies sought from the beginning to settle their
cases out of court. But spurred on by the hard-line approach of the
National Rifle Association, the gun makers, at least for the time
being, say they are confident they can win in court and have no
interest in settlements.
</P>
<P>
   This issue broke into the open last month when Richard Feldman,
Ricker's predecessor as director of the American Shooting Sports
Council, was forced to resign. Feldman, who was traveling in Europe
this week and could not be reached, had been having quiet
discussions with some of the lawyers about settling lawsuits. Those
in the industry who demanded his ouster said he was too eager to
compromise with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we'll have to litigate these things to
judgment,'' said John Coale, a lawyer who was involved with the
Castano group and who now represents New Orleans in its case
against the gun makers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
