<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COHEN-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      03-20 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COHEN-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWO FOR AMERICA' BEAT THE DRUMS FOR THE MILITARY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind., Mass., Minn.)  By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among the defense secretaries of the last half
century whose pictures on magazine covers decorate a drab corridor
of the Pentagon, one stands out. It is not George Marshall, the
``Man of Crisis'' on a 1950 U.S. News &AMP; World Report, or Caspar W.
Weinberger, who wonders ``How to Spend a Trillion'' on a 1981 Time
cover.
</P>
<P>
   It is William S. Cohen, the current secretary of defense, who
shares the front of Parade magazine with his wife, Janet Langhart
Cohen, under the headline, ``Two For America.''
</P>
<P>
   That portrait is not just another example of Cohen's famous
sentimentality. (True, the former Republican senator, who married
three years ago on Valentine's Day, has written, among other
things, an ode to the F-15 fighter jet.) The headline is an apt
description of a rare public relations campaign by the husband-wife
Cohen team. With public appearances, musical events and Mrs.
Cohen's new weekly television show broadcast to armed forces bases
around the globe, the Cohens are on a mission to bridge the gap
between the civilian and military cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cohen has undertaken a role that is almost unheard for a
Cabinet spouse, even one known as the first lady of the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   But for Janet Cohen, 56, it is just the latest interesting twist
in a 30-year television career, though the first time she has
worked free.
</P>
<P>
   While courts the civilian world, beating the drum for increasing
military pay as well as the military budget, Janet Cohen acts as a
one-woman morale booster for the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   With all the high-voltage emotion that was her professional
trademark as anchor, correspondent and talk show host at ABC, NBC,
CBS and Black Entertainment Network, she tells the troops they are
``awesome,'' that the country appreciates their hard work and that
they should keep at it.
</P>
<P>
   Think part Eleanor Roosevelt, part Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission is to support Bill,'' Mrs. Cohen said in an
interview last week. ``He's the passion of my life, and it's
impassioned me about our military people.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated in her penthouse apartment with wraparound balconies
overlooking Pennsylvania Avenue, she said: ``My role just evolved
on my travels with Bill where we talked about the need for the
country to reconnect with the military, to let them know the fine
job they're doing, how we're all in awe of our military.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months she has started her weekly television
series, ``Special Assignment,'' for the armed services
international broadcast network, in which she interviews civilian
and military leaders. Her first subject was President Clinton,
aboard Air Force One, and she has lined up Tom Cruise, Hollywood's
``Top Gun,'' and Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, for later
programs.
</P>
<P>
   With her husband, she recently was the host of a ``Pentagon
Pops'' musical salute to the military performed by military
musicians at Constitution Hall. At the event, Cohen said the show
came about because ``Janet simply asked, `Why not the best music
for the best military in the world?' ''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the month she will have her own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Her volunteer efforts are not just a vanity project, Pentagon
officials say, but a high-profile effort to bolster recruiting
goals that have proved out of reach despite plans to raise military
pay by more than 4 percent, with bonuses of about 10 percent, and a
national nostalgia for the patriotism of World War II started by
the movie ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy when we're competing against one of the most
vibrant economies in history,'' Mrs. Cohen said. ``And that means
holding onto the families, too, by giving them good housing, pay,
retirement, medical care and education for their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   While this is the basic boilerplate message of her husband, the
same points, when made in front of the troops by Mrs. Cohen, a
former model and one of the first African-American women to break
into national television, seem more like entertainment, and that
has earned her high marks in some serious circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising the esprit de corps is critical, which is why what
she's doing is so worthwhile,'' said Michael O'Hanlon, a military
analyst at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Kati Marton, who is writing a book on ``First Couples'' and is
part of a power couple with Richard C. Holbrooke, whose nomination
as ambassador to the United Nations is pending in Congress, said of
Mrs. Cohen: ``What she's doing is very much in keeping with that
activist engaged role that Eleanor Roosevelt pioneered. She is
essential to her husband's well-being and his job, and she is
taking a full role in both.``
</P>
<P>
   Reared in the housing projects of Indianapolis by a single
mother, she studied at Butler University and Indiana University but
quit when she won a $500 beauty contest in Chicago. That led to
modeling jobs in Chicago and then her big break as the weather
woman on a Chicago television station.
</P>
<P>
   After that she was the host of the morning program ``Indy
Today'' on an Indianapolis television station, then moved to a
network affiliate in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very, very lucky,'' Mrs. Cohen says. She had been
married twice when she began dating Cohen, who was then a senator
from Maine and who also was divorced.
</P>
<P>
   They married shortly before Cohen, now 58, was named defense
secretary in late 1996. She is now running Langhart Communications,
teaching corporate executives how to handle the news media. But she
also has traveled with her husband to Spain and Bulgaria, to the
Middle East and South Korea. Whenever she visits the troops, she
mingles with them, eliciting the whoops and yells normally
associated with movie stars, not politicians' wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the national anthem, you go to the bases, and it has
a different feeling,'' she said. ``I get very emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   The most ambitious of Mrs. Cohen's projects is the Special
Assignment segments for the 156 stations of the armed forces
international network overseas and replayed on videotape on the
bases in the United States. She started the series this month with
her 30-minute interview of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Her toughest question was, `Sir, with all due respect, you
offered the highest budget proposal in a long time _ ever. But is
it enough when you talk about the things we're asking of them to
do?''
</P>
<P>
   After agreeing that nothing was too good for the military, the
president was steered by Mrs. Cohen to describe the idealism of the
troops who helped the Central American victims of Hurricane Mitch
and served as peacekeepers in Bosnia, as well as their sacrifices.
He needed little prompting.
</P>
<P>
   In her weekly interviews, Mrs. Cohen says she will be mining
that strain of idealism as she invites members of the armed
services, celebrities, business leaders and politicians to make
what she calls ``testimonials on air'' for the military.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen sees nothing but good in her efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She touches people,'' he said in an interview. ``She can
infuse them with a sense of real spirit. As to the difference she
is making, out in the field, every single leader that I meet, the
first question is, `Why didn't you bring your wife?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
