<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, March 21, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Two disturbances in separate branches of the jet stream will
begin to merge along the East Coast on Sunday. Low pressure moving
through the Southeast will have an ample supply of moisture while a
cold front pushing through the Great Lakes will draw chilly air
southward from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The two areas of unsettled weather will join over the Northeast
on Sunday night as wet snow begins to accumulate in the northern
Appalachians, specifically in western New York and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The day will dawn bright and crisp in New England, but high
pressure will slide offshore by midday allowing clouds to quickly
increase. A cold rain will soak parts of the middle Atlantic region
as chilly air is wedged along the east slopes of the central
Appalachians. Showers and a few thunderstorms will accompany a cold
front along the southeast coast. However, much of Florida will stay
dry.
</P>
<P>
   A swath of light snow will coat upper Michigan and northern
Wisconsin. Snow showers will extend southward around Lake Michigan.
Winds will increase to gale force over Lake Superior. A few showers
of rain and wet snow will develop in the eastern Lakes by
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure extending from Manitoba to Texas will promote dry
and seasonable conditions in the Plains and eastern Rockies. A
complex disturbance will produce showers from Idaho to the northern
Sierra with snow above 5,500 feet. The Northwest will not be as
warm or bright, as showers move north. Clouds will persist along
the California shoreline, but the deserts of the Southwest will see
sunshine with seasonably mild air.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Equinoctial Storms
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of spring Saturday night was an astronomical event,
not a meteorological one, but ancient mariners believed that the
time of equinoxes was likely to be accompanied by severe storms.
However, there is no meteorological basis for these so-called
equinoctial storms. Strong storms are common near the equinoxes
since tempests derive their energy from contrasting air masses.
Fierce storms are no more likely at the equinox than on other days
at the seasons' change. Coincidentally, this year a fierce storm
was pounding southern Alaska at the equinox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
