<P>
   HAITI-FAILURE _ PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ In the fall of 1994,
President Bill Clinton confounded his critics by successfully using
20,000 U.S.-led forces to overthrow a brutal military regime here
and give democracy a second chance. Almost no blood was shed. A
triumph in foreign policy was declared. But today, after nearly
five years of pouring more than $2.2 billion of American taxpayers'
money into this tiny island nation, there is little to feel
triumphant about. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-FLOPS _ PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ The history of U.S. aid in
Haiti is peppered with some pretty big flops. But none is more
notorious than the pig fiasco. It started in the late 1970s, when
the United States found swine fever among pigs in the Dominican
Republic, which shares the same island as Haiti. The U.S. Agency
for International Development came up in 1982 with what sounded
like a good plan to ward off the fever in Haiti: Haiti's 1.3
million Creole pigs were destroyed, and were to be replaced with
American stock better suited for export. (The Creole word for
``pig'' and ``bank'' is the same.) Formerly, poor Haitians could
buy a piglet that could eat garbage and scrub and survive in the
heat with little water. When money was needed for a crisis or a
wedding, the ``bank'' could be cashed in. After AID launched its
program, and the Creole pigs were slaughtered, the average Haitian
couldn't afford to buy American pigs or pay for the
vitamin-enriched feed they needed. The result was that they were
worse off than ever before. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-DATA _ Data on Haiti for charts and graphics. Quotes from
lawmakers on U.S. Haiti policy and political situation. (Emling,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Package has moved.
</P>
