<P>
   MEDICARE _ WASHINGTON _ Here's what was supposed to happen: A
blue-ribbon panel of policy experts and key lawmakers would
redesign Medicare so that it would remain solvent into the old age
of today's Baby Boomers and beyond, and Congress and the White
House would embrace the reforms. Here's what happened: The panel
was so deeply divided over policy differences that it failed to
adopt a plan, and both sides ascribed partisan politicial motives
for its failure. Here's what's going to happen: The failed plan's
main sponsors will introduce it as legislation in Congress, where
it faces a doubtful future. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   REMIS-SPYCASE _ A folo on the REMIS espionage case, which is
especially intersting in light of the current flap over the Chinese
getting information on U.S. nuclear technology. The deputy
commander of the Air Force has called the REMIS breach ``the most
serious nonviolent crime commited in the last 20 to 30 years and
there are no laws that cover this type of crime.'' We know more now
about the REMIS system, and how it details the Air Force's combat
readiness. The guy who designed the Safeguyard system called it the
worst security breach he's ever seen. Zhangyi ``Steven'' Liu, who
pleaded guilty to illegally accessing the critical U.S. Air Force
database, and was sentenced, was allowed to withdraw his plea, and
his trial is skedded for March 29. (Hills, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-STUDENTS _ As many as 45 Nobel laureates are slated to
meet and eat with science students from Georgia and other states at
a Saturday luncheon kickoff for the American Physical Society's
annual meeting in Atlanta. We explore the conversations at the
tables and in the hallways. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   VALDEZ-ANNIVERSARY _ Ten years after the Exxon Valdez ran
aground in Prince William Sound, the once-pristine harbor is now
starting to show signs of recovery. A look at the world's worst oil
spill and its legacy. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIALTEEPEN-COLUMN _ I had thought we'd be electing a
president of the United States next year, not the pastor of the
United States, but much of the Republican field seems to be running
for a real pulpit, not just the bully one. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ I'm not going out shopping for Y2K. If
whatever is supposed to go down on Jan. 1 does go down, I've got my
leftover supplies from the 1999 hurricane season that ends Dec. 1 _
that is, provided we don't get nailed with a dead-on hurricane as
we did in 1992. Glad we were prepared for that. (Howard Kleinberg
is a columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Are taxes too high? Depends on what
kind of taxes you've got in mind. Take payroll taxes. (Glass, Cox
News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-NEWMOTOWN _ Through the rose colored glasses sitting low
on his nose, Bunmi Junadi is looking out for the rich and fabulous.
That's his job. The bald-headed Nigerian was hired by musical
millionaires Sean ``Puffy'' Combs and Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid as VIP
coordinator for Justin's, their newly opened Buckhead restaurant.
The objects of his pampering are metro Atlanta's black glitterati,
a growing cast of African-American celebrities who are putting down
roots, hanging out their shingles, and searching for the perfect
place to see, and be seen. Long known as a magnet for
nine-to-fivers of all races who move to the metro area from
everywhere, Atlanta has quietly developed a distinctive celebrity
scene as African-American entertainers are decamping from
established glam capitols like Los Angeles and New York. (Harris,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   DETOX-RAWFOOD _ A visit to the Optimum Health Institute, a
nonprofit center for health detoxification that stresses raw foods,
wheatgrass juice and colon therapy. The residential center, based
out of California, runs from $600-700 a week for patients, who may
stay up to three weeks. Some patients just want to detoxify, others
(including some cancer patients) have used the center as an
alternative to mainstream medicine. (Bonnin, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/DETOX-WHEATGRASS _ Sider on wheatgrass juice, the centerpiece
of OHI's detoxification regimen. What is it and how did it gain
such prominence. (Bonnin, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ARTS/ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   The following stories, which moved Wednesday, are a 4-part
series on Lonnie Holley, the Alabama folk artist who has endured
nothing but trouble since he was one of the stars of the Olympic
Arts Festival in 1996. Holley, one of the South's most important
folk artists, has known a world of trouble in his 49 years. But
nothing has prepared him for the random misfortunes that have
bedeviled him like Job over the past couple of years. This is a
story about a man who has struggled against great odds to make his
art and to keep his family together.
</P>
<P>
   All stories MOVED Wednesday. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEHOLLEY-PART1 _ COLUMBIANA, Ala. _ We start with Holley's
arrest, then back up and tell the story of how he got there.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 90.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEHOLLEY-PART2 _ HARPERSVILLE, Va. _ We look at Holley and
his family and their current troubles. Holley has raised five
children by himself, and by all accounts did a great job against
the odds. But in recent years, his kids have had all manner of
problems. And it could get worse. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 58.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEH0LLEY-PART3 _ BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ We look at Holley's
career in the context of the world of folk art. The reasons for
folk artists' struggles are complicated but the results are the
same: renowned, respected artists who wouldn't qualify for an auto
loan. We also look at the efforts of various dealers and do-gooders
to help him and his family. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 50.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEHOLLEY-PART4 _ We sort out the endings, happy and
otherwise. The first good news, it seemed, Holley had gotten in
years was that juvenile authorities had been so impressed with
Holley's 16-year old son Kubra that they took it upon themselves to
nominate him for the Alabama School of Fine Arts, a magnet program
in Birmingham for gifted children from across the state. While
oldest son Ezekial appears headed for prison, and third son A.J.
for juvenile boot camp. And Holley? He'll probably plead guilty to
reduced charges and get probation, and he's finally painting again.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 30.
</P>
