<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST AND FLIGHT ATTENDANTS AVERT STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Nev.)  (jw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Averting a strike minutes after a deadline had passed, America
West Airlines and the union representing its 2,300 flight
attendants reached tentative agreement on a contract early
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the five-year agreement were not released but William
McGlashen, president of the local chapter of the Association of
Flight Attendants, said the deal gave workers higher wages and more
flexible work rules.
</P>
<P>
   The contract must be ratified by a majority of union members,
who rejected a settlement in 1997. But Jeff Zack, a spokesman for
the union, said this agreement was far superior to the earlier one,
because it provided a larger raise and an increase in the hourly
payment that flight attendants receive when they are away from
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we won't have too much trouble getting this thing
passed,'' Zack said.
</P>
<P>
   America West and the union had been trying to agree on a
contract since 1994, when the flight attendants voted to organize.
After a federal mediator declared the two sides at an impasse last
month, the union threatened to stage a crippling series of random
walkouts if there was no settlement by midnight Friday, the end of
a 30-day cooling off period ordered by the mediator.
</P>
<P>
   The airline responded by threatening to fire any attendant who
took part in a selective strike and, if necessary, to shut down its
operations.
</P>
<P>
   A strike at America West, which is the country's ninth-largest
airline and carried less than 3 percent of the domestic industry's
passengers last year, would not have been as disruptive as last
month's 10-day sickout by pilots at American Airlines, the
country's second-largest carrier. But it would have had a major
impact in Phoenix, where America West is based and dominates the
local airport, and in Las Vegas, where it is the second-largest
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The main issue was money. America West's flight attendants are
among the lowest-paid in the industry, earning a maximum of $22,000
a year after 12 years on the job. About two-thirds of its
attendants had reached the top pay grade and had not had a raise
since 1995. Since then, the airline, along with the industry, has
had several years of record profits. In 1998, America West
Holdings, the airline's parent company, earned $108 million on $2
billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company offered to raise the flight attendants' pay an
average of 45 percent and to about double the expense payments over
the life of the contract. Going into the final round of
negotiations last week, the two sides were only $16.5 million
apart. The union demanded more money but the company said that it
could not raise its offer and remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the two sides compromised and both emerged from the
negotiations satisfied, said a spokesman for the National Mediation
Board, which supervised the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   William Franke, America West's chairman and chief executive,
said in a statement, ``The contract, while very difficult to
negotiate, addresses the principal concerns of both parties.'' He
flew to Washington to take part in the final round of negotiations
and announced the agreement at 2 a.m. Saturday at the National
Mediation Board's headquarters with Patricia Friend, the national
president of the flight attendants union.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The deal spares both sides an expensive and risky battle.
Industry analysts had said that a strike would have cost America
West $2 million to $5 million a day. Already the threat of a strike
had hurt the airline because many travel agents booked advanced
tickets on competitors.
</P>
<P>
   For the union, the settlement avoids a legal test of its
controversial threat to stage random walkouts. The tactic is
designed to have the same impact as a full-fledged strike while
allowing most of the flight attendants to keep working.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic was tried only once, in 1993 at Alaska Airlines, and
a federal court judge held that it was wrong for the airline to
fire flight attendants who took part. But Neil Bernstein, who
teaches labor law at Washington University in St. Louis, said that
such employees could be fired under the National Labor Relations
Act. The issue has never been fully tested in court under the
Railway Labor Act, which governs labor issues in the airline
industry.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, America West filed a lawsuit in Arizona asking a
federal judge to rule on whether it could fire attendants who took
part in intermittent strikes. Stephen L. Johnson, an America West
spokesman, said, ``If the contract is ratified, the lawsuit will be
withdrawn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
