<SLUG> BC-D.C.-COLLEGE-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL OFFERS COLLEGE OPTIONS TO STUDENTS IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: D.C., Md., Va.)  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Legislation has been introduced in Congress that
would expand academic options for high school graduates from the
District of Columbia by substantially reducing their tuition fees
at state colleges nationwide and by providing about $2 million for
the local public university.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, written by Rep. Thomas Davis III, R-Va., chairman of a
House subcommittee on the District of Columbia, would allow
students from Washington to qualify for the tuition rate paid by
state residents at public colleges and universities throughout the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who has eight co-sponsors for the bill, submitted the
measure to the House on March 4, calling it ``landmark bipartisan
legislation,'' which should move quickly through both houses. The
bill has yet to be introduced in the Senate. It is supported by the
Clinton administration, which included about $15 million for the
program in its budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the bill would be of special help to district
students ``who study hard and work hard and find out-of-state
public colleges out of reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony Williams, in consultation with the secretary of
education, would administer the program. The bill also provides for
contributions from private donors.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than a dozen private colleges or universities in
Washington, and highly regarded state universities in adjoining
Maryland and Virginia, but the city, which has about 500,000
residents, has only one public university, the University of the
District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of students living in the city, who now pay
out-of-state tuition for attending any public college other than
UDC, could see their tuition at public universities cut by more
than 50 percent. Students from the district paid $7 million in
out-of-state tuition fees last year.
</P>
<P>
   The program would pay the difference between out-of-state and
in-state tuition costs for district students attending state
colleges, so there would be no cost to the universities or colleges
under the program. Students from the district would continue to
have to meet admission requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Arrington Booker, guidance counselor and college
coordinator for Woodrow Wilson High School in northwest Washington,
said that students were excited about the new options in the
proposed legislation and the possibility of experiencing other
regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seniors come into my office and add state schools to
their college lists after applications had been sent out,'' Booker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, called The District of Columbia College Access Act,
would also make UDC eligible for annual federal grants by including
it among the colleges designated a historically black college or
university.
</P>
<P>
   But many students still believe that the college is neglected by
the city. The university was forced to shut down for three months
in 1996 because of a lack of money to pay staff members. The school
lost nearly half of its students in the city's budget crisis from
1996 to 1998, when enrollment fell to 4,700 from more than 9,000,
but enrollment rose to 5,284 this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Eleanor Holmes Norton, the district's nonvoting delegate in the
House and a co-sponsor of the measure, pressed lawmakers to include
money for the university in the legislation as part of her campaign
for assuring D.C. residents equal status with those who live in the
50 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents and students should not have to move out of town to
attain public higher education options that they can afford for
their children,'' Ms. Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsors hope it will be an incentive for remaining
in a city that has lost tens of thousands of residents to the
suburbs in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``One-size-fits-all does not work in higher education,'' Ms.
Norton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
