<HEADER>
A7923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES21-COX     03-20 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans still keeping up with Chipper Jones
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Phyllis Jobe of Jonesboro, Ga., was an
usher at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium when she first became a
Chipper Jones fan. From her place in the stands, she would beam at
the young third baseman with the squeaky-clean image, the wide
smile and the hero's persona and joke with her friends that she'd
like her daughter to marry him.
</P>
<P>
   That was before she knew he was married, long before she knew he
was separated. Like thousands this winter, she followed Jones'
offseason saga, when he admitted publicly to having extramarital
affairs, fathering a child out of wedlock and not being the
All-American guy that people thought he was.
</P>
<P>
   When Jobe arrived at the Braves' spring-training complex in
Disney last week, she still looked for Jones. She cheered for him,
as a player, because she's still a fan.
</P>
<P>
   And as a player, Jones hasn't disappointed. His spring
performance has, in fact, been incredible. Going into the weekend,
he was leading the Grapefruit League with a .611 batting average, a
1.222 slugging percentage, and a .750 on-base percentage. He's had
some excellent defensive plays at third base and has hit some
towering home runs, including one off the top of the scoreboard in
left-center at the Braves ballpark at Disney's Wide World of
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's still a fantastic ballplayer, and at least he
didn't lie about (his affairs),'' Jobe said. ``Of course, I guess
it's pretty hard to lie when you have a baby. But it hasn't really
decreased my thoughts of how he is as a player. But I was so
excited to see the kids really admire him so much, and that's kind
of bad. That's kind of bad for the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobe's thoughts seem to typify the reaction Jones has received
from fans in spring training. When he arrives at the ballpark in
the morning, he is greeted by autograph-seekers at the players'
entrance. He still goes about his work in batting practice to a
high-pitched chorus of ``Chipper!'' His introduction still draws
the loudest cheers. In games, he's not hearing boos.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction has been much better than Jones had envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept picturing something sad,'' Jones said. ``Every time I
think about fans booing a certain player, I think of Boston fans
booing Mo Vaughn. How can you boo Mo Vaughn? The guy's an MVP every
year. He's out in the community helping kids like no one else on
that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones figured that if Vaughn could get booed during his contract
negotiation with the Red Sox, then he would be an easy target. So
far he hasn't been.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's a big sigh of relief,'' Jones said. ``Granted,
these fans here aren't the fans that are going to be watching us in
Atlanta, but hopefully the reaction will be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he gained confidence about his image after visiting
students at Troup County High School in LaGrange in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked out, everybody was great and supportive,'' Jones
said. ``Everybody in there knows I messed up. I even addressed it
during my talk: `Look I made a huge mistake in my life, but I'm
dealing with it and I'm moving on.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It really made me feel kind of to the point that it never even
happened, that nothing had changed, that everybody's attitude was
still the same. They still looked up to me, and they respected me
for the player I am and for the entertainment I help provide. . . .
It's not going to affect whether or not I play an All-Star third
base. I feel that I'm always going to play that caliber of baseball
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has been a good escape, Jones said, and he credits
personal problems for this spring's hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear was that I'd come down here this spring, not
play that well, and people would think that it was affecting me,''
Jones said. ``I didn't want that to happen. So I was more intense
in my workouts this offseason and more intense down here. And
things have worked out. Hopefully, that will dispel anybody's fears
of what has happened affecting the way I play.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he was surprised that he managed to keep all but one
of his endorsement deals. Wendy's dropped him within a month or so
of his public admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd lose them all,'' Jones said. ``It really kind of
fired me up when people came back to me and said, `Hey, we're
sticking with you. You've gone through a tough time. Yeah, you made
a mistake, and you're struggling, but we've got faith in you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jones knows he'll face a tougher test when he returns to Turner
Field for exhibition games on April 2-3 and Opening Day on April 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (reaction) is mixed or dominantly one way or the other,
it's not going to crush me,'' he said. ``I feel that if I go out
there, and I'm the same player I've always been, and I still
provide the same excitement out there, (the problems) eventually
will get behind me. People may not forget about it, but maybe
they'll look past it. I'm not a bad guy by any means. I just messed
up. I've asked for people's forgiveness. If they give it to me,
great _ `I love you.' If they don't, I understand.''
</P>
<P>
   For fans like Jobe, that might be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I'll never forgive him, because I don't have
anything to forgive,'' Jobe said. ``But I really looked up to him a
lot as a player, especially for our young children. But maybe
that's just life. Maybe that's just what children need, is to know
that people are not perfect. And you shouldn't hold them in such
high esteem because we're all human and we all make mistakes. Some
mistakes we have to pay for longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
