<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUCCI-LAWSUIT-610&AMP;ADD     03-20 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-LAWSUIT-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTCH COURT TO HEAR FIGHT FOR CONTROL OVER GUCCI 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The high-stakes, high-drama struggle for control of
Italy's fabled Gucci fashion house goes back to a Dutch court on
Monday, after the French luxury-goods maker LVMH Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton SA said it would seek to invalidate a deal Gucci
struck on Friday to sell 40 percent of its shares to one of
France's wealthiest takeover investors.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH, which makes Louis Vuitton leather goods and Moet &AMP; Chandon
champagne, will argue that the deal is meant to foil the designs of
LVMH to seize control of Gucci. In the French company's view, this
violates a ruling this month by the Dutch court that the two
companies negotiate a compromise in their 2-month-old struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between Gucci, the fashion house founded by the
Florentine family of the same name, and LVMH, the creation of
Bernard Arnault, one of France's most successful industrialists, is
outdoing dramatic opera for its plot twists, intrigues and
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   It took a fresh turn on Friday, when Gucci said Francois
Pinault, a self-made billionaire whose mixed holdings include the
French Au Printemps department-store chain and London's famed
Christie's auction house, had agreed to pay $3 billion for a 40
percent stake in Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci said Pinault had also bought for $1 billion the French
drug maker Sanofi's beauty-products brands, including Yves Saint
Laurent, Krizia and Kenzo, with an eye to bringing them into Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci's surprise move was clearly intended to enlist Pinault as
a white knight to foil Arnault. The latter Frenchman has been
seeking control of Gucci since January, when he announced that he
had assembled a 34.4 percent stake in the Italian fashion house.
Gucci is potentially the second-biggest global luxury-goods group
after LVMH.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the luxury-goods business, the struggle has been
indicative of the way the business will change in the next few
years, as hot niche brands are absorbed by big groups that can
compete around the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Arnault initially responded by doing something he had
previously said he would never do, making a bid for all outstanding
Gucci shares, at a cost of about $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The bid not only exposed Arnault's weakness _ on Thursday he had
said a full bid for Gucci was ``too risky'' _ but also confronted
Gucci with a difficult choice. On Sunday, the day before the court
hearing, Gucci's board is meeting the company's chief executive,
Domenico De Sole, to discuss options.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, they are several. Gucci can reaffirm the deal with
Pinault, or overturn it and accept Arnault's counteroffer. That
move could, however, provoke a damage suit from Pinault. The board
could also postpone a decision until the court in the Netherlands,
where Gucci is incorporated, meets on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Any decision the board takes would ultimately be subject to
shareholder approval. Among the shareholders are De Sole and Tom
Ford, Gucci's creative director, and they clearly favor Pinault's
offer, considering that of Arnault a possible ruse. Although
Arnault has bid $85 a share, well beyond Pinault's $75-per-share
bid, Arnault's offer was made contingent on Gucci's backing out of
the deal with Pinault.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Gode, a close associate of Arnault, accused De Sole of
duplicity.
</P>
<P>
   While De Sole claimed to resist LVMH's advances in order to save
Gucci from French hands, he negotiated at the same time to give
control of Gucci to a competing French group. And while De Sole had
in the past accused LVMH of bad faith for refusing to make a full
bid, it now agreed to Pinault's taking control with only 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He speaks with a double tongue,'' Gode said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The dramatic aspects of the struggle are rooted in the
personalities of the two main antagonists. Both Pinault and Arnault
are keen art collectors and connoisseurs of great wines; they also
share the reputation of being savvy but ruthless businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the similarities pale. Arnault is a graduate of the
prestigious Ecole Polytechnique and learned his financial craft
from Antoine Bernheim, of the influential Lazard Freres investment
bank; Pinault is a high school dropout who parlayed his father's
lumber business into what is by some estimates France's largest
private fortune, worth $7 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
