<HEADER>
A7937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-EISENBUD-NYT &LR;      03-20 0318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EISENBUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULE EISENBUD, PSYCHIATRIST AND PARAPSYCHOLOGY RESEARCHER, DIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Jule Eisenbud, a psychiatrist, author and researcher best
known for his interest in parapsychology, died on March 10 in
Denver. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenbud did research in many areas of psychiatry,
psychoanalysis, anthropology and hypnosis during his career, but he
came to prominence largely through his book ``The World of Ted
Serios'' (William Morrow &AMP; Co., 1967). In it, he described his work
with Serios, a Chicago bellhop, who claimed to produce
``thoughtographs,'' dream-like images of his thoughts, on film.
</P>
<P>
   The work brought Eisenbud wide public attention and some
ridicule. It was criticized in a review in The New York Times by
H.J. Eysenck, a professor of psychology at the University of London
and the author of a dozen books, including ``Sense and Nonsense in
Psychology.'' Eysenck wrote, ``Dr. Eisenbud seems to have little
notion of what experiments are and less liking for the rigors and
methodological niceties of scientific research.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrice Keane, executive director of the American Society for
Psychical Research in New York, said that Eisenbud's professional
standing helped shield him from the sting of such criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Jule Eisenbud was born in New York on Nov. 20, 1908. He received
bachelor's and medical degrees from Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, he began private practice in psychiatry and
psychoanalysis. In 1950, he moved to Denver with his family, where
he continued his practice and became associate clinical professor
of psychiatry at the University of Colorado Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenbud's wife, Molly, died in 1995. He is survived by two
sons, John and Dr. Eric Eisenbud, and a daughter, Joanna Moldow,
all of Denver, as well as five grandchildren and one
great-grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
