<HEADER>
A7971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-CIVILITY-1ST     03-20 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CIVILITY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-890&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass., N.Y., Wash., Mich., Texas, Calif.)  
 LAWMAKERS GET AWAY FROM CAPITAL FOR LESSON IN BEING NICE (Eds:
Updates with new material.)  
(jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERSHEY, Pa. _ During fights on the House floor, they have
plenty of opportunity to snipe. During committee hearings, they
have ample occasion to seethe.
</P>
<P>
   But in this candy-coated realm of chocolate kisses, members of
Congress had a rare chance this weekend to do something different.
They got to share.
</P>
<P>
   Descending on a rambling lodge and conference center for what
was billed as a three-day course in civility, nearly 200
Republicans and Democrats, some with their spouses and children in
tow, came together to exercise their diplomacy and exorcize their
demons, primarily in small discussion groups that were meant,
according to organizers, to provide ``safe environments'' for the
venting of feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers listened on Friday afternoon to a keynote speech by
John Hume, a Nobel-winning architect of peace in Northern Ireland,
on the theory that anyone who could soothe the tensions there might
be able to do as much for Ways and Means.
</P>
<P>
   They were scheduled Saturday for line dancing at a Family
Country Hoedown, on the theory that if they could kick up their
heels together, then maybe _ just maybe _ they could break the
impasse over Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   These were lofty goals indeed, but not, participants insisted,
beyond all reach.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on Hume's remarks, which alluded to the Northern
Ireland accord, Rep. Richard Neal, D-Mass., said, ``The odds that
he faced getting the Good Friday agreement were clearly more
difficult than the odds we face here.''
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan retreat, from Friday to Sunday, was a reprise of
a similar gathering here two years ago, but lawmakers conceded that
this one came at an even more difficult moment, on the heels of the
impeachment ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence here seemed to signal both a genuine desire for
some degree of reconciliation and a genuine concern about their
everyday estrangement from each other.
</P>
<P>
   As they boarded a chartered train leaving Union Station in
Washington on Friday morning and as they took breaks from their
scheduled activities here Friday and Saturday, they spoke ruefully
of the frenetic pace in Congress these days and the impersonal
atmosphere around Washington, where they said fewer and fewer
lawmakers were anchoring their family and social lives.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Quinn, R-N.Y., said between events that there was an
incalculable benefit to ``getting to know someone over a tuna fish
sandwich and a Pepsi instead of a minimum wage agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But the failure of a majority of House members to come to
Hershey, the self-christened ``sweetest place on earth,''
underlined a feeling among many that all they would get here were
empty calories. Several of them said the event was a futile
charade, more useful for public relations than political harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the point,'' said Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., who
stayed away. In a telephone interview on the eve of the retreat,
McDermott said that if Republicans were really interested in
rapprochement, they would not have been so stingy in awarding
committee assignments to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in some place in the Bible, it says that by your deeds
you shall be known,'' McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
   Following reports earlier this week that many more Republicans
than Democrats would show up, organizers declined Saturday to
provide a list of participants and were hazy about the overall
attendance figure, which they said was almost evenly divided
between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were relegated to the periphery of the conference
center and details of the schedule were kept under wraps, but this
being Congress, there were any number of leaks, revealing an
itinerary rife with items that had an ambiguous connection to
civility and healing.
</P>
<P>
   After a Friday night event at which the actor Sam Waterston
performed his reportedly uncanny imitation of Abraham Lincoln,
early risers could attend an aerobics workout at 6:45 Saturday
morning led by Sandie Knollenberg, the wife of Rep. Joe
Knollenberg, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon was set aside for diversion and relaxation,
with lawmakers and their families choosing among such options as a
journey to Gettysburg, a trip to the chocolate museum, high tea at
the Hotel Hershey and a skating exhibition known as World on Ice.
That was all leading up to the hoedown, where the kind of
iridescent necklaces popular at circuses would be scattered around
the tables as a festive icebreaker. (Two years ago, it was hula
hoops.)
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said that none of this strayed from the retreat's
purpose of fostering greater civility in Congress. A common refrain
was that once a lawmaker had seen a colleague from across the aisle
changing a toddler's diaper, it would be harder for him or her to
summarily demonize the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all is said and done, relationships count,'' said Rep.
James Rogan, R-Calif., who had been among the prosecutors of
President Clinton during his Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan was taking a break from the discussion groups, each
consisting of about 20 to 25 lawmakers and spouses along with a
trained ``facilitator,'' to meet reporters at their request in a
nearby restaurant. He beckoned them into a circular booth too small
to accommodate everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get you all close to me,'' he joked, ``because I'm
missing my group hug for the minute.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although Rogan and other lawmakers who emerged from the
conference center were mum about the specific content of the
dialogues inside, they said that Democrats and Republicans were
sharing grievances, hopes and personal stories in an informal
manner that would be unusual on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Sawyer, D-Ohio, one of the principal organizers of the
retreat, said Saturday afternoon, ``The most compelling thing so
far, given what we have been through in the last year, is how
constructive everything has been.''
</P>
<P>
   That boded well for a wish that Rep. Joseph Crowley, D-N.Y.,
expressed at the start of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that at the end of this weekend,'' he said with a
smile, ``I can lay a big Hershey's kiss on a Republican, preferably
female.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
