<SLUG> BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE DRAW COULD TURN INTO A KNOCKOUT AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like any title fight, it was supposed to be over
after 12 rounds, but with all the commotion over the debatable draw
between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis, it's as if it were now
scheduled for 12 weeks, if not 12 months or more. That might be how
long its implications will be examined in Washington and in the
Manhattan district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   But if boxing's political and promotional structure eventually
is changed for the better because of the outcry, the debatable draw
will have been worth more to boxing than all the lore of the
Thrilla in Manila or The Long Count.
</P>
<P>
   Unless evidence of criminal bribery in the judging of the
debatable draw is uncovered by the district attorney's office, the
vote for Lewis by the South African judge, the vote for Holyfield
by the American judge and the vote for a draw by the British judge
are no longer relevant. You can't indict an honest opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout its history, boxing has had a wildly unpopular
decision every so often. As long as humans are the judges, it
always will.
</P>
<P>
   The real value of the debatable draw is that it has drawn
attention to the Muhammad Ali Boxing Reform Act, a bill introduced
by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. It was approved unanimously in the
Senate last Oct. 8, but there has been no companion legislation in
the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing's pirates, alias its promoters, notably Don King and Bob
Arum, have known that they can never be accused of breaking any of
boxing's laws because there are virtually no laws.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Ali Act were to become law, boxing promoters and
officials of the worldwide alphabet soup of title-sanctioning
bodies would be subject to jail time and substantial fines.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's key provisions include limiting a promoter's now
virtually limitless option clauses to one year, requiring a
promoter to file a fighter's complete contract rather than a
quickie form, prohibiting a promoter from coercing a fighter to
hire a promoter's relative as a manager, and requiring public
financial disclosure from the alphabet-soup bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Home Box Office, which is just as much a promoter as King or
Arum, has a six-bout contract with Lewis. Did that have any
influence on HBO's supposedly objective commentators' support of
Lewis throughout the debatable draw?
</P>
<P>
   In a New York Senate Committee hearing last Thursday, King
acknowledged that his son, Carl, managed ``several'' fighters. And
for all of King's insistence under oath that ``I stay clear of all
judges,'' he was not interrogated about his relationships,
financially or otherwise, with the World Boxing Council, World
Boxing Association and International Boxing Federation presidents
who appoint judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional boxers and the integrity of the sport,'' McCain
told the committee in a statement, ``would be far better served by
competitive bidding among promoters for major events.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator also targeted the ratings systems by the
alphabet-soup groups as having ``no credibility or consistency; a
boxer's rating is often manipulated to suit the particular whims of
a particular promoter or the organization's own bottom line.''
Holyfield, for example, is ignored in the WBC ratings; Lewis is
ignored in the WBA and IBF ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the Holyfield-Lewis judges were, in effect, chosen to
represent the different ratings groups,'' the senator pointed out,
``shows how deeply entrenched conflicts of interest are.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator was in a ringside seat a week ago for the debatable
draw, but his credibility as a boxing reformist predated the boos
that thundered throughout Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, along with Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., sponsored the
Professional Boxing Safety Act, the 1996 law that prevents a
fighter with a revoked or suspended license in one state from being
licensed by another state. That law kept Mike Tyson from fighting
elsewhere after Nevada revoked his license for biting Holyfield's
ears.
</P>
<P>
   According to McCain, the Ali Act does not require taxpayer funds
or the creation of government bureaucracies. But it does require
the House of Representatives to introduce it and then approve it
for President Clinton's signature as law.
</P>
<P>
   When and if that happens, the Holyfield-Lewis heavyweight
championship unification bout will have resulted in a knockout
after all _ a knockout of the pervasive power of the promoters and
the alphabet-soup governing bodies that have infected boxing for
too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
