</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WINNING IS LESS IMPORTANT ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE
STREET
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Where I come from,'' growled Jennifer Llaneras, a
14-year-old artist and shortstop from East Harlem, ``girls are
supposed to be china dolls and stay on shelves. Not me. I'm here to
play, not be displayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Confident in her exit line, Llaneras swaggered out onto the gym
floor last week and began throwing a softball hard enough to make
leather complain. She glanced over her shoulder only twice to check
audience response. Her coach smiled and mouthed, ``Attitude.'' He
liked that. He might have a team this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Softball is a nice release,'' said the team captain, Meta
Duevell, an 18-year-old photographer from Brooklyn who plays first
base and bats clean-up. ``The people across the street may have it
harder, but we have a reason to be here, too. We want to do
something, not just sit around. And Jake makes it fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Marty Jacobson is known as Jake among his ``softball
girls'' at the highly selective Fiorello H. La Guardia High School
of Music, Art and the Performing Arts, as well as among his
``soccer guys'' across the street at the gritty Martin Luther King
Jr. High School. Side by side and worlds apart, both schools front
on Amsterdam Avenue and face Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   The mercurial 52-year-old coach shuttles between them, lugging
heavy baggage. As most teachers and students on both sides of the
street know, his spectacular career has been clouded recently by
defaulted games and a suspension. It is not clear whether he will
be rehired as soccer coach at King, where he works full time as a
guidance counselor.
</P>
<P>
   What few know is that tests he had recently revealed the
presence of the hepatitis C virus, a potentially life-threatening
condition. Jacobson has also suffered liver damage.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the dawning of the softball season is an emotional spring.
The 14-game league schedule begins next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not as intense over here,'' said Jacobson, his face
and body atypically relaxed as the girls warmed up with plastic
balls and bats. They were waiting for the soccer, tennis and
handball teams to leave the yellow gym. ``Ultimately, they're all
kids, they need encouragement, they need to know they're safe at
school. But here, we come back singing on the subway after a
defeat. That would never happen at King.''
</P>
<P>
   King is a hard school, typical of the city, the teachers a mix
of saints, pros and clock-watchers, the students predominantly
blacks and Latinos from Manhattan and Brooklyn scrabbling to make
it on a tough, tilted field. Their best-known sports team is male,
mostly blacks born in Africa and the Caribbean who came to Jake
through the worldwide soccer network.
</P>
<P>
   The team has been undefeated on the field in the past two years
as it won two straight city championships. For the players, many of
whom are isolated by language and lifestyle from the rest of the
student body, soccer is an identity and often the only way to get
to college.
</P>
<P>
   Students on the La Guardia side of the street, who need a
portfolio or an audition act for admission, tend to enter with an
identity and a life plan. The school combines two celebrated high
schools: Performing Arts, which inspired the film ``Fame,'' and
Music &AMP; Art.
</P>
<P>
   Student actors, vocalists, musicians, artists and dancers (who
are prohibited from varsity sports) often leave private schools to
attend La Guardia. Sports is usually a diversion and a nice
extracurricular activity to list on college applications.
</P>
<P>
   In nine years at La Guardia, Jacobson has rarely posted a
winning season. When the team did qualify for the city championship
tournament, the starting pitcher and catcher were unable to play
because of the spring drama festival. La Guardia lost.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Nathanson of La Guardia, the rare athletic director in
the city with a Ph.D., originally hired Jacobson as boys' soccer
coach. Jacobson was already a counselor at King. Five years ago,
after making La Guardia soccer competitive, Jacobson left, with
Nathanson's blessing, for the King soccer job. But he stayed with
softball, which pays about $5,200 ($31 an hour for 168 hours) a
season. Soccer (120 hours) pays about $3,700.
</P>
<P>
   Like many coaches, Jacobson complains about the disparity
between the pay and the time and emotional demands of the jobs.
There is an almost preppy feel to a La Guardia practice (``I like
the outfield very much,'' cries Krystyna Printup, a painter from
Rego Park, Queens, angling for an audition) and Jacobson seems more
doting uncle than the demanding father figure he is at King, where
urban realities have made him an easy touch for holiday dinners or
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   La Guardia girls miss practice because of violin lessons and
photography shows. King boys miss practice because they have to
work overtime in fast-food restaurants. When senior catcher Kate
Hoffman borrowed $5 from Jacobson, her father returned it at the
next game. The 1997-98 season's King star, Mansour Ndiaye, simply
became part of Jacobson's family for food, clothing and weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Mansour, who dropped in to softball practice last week, is an
easy favorite son. A freshman starter and budding star on the
University of Connecticut's excellent team, he is also fulfilling
his promise as King's salutatorian, running a 3.84 average as an
engineering student.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what combination of Jacobson's cocky
carelessness and the jealous pettiness of opposing coaches almost
derailed King this past season. Two players were ruled ineligible,
one for missing school on a game day for a doctor's appointment
without proper consent, and the other for being overage.
</P>
<P>
   Games were forfeited, although not enough to affect King's
winning the championship. But it was enough, according to Principal
Stephanie D'Amore, to taint the title. She suspended Jacobson. She
subsequently rescinded the suspension, but has yet to announce
whether she will allow him to return as coach. Through the
teachers' union, he can appeal her decision.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1609EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
