<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-2TAKES     03-20 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: her decision.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of more pressing urgency is Jacobson's health. Remarkably fit
and physically active _ he referees and competes in basketball,
among other sports _ he was shocked by the diagnosis of hepatitis
C.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson is a recovering drug and alcohol abuser; he says he has
been sober for 15 years. A biopsy indicated Stage II liver disease;
he is currently asymptomatic, but there is scarring. He is
discussing treatment options, including drugs that may temporarily
tire and sicken him.
</P>
<P>
   This would interfere not only with counseling and coaching, but
with a new Nike contract. The shoe company discovered Jacobson last
season, donated equipment to the Martin Luther King team and hired
him as a consultant; one market scenario has soccer's next American
wave coming from the kind of inner-city immigrants who have won for
King.
</P>
<P>
   So Jacobson happily crosses the street into La Guardia softball,
where the daily dramas of adolescence are no less urgent for the
actors, but the game has a softer, more playful edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, they're just as needy as the boys,'' he said,
``but life feels easier on this side of the street because winning
isn't so important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Softball is my life,'' sang out Ruthy Henry, a vocalist from
Staten Island. She checked to see if Jake was in earshot. ``I love
it even more than singing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Erica Feldherr, who played for four years on a Little League
team in Jackson Heights, Queens, admitted that she did not find
softball satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball, I want to play baseball,'' she said. ``I want a
league of my own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
