<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-LAWYER-2TAKES     03-20 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-LAWYER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM LAWYER TO MISSING MAN TO FEDERAL FUGITIVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Mass., Conn.)   By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARLBOROUGH, Conn. _ The frequent requests for fees in advance,
the secretiveness, the blithe disregard for phone messages, all
made Dennis B. Messenger wonder about the lawyer representing his
brother on a murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   But then the lawyer, F. Mac Buckley, turned on the charm that
had made him one of Connecticut's best-known criminal defense
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Over sole and lobster at the Chowder Pot IV restaurant in
Hartford, he regaled Messenger with tales of his years of freeing
mobsters, moonlighting as a boxing promoter and dabbling in
politics. He barely paused to chew as he told how he had worked his
way through college and law school, then got his start as a federal
drug prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   This was the full Mac Buckley treatment _ an entrancing dose of
the chatter and blather that the burly lawyer had honed with juries
and unleashed on ESPN as a commentator during the O.J. Simpson
trial. Messenger said that Buckley, 57, went on to boast about his
estate here in the Connecticut countryside, then confided that he
loved his work so much that he would never retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't conventional, but I could see he was powerful in the
state and knew how to work the system,'' Messenger recalled
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Messenger picked up the check. He now believes he was being
snowed.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley vanished on March 1, leaving behind several clients _
including Messenger's brother, David _ who now accuse him of
absconding with hundreds of thousands of dollars that he held in
trust for them. As clients got over the shock of his disappearance
and began checking their accounts and then calling the authorities,
Buckley went from missing man to wanted man. Warrants were issued
charging him with forgery and embezzlement, and last week he was
declared a federal fugitive. Investigators said that they expected
more charges.
</P>
<P>
   The country estate turned out to be just a house; the adjoining
50-acre farm was sold off four years ago, although Buckley still
sometimes gave Buck Hill Farm as his address. The house was put in
the name of Buckley's wife, Donna, in 1990, and she is the
registered owner of their three cars.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley was last seen pulling out of the driveway of the
260-year-old Colonial house in his teal 1998 Lincoln Navigator with
a New England Patriots sticker in the back window. His family said
that about noon he called his office in Hartford from his cellular
phone to say he was headed for federal court in New Haven, where he
was due at 2 p.m. The judge and other lawyers waited until 5 and
then gave up.
</P>
<P>
   In the first days after the disappearance, Buckley's family and
friends said they feared he might have been done in by a former
client or an enemy of one of the gang members and mobsters he had
defended over the years. State troopers in cruisers and a plane
scoured the 45 miles between Marlborough and New Haven, checking
every exit ramp and parking lot. They then searched airports and
train stations throughout Connecticut, Massachusetts and New York.
They found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say that in the first few days Buckley was
missing, a signal was picked up from his cellular phone _ which was
briefly switched on, although he was not making calls _ near
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they have one other clue. Late in the
afternoon on March 5, a man approached a caretaker at St. Agnes
Cemetery in Menands, N.Y., just outside Albany, and asked to be
directed to the grave of Buckley's father. The caretaker checked
the register, pointed the man toward the plot and never saw him
again. Later, the caretaker was shown Buckley's photo, and he said
he was certain that Buckley was the visitor he had helped.
</P>
<P>
   A senior state official said that Buckley's family did not
report him missing for 30 hours, and even then relatives made the
report only after the police had heard about the disappearance from
other lawyers and went to the Buckley home. He left behind five
daughters including one, Moira L. Buckley, who was his law partner.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Buckley's shingle was removed from the lawn outside
his office in Hartford, and his nameplate on the front door was
painted over.
</P>
<P>
   But such was Buckley's mystique that many of his neighbors and
associates refuse to believe that he disappeared intentionally. In
the courthouses and law offices of Connecticut, the tales have
grown increasingly wild: that he has joined the federal
witness-protection program, that he has enlisted in the Irish
Republican Army, that he is on a gambling spree in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, his clients are left with no lawyer and, some
say, no money. John T. Spellman, an owner of Marlborough Tavern,
where Buckley used booth A-2 as a satellite office for meeting
clients, is left puzzling over what the lawyer told him in their
last conversation. ``I'm like Frank Sinatra,'' Buckley said he had
just told his doctor, spurning advice to give up cigars and liquor.
``I've done it my way. I'm not afraid to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends suspect the image-conscious Buckley would be dismayed to
learn that his ``wanted'' posters identify him as Francis McKeon
Buckley, the name he was given when he was born in New Haven. He
grew up in Scarsdale, N.Y., and graduated from the College of the
Holy Cross in Worcester, Mass., in 1963 and Georgetown University
Law Center in 1967. He often described himself as ``a Golden Gloves
boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   He clerked for a Connecticut Supreme Court justice, then learned
both sides of the legal trade as an assistant federal prosecutor
and an assistant public defender. He lost when he ran for Congress
as a Republican in 1974, then settled the next year for being
elected a councilman from Newington.
</P>
<P>
   At nights and on weekends, he was a boxing trainer and promoter,
and groomed one champion, the welterweight Marlon Starling. Buckley
was tough with his boxers, making them lose weight and work out in
rubber suits when others were resting up for bouts. But he made
friends around inner-city gyms by paying down-and-out fighters to
spar with his boxers. He often took a carload of poor youngsters to
see out-of-town fights.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley was at home with Connecticut society, where he bought a
$3,500 box at January's inaugural ball for Gov. John G. Rowland, as
well as in Hartford's housing projects, where youngsters who knew
him from boxing called him ``Big Daddy Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom, Buckley used sarcasm, street slang and
disarming frankness to dazzle juries. During his summations in mob
cases, jaded clerks from throughout the courthouse squeezed into
the benches as spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost it and he shot him,'' Buckley said of one client,
arguing that a murder charge was too serious. He derided a drug
informer's work as ``just a sloppy, slanted job.'' Two bumbling
informers in another case became ``the dynamic duo.''
</P>
<P>
   William F. Dow III, a New Haven lawyer, said Buckley entertained
other lawyers with his street machismo, but drove them crazy with
his sloppy habits. ``He was always late, always out of contact, no
one ever knew how to reach him,'' Dow said. ``That was always part
of the mystery about Mac _ how someone that difficult to get hold
of could be so successful. The answer was that he was a great
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But his habits also prompted a stream of complaints from clients
to the Statewide Grievance Committee, which disciplines lawyers,
and led to a reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Buckley disappeared, a lawyer for the grievance
committee had recommended that Buckley's law license be suspended
because of the case involving Messenger's brother. The brother,
David, who is awaiting trial on a charge that he murdered his wife,
was a salesman for a scientific instrument company and had assets
of $500,000 to $1 million, relatives say.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the grievance committee said Buckley ``induced
David Messenger to provide him a complete power of attorney and may
have dissipated David Messenger's assets.'' Acting on the
complaint, a Superior Court judge suspended Buckley's law license a
week after his disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal charges against Buckley, which were filed 12 days
after he disappeared, stem from the case of a couple in Hebron,
Conn., who had entrusted to Buckley the $580,000 they received in a
settlement in 1994 after a daughter was killed in a drunken driving
accident. Buckley, in an unusual move for a lawyer, invested the
money for the couple, David and Sharon Fracchia.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit, the couple charged that on Feb. 1, Buckley
converted two of their certificates of deposit into a check for
$144,554, then signed their names on the back and cashed it at a
bank in Malden, Mass. The lawsuit said he had failed to keep them
posted on the state of their account and had repeatedly ignored
their requests for updates. In addition to the missing check, about
$300,000 in investments is unaccounted for, said a lawyer for the
couple, Robert J.T. Britt of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley responded with prickly indignation to the string of
formal complaints from clients who said he had ignored them or
missed deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   In the case that drew a reprimand in 1997, involving failure to
release records to a prisoner who wanted to fire him, Buckley wrote
to the grievance committee that the prisoner would have to get
someone to pick the records up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of time and money copying and I don't intend to
finance the shipping,'' Buckley wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the last three months, according to lawyers and court
papers, Buckley had explained his lapses by complaining variously
of back trouble, a cardiac problem and acute sinusitis.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who say Buckley abandoned them is Debbie Brahm, 32,
of Marlborough, who hired him to handle her divorce several years
ago. Ms. Brahm, a mother of two, had met Buckley when she worked at
a convenience store and he came in every morning to buy the New
York newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   After taking her case, she said, ``He never returned my calls.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she paid him several thousand dollars in cash and
cannot afford to pay another lawyer to start over again. She is
hoping his daughter, Moira, will pick up the case, but has begun to
worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't returned my calls, either,'' Ms. Brahm said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
