<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JETS' MOVES DRIVEN BY DESIRE TO WIN NOW
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ And then there was one _ maybe.
</P>
<P>
   With their trade on Friday of quarterback Glenn Foley to the
Seahawks, the Jets have tidied up virtually all the odds and ends
they brought into the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   And they have emerged significantly stronger in at least three
positions, even before their conditioning program starts on
Wednesday. The Jets appear to be so strong that the Caesars Palace
oddsmaker Vince Magliulo makes them the third choice to win the
Super Bowl behind the Vikings and the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Foley fetched a seventh-round draft pick as the Jets began the
process of accumulating choices. They will not, after all, have a
first-round selection. That goes to the Patriots, the last remnant
of the deal that allowed Bill Parcells to jump to the Jets. It is
looking like a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The second season under Parcells ended in the AFC championship
game in Denver, with the Jets coming a fumble, or a dropped ball or
one tackle away from going to the Super Bowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on the scope and quality of the Jets' eight major
off-season moves _ has any team been busier? _ Parcells believes
the Jets have a shot at the Super Bowl. He wants it now. Actually,
that has always been his philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the NFL these days,'' Parcells likes to say, ``two years is
an eternity.'' In other words, planning for the year 2000 is a
waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest off-season move, Parcells said, was the upgrade at
punter, where one of his favorites from New England, Tom Tupa,
replaced John Kidd. Tupa is also a quarterback, which gives the
Jets a personnel edge; they will be able to dress an extra
special-teams player because Tupa fills two positions.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa is also a proven cold-weather kicker, having played well at
Cleveland under Bill Belichick, who may even be the Jets' head
coach a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Jets picked up a Pro Bowl safety in Steve
Atwater; a former Pro Bowl tight end in Eric Green, a starting
outside linebacker in Roman Phifer and a defensive end, Mike
Frederick, who could push Rick Lyle at the left side.
</P>
<P>
   The team also reined in Dwayne Gordon, who had tested free
agency after splitting starting time with Pepper Johnson at inside
linebacker last season. Johnson's retirement at the age of 35 is
likely. Then the Jets re-signed Vinny Testaverde, who produced the
finest statistical quarterback season in Jets history. Finally,
they traded Foley.
</P>
<P>
   If they were not perilously close to the salary cap, the Jets
might be bringing in a right guard to replace Matt O'Dwyer, who has
not been plucked as a free agent. Once the free-agency buying spree
around the NF L settles, someone of experience and quality may be
available.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Jets have a better punter, free safety and tight
end than last season. This is not inconsiderable. Atwater, who was
brought in after the Jets had tackling problems with all three free
safeties they used, finds a defensive style more suited to his
current speed, and age (32).
</P>
<P>
   He will also have a rigorous off-season conditioning program _
something he failed to benefit from each of the last two years
because of off-season surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who has been known for his indifferent attitude toward
conditioning, will be in better shape or he won't be a Jet. He
replaces Kyle Brady, who had another ``almost'' season but could
never string together more than two or three games as a factor on
offense. In four years as a Jet, Brady caught a total of 93 passes
and 10 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   And Tupa? He replaces the conference's poorest punter in gross
average. Kidd had a decent net average and was an excellent holder,
but each of Tupa's kicks traveled an average of 3.4 yards farther.
Tupa is also a very good holder.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have also acquired depth, and probably a
first-stringer, at linebacker by signing Phifer, an eight-year
starter with the Rams. He played in obscurity on that perennially
troubled franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets will now go to a four-linebacker alignment, using
Phifer and Mo Lewis on the outside, and Marvin Jones and Bryan Cox
on the inside. At the least, Phifer is insurance, joining a good
group of linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our linebackers,'' Chad Cascadden said,
``you've got six players who were starters _ Marvin, Mo, Bryan,
Dwayne, Phifer and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Frederick, another former Raven/Brown with a
connection to Belichick and Scott Pioli, who handled pro personnel
with those teams and now does so with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, a baseball historian, knows the futility of the ``wait
till next year'' cry. He believes the Jets' future is in the
present. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
