A7989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAGIC-HARDAWAY-NY     03-20 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAGIC-HARDAWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDAWAY NEEDS TO BE LOVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barely eight days ago, the luster had worn off Orlando's quick
start. The Magic had lost embarrassingly to Dallas, Penny Hardaway
was pouting and all the old liabilities _ fragile egos, poor
shooting and bad chemistry _ had begun to resurface.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic, which has been fighting for respectability ever since
Shaquille O'Neal went Hollywood, appeared to be fraying at the
edges again. Its losing streak numbered only three games, but
Hardaway was feeling insecure about his position and the team's.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of his anxiety, he felt he had no relationship
with coach Chuck Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't talk, and I figured that meant he really didn't
have confidence in me,'' Hardaway said. ``I shouldn't have assumed
that, but that's just how it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we make all this money and everything, and you wouldn't
think some of us need reinforcement,'' he added. ``But you want to
hear from your coach that you're doing well, even at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, regarded as the ultimate players' coach, a coach who once
gave Isiah Thomas and the Detroit Pistons a day off because Thomas
was angry over a newspaper column, quickly remedied the situation
by meeting with Hardaway at an Oakland, Calif., hotel before the
Magic met the Golden State Warriors a week ago last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically told me to have fun, don't take things too
seriously and to communicate with him any time I wanted to,''
Hardaway said. ``I'm not saying that was the main reason we haven't
lost since, but it definitely helped. He let me know how important
I was to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   With their victory over the Knicks here Thursday night, the
Magic have won four straight and head into Sunday's nationally
televised home game against the Lakers with the second-best record
in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, having missed 86 games over the past two seasons
because of surgeries on his left knee, is slowly regaining his form
as the multidimensional player who led the Magic to the finals in
1995 along with O'Neal, whom he will play against today for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   The two were teammates in the All-Star Game last year and on the
1996 Olympic team, but have not competed against each other since
O'Neal signed with the Lakers in '96 because they were injured in
different seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for TV,'' said Hardaway, who added that he has no
relationship with O'Neal, even though the two own homes two minutes
from each other in Isleton, an Orlando suburb. ``Shaq had to do
what he had to do for himself. I'm glad he's not here now. Him
being unhappy would have made us unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway has still not completely recaptured the form that made
him one of the game's best 10 players three years ago. But his
averages of 15.4 points, 6 rebounds, 5 assists and 2 steals per
game are not bad, given he played only 19 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Criticized by his teammates for babying his injury and not
playing when he could have last season, Hardaway is widely
perceived as a player who is not mentally strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me, that guys would question my heart,'' Hardaway
said. ``But, you know, no one knows your body but you. For them to
say that without going through what I went through was not right.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not help his cause when he endorsed the firing of Coach
Brian Hill two seasons ago. Whether his meeting with Daly will pay
long-term dividends is unclear. But Hardaway, who for some reason
needs to know he's not taken for granted, seems to be a more secure
and confident player.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1638EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0178 </DOCNO>
