<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nolan a coach minus team
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Creating a resume and sitting by a silent telephone can be a
humbling experience for a man, particularly one approaching his
41st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Ted Nolan has been at the bottom. As a Native
American from the Ojibway tribe, he grew up on a reservation in
Sault St. Marie, Ontario, one of 12 children, with no plumbing and
no Kroger. If you wanted food, you killed it.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Nolan would become known for his skills as a hockey
coach and master motivator, leading the surprising Buffalo Sabres
from fifth to first in the Northeast Division in 1996-97 and into
the second round of the playoffs, earning NHL coach of the year.
His reward from the Sabres: a token offer of a one-year extension,
which he rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan has been without a head coaching job since. Why, he said,
``is the million dollar question,'' although he has some
suspicions. But after more than a year of giving motivational
speeches _ an average of four per week _ and doing some scouting
for Canadian Hockey, Nolan is itchy to return to coaching. That's
why he completed a resume for the first time last week and plans to
start sending copies.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, he will be mailing one to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell has said Nolan will be
among as many as a dozen potential coaches he will do a background
check on, a process that will lead to about five interviews. ``As
you approach a search, you have to look at everybody who's had
success in the league, and he has,'' Waddell said. ``For whatever
reasons, he's not working now. I'm surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said, ``I would feel honored just to be contacted'' by the
Thrashers. He appears to fill the prerequisites for the job. He
favors an attack style of hockey, which jibes with Waddell's plans
on how to build the roster. He has strong motivational skills,
which is imperative for any coach but particularly one heading a
group of castoffs thrown together on an expansion team. Further,
his good looks and reputation for dressing well wouldn't hurt in
marketing, when the franchise is owned by a media conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan has turned down assistant coaching offers from Tampa Bay
and the New York Islanders. ``I feel I'm a head coach, and I have a
little more to offer,'' he said from his home in Ontario. ``Head
coaches make decisions. Assistant coaches make suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't help much in Buffalo. The Sabres were team turmoil
during Nolan's two years. Ownership was in the process of changing
from the financially strapped Seymour Knox to John Rigas. Knox got
sick and died. Two executives, John Moss and Larry Quinn, were
vying to run the franchise. Nolan and general manager John Muckler
also battled. Although Nolan was popular with most players, he had
problems with goalie Dominik Hasek, who left the ice in the middle
of a playoff game, claiming an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn eventually won the power struggle. He fired Muckler, then
Nolan. Then Quinn himself was fired the next year. Muckler accused
Nolan of backstabbing him to ownership, which Nolan vehemently
denies. He says he merely gave the name of his mentor in junior
hockey, Sherry Bassin, to Rigas when the owner asked, ``Who did you
learn from?'' Word got back to Muckler, who took it the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our disagreements,'' Nolan said. ``But when I heard
stories about the backstabbing, that really hurt. Small minds. `He
did that; she did this.' I was never into that. I'm more into
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue was the whole organization was in a tailspin. I
was the new kid on the block, and I got caught in the crossfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Has he been blackballed?
</P>
<P>
   ``To a point,'' he said. ``But if I'm an organization, I'll talk
directly to the horse, rather than listen to innuendo and rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans held rallies in support of Nolan, and fans canceled 1,600
season tickets after they perceived that he and popular center Pat
Lafontaine both had been run off.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan still draws crowds _ but only when he makes speeches to
office managers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
