<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL EAST NOTES: Trading deadline
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NHL's trading deadline Tuesday tends to bring a flurry of
deals. Three teams in the East could be the most active:
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington reached the finals last season but has been
decimated by injuries all year, with more than 400 combined games
lost. The Caps have nine potential unrestricted free agents, and
general manager George McPhee is more concerned about next season
than the playoff stretch. Among those on the block: Mark Tinordi,
Dale Hunter, Joe Juneau and Brian Bellows.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Islanders general manager Mike Milbury doesn't have a
mandate, because owner Howard Milstein is preoccupied with his
potential purchase of the Washington Redskins. But budget
casualties could include goalie Tommy Salo and forward Trevor
Linden.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tampa Bay general manager-coach Jacques Demers might not
survive himself, but he'll outlast forward Wendel Clark, who could
be headed to Dallas. The Lightning also would love to dump $3
million goalie Bill Ranford.
</P>
<P>
   Executive suite
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia players, who take a 12-game winless streak (0-8-4)
into today's game against Detroit (Fox, 3 p.m.), have more to fret
about than general manager Bob Clarke taking away their three-day
vacation in New Orleans. The Flyers' plummet from first to sixth in
the Eastern Conference overall standings even has owner Ed Snider
fuming in public. ``I think 50 percent of this game is mental, and
this team has had a complete mental collapse,'' Snider said. ``I've
never seen anything like it. To see a team play so well and then
play so poorly _ the same team _ for such long stretches, I've
never seen this happen.'' Things boiled over Tuesday, when two
apparent Philadelphia goals were disallowed in a 5-2 loss to St.
Louis, and coach Roger Neilson threw a stick onto the ice, drawing
an ejection, two-game suspension and $10,000 fine. The Blues' Chris
Pronger joked, ``His javelin throw was a little off center. He was
trying to throw it toward the referee, but he shanked it, and it
went towards the linesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky update
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' Wayne Gretzky is targeting a March 27 game against
the Flyers as his possible return from a protruding disc in his
neck, but that date might be too optimistic. He hasn't played since
Feb. 22 _ and he has received no shortage of advice on treatment.
``I heard everything from acupuncture to soft tissue specialists
and a couple of voodoo doctors. But I believe in the old system.
The doctors have been to a school for a lot of years.''Bobby Orr
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
</TEXT>
