<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL WEST NOTES: The Low down
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the team's financial difficulties and several public
declarations of support from general manager Glen Sather, Edmonton
coach Ron Low might be the least secure coach in the league right
now. The Oilers reached the second round of the playoffs the past
two years, but are headed for their fourth consecutive sub-.500
season under Low and their worst record since George Burnett was
fired 35 games into his brief tenure in 1994-95. Thursday night's
4-1 home loss to New Jersey might have been the low point. Four
minutes into the second period, Edmonton trailed 3-0 and was being
outshot 30-4. ``I was embarrassed,'' Low said. ``If the fans had
thrown their tickets onto the ice, it would've been a good
response. The players said a lot in our team meeting (Monday), but
if you're going to talk the talk, you better walk the walk. If you
don't, it's trouble.'' For the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Cat fight
</P>
<P>
   The verbal war between Vancouver general manager Brian Burke and
coach Mike Keenan unfortunately didn't end when Keenan was canned
at the All-Star break. Keenan went on Canadian television last week
and said Burke told him to fire assistant coach Stan Smyl and
predicted Mark Messier would be traded before his contract expires
next year. Burke is investigating whether the comments constitute a
confidentiality breach that would enable the Canucks to cut off
their financial obligations to the ex-coach. ``I think it's
pathetic he's dragged Mess into this,'' Burke said. ``He has
something personal against me and (ownership). He shouldn't be
worrying about us. He should worry about finding a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Wily Coyotes
</P>
<P>
   So what are the chances Jerry Colangelo has his fingerprints on
this one? Colangelo, who operates the entire Phoenix sports world
except the NHL's Coyotes, has been upset that the hockey team is
seeking a new arena project in neighboring Scottsdale. The Coyotes
are losing $4million to $6 million per year, in part because of
unsold obstructed seats at AmericaWest Arena. But word now has
leaked that Suns minority partner Barry Kemp, Colangelo's pal,
heads a group that has offered Coyotes owner Richard Burke $80
million to $100 million for the team. Was publicizing the offer
meant to derail the new arena plans? Burke, who has turned down the
offer, said, ``I'm not one who attributes motives, but the first
time this came up was when the Los Arcos project (in Scottsdale)
was announced. The second time around, it was the (Scottsdale) City
Council vote. And the third time was the legislative vote (on
stadium districts). Los Arcos will happen, and we're going to stick
it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   A recent nine-game winless streak probably smothered Nashville's
playoff hopes, but coach Barry Trotz isn't conceding anything
publicly: ``We were holding onto the ledge with our fingers, and
now we've got our hands over the side. Who knows? Down the line, we
might even be standing up on that ledge.'' . . . The winless streak
hasn't affected attendance in Nashville, where the average is over
16,000 for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
