<SLUG> BC-BBN-BREWERS-PULSIPHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULSIPHER RISES ABOVE INSULT AND INJURY TO BECOME A STARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX, March 20 _ Bill Pulsipher feels Kerry Wood's pain.
Pulsipher, however, has shed his own pain _ from his Tommy John
elbow to his exile from the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I ever wanted was to be a starting pitcher in the major
leagues, so having that opportunity is all you can ask for,'' said
Pulsipher, a starting pitcher with the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   The road to the Brewers' rotation was filled with detours and
potholes. The most severe obstacle was the torn ligament Pulsipher
suffered in his left elbow in 1996 in a scenario that strikingly
resembled the injury that last week knocked out Wood, the Chicago
Cubs' young phenom, for at least this season. But Pulsipher
suffered a jarring ride through New York as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '95, when I first got there, it was my job,'' the
25-year-old left-hander said at the Brewers' camp. ``I was told all
through the minor leagues you're going to be the future, future,
future, future. Then you get injured and then they get a new
manager and everything changes. Suddenly you have a new future.
That was the first time in my life my future had to be
rearranged.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher needed two years to recover fully from the elbow
injury, the one that required a ligament transplant a la Tommy
John's pioneering operation 25 years ago. When he returned to the
Mets, he found Bobby Valentine and no starting opportunity there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby had a different agenda, I guess,'' he said. ``I guess I
fell out of favor.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets traded him to the Brewers last July 31, Pulsipher
was jolted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come up through an organization, with some of the
accolades, you expect to play with the organization for a long
time,'' he said. ``When I got called back up last year, the first
thing Dave Howard told me was welcome back for the next 15 or 20
years. What are you supposed to think?''
</P>
<P>
   The shock of the trade, however, has dissipated. ``It was time
for me to go,'' he said. ``I don't think I was wanted there any
more, so better to go somewhere you're wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner is delighted that he has Pulsipher. ``He is a breath
of fresh air,'' the manager said. ``He's refreshing. He's fun to
watch. I'd pay to watch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher, who takes Prozac to ward off depression, passionately
enjoys pitching and reacts exuberantly to big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does whatever hits his mind to do at the moment,'' Garner
said. ``He's not trying to show people up. He's just having a good
time and showing it. He's full of life, full of energy. Our ball
club needs some of that. We have a bunch of nice guys who sit
around and read books. That's fine; I like that. But I like to see
that adrenaline kick in once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher was not so demonstrative during his lengthy
rehabilitation following his elbow operation. Wood faces a similar
period, Pulsipher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His story is exactly what my story was,'' Pulsipher said. ``In
'95 I was shut down with two weeks to go in the season. `You have a
sprained ligament,' I was told. Last year Kerry Wood had a sprained
ligament. I knew last year it was just a matter of time before he
had `Tommy John.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A sprained ligament doesn't go away, Pulsipher said; ``it just
gets worse.'' Recalling that he was told to rehabilitate his
sprained ligament for six weeks, he said: ``I was told everything's
going to be fine; put this behind you. Three weeks into spring
training, your arm's killing you every day. You feel something pop
and it's time to go get it fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher said he was throwing from a mound about six months
after the April 1996 operation, but it took another year for him to
say he was 100 percent recovered. He expressed optimism that Wood
eventually would return to the mound and the performance level he
exhibited last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be pitching next year,'' Pulsipher said. ``I'm not sure
it will be in the major leagues, but he'll be pitching somewhere.
If he's lucky, he comes back in a year. If it's normal, it's going
to be a little more than a year. But there's no doubt in my mind
he's going to be back. He's only 21 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood has acknowledged that his style of pitching, in which he
threw across his body, put additional stress on his elbow.
Pulsipher said he, too, had ``terrible mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm was dragging behind my body, which was putting stress
on my elbow,'' he said. ``But why fix it? Nobody was hitting me.
Are you going to make up something? What if you start getting hit?
You'd automatically go back to what works if you get in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
