<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let Sosa Be Sosa
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Milwaukee Braves manager Phil Garner didn't like Todd
Stottlemyre's dislike of Sammy Sosa's gesture of bowing to the fans
last week after hitting a pair of home runs against the Arizona
pitcher. Sosa picked up the gesture while he was in Japan last
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players like to talk about entertainment, but they don't
entertain,'' Garner said. ``They just want to go play their game.
They don't want to acknowledge the fans. Show me another player in
the game who acknowledges the fans like he does. In Chicago he
sprints out there, runs from the right field line to center field,
and the fans go crazy. I wish Stottlemyre would do that. Walk out
on the mound and tip his hat, saying hello guys, get behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers played an exhibition game in Mexico yesterday, but
Jim Gantner, one of their minor league coaches, informed the team
he couldn't cross the border. ``I don't have my gift certificate,''
he explained.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Jim Gantner, who when he was the team's first
base coach was told by Garner to correct the problem of players
missing signs by working out an unmistakable hit-and-run sign for
runners on first base. One day Dave Nilsson was on first when
Garner flashed hit-and-run on two consecutive pitches only to have
Nilsson remain stationary at first.
</P>
<P>
   After the inning, Garner confronted Gantner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gantner,'' Garner said, ``didn't I tell you to give him a
sign?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did, I gave him the sign,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your sign?'' the manager asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I winked,'' Gantner said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: Gantner was wearing sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Days for Blue Jays
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays are the only team since the 1977-78
Yankees to win successive World Series, but they have fallen on
hard times in recent seasons. The 1999 season hasn't even started,
and they have changed managers, becoming perhaps only the third
team to fire their manager in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   What malady has afflicted the Blue Jays? Ed Sprague, who was the
third baseman on the second World Series team and remained with the
Blue Jays through much of last season, offered his view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they got caught up in not knowing whether to rebuild
or make a run for it,'' Sprague said. ``They've been caught in half
seasons. If the team isn't doing well at the All-Star break and
trade deadline, then they trade a guy. It started with the Cone
trade in '95. We traded for Cone in the spring, but by the end of
July we weren't in it and we traded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that we had a bunch of half seasons. If we weren't in
it, we'd trade and try to get a prospect or two in August or
September. That winter we'd go out and make a couple trades and be
competitive again. If that didn't work out by the next July, we
traded more prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '90s we were always the team that went out and
traded for somebody. In '95, '96 and '97 we were the team that was
always trading somebody. They never had one year and said this is
our team, we're gong to go with these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what hurt us. From an emotional standpoint,
players felt like if you went into July, you didn't known what
direction you were going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Rings for the Price of One
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland got to have his ring and wear it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland, who managed the Florida Marlins to the World Series
championship in 1997, recounted how he took his championship ring
and put it in a safety deposit box in a Pittsburgh bank, keeping it
for his son, Patrick, who is 7 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The ring thus did not adorn his hand when he had dinner with H.
Wayne Huizenga, then the Marlins' owner, late last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says I thought you liked your ring,'' Leyland related. ``I
said I love my ring. He said well how come you don't wear it? I
said I have it in a safety deposit box for my son. He said oh.
Well, three weeks later a guy from Huizenga Holdings walked in and
said here, Huizenga says wear your ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Sporting his second World Series ring, Leyland added, ``I
figured that anybody who would do that I better wear it in case I
run into him at a 7 Eleven.''
</P>
<P>
   American Baseball and Cuba
</P>
<P>
   A two-game exhibition series between the Cincinnati Reds and the
Los Angeles Dodgers in March 1959 marked the last time major league
teams played in Cuba, but they were not the last games American
teams played there.
</P>
<P>
   The Havana Sugar Kings played in the International League, one
of the Class AAA minor leagues, in 1960 and `61, before moving to
Jersey City, N.J., after Fidel Castro outlawed professional
athletes in Cuba. American players also played in the Cuban winter
league in the winter of 1959-60.
</P>
<P>
   Preston Gomez, a Cuban native, managed the Sugar Kings in the
1959 Little World Series between the winners of the playoffs in the
International League and the American Association. Gene Mauch
managed Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two games were in Minneapolis,'' recalled Gomez, a
former major league manager and now a special assistant to the
Anaheim Angels' general manager. ``The weather was so cold both
league presidents decided to play the rest of the games in Havana
and the series went to seven games. We won the seventh game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez said Castro, who gained power in January 1959, visited
both clubhouses after each game and talked to the players and
managers. Contrary to Cuban mythology, Gomez said, Castro was not
pursued as a potential major league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
