<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S KRZYZEWSKI IS WORRIED; TEMPLE'S CHANEY IS AWED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It will be Duke (35-1) against Temple
(24-10) Sunday afternoon for a berth in the Final Four of men's
basketball, and if you believe the rival coaches, both teams will
have a difficult time winning.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, the nation's top-ranked team, has won its last 30 games
and is a solid favorite. The Blue Devils are seeded first and
Temple sixth in the East regional of the NCAA tournament at the
Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday night's regional semifinals, both teams won
comfortably, Duke by 78-61 over Southwest Missouri State (22-11)
and Temple by 77-55 over Purdue (21-13). Duke's depth and
versatility impressed the near-capacity crowd of 19,233. Temple's
shooting and floor leadership were memorable, too. But the winning
coaches also saw the dark at the end of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Duke played with endless energy. The sophomore Elton Brand, 6
feet 8 inches and 265 pounds, was a force inside, and when he was
double-teamed, which was often, the ball ended up with Trajan
Langdon, the senior shooting guard. Langdon finished with 24 points
and 8 rebounds, Brand with 14 points, 8 rebounds, 5 blocks and 4
steals. As Brand said, ``When Trajan plays the way he did, it takes
a lot of pressure off me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski was not thrilled. Perhaps he
had been spoiled by Duke's 41-point victories in its first two
games in this tournament. This, he said, was not one of Duke's
better games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us to loose balls,'' the coach said. ``They didn't
turn it over much. In the first half, it was a 2-point game, a
4-point game, and our defense wasn't that good. We played better in
the second half. We have more talent than they do and we should
have won. We hope we can play better Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State had never reached the round of 16
before, and coach Steve Alford warned his players that if they held
Duke in awe, they would be out of the game in 10 minutes. ``I told
them, `If we're going to get beaten, let's be aggressive,''' Alford
said. And they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we underestimated their quickness,'' said
William Fontleroy, Southwest Missouri State's junior guard.
``They're not a perfect team.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Temple, but John Chaney, in his 27th year as a head
coach, had his Temple team playing perhaps above its head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited that our kids played as well as they did,'' Chaney
said. ``I'm as much surprised as everyone who has seen us play
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple made 52.7 percent of its shots, many off balance or from
far out. Mark Karcher, a 6-5 sophomore forward, sank 5 of 12
3-point shots and scored 21 points. Pepe Sanchez, an extraordinary
6-4 junior point guard from Argentina, broke up Purdue's pressing
defense and had 17 points, 9 assists, 6 rebounds and 6 steals.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney was afraid this performance was a one-time thing. Listen
to these responses at a post-game news conference:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Were you surprised the way your team shot?
</P>
<P>
   A. Very much surprised. I was also surprised we didn't play
better defense.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you shoot this well again?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know. Maybe one surprise leads to another.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What were you thinking when you were watching your players
shoot?
</P>
<P>
   A. That it's going to come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   So much for overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the game turned on a freakish 10-0 run by
Temple in a 40-second span. It included one technical foul on
Jaraan Cornell of Purdue after a scuffle with Quincy Wadley and
another on Coach Gene Keady of Purdue for protesting that call too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things where you try to stick up for your
players,'' Keady said. ``We all overreacted.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple was unshakable, but now it faces a monumental task. In
Krzyzewski's 18 previous seasons at Duke, his teams have won two
national championships and have played in seven Final Fours.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney has never led Temple to a Final Four, and as Sanchez
said, ``We practice at 5:30 in the morning because we want to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney knows what his team faces. ``I've been excited and
completely awed watching Duke just play,'' he said. ``They've been
an unbelievable team. They've got mix-and-match parts in every
area. They've got a professional player under the basket and the
best shooting guard in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   If Chaney is not claiming victory, Temple supporters are. As the
Owls were closing out Purdue, their fans were chanting, ``We want
Duke, we want Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney responded to that with fatalistic humor. ``I don't want
to see Duke,'' he said. ``I've got to see them. Who wants to see
Duke?''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOTBALL-FAMILY-2TAKE     03-20 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-FAMILY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FOOTBALL SAGA: SAINT, SINNER AND SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT H. BOYLE   
 (Robert H. Boyle is a special contributor to Sports Illustrated and
the author of ``The Hudson River: A Natural and Unnatural History''
and other books.)  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kelly Sullivan was 6 years old when his mother, Gail, drove him
and his 10-year-old brother, Ramsey, to Clinton Prison in
Dannemora, N.Y., for their first family visit with their father.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph George Sullivan, inmate No. 82-A-5729, was a football
enthusiast serving two consecutive life sentences for three of the
30-some murders he can recall committing. Called ``the most
dangerous man in America'' and nicknamed Mad Dog by the FBI,
Sullivan was the only man to escape from Attica, and for the first
five years of family visits only Gail Sullivan and the two boys
were allowed in the visitors' compound when he was temporarily let
out of solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every visit, I'd spend like four, five hours with Kelly and
Ramsey,'' Joe Sullivan said recently. He had his sons do push-ups,
sit-ups, 50-yard dashes, forward and backward crisscross drills,
and running and standing long jumps for at least an hour before
they played.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we didn't have a football, I used to put rags together
with towels and make it hard and then tie it. If we needed an extra
man, I used Gail. Until I was 50 years old, I was beating them in
the 50-yard dash. First Ramsey beat me, and I was thrilled. And
Kelly was always trying to catch up, first with me and then with
Ramsey. Then, when he was 16 years old, he was beating Ramsey at
20.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly kept going. Last fall, as a 17-year-old running back, he
helped lead Monroe-Woodbury High School in Central Valley, N.Y., to
an unbeaten regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best runner I've had in 22 years of coaching,'' said
Pat D'Aliso, the football coach at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Sullivan's football talent has continued to weave a bright
thread in the family tapestry, a poignant saga that sweeps through
the vicious underworld of crime and onto the fabled playing fields
of Notre Dame. It is football and the dream of Notre Dame that
unites Kelly, his father, Joe, and his great uncle, the first
Joseph George Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   It is Kelly's great uncle _ his father's namesake _ who is the
family beacon; Uncle Joe Sullivan was a Notre Dame captain-elect
whose legend in South Bend places him alongside George Gipp and
Knute Rockne.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, now 18, is well aware of the family's Notre Dame football
connection. His father made sure of that with both of his boys. ``I
told them how I was named after Joe,'' Joe said. ``I showed them
his picture, what a great player he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed the boat, but Notre Dame was to be the family
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys got the message. ``He always told me to root for Notre
Dame because it was our team, that Uncle Joe went there,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey, who preferred baseball, added, ``We were told if you
wanted to play football, Notre Dame is where you wanted to go.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to go there because of Uncle Joe Sullivan. Born in
1913 in New York City's Greenwich Village, one of eight children,
Uncle Joe went to St. Francis de Sales Parochial School in Queens
and served as an altar boy. He was the star tackle and captain of
the 1931 St. John's Prep team that defeated archrival Brooklyn Prep
for the first time in 12 years. Voted the outstanding city high
school athlete in 1932 and the national schoolboy shot-put
champion, he won a trip to the Olympics in Los Angeles and a
scholarship to Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   In his sophomore year in South Bend, Sullivan sat on the bench
and watched a senior all-American, Moose Krause, play left tackle
on both offense and defense in the days before two-platoon
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``And surely Krause was good enough to watch,'' columnist Bill
Corum wrote in The New York Evening Journal. ``But when the New
York Irishman finally got his chance as a junior, he soon made the
coaches forget even the powerful, potent Krause. Quiet and reserved
almost to the point of shyness off the field, Sullivan turned out
to be such a flaming fighter in action that when the time came to
elect a captain, he was the unanimous choice of the squad; the
recognized and accepted leader before the first vote was cast.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan was a superior player, but his presence went way beyond
football. ``Joe was one of the finest tackles ever at Notre Dame,
and that puts him in pretty classy company,'' said Wallace
Fromhart, now 84, who was quarterback and deep safety on the 1936
team. ``He was a wonderful kid, wonderful. Very humble, he never
bragged. He was very strong, and if he made a great play, he never
said anything because he believed that's what he was supposed to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's where the legend begins: In January 1935, Joe came
down with pneumonia, then mastoiditis, and underwent surgery.
Students prayed for the recovery of Big No. 79, but on March 8, he
was rushed by train to New York Hospital, where he died March 20
after three operations for a brain abscess.
</P>
<P>
   His death, after that of Gipp in 1920 and Rockne in 1931, was
called the third major shock to Notre Dame football. Coach Elmer
Layden, the fullback for Rockne's Four Horsemen, and the other
Horsemen were among those who attended the solemn requiem mass;
Layden announced that an acting captain would be chosen for each
game in a season dedicated to Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 2, with Notre Dame trailing undefeated Ohio State, 13-0,
before a crowd of 81,000 in Columbus, Layden invoked Joe's spirit
in his halftime pep talk. It was All Souls' Day, and Layden told
his players, ``You all know what today is, and Joe is surely
looking down on all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of its greatest come-from-behind victories, Notre Dame
scored three touchdowns in the last quarter, two in the last three
minutes, the last one with seconds remaining, to win by 18-13.
Sullivan's father, Tim, a New York police lieutenant, was listening
to the game on the radio. Two days later, he had a heart attack and
died.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Ronald Reagan played the Gipper in ``The Knute
Rockne Story,'' his favorite story about the Fighting Irish spirit
was how the dead captain-elect had inspired the upset of Ohio
State. When Edward Sullivan, one of Uncle Joe's two younger
brothers who also went to South Bend to play football, first
arrived at Notre Dame, the Rev. John Cavanaugh, Joe's confessor and
later the university president, said: ``Eddie, never bother to read
`The Lives of the Saints,' for Joe was the greatest guy to come to
Notre Dame spiritually and physically. Just try to be half as
good.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The torch next passed to another Sullivan, Joe's namesake
nephew, born in 1939, the oldest son of his brother Gerard, a
decorated police detective, and his wife, Nora. There was no way of
knowing then that the boy would show his football moves only behind
bars as a legendary prison halfback. But when little Joe was 8, he
began sneaking down into the cellar of his grandmother's house,
where he would undo a taboo steamer trunk and, alert for footsteps,
would hold his uncle's high-topped cleats, blood-stained jersey and
battered leather helmet and dream of running out onto the field
under the Golden Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma favored me just a bit, being her first grandson and
named after Uncle Joe to boot,'' Joe said. ``One Sunday, without
saying a word, she handed me a book, `All-Stars of Christ,' to the
shock of all my aunts and uncles because they never spoke about Joe
around her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book went far beyond Uncle Joe's athletic prowess and
spoke of his gentle decency as a God-fearing man. Well, I have
failed miserably, and I disgraced his legacy long ago by not
becoming the man I planned to be, but an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe was 13 when his father died of cancer at age 36. Between his
mother's grief and her struggle for money, Joe went adrift. He
skipped school and ran away for weeks at a time. A chronic truant,
he was sent to a training school, ran away and was arrested for
stealing a car, and ended up in a reformatory and then prison. It
was the start of a long career of crime that included a conviction
for manslaughter in the second degree, a sentence of 20 to 30 years
and a trip to Attica, where he became a legend of another kind.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, Joe said, he ran 10 miles a day, did 2,000 push-ups a
day, pumped iron and went out for football during the days when
organized games gave inmates the opportunity for serious hitting
and wagering. He played 13 seasons of hard-rock prison football; in
one, he scored 32 touchdowns in 10 games. Sullivan's star status
could be measured the only way it counts in prison _ in cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guards bet thousands of dollars on those games,'' Joe
recalled. ``A guard would say, `Hey, Sully, play for us over here
in A-Block or C-Block.' Some of these guards offered me 20 cartons,
30 cartons to play for them. This is the money in there.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, urged on by bank robber Willie Sutton, who had cancer,
Joe took advantage of the tower guards who got bored in
escape-proof Attica. When they turned to watch a truck come through
the back gate, Joe shimmied up the 32-foot wall in 15 seconds on a
makeshift pole that other inmates dismantled the instant he jumped
to freedom. For five days, guards searched the 30 buildings within
the walls because, as the distraught superintendent explained in
published reports: ``I felt he simply couldn't have gotten out. I
still don't see how he could have gotten out.''
</P>
<P>
   Caught six weeks later in Greenwich Village, Joe was sent to
Clinton Prison. In 1975, the parole board agreed to release him if
he revealed how he had escaped from Attica. He said that he had
hidden under sacks in a departing truck; the parole board released
him.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Joe took no-show jobs through mob connections, married
Gail Weiner, an account executive in a small advertising agency in
Manhattan, and worked for Fat Tony Salerno, boss of the Genovese
family. The job led to a series of killings, Joe said, and in 1982,
Joe was sent back to prison, this time for life, for three murders.
His sons were little more than toddlers: Kelly was 2 and Ramsey 6;
Gail was left to bring them up alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's two Joes, without a doubt,'' said Gail, now a teacher at
a public elementary school in the Bronx. ``There's the one in
prison and the other one who'd rather be home, a father and a
husband. He tries for us. That's why I love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 60, Joe Sullivan is in the Sullivan Correctional Facility, a
state maximum-security prison in Fallsburg, N.Y., in Sullivan
County. Gail, Kelly and Ramsey, a graduate of SUNY-Albany who is
planning to go to law school, visit him often. Gail supplements her
income by teaching computer programs in a New Jersey business
school and by teaching typing and word processing to inmates at a
federal prison near the family home in Monroe, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like their mother, both Kelly and Ramsey are Jewish. Kelly,
Ramsey, Joe and Gail each wear a gold necklace with a Star of David
enclosing a shamrock, and at Kelly's bar mitzvah, a friend gave him
an antique Notre Dame pennant, which hangs on his bedroom wall next
to an Irish flag.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly is terse when asked about what his father did.
``Obviously, it was wrong,'' he said. He is equally tight-lipped
when his peers ask where his father is and why. Kelly and Ramsey do
not talk about their father as a killer. ``It's in the past,''
Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   With his friends, quarterback Andre McCleod and
linebacker-receiver Dave Colabella, Kelly spearheaded
Monroe-Woodbury's drive to the New York Class AA section
championship last season. Aided by his 4.4-second speed in the
40-yard dash, he set a school record of 1,450 yards rushing.
Although he broke his left hand and served mainly as a decoy in the
team's final two-and-a-half nonsection games before losing to Troy,
15-13, in the quarterfinals of the state championships, Kelly ended
the year with 16 touchdowns and 1,572 yards on 173 carries. ``It
was almost a first down every time he touched the ball,'' Pat
D'Aliso, the coach, said.
</P>
<P>
   Now 5 feet 9 inches and 175 pounds, Kelly is going to spend a
post-graduate year at The Kiski School in Saltsburg, Pa., to build
up his grades and body before attending college. A strict academic
school, Kiski numbers 54 all-Americans and 11 members in the
College Football Hall of Fame among its graduates. The headmaster,
John A. Pidgeon, said, ``His potential is considerable in view of
the fact that he's had so much pressure in his life and has
obviously come through it well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's father would like him to renew the family ties to Notre
Dame. But with the years has come a certain flexibility in his
outlook. ``With what I've been through,'' Joe said, ``I just want
him to have a happy, decent life.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the dreams of the father have made an impression on
the son. ``I want to go to Notre Dame,'' Kelly recently told his
mother, ``even if I can't play football there.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
