<HEADLINE>
IOWA STATE WOMEN UPSET UCONN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeats for all needing)  
(mk) 
 By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ When it was over, when they had shocked the entire
nation and fiddled with the balance of power in women's basketball,
the Iowa State players celebrated beneath a 64-58 scoreboard. The
Cyclones huddled and bounced and hopped, a giddy group of winners
who had just done something almost no one had expected.
</P>
<P>
   They got hot at the right time against top-seeded Connecticut
Saturday in the Mideast Regional semifinals of the NCAA tournament
and bounced the disbelieving Huskies out into the cold. In the
process, the Cyclones denied the Huskies a sixth straight
30-victory season and, most important, a sixth straight appearance
in the final eight.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State will play either second-seeded Clemson or
third-seeded Georgia Sunday for a chance to go to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 52-47 with five minutes left, Iowa State (25-7) made its
run. The Cyclones, the nation's second-best 3-point-shooting team,
finally started hitting their long-range bombs, something they had
not done until that point.
</P>
<P>
   The freshman forward Tracy Gahan began the surge with a
3-pointer from the right wing to pull Iowa State to 52-50 with 4
minutes 37 seconds left. One minute later, the junior guard Stacy
Frese hit one to trim the deficit to 54-53. Then, after the UConn
forward Svetlana Abrosimova missed a driving layup, the Cyclone
sophomore guard Megan Taylor hit a 3 to give Iowa State a 56-54
lead at the 2:19 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones would never trail again. Another Frese 3-pointer
and two free throws preserved the victory as Connecticut misfired
when the Cyclones applied the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   For the top-seeded Huskies (29-5), a third straight sterling
regular season ended in postseason disappointment. For the third
straight season, UConn entered a regional heavily favored to
advance to the Final Four. Two years ago, a Tennessee team with 10
losses beat the Huskies in the last eight. Last season, an
unheralded North Carolina State team sent them home in the last
eight.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they head back to Storrs, Conn., even earlier. The pregame
chatter from the Huskies was that they were relaxed. They had put
that lackluster performance against Xavier in the second round
behind them. Their concentration and intensity level were different
now, the players said.
</P>
<P>
   And Connecticut seemed in control after it went on a 10-2
second-half run to turn a 37-36 deficit into a 46-39 lead _ its
biggest lead of the game _ at the 11-minute mark. The Huskies, for
the second game in a row, looked sluggish at the start, still
struggling with offensive execution, still looking like a team in
desperate need of a floor leader. UConn committed 13 turnovers in
the first half and entered the locker room with the score tied at
28-28, thanks mostly to the play of the freshman forward Tamika
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies forced 11 turnovers and held Frese, Iowa State's
leading scorer at 17 points a game, to two points in the half. But
because of their own turnovers and poor first-half shooting (12 of
35, 34 percent), the Huskies were unable to capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's stars, Abrosimova and Shea Ralph, who entered the game
averaging a combined 34 points, had a combined eight points on
two-of-15 shooting at halftime. If not for the play of Williams, a
native of nearby Dayton, Ohio, the Huskies' struggles would have
been worse. Williams scored 12 points and was five of six from the
field in the half, including 10 points in the final 7:42 before
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   With UConn trailing by its biggest margin of the half at 18-12,
Williams scored five points during a 7-0 run that briefly reclaimed
the lead for the Huskies at 5:43.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
