<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      03-20 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' PROSPECT ESCOBAR HAS THE LOOK OF A FUTURE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Watching players, some of them barely out
of high school, on Friday afternoon, it was hard to imagine that
anyone on the remote field at Dodgertown in nearby Vero Beach was
anywhere close to a year and half away from the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Single A ball seems all the more removed from the majors
than just in name, even if the field in question is, literally,
only a few fields away from the stadium in which the Dodgers play
their exhibition games. But then a 20-year-old center fielder in a
blue and orange Mets uniform lopes to his right to run down a
well-hit ball in the gap between left and center, making a tough
play look effortless, turning what could have been extra bases into
an easy out.
</P>
<P>
   A few innings later, the same player _ now at bat _ drills a
pitch off the right-center-field fence against a blowing wind. His
long, graceful and powerful strides propel him to a stand-up
triple.
</P>
<P>
   And it soon becomes clear why assistant general manager Jim
Duquette, who oversees the Mets' minor league operations, said: ``I
don't like timetables. But if everything goes the way we think,
Alex could be in the major leagues in two years. Maybe one and a
half.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Alex Escobar's countryman, Edgardo Alfonzo, put it best.
At 25, Alfonzo is already one of the better players to come out of
Venezuela. But when he is asked about Escobar _ who was born in
Caracas and grew up in Valencia _ Alfonzo's eyes widen. ``Oh,
man,'' Alfonzo said. ``He's going to be one of the best players
ever from Venezuela. I'll tell you that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And to think, Escobar is coming off his first full season in the
minor leagues. Or that Escobar had only one home run and eight
stolen bases in parts of two injury-plagued professional seasons
(he had hamstring problems) before exploding for 27 homers, 91 runs
batted in, 49 stolen bases and a .310 average for Single A Capital
City last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But it was still the lower ranks of Single A. Baseball America,
the trade magazine, ranked him the 11th-best prospect in baseball.
In terms of outfielders, that placed Escobar third. Neither
Duquette nor Mets general manager Steve Phillips would say that
Escobar is the best prospect in his organization. ``But, other
periodicals rate him that way,'' Duquette said. ``And I wouldn't
disagree with them.''
</P>
<P>
   One National League scout rated Escobar as a potential impact
player in the majors. ``This was the best player I've seen at this
level all year,'' his report said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Mets, who signed Escobar at 16 for
$80,000, feel the same way. Duquette mentioned two of the brightest
young outfield stars in the National League today when discussing
Escobar: 23-year-old Vladimir Guerrero, and soon-to-be 22-year-old
Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not talentwise, even though some people feel that Alex is a
combination of the two,'' Duquette said. ``But in how quickly they
moved through the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones broke into the majors at 19, climbing from Single A to
Double A to Triple A to the Atlanta Braves _ all in 1996. Guerrero
did the same in the Montreal Expos' organization in 1996 at age 20,
and he skipped Triple A.
</P>
<P>
   Is Escobar's throwing skills in the same league with Guerrero's
rifle-like arm?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that good,'' said Escobar, who did throw out an overly
ambitious runner trying to stretch a single into a double on
Friday. ``But it's getting close.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like Jason Tyner, the Mets' baby-faced first-round pick in last
summer's draft, there is some question as to where Escobar will
play once he reaches the majors. But unlike Tyner, there is no
question that Escobar _ who, at 6 feet 1 inch and 188 pounds, looks
so much more mature than the rail-thin Tyner, even with his hair
cropped close to his scalp _ can handle center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you take him off a premium position like that is
if you have a prototype player there,'' Duquette said. ``Someone
like Kenny Lofton or Brett Butler. And we think Tyner could be that
type of player.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tyner is, the Mets feel that Escobar could glide from his
natural position in center to right field as easily as Escobar
shifts from his native Spanish to English when conversing with his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only position I've played since I was little,''
Escobar said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyner is scheduled to start the season with Double A Binghamton.
Escobar, who learned English in high school, is to begin the year
with Single A St. Lucie. When the weather warms up in the north, he
will head for Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will be watching the progress of each player closely.
Their projected starting outfield this season _ Rickey Henderson,
Brian McRae and Bobby Bonilla _ could all be gone in two years. And
nobody knows if Bonilla's health will even allow him to play that
long, meaning the Mets could be grooming Escobar, Tyner and perhaps
the often-injured Jay Payton as their outfield of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that future looked especially bright at Dodgertown on
Friday, as Escobar displayed the five tools that scouts look for _
the ability to hit, hit for power, run, field and throw _ in one
afternoon. Scouts do caution that Escobar needs to cut down on his
strikeouts (Escobar fanned 133 times in 112 games last season).
Still, the Mets like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get a big head, and go from prospect to
suspect,'' Escobar said. ``I just want to be me every day.''
</P>
<P>
   If Escobar continues to develop for the Mets, that should be
more than enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
