<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-20 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: )  
 SPORTS COLUMN: JARVIS AND O'BRIEN MEET AT CROSSROADS OF AN
INCREDIBLE JOURNEY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ After each of his victories in the last two
weeks, Mike Jarvis has referred to St. John's voyage through the
NCAA tournament as an incredible journey. For Jarvis and Ohio
State's Jim O'Brien, this journey borders on a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Last season at this time, Jarvis and O'Brien could not have been
farther from the Promised Land. O'Brien had finished 8-22 in his
first season at Ohio State, good for last place in the Big Ten.
Jarvis was in Washington completing a
familiar-but-not-so-incredible journey at George Washington. The
Colonials had been knocked out of the NCAA tournament _ again.
Jarvis began to face a wrenching reality: His team was merely gator
bait, a delectable morsel for larger programs with greater
resources.
</P>
<P>
   At 53, Jarvis was beginning to wonder how long he would be
chasing the carrot. Not only would GW not reach the hallowed
mountaintop, but getting to the base of the mountain was also a
chore. Jarvis was caught between two cliches: good things come to
those who wait, and create your own breaks.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, who left Boston College after 11 seasons after a
dispute with the administration, hoped for revival and resilience.
A season later Jarvis and O'Brien, 48, are on the coaching
equivalent of cloud nine. St. John's and Ohio State played Saturday
night in the South Regional final. St. John's had an opportunity to
reach the Final Four for the first time since 1985; Ohio State for
the first time since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd how their paths have crossed on this journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up rooting for St. John's,'' the Brooklyn-born O'Brien
said. ``St. John's recruited me when Lou Carnesecca was coaching
there.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1978 to 1985, Jarvis, as head coach at Cambridge Rindge and
Latin, coached some of the best high school players in the nation.
His last year at the Boston high school was the year when St.
John's reached the Final Four. The player who wrecked St. John's in
that national semifinal game was Patrick Ewing, the best high
school player Jarvis coached. It was in his capacity as the Rindge
and Latin head coach that Jarvis first met O'Brien, an assistant at
the University of Connecticut who was recruiting Carl Hobbs at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Brien became the head coach at Boston College in 1986,
Jarvis was beginning his second season as head coach at Boston
University. From 1986 to 1990, O'Brien and Jarvis competed in the
same city. While the two had a cordial relationship off the court,
there was no on-court relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was interested in playing us,'' O'Brien recalled on Friday.
``We had no interest in playing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, who also played against Jim Calhoun's teams at
Northeastern, understood the pecking order and scheme of things.
This is the food chain in Boston: Celtics, Boston College, Boston
University. ``I wouldn't have played BU if I was at BC, either,''
Jarvis said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   So, 12 years later, Jarvis and O'Brien finally got to play.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this season has been more like a crusade for
Jarvis. A season of settling old scores. He is playing teams that
once routinely had eaten the likes of Boston University and George
Washington for appetizers, and he is now playing them with a
formidable arsenal of players. Ron Artest, a versatile
6-foot-7-inch forward, and Erick Barkley, a wiry and efficient
point guard, are all-America-caliber talents that Jarvis never had
access to at Boston University or George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For O'Brien, who had access to players at Boston College but
felt he lacked the support of his bosses when it came to flexible
admissions, Ohio State represents unlimited potential. Scoonie
Penn, the leader of his backcourt, played for O'Brien at Boston
College, then followed him to Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Jarvis punished Indiana and gave Bob Knight's team
a clinic on zone defense and transition basketball. On Thursday,
Jarvis' team routed Maryland, a program that always cast a huge
shadow over George Washington. In each instance, Jarvis underplayed
personal rivalries and stuck with his Incredible Journey script.
It's not about vengeance, not about ``Me vs. Him,'' no Jarvis vs.
Calhoun or Jarvis vs. Williams or Jarvis vs. O'Brien. In fact,
Jarvis said that this season, St. John's run was not about reaching
the Final Four or even winning the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   While his players talk about staying focused and winning it all,
Jarvis described his goals in much broader terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids look at the destination, more than an older person like
me who looks at the journey,'' he said. ``These kids decided right
away where they wanted to go; they knew where they wanted to get. I
wanted to take the ride. And I'm still on the ride. These guys are
focused on destination. I'm a journey guy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
