<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE21-COX     03-20 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE21-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Low scores at midterm
</P>
<P>
   By Curtis Bunn
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Sercie
</P>
<P>
   The Year of the Brick reached its midway point this weekend, and
it's a wonder a record was not set for cracked backboards. Masonry
work reigns in this postlockout, freaky 50-game season. And one
more thing was clear through the flying particles: The NBA
championship is as wide open as it's been since, well, Michael
Jordan retired to pursue baseball in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   There are many factors in teams' cockeyed shooting, not the
least of which is defensive schemes so intricate and thorough it
would boggle the mind. For instance, films of opponents are so
finely broken down that Team A knows exactly how many times Team B
starts its offense on the right side, how many dribbles a player
probably will take before raising for a shot, what angle passes to
the post come from and just about anything else but how many times
a player chews gum before taking a free throw.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the NBA has no secrets. Defense dominates, which
means the club that can put together enough offense amid the
bumping and grinding has the best shot at winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it's the late start (to the season), some of it is
that guys just don't shoot as well anymore,'' Miami coach Pat Riley
said. ``And then there's defenses and physical play. Teams lock in
on people and situations. It's not easy to score in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   That was never more apparent than this season. No team has an
average as high as 100 points per game, and the league average is
just over 91 points. Compare that with 10 years ago, when the NBA
average was 109.2 points, with 24 of 25 teams scoring more than 100
a game.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the combined shooting average was 43 percent going
into the weekend, 48 percent in 1989. Eighteen teams' shooting
percentage was less than 44 percent. Even foul shooting was down
from 10 years ago, from 76 to 72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks scored just five points in the third quarter
against Chicago two weeks ago. The Hawks had a stretch of home
games where they scored 68, 73 and 73 points, respectively.
Virtually every club set or approached some sort of record for
offensive futility.
</P>
<P>
   Which helps create a wide-open race for the title. There is no
apparent front-runner in either conference. Most impressive has
been the Utah Jazz, which won the Western Conference last year. But
the ever-changing Los Angeles Lakers, with Glen Rice in the fold
and _ presumably _ Dennis Rodman, have the talent and depth to make
a serious challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more excuses,'' center Shaquille O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Portland Trail Blazers, who have meshed
nicely under first-year coach Mike Dunleavy. Once considered
enigmatic, the Blazers have been stunningly efficient _ and
explosive. The rest of the pack in the West, including Houston and
San Antonio, seems to lack the necessary firepower.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the Indiana Pacers seem to have stepped back from
last year, when they took Jordan's Bulls to seven games in the
conference finals. There's little fire there. The Pacers seem a
year older.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Riley's Heat could be at the top of the class. Miami
plays unrelenting defense and unselfishly on offense.
Significantly, they have a clutch point guard in Tim Hardaway who
can create off the dribble at the end of tight games.
</P>
<P>
   No other team established itself in the season's first half.
Detroit, Orlando, Atlanta and New York represent a second tier that
appears to be more pretender than contender.
</P>
<P>
   All this parity should make for an interesting playoff run in
May. It's uncertain who will win the title in June, but it's pretty
certain they'll do it after shooting poorly.
</P>
<P>
   MIDSEASON REPORT
</P>
<P>
   ROOKIE OF THE HALF
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Paul Pierce (right). For his overall game, Pierce gets
the nod over the spectacular Vince Carter of Toronto. Carter is a
thrill a minute who has to work on his jumper and defense.
</P>
<P>
   COACH OF THE HALF
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Pat Riley. With two starters out all season, Mr.
Slickback has somehow fashioned a club that held the best record in
the East going into the weekend. His team believes in his
philosophy of defense and unselfishness and plays with a passion
and pride.
</P>
<P>
   SURPRISE TEAMS
</P>
<P>
   Portland, Philadelphia, New Jersey. Any team with Isaiah Rider
on it is primed to implode at any time, yet the Trail Blazers have
led the Pacific Division from the start. Most surprising is that
they're doing it with team ball. The 76ers, led by Allen Iverson,
have emerged as a tough defensive club and challenger in the
Atlantic. Below them are the Nets, who hope to reverse their
fortunes after getting Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   MOST IMPROVED
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Joe Smith (left). The former No. 1 pick looked like
a spent fighter last year _ dazed and lifeless with Golden State.
But he's been a force inside teaming with Kevin Garnett, making the
loss of Tom Gugliotta less of a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   MVP THUS FAR
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal. Over the years, O'Neal has taken his hits for
having interests outside of basketball. The Lakers all-star center
contended he was not fazed by the criticism, that he would
persevere. And guess what? He has.
</P>
<P>
   So drastic has O'Neal's growth been in the last two years that
he is the stabilizing force on a Lakers club that seems primed for
an NBA championship. And it all evolves around O'Neal, who might be
selected the league's MVP if the vote were held at the season's
midway point.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, O'Neal's success goes beyond his gaudy averages
of 28 points, 13 rebounds, 3 blocks. Additionally, The Diesel has
functioned as team leader and spokesman; he even speaks at times
with emotion and not that irritating monotone. It's clear now more
than ever that he's playing to win championships.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing more, nothing less. When he bolted Orlando as a free
agent for the Lakers, critics said that if he really wanted to win
he would have continued his tandem with guard Penny Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   However, many people did not realize that wherever O'Neal went
would become contenders or that the Lakers were more loaded than
Orlando. Now, at 27, O'Neal is on the cusp of something great
because he's holding things together on the court and in a locker
room diseased by Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has been admirable as players around him either come and
go or struggle to find their niche. Others who have been
outstanding so far this season: Philadelphia's Allen Iverson,
Utah's Karl Malone, Miami's Alonzo Mourning, Seattle's Gary Payton.
But none has been more valuable than O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
