<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAWEST21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA WEST: Shaq blasts Sager
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal is levying harsh criticism at NBA
reporter Craig Sager of TNT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig Sager's a liar,'' O'Neal said after a Sager report
claimed that Lakers players voted 12-0 to fine Dennis Rodman for
leaving the team to go to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any votes that go down are called by the (players' team)
president, handled by the president and tallied up by the president
_ me. There were no votes. I don't know what ... Craig's talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Kurt Rambis said the TNT report is just another
part of the tabloid haze that surrounds Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's crazy,'' Rambis said. ``That's ludicrous. First of all,
we handle our disciplinary problems internally through management.
Players are given a set of rules. They don't determine who gets
fined or anything like that. They don't have a say in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Humbling experience
</P>
<P>
   The world has turned upside-down for Dennis Scott, waived by the
Knicks eight days ago, then signed Wednesday to a 10-day contract
by Minnesota. ``Nine years ago, I'd watch people come in for 10-day
contracts, and I thought I'd never have to go through something
like that,'' Scott said. ``But my mother used to say that life
isn't the destination _ it's the journey and how you survive it.
Right now I'm fighting and pushing. I know I can do well, I can
still put up some good numbers. Hopefully, I can do that here.''
With Anthony Peeler and Malik Sealy ailing, T-Wolves coach Flip
Sanders gives Scott typical 10-day billing: ``He's been around, and
he knows how to play. It's really a matter of how he feeds off of
the other players.''
</P>
<P>
   Three who are free
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 Lorenzen Wright (Clippers), No. 9 Samaki Walker (Dallas)
and No. 10 Erick Dampier (Golden State, via Indiana) are the picks
among the top 10 from the 1996 draft who did not sign extensions
before last week's deadline. As a result, they become free agents
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Models of consistency
</P>
<P>
   St. Patrick's Day marked the first anniversary of Denver's last
road victory, at Washington. Going back to the end of 1996-97
season, the Nuggets have lost 66 of their last 69 road games. They
are 0-12 this season, were 2-41 last season, and finished 1996-97
winning only one of their final 16 road games. Their current road
losing streak is up to 19. They have lost 29 of the last 30 on
road. ... Opposite end of the spectrum: The Utah Jazz has gone 94
games without losing two straight. That dates back to Nov. 20,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Not-so-great Scottie
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen shook the Rockets' world by complaining about his
discomfort with the offense. In truth, coach Rudy Tomjanovich has
rewritten the plays to include Pippen, calling his favorites and
adjusting them to Pippen's specifications. But the Rockets also
have charted the results, and the plays that begin with Charles
Barkley posting up have resulted in field goals or fouls more than
twice as regularly as anything designed for Pippen. Although Pippen
is Houston's best defender and passer, he has shown an alarming
inability to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain man
</P>
<P>
   The Kings hope Oliver Miller is ready to turn his life around.
Team president Geoff Petrie said Miller will remain at the Red
Mountain Spa in St. George, Utah, until he reaches a weight
mutually agreed upon. ``We gave him a goal weight, and he's
hopefully working toward that,'' Petrie said. The 6-foot-9 Miller
weighed more than 350 pounds when he reported. He claims, ``I'm
ready to play. I know my body fat has dropped from 26 percent to 16
percent. My fat mass was at 94 and now it's at 74. All I know is, I
feel a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
