<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY SENT MIAMI PACKING BY CONTAINING SZCZERBIAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Wally Szczerbiak could not rescue Miami University
one more time. He could not keep his and Miami's magical journey
through March alive, not by himself. That is really what it
amounted to as Szczerbiak and four sometimes invisible teammates
fought a deep Kentucky team and lost, 58-43, Friday night. The
matchup was a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak was the premier player on the court, but Scott
Padgett was almost his equal and the Wildcats proved that they were
the premier team with smothering defense and more than enough depth
to outlast the one-dimensional Redhawks.
</P>
<P>
   It was an awful experience for Miami of Ohio, which could have
made the game much more competitive if someone not named Szczerbiak
occasionally slashed to the hoop or drilled a jumper.
</P>
<P>
   So it is the team with the best players, not the team with the
best player, which marched through the semifinals of the Midwest
Region to oppose first-seeded Michigan State on Sunday. The
Spartans slogged past 13th-seeded Oklahoma, 54-46, in a game that
even Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves called ugly.
</P>
<P>
   The ugliest moment came as Cleaves and Eduardo Najera collided
when Najera set a screen and both crumbled to the floor. It was a
gruesome sight, but both returned to play and Cleaves, who has a
bruised forehead, will start on Sunday. In the prettier contest,
Padgett had 17 points, including 14 in the second half and 12
during one dazzling streak that destroyed Miami. If the Wildcats
(28-8) beat Michigan State (32-4), they will scamper into the Final
Four for the fourth consecutive season and will be trying to snatch
their third title in that period.
</P>
<P>
   Padgett and third-seeded Kentucky prevailed. Like Oklahoma
(22-11), Szczerbiak and 10th-seeded Miami (24-8), which has now
lost 18 straight to the Wildcats dating to 1927, went home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have any competitiveness in you and you know the guy
that you're going to be guarding is talked about as the man, you
got to take it personally a little because you got to have some
pride,'' said Padgett, about playing against Szczerbiak. ``Yeah, I
took it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak finished his glorious career with 23 points, only
eight of which came after intermission. Padgett and Jamaal Magloire
were the two players who defended him most often.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats were very physical with Szczerbiak and much more
open to letting him shoot jumpers. Szczerbiak, who went 8 for 16
from the field, was stymied by Kentucky's constantly shifting zones
and the Wildcats obliterated the screens that Miami sets to get
Szczerbiak open. The other players on Miami (24-8) were a gory 6
for 28 from the field. Only two other Redhawks had more than two
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to do whatever it took to keep us in the
game,'' said Szczerbiak. ``Unfortunately, it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   A dejected Charlie Coles, Miami's coach, said: ``I hoped we
would have played well if we lost. I don't think we did.''
</P>
<P>
   How one-dimensional were the Redhawks? Another player did not
score a field goal until there was 2:50 left in the half. It was
obvious that Szczerbiak needed to have a tremendous game to even
keep the contest close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Wally was going to get his points,'' said Padgett.
``We wanted to play good team defense and make other people make
the plays for them. I know this is crazy to say, but he only got 16
shots. I guess we limited him a little.''
</P>
</TEXT>
