<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-ARGENTINA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIP TO ARGENTINA PROVES FRUITFUL WITH ROD AND REEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER KAMINSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If an angler subdues a large trout, and there is no one there to
see it, did it really happen? Or, more to the point, will any of
the angler's friends believe it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bloody likely,'' I thought recently, after I landed a
22-inch rainbow in the exquisite Arroyo Verde of Patagonia in
southern Argentina. I yelled as loudly as a man who has been
surprised by a tiger. ``Dick! Javier! Yo! Guys!''
</P>
<P>
   I cradled the fish, holding it by its flanks, moving it back and
forth to revive it as my cohorts answered my alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice fish,'' Dick Moore said. Dick is my neighbor in Brooklyn,
N.Y., and though a lifelong fisherman, he had, to that point, been
a desultory fly-rodder. But in the course of six days arranged by
an old fishing pal, one of Patagonia's pioneering outfitters, Jorge
Truco of San Martin de los Andes, I saw the lure of this sport hook
Dick as surely as my hopper had lodged itself in that rainbow's
jaw.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed at the Estancia Quemquemtreu, an immense ranch in the
high desert region of Patagonia. The estate managers, Paula and
Martin Zimmerman, are quintessential Argentinians: good-looking and
with style to burn (they can elevate blowsy pants, a beret, and a
scarf to Astaire-like elegance). Quemquemtreu livestock provided
the fare for meals of broiled meat prepared over the wood fire and
iron grill _ the hallmarks of Argentine ranch cookery. Paula's
garden yielded squash, tomatoes, onions, lettuce and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   On our first morning, Dick and I were driven by our guide,
Javier Panutti, to a private stretch of the Chimehuin, a brawling
freestone river where the legendary Bebe Anchorena had once taken
the world record dry-fly brown trout and the world record wet-fly
brown. Off in the distance, the dormant volcano, Lanin, reared over
the plain.
</P>
<P>
   We pulled into a field, and as we did, a small herd of red stag
and two guanacos (a relative to the llama) bolted away. Javier led
us across a series of braids and channels, not unlike the Madison
River of Montana. We fished only at the head of runs or in
well-oxygenated riffles. A long, dry, hot spell sent the trout to
colder or, failing that, well-aerated water.
</P>
<P>
   On our way through the bankside grass, we had kicked up a lot of
grasshoppers. I tied on a hopper imitation. Dick, who was just
beginning to get his casting together, stayed with wet flies. We
both caught plenty of fish. Most satisfying to me was a rainbow
that required a cast to the limits of my 4 weight rod. I reached
out to the spot, 60 feet away, where Javier directed me. With a
whole channel's worth of strong current between rod and fly, the
cast had to be on the money. I would get, at most, two feet of
drag-free float.
</P>
<P>
   The trout struck with a wallop, leaping out of the water and
sprinting downstream in the fast current. I pulled back as hard as
my tackle would allow. The fish turned and finally surrendered. An
18-incher that Javier unhooked and revived.
</P>
<P>
   For the next four days, we sampled the waters within a two-hour
drive. When a thunderstorm clouded up the Collan Cura, normally a
good dry-fly river, a chance encounter at the yearly agricultural
fair in the nearby town of Junin led to an invitation to the Arroyo
Verde, a stream of great clarity and wary fish. Wherever we went,
though, we were pursued by the cast-bedeviling winds that the
Mapuche Indians call Puelches. Their steady gale lasted for days,
but wind is an omnipresent fact of life in fly-casting.
</P>
<P>
   On our last morning, Javier took us to a little river, the
Quilquihue. Its course through a few miles of tall fir trees
promised some relief from the Puelches. I walked downstream. I took
a half-dozen good trout. I was hungry and my thoughts turned to a
final meal in Junin where Senor Buamscha, a second-generation
Lebanese restaurateur whom I had met a dozen years ago, served up
smoked red stag and slabs of grilled meat.
</P>
<P>
   I made my way upstream to Dick, who was casting in midpool.
Since there was nothing happening, I was about to tempt him with my
visions of a final gaucho feast. For some reason I didn't, and I am
glad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Dick,'' I said, ``they're only going to be at the head of
the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the left side of a V formed by the current, I asked
him to cast to the crotch of the V, where a trout cooperated by
striking. Dick, the trout and I were all caught off guard when the
trout rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cast a little further upstream,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Another fish struck, and Dick landed him, a handsome rainbow:
the first fish he had taken on a dry. His cast looked crisp and in
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've probably alerted all the fish in that arm of the
current,'' I said. ``Walk up alongside it and cast over it to the
other part of the V.''
</P>
<P>
   A nice cast and an upstream mend gave his hopper a good float.
Wham! A terrific rainbow hit and rocketed into the air _ once,
twice, three times _ as it fled to the depths of the pool. Dick
fought it patiently and landed his best fish of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't get any better,'' Dick said. ``We might as well leave
on a high note.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
