<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/20/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- March 20, 1999 -- OBIT-FORREST-B&AMP;W, 3-20 --
Ray Forrest in the first television commercial on July 4, 1941.
Forrest, who worked for many years at his family's jewelry store in
Paterson, N.J., died March 11 at a hospital near his home in
Kinnelon, N.J. He was 83 and all but forgotten as the man who
became a hero to hundreds in 1939 as the nation's first television
personality. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 20, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS, 3-20 --
Derek Jeter is displaying his skills in the best place to have them
displayed: New York. The Yankees' shortstop will receive his second
championship ring next month. He has averaged nearly 200 hits per
season. He has finished third in the most valuable player
balloting. He is among the game's most popular players. And he is
only 24 years old. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- March 20, 1999 -- BKC-EAST,
3-20 -- In the bumping and infighting under the basket, Duke's 6-8,
265-pound center Elton Brand usually comes up with the ball. In
Friday night's regional semifinals, Duke won comfortably, 78-61,
over Southwest Missouri State. (Barton Silverman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BOULDER, Colo. -- March 20, 1999 --
COMPUTER-SNAFU-REVIEW, 3-20 -- 18-year-old Truman Bradley of
Boulder, with lawn ornament. Bradley received a form letter from
Arizona State University, in which the prospective student's Social
Security number had been inadvertently substituted for his name.
The university says only a handful of such faulty letters were
mailed, and the glitch has been corrected. (Kevin Moloney/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LOS ANGELES -- March 20, 1999 -- PORN-PALACE-REVIEW,
3-20 -- Mati Asgarian, left, and George Seno browsing at Hustler
Hollywood - a 9,000-square-foot up-market sex emporium - after an
evening at an oxygen bar. Opened last December, its sleek design,
aromatic candles and Kama Sutra massage oils are intended to appeal
to women. It is the flagship of what owner Larry Flynt hopes will
be a nationwide Hustler chain. (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 20, 1999 --
POLITICAL-HANGERS-ON-REVIEW, 3-20 -- Former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., has indicated that he may want to run again for his old
job. Like ghosts of elections past, defeated politicians trying to
reclaim old glory demand attention from voters and the media. But
the people they often end up scaring the most are members of their
own parties. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MILWAUKEE -- March 20, 1999 -- WELFARE-TAXES, 3-20 -- In
the first tax season after Wisconsin's welfare reductions, tax
preparers have arrived in droves on Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
Drive in Milwaukee, joining the check-cashing stores, as they seek
the business of the neighborhood's new workers. These people are
waiting to get their checks cashed. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HARRISBURG, Pa. -- March 20, 1999 -- CONGRESS-CIVILITY,
3-20 -- Members of Congress, some with their families, arriving in
Harrisburg on their way to the Second Bipartisan Congressional
Retreat in Hershey, Pa., this weekend. Nearly 200 Republicans and
Democrats came together to exercise diplomacy, exorcise their
demons and relax. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- March 20, 1999 -- COHEN-PROFILE, 3-20 --
Janet Cohen, in the Washington apartment she shares with her
husband, Defense Secretary William S. Cohen, has gone from 30 years
on television to a new role as a one-woman morale booster for the
armed services. ``My mission is to support Bill,'' Mrs. Cohen says.
``He's the passion of my life, and it's impassioned me about our
military people.'' (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ALBANY, Calif. -- March 20, 1999 -- TEXTBOOK-ADS-2, 3-20
-- Detail from a page of ``Mathematics: Applications and
Connections,'' published by McGraw-Hill, showing Nikes next to a
math problem. A spokesman for McGraw-Hill said the publisher
received no payments from companies whose products appear in the
book. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ALBANY, Calif. -- March 20, 1999 -- TEXTBOOK-ADS-1, 3-20
-- When Joe Stein discovered what appeared to be advertisements
intertwined in his son Noah's sixth-grade mathematics textbook, he
filed complaints with local officials. ``I found it offensive that
the lesson he was learning was about commercialism and how even the
school district and other public forums weren't free from this sort
of thing,'' he says. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SANTA ANA, Calif. -- March 20, 1999 --
TATTOO-CHRISTIANS-2, 3-20 -- Rob Silva, a tattoo artist at Sid's
Tattoo Parlor in Santa Ana, puts a tattoo of Jesus' face on Robert
Goodwin's arm. The three men who work at Sid's are born-again
Christians. So too are many of their young customers, who include
Christian rock musicians. (Jill Connelly/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SANTA ANA, Calif. -- March 20, 1999 --
TATTOO-CHRISTIANS-1, 3-20 -- Rob Silva, a tattoo artist at Sid's
Tattoo Parlor in Santa Ana, works on a client. The shop is known
for its Christian tattoos. ``This is a job, but our lives are a
ministry,'' says Sid Stankovits, 27, proprietor of the tidy,
brightly lighted space in a modest strip mall here. ``We're totally
blessed that we can bring our ministries into our jobs.'' (Jill
Connelly/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HOLLYWOOD -- March 20, 1999 -- OSCARS-HOLIDAY-2, 3-20 --
Photos mark the seats of nominees for the Academy Award Ceremony at
the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion in Los Angeles. For the first time in
its 71-year history the event is being held on ``Oscar Sunday'' in
a bid to win even bigger television viewership for the industry's
single biggest self-advertisement. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOLLYWOOD -- March 20, 1999 -- OSCARS-HOLIDAY-1, 3-20 --
Tina Hernandez of Huntington Beach has camped out since Tuesday for
bleacher seats to watch the arrivals at the 71st Academy Awards
Ceremony. She has attended the event for the last 16 years. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
