<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-CELTICS-NY     03-20 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CELTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING IS BACK IN KNICK LINEUP,   BUT IT'S STILL THE SPREWELL SHOW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Latrell Sprewell was blinking, buzzing and glowing
like a neon sign on a deserted road Saturday. For miles and miles
of this game, there was just Sprewell and no one else on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing was nearly invisible in his return. Allan Houston
and Larry Johnson were part of the background scenery as Sprewell
bolted off the bench late in the first quarter and stirred the New
York Knicks out of their malaise for a simple 96-78 victory against
the Boston Celtics at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell came in when Ewing looked a little out of sync in his
first game back in two weeks, and when the Knicks were struggling
to keep pace with the frenetic Celtics. Instantly, the game turned
as Sprewell began running and driving and dunking, collecting 18 of
his 27 points in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were on wheels, with Marcus Camby, who grabbed a
season-high 15 rebounds, and Chris Childs (7 assists) flying
alongside of Sprewell. The Knicks ended the game with a 46-42
rebounding advantage and found some revenge after losing in Boston
three weeks ago. They turned the ball over 26 times in that game,
but just 11 times Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were led by Ron Mercer's 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Popular thinking held that Ewing's return to the lineup after
missing six games with Achilles' tendinitis would mean a return to
the languid side for the Knicks. But Sprewell would not stand for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Practically ignoring Ewing's presence, Sprewell turned the game
into a one-on-five affair in an electrifying display in the first
half. Once Sprewell arrived with five minutes left in the first
quarter, and his team trailing by 5 points, Ewing shot once more
before coach Jeff Van Gundy took him out at the start of the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That was when the Knicks really found freedom on the wings of
Sprewell. With Camby and Childs as partners in his uptempo style,
Sprewell began leaking out on the breaks and finding easy dunks on
cross-court passes. He was slicing inside of Antoine Walker and
Paul Pierce to draw fouls and tap in put-backs. Then, off a miss by
Houston with four minutes left in the half, Sprewell darted toward
the baseline, grabbed the ball and took a leap inside of Kenny
Anderson for a dunk as he was being fouled.
</P>
<P>
   It was all Sprewell, all the time. Not only did he score 9 of
his 21 first-half points in the 14-3 run that sent the Knicks into
halftime ahead, 55-45, but he aggressively handled Mercer, who had
danced away from Houston to score 12 first-quarter points. Mercer
was shut down by the omnipresent Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   The lead Sprewell set up for his teammates in the first half was
pushed to 73-57 by the starters with four minutes left in the third
quarter. Then Sprewell arrived again, and the Knicks' lead swelled
to 80-60 by the end of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of pushing the Knicks toward chaos _ which is what they
did three weeks ago in Boston, where they humiliated the Knicks,
90-84, and forced 26 turnovers _ the Celtics were being pressed
into 16 turnovers before the third quarter was over.
</P>
<P>
   In this kind of game, with Sprewell's energy level off the
charts, the Knicks did not need to lean on their star center.
Ewing, who took six shots before Sprewell took over, ended the
first half 2 of 7 and with a scowl on his face. At one point toward
the end of the second quarter, he appeared to scold Houston for not
passing to him.
</P>
<P>
   If Ewing's pride was wounded, it did not matter. That Johnson
was 0 for 3 and Houston was 2 for 6 was also of little consequence.
The Knicks were off and running with Sprewell in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Knicks maintained their roll in the third quarter,
Van Gundy was most likely taking little comfort in it. If the
Knicks had established anything in the first half of the season, it
was their inability to sustain a good feeling from one game to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   It was that inconsistency that had left Van Gundy shaking his
head more than a few times as the Knicks hit the halfway point of
the shortened season Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we're at or where we're heading,'' Van
Gundy said. ``I don't have a great feeling for it with as many new
people as we have. Really, that's where I'm at. Not knowing their
personalities and characteristics, I don't know if we are going to
get better as the year goes on, tougher, or if a little adversity
is going to get us sideways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more a statement of not knowing our team. I could have
had a better idea in the past years.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   After spending his career as a starter and reaching all-star
status at Golden State, Latrell Sprewell reluctantly has gone along
with being a sixth man for the Knicks. Coach Jeff Van Gundy is
aware of the asides Sprewell has mumbled to indicate his
displeasure with the position. ``I would like him to be more
accepting, but I can understand it,'' said Van Gundy, who has used
Sprewell off the bench because it gives the Knicks balance and an
injection of energy. ``That he is less than pleased, I would expect
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever irritation playing off the bench has caused for
Sprewell, he has been playing heavy minutes and producing in his
role. Van Gundy did not rule out moving Sprewell into the starting
lineup _ the role the Knicks originally envisioned for him _ if the
team continues to play inconsistently ... The Celtics rookie Paul
Pierce reinjured his ankle two days ago, and did not start
Saturday. In Boston's 94-80 victory against the Knicks on Feb. 26,
Pierce scored 24 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
