u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MAZZIA-NYT &LR;      03-20 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MAZZIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINO MAZZIA, STUDENT OF DEATHS UNDER ANESTHESIA, DIES AT 77  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif. )   By RICHARD SEVERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Valentino D.B. Mazzia, who was a pioneer in the
investigation of operating room deaths in New York and who also
served as chairman of the department of anesthesiology at the New
York University School of Medicine, died on March 10 at Mount Sinai
Hospital. Mazzia, who held degrees in medicine and law, was 77 and
lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Baden, the forensic pathologist and a longtime
friend, said Mazzia died of cirrhosis of the liver caused by
hepatitis C, which he contracted years ago in his work as an
anesthesiologist. He had received two liver transplants, Baden
said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1961 to 1972, before he turned to law, he worked with Dr.
Baden and under Dr. Milton Helpern, who was then New York's City's
Chief Medical Examiner. Baden said that Mazzia's work led to
improvements in anesthesiology and surgical procedures in operating
rooms around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``His greatest contribution was helping to create the specialty
of forensic anesthesiology by actually going to the scene, which
was the operating room, to see if something went wrong,'' Baden
said. ``He would go in and say, `You can't use this room until it
is checked out,' if there was a death. He investigated on the spot
and not later from a file.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzia was born in New York City on Feb. 17, 1922, the son of
Alexander Mazzia and the former Francesca D'Alessandro. A 1943
graduate of City College, he earned his medical degree from New
York University in 1950. He taught at Cornell University Medical
School from 1952 to 1961. He was chairman of the anesthesiology
department at New York University in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   He then became interested in the legal aspects of medicine, and
in the early 1970s he earned a law degree from the University of
Southern California and a doctorate in jurisprudence from the
University of Denver in 1978. For the next two decades, he worked
as a malpractice lawyer, mostly in New York and in the South.
</P>
<P>
   From 1971 to 1973, Mazzia was director of anesthesiology at the
Los Angeles County-Martin Luther King Jr. General Hospital, and he
practiced medicine in the 1970's in Bakersfield, Calif., and in Las
Vegas, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzia was a consultant in several well-known criminal cases. He
worked with the prosecution in the second murder trial of Dr. Carl
Coppolino, in Naples, Fla., in 1967. Dr. Coppolino, charged with
killing his wife with a muscle-relaxing drug, was convicted of
second-degree murder and sentenced to life in prison; he was
granted parole in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzia was also a consultant with the defense in the trial of
Dr. Mario E. Jascalevich in Hackensack, N.J., in the late 1970s.
Jascalevich, known as Dr. X before he was publicly identified, was
acquitted of murdering three patients with another muscle relaxant,
curare.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzia's survivors include his wife, Rosana; a brother,
Alexander L., of Palos Verdes Estates, Calif.; a sister, Leticia L.
Kahrilas of Placentia, Calif., and three children from a previous
marriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
