r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-OSCARS-TEX     03-20 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-OSCARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S HOW SPORTS SHOULD GIVE OUT OSCARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER AND RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers has tallied the votes. The red carpet has
been rolled out. Joan Rivers' fashion fangs are bared.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing from tonight's 71st Academy Awards is a
splash of sports.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem a natural marriage between sports and movies, two
of this nation's primary pastimes. Unfortunately, Hollywood is more
interested in ``the smell of napalm in the morning'' than the smell
of the locker room, and more fascinated by DeMille and De Niro than
by DeBartolo or DeClercq.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are some ties. Best actor nominee Tom Hanks (Saving
Private Ryan) once portrayed a female-league baseball manager in A
League Of Their Own. And his best actor foe Nick Nolte (Affliction)
once played a football wide receiver in North Dallas Forty. And the
director of best picture candidate Shakespeare in Love is _ wham! _
John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Different John Madden? Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   If only the world of movies were more reflective of the world of
sports. Oscars Gamble, Robertson and De La Hoya would be leading
men, and movies like The Waterboy _ actually about Texas Motor
Speedway vice president Eddie Gossage dispelling rumors that his
track is leaking, then calling off qualifying for the Texas 500
because of seepage, would receive more respect from the Academy for
their hidden sports subplots.
</P>
<P>
   With the desire to meld sports and movies, here are the
Star-Telegram's nominees we'd like to see take home awards tonight.
And the winner, and our own special runner-up, is ...
\Nsubheds:Best picture Doctor Doolittle: After blowing into town
atop a cloud of his own verbal bluster, Mavericks GM Don Nelson and
his Ph.D. in basketball fail to back up his words.
</P>
<P>
   One True Thing: The New York Yankees win the World Series in the
sequel to the flop One False Thing in which the Rangers promised to
score multiple runs in a series against New York. \Nsubheds:Best
director Six days/Seven nights: Tom Schieffer nervously counts the
hours until catcher Pudge Rodriguez arrives at spring training to
officially denounce his leadership skills.
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Red Line: A black-clad Ken Hitchcock gives a chilling
performance in this examination of the underworld that is the NHL's
illegal two-line pass. \Nsubheds:Best actor The Man in the Iron
Mask: Suspenseful drama depicts the postseason misery of Stars
goalie Ed Belfour, who violently checks to see if in-the-crease
opponents are wearing Iron Cups.
</P>
<P>
   The Horse Whisperer: Tragic tale of a freak vocal chord injury
that renders loquacious Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe
speechless. Almost. \Nsubheds:Best actress The Parent Trap: Gymnast
Dominique Moceanu does backflips after reclaiming her fortune and
winning her legal independence from a domineering dad.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary &AMP; Jackie: The seedy story of the ladies Carmen Electra
found in hubby Dennis Rodman's hotel suite. \Nsubheds:Best
screenplay _ original The Negotiator: NBA union chief Billy Hunter
fights for a fair deal but winds up sending players into a league
where nobody shoots straight and small-market teams can't afford to
keep their players.
</P>
<P>
   Gods and Monsters: Spine-tingling thriller in which Cowboys
owner Jerry Jones details his draft-day plans to pick a god (but
only if he plays like a monster) and a monster (but only if he acts
like a god). \Nsubheds:Best original score A Perfect Murder:
Nebraska's baseball team scores more than Warren Beatty in its
record rout of Chicago State, 50-3.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Impact: Meteoric rookie Randy Moss shakes the NFL with a
tidal wave of bombs that lead the Vikings to a record 554 points.
\Nsubheds:Best foreign film You've Got Mail: If it's addressed by
the International Olympic Committee and you're a potential host
city, the package is likely to contain cash, plane tickets and
college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The Wedding Singer: A flop as a Mavericks first-round draft
pick, German 20-year-old Dirk Nowitzki, stays in America and takes
a job performing at Oktoberfest. \Nsubheds:Best visual effects A
Civil Action: Raiders owner Al Davis bogs down California's entire
legal system by keeping his football team in perpetual motion and
creating the mirage that his business is good for their business.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasantville: The Broncos' back-to-back Super Bowls colorize
previously blase Denver until John Elway's retirement creates a
sudden Mile-High Armageddon. \Nsubheds:Best short film Out of
Sight: Biographical tear-jerker follows the kaput career of boxing
judge Eugenia Williams after her mathematically inept
Holyfield-Lewis decision. \Nsubheds:Best costume design A Simple
Plan: Despite his all-business approach on the field, University of
Texas running back Ricky Williams disguises himself off it with
dreadlocks, earrings, a Heisman Trophy, an extra 20 pounds and even
a Rangers uniform.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
