<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PRICE-BOOM-REAL-     03-20 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PRICE-BOOM-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SUBURBAN HOUSING MARKET, ONLY DIRECTION IS UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By just about any measure, 1998 was quite a year for the
residential real-estate market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Mark McGwire housing economy,'' was the way James Hughes,
dean of the Rutgers University School of Planning and Public
Policy, put it, ``like hitting 70 home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, for the housing industry,'' Hughes said, ``all
the economic and demographic stars were in full alignment.'' So,
whether viewed from a national, regional or local perspective, a
lot of people bought houses _ despite near-pandemic price
increases.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburban arc around New York City, every one of 577
ZIP-code areas in 14 counties saw prices increase last year,
according to repeat-sales figures compiled by Case Shiller Weiss,
which surveys housing prices nationally. The year's performance was
so strong that observers and interpreters of the market are
debating its sustainability.
</P>
<P>
   Lifting off from a launch pad of solid economic fundamentals _
low inflation, low unemployment, low and very stable mortgage rates
_ the industry set records:
</P>
<P>
   The 4.78 million sales of existing homes in the United States
last year broke the previous record of 4.21 million sales set in
1997, which had broken the previous record of 4.08 million sales
set in 1996, according to the National Association of Realtors.
``You're talking 550,000 more homes sold last year than in 1997,''
said Fred Flick, chief economist for the association. ``That's a
pretty sizable increase.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of 888,000 newly constructed homes last year broke the
national record of 819,000 set in 1977, according to the Census
Bureau. ``You had all regions going full throttle,'' said Steven
Berman, a statistician for the bureau's residential statistics
branch. ``The Midwest set a record of 166,000 new homes sold. The
South set a record, 397,000. The West had its third best year ever,
244,000. And the Northeast had 82,000 sales, its highest since
1989, when it was 86,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the nation's home-ownership rate set a record
in 1998, with 66.3 percent of all households owning their own
homes, the Census Bureau reported.
</P>
<P>
   New York state set a record for existing-home sales, according
to the New York State Association of Realtors, with the 86,661
transactions surpassing by 14.3 percent the high of 75,796 sales in
1996. ``It was a tremendous year for New York's real estate
market,'' said Charles Staro, executive vice president of the state
realtors association, ``evidenced by the fact that 37 of our 40
local boards posted sales gains.''
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester County, to cite one dramatic example, sales last
year jumped 50.1 percent, spurring _ in the opinion of one
real-estate executive in neighboring Rockland County _ a 94.8
percent vault in Rockland's sales as house-hungry buyers widened
their sights.
</P>
<P>
   Those were extremes, to be sure. But sales-volume increases in
neighboring states last year were certainly healthy: 13.4 percent
in New Jersey and 13.9 percent in Connecticut. For the 10 counties
of northern New Jersey closest to New York, the increase was 7.2
percent; for Fairfield County, Conn., it was 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And as demand goes, so goes price. Throughout the three-state
metropolitan region, according to the National Association of
Realtors, median prices rose 5.7 percent, from $177,900 in 1997 to
$188,100 last year. Around New York City's suburban arc, price
increases ranged from 3.4 percent for northern New Jersey ($199,300
in 1997 and $206,100 last year) to 24 percent in Westchester
County, N.Y., ($293,400 in 1997 and $363,900 last year).
</P>
<P>
   Tracking real-estate trends by the numbers defies absolute
precision. Although single-family house sales are reported by local
realty boards, not all real estate agents are members of the boards
and not all sales are made through agents, so not all sales in a
given area are recorded.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, while one board may use median prices _
meaning half the sales are above that figure and half below _
others calculate an average. Still, the numbers serve as barometers
of market patterns, especially when they all point in the same
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's trend, if that term suffices, is borne out by the
findings of the Case Shiller Weiss repeat-sale survey. Of the 577
ZIP-code areas in 14 suburban counties, according to the survey, as
well as in the 130 ZIP-code areas in the New York City boroughs of
Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx and Staten Island (the survey does not
include Manhattan), every one experienced price appreciation. In
1997, by comparison, 56 ZIP-code areas saw prices drop, and the
year before that the number was 117.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals are as good as ever,'' Hughes of Rutgers
said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 1, the nation's economic expansion entered its 96th
month, or eighth year. In November, it surpassed the longest
peacetime expansion of 92 months, which occurred from 1982 to 1990.
The nation is now 10 months shy of matching the all-time record of
106 months, from 1961 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past several years of this expansion,'' Hughes said,
``the new information-age economy has finally started generating a
lot of jobs, and labor shortages have appeared.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, said John Weiting, the regional commissioner of the
U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, the nation's unemployment rate
stood at 4.4 percent, matching its lowest levels in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In the 31-county area that the bureau designates as the New York
region, 173,000 jobs were created in 1998, Weiting said, reaching
8.1 million. And while those jobs represented a ``bit of a cooling
off'' from the 203,000 jobs created in 1997, he said, ``the year
still came in as the second best for the decade'' _ and was part of
the region's continuing rebound from the moribund days of the early
'90s when information-age jobs were still aborning and the dreaded
economic watchword was downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   Further fueling the housing market, demographers point out, is
the fact that the peak year for the baby boom was 1957, when there
were 4.5 million births nationwide; so more baby boomers than ever
are now 42 years old. ``Never before have we had such a
concentration of individuals in their peak income-earning years,''
Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when the first boomers entered the market,
they were at the lower rungs of the house-buying ladder. ``Today,
their house-purchasing power is immense,'' Hughes said, ``so the
trade-up market is the foundation for the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand has been propelled by low mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the big story in the last 12 months,'' said Keith
Gumbinger, vice president of HSH Associates, a mortgage statistics
company in Butler, N.J., ``is that mortgage rates touched 31-year
lows and climbed back only to 20-odd-year lows.'' Mortgage rates
dropped to 6.68 percent during the week ending Oct. 2 _ a low last
hit in 1967. On Wednesday, the rate stood at 7.03 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As Gumbinger said: ``The underlying story has been the
unrelenting stability of interest rates. I mean, really, we have
seen, almost no significant change, aside from that 31-year low.''
The range of mortgage rates in 1998, including the 31-year low, has
been .6 percent. ``That's the most stable year since 1977,''
Gumbinger said.
</P>
<P>
   So the buyers came, and spent.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout northern New Jersey, according to the New Jersey
Association of Realtors, sales rose 7.2 percent, from 63,100 in
1997 to 67,700 in 1998. The median price rose 3.4 percent, from
$199,300 to $206,000.
</P>
<P>
   By way of example, in Bergen and Passaic counties, the median
price rose from $205,400 to $213,500, or 4 percent. Middlesex,
Somerset and Hunterdon, taken together, experienced a 4.2 percent
increase, $176,700 to $184,200.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's spurring it,'' said Patrick O'Keefe, executive vice
president of the New Jersey Builders Association, ``is New Jersey's
housing deficit.'' O'Keefe said that although New Jersey's
population continues to grow, housing construction is down 40
percent from its 1980s rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also,'' O'Keefe said, ``a considerable wealth effect
in northern New Jersey, particularly on the Gold Coast,'' the
communities along the Hudson River, ``which benefits from the
dearth of construction in New York City. Therefore, even very
expensive units on the Jersey side of the Hudson are in demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The profile of northern New Jersey's buyers, O'Keefe said,
includes, particularly, empty-nesters and upwardly mobile young
people. ``At these prices they must be combining incomes,'' he
said, ``but I'm not sure of the marital arrangement; such
arrangements have changed since I was young.''
</P>
<P>
   As confirmed by the Case Shiller survey, both groups seem
willing to pay. The survey is based on a table showing the average
price for all single-family homes sold in most ZIP-code areas, year
by year (some areas are omitted because of insufficient data).
</P>
<P>
   To determine price fluctuations in 1998, for example, the survey
took the purchase price of each home sold in each ZIP-code area
during the year just ended, compared it to the price the house
brought the last time it sold, and then, using the annual index,
adjusted the earlier purchase price to what it likely would have
been had it sold in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 sales prices for homes within each ZIP-code area were
then compared with the estimated 1997 prices to compute the average
change.
</P>
<P>
   For the 318 ZIP-code areas in the 10-county northern New Jersey
region, 58 saw prices rise by up to 4 percent, 100 by 4 percent to
6 percent, 107 by 6 percent to 8 percent, 46 by 8 percent to 10
percent, six by 10 percent to 12 percent and one (in the Monmouth
County community of Rumson) by more than 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wedged between northern New Jersey and Westchester,
triangle-shaped Rockland County stepped out of the shadows last
year. Sales zoomed, the state association of Realtors reported,
with 2,267 transactions last year representing a whopping 94.8
percent increase over the 1,164 deals in 1997. The median price
also jumped, from $203,400 to $235,350, or 15.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rockland has been a secret for a lot of years,'' said Karen
Glazer, past president of the county board of realtors and co-owner
of Glazer Realty in Spring Valley, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The Case Shiller survey does not cover Rockland, because of
insufficient data, but Ms. Glazer provided broad price estimates.
``One-bedroom condos all over start about $100,000,'' she said.
``Town houses, one- to three-bedrooms, start about $225,000. For
the fancier ones in Suffern, Nanuet, top price would be about
$300,000.'' A high ranch around the county, she said, ``is going
for $250,000, but there's new construction going for $500,000 to
$750,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the soaring sales volume, Ms. Glazer said: ``You
know what it is? Because prices have skyrocketed in Westchester,
people have gone farther north, over a bridge _ the Tappan Zee or
the George Washington _ to discover reasonably priced homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Westchester has not suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Westchester County Board of Realtors did not
respond to several requests for comment, but according to the state
Realtors association, sales in the county jumped 50.1 percent, from
5,750 in 1997 to 8,628 last year. And the median price rose 24
percent, from $293,400 to $363,900.
</P>
<P>
   The Case Shiller survey showed that of Westchester's 65 ZIP-code
areas, six saw prices rise 4 percent to 6 percent, 20 by 6 percent
to 8 percent, 17 by 8 percent to 10 percent, seven by 10 percent to
12 percent and in 15 _ or almost one-quarter of the total _ by at
least 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester's neighbor to the east, Fairfield County,
according to the Case Shiller survey, nine of the 45 ZIP-code areas
saw prices rise by 4 percent to 6 percent, 16 from 6 percent to 8
percent, eight between 8 percent and 10 percent, 11 by 10 percent
to 12 percent and one (in Norwalk) by at least 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Valvo, editor of The Commercial Record, a business
weekly that covers the state, said that in addition to ``enjoying
the economic beneficence of New York City,'' most of Fairfield was
building on ``the continued development of Stamford and suburban
areas like Shelton.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Commercial Record statistics, sales in Fairfield
County increased from 17,743 in 1997 to 19,598 in 1998, or 10.5
percent. The median price rose 3.9 percent, from $203,500 to
$211,500.
</P>
<P>
   Within Fairfield County, even long-struggling Bridgeport saw
sales increase 14.2 percent, from 1,769 to 2,021, while the median
price rose 12.1 percent, from $74,500 to $83,550. In New Canaan,
where the 460 sales recorded last year represented a 3.1 percent
increase over the 446 sales in 1997, the median price jumped 10.9
percent, from $505,000 to $560,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There were good times on Long Island, N.Y., too, said Joseph
Mottola, executive officer of the Long Island Board of Realtors,
``because of a confluence of things _ interest rates, mortgage
products to fit unique needs, low unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear about downsizing any more,'' Mottola said.
``You hear about companies unable to fill jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Multiple Listing Service of Long Island, there
were 8,199 sales in Nassau last year, 4.6 percent more than the
7,835 in 1997. The median price jumped 10.2 percent, from $209,466
to $230,791.
</P>
<P>
   The Case Shiller survey showed that of the 63 ZIP-code areas in
Nassau, 19 saw prices rise 4 percent to 6 percent, 35 by 6 percent
to 8 percent and nine by between 8 percent and 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to offer a range of median prices across Nassau, Mottola
checked his records and said: ``At the less expensive end, we have
Levittown: '97 is $146,000 and '98 is $158,000; Baldwin went from
$167,000 to $170,000, Glen Cove, $250,000 to $254,000.''
</P>
<P>
   In Suffolk, sales rose 7.4 percent last year to 11,244 from
10,470 in 1997, while the median price was up 7.5 percent, from
$164,662 to $176,957. And according to Case Shiller Weiss, of
Suffolk's 86 ZIP-code areas, one appreciated by up to 4 percent; 24
by 4 percent to 6 percent, 37 by 6 percent to 8 percent, 23 by
between 8 percent and 10 percent, and one (Wading River) by 10
percent to 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing three communities as examples in Suffolk, Mottola said:
``For Brentwood, the '97 median was $106,700 and '98 was $112,000.
Northport, '97 was $262,500 and '98 is $281,000. And in Cold Spring
Harbor, '97 was $470,000 and '98 was $522,500.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely five months ago, in October, prospects for a booming
residential market seemed, at best, imperiled. The so-called Asian
economic contagion had begun to infect South America. The Russian
economy virtually collapsed. The stock market swooned. And home
buyers, particularly high-enders hooked to quarterly reports,
headed for the bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   But in some ways the turmoil bolstered the housing market. A
world oil glut kept fuel prices and, consequently, inflation down.
The flight of capital to the United States kept interest rates
down; on top of which the Federal Reserve Board, in three quick
hits, further lowered interest rates and, consequently, mortgage
rates. The stock market roared back. And all of that meshed with
the propitious demographics of house buying.
</P>
<P>
   But is it sustainable?
</P>
<P>
   With a Realtor's institutional optimism, Flick, the economist
for the National Association of Realtors, believes that even after
the baby boomers settle into their trade-up homes and the so-called
baby bust begins to siphon off demand, immigrants will plug the
gap. ``Immigrants are coming in at roughly 1 million a year, and
analysts have found that after six years' residency about 70
percent become homeowners,'' Flick said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in about a decade, he said, the millennium generation _
those people currently 18 or 19 years old _ will enter the market.
``The boomers were wealthy and fruitful and multiplied,'' Flick
said. ``There are about 80 million boomers and about 70 million
millennium kids. So, like that Stephen King novel, `Children of the
Corn,' they will come with their scythes and harvest the housing
market of the next, say, two decades.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that assumes, said Hughes of Rutgers, ``that the economic
stars will stay in alignment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have a real global economic meltdown that ultimately
feeds back to the United States,'' he said. But at least for now
the nation's housing fundamentals remain firm. ``The nation and the
region have none of the imbalances that caused the great
real-estate bubble of the 1980s,'' Hughes said. ``Today's builders
are the survivors of the debacle. They are more conservative, so
overbuilding and speculative development are nonexistent today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rae Rosen, a senior regional economist for the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York, is, well, reserved. ``Certainly, for the region,
we've probably hit the cyclical peak in terms of job growth, income
growth and housing activity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosen wonders if the boom can last: ``It will be difficult
to sustain the '98 growth rate in '99. It will still be good, it
just won't be great.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hughes, the nation's economy and housing performance in 1998
constituted a ``go-figure'' market. ``We were an oasis of
prosperity in a turbulent economic world _ go figure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
