<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      03-20 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 TEACHER'S SEXUAL ABUSE TRIAL FORCES PARENTS AND STUDENTS TO CHOOSE
SIDES
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORHAM PARK, N.J. _ Until police came, the worst thing anyone
at Briarwood Elementary School said about David Ford was that he
should, perhaps, push his third- and fourth-grade math students a
little harder and cut back on the birthday parties. Other teachers
hold one party for several children, but Ford brought in cupcakes
for each birthday boy and girl, and eventually Jack Wootton, the
principal, had to speak to him about it.
</P>
<P>
   But now Ford is in the last week of a criminal trial where
prosecutors are saying the worst possible things about him.
</P>
<P>
   They accuse him of groping and rubbing 12 little girls as they
stood at his desk in front of the class, sometimes while other
students were waiting in line with their problems. It is, his
lawyer acknowledged, as ugly a charge as you can make about a
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worse than murder,'' said the lawyer, Alan Zegas, who in his
opening statement cited Arthur Miller's witch-hunt play, ``The
Crucible'' _ in which little girls are false accusers _ and
McCarthyism. ``The worst label is not witch or Communist,'' he
said. ``The worst thing is to be called a sexual predator, and even
worse than that is to be accused of sexually abusing children.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the monstrousness of the charges, it is surprising that so
many people still believe in Ford's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ford's defense team brought in parents and students
and teachers who stuck with Ford _ youngsters who remember Ford
only as a friendly teacher who might give them a pat on the back or
on top of the head and who said they never saw what the accusers
claim. And there were parents and teachers who do not believe the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked with Dave too long to believe all this,'' said
Margaret Skar, a fifth-grade teacher at the Briarwood School. ``My
opinion is based on his professional background.''
</P>
<P>
   Eva Steinway told the court how Ford, a 59-year-old grandfather,
had helped her son adjust to his move from Jersey City. And when he
took the stand, her son said he had not seen any of the things some
of Ford's accusers said they saw. All the children's names are
shielded by the court.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has rejected several plea deals, even though it has meant a
trial that has ruined him financially.
</P>
<P>
   Debbi Kyprianou, a former PTA president who was the class mother
in Ford's homeroom and often made unannounced visits to his class,
testified that she believed in Ford's innocence. ``I'm very
intuitive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a key part of Ford's defense, Mrs. Kyprianou said that a
telephone chain to parents about ``an incident involving a
teacher'' created chaos among Florham Park parents and students
before the 12 accusers had even been interviewed by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   That chaos _ hysteria, Zegas called it _ tainted the girls'
stories, the lawyer maintains. And Ford's case may have received a
boost when one girl, a friend of some of the accusers, wrote to
prosecutors saying she had helped them make up the charges. But the
girl then recanted, saying she only wrote the letter to avoid
testifying.
</P>
<P>
   So what do the prosecutors make of the way so many people are
sticking with Ford? It turns out it's not all that unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's the defendant who's actually on trial, but it is
really the victims who feel the brunt of society's reaction,'' said
Leslie Wade, one of the Morris County prosecutors on the case. ``We
once had a teacher who pleaded guilty to sexual abuse of a girl and
we had kids writing editorials in the school newspaper claiming he
was innocent even after he admitted he was guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Ford made other Briarwood teachers newly
conscious of how they dealt with their students, and some asked the
principal, Wootton, what they should do, say, if a child hugged
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like puppies,'' said Roberta Rountree, one of the
teachers who testified for Ford. ``They want to be held, they want
to hold your hand, and now all of us are so conscious of how
anything we do might be interpreted.'' Now, teachers never allow
themselves to be alone in a classroom with a student, Mrs. Rountree
said.
</P>
<P>
   So with all this concern, what did Wootton say to teachers who
didn't know to react to third graders' hugs?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to hug right back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
