<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-POLICE-SHOOTING-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SHOOT 2 TEENS IN STOLEN CAR IN BROOKLYN
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police officers investigating a car theft in Brooklyn
on Saturday morning shot and wounded two teen-age suspects when
they tried to run over the officers, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old boys, whose names were not released because of
their ages, were taken to the Brookdale Hospital Medical Center,
where they remained in stable condition, the police said. One was
shot in the neck, and the other in the right cheek, the police
said. No weapons were recovered from the suspects, they said.
</P>
<P>
   A third suspect, Adrian Edwards, 21, of Maple Street in
Brooklyn, was apprehended as he tried to flee the parking lot at
the Starrett City housing projects in East New York shortly before
officers opened fire. Only two of the six officers at the scene
fired their service pistols, discharging a total of four rounds,
police said. No charges have been filed against them.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Nick Vreeland, a Police Department spokesman, said the
incident began shortly before 6:30 a.m., when officers in a patrol
car spotted the three driving down Pennsylvania Avenue near
Flatlands Avenue in a white Acura that had been reported stolen. He
said the officers decided to follow the car, calling in
reinforcements after the suspects spotted them and tried to speed
away.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the chase, which included three patrol cars,
ended when the suspects rammed into several cars inside the parking
lot at Seaview and Van Siclen avenues. As Edwards ran from the car,
the two 15-year-olds got into a dark green BMW 325i they had parked
in the lot. They drove toward the officers standing in the lot's
entrance, and the officers opened fire, stopping them, police said.
All six officers were later taken to Jamaica Hospital in Queens for
treatment of minor injuries and trauma, police said.
</P>
<P>
   According to department guidelines, an officer is not supposed
to shoot at a moving vehicle unless deadly force other than the
vehicle _ such as a gun _ is being used against him. Although no
weapons were found on the suspects, Vreeland added that these
guidelines are not the same as rules, and that when investigating a
shooting, the Police Department must ``look at the totality of the
facts involved in the specific incident.'' Forensics investigators
were scouring the lot for evidence Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Coming at a time of intense criticism over the police shooting
of Amadou Diallo, the shootings drew an immediate skeptical
response from the Rev. Al Sharpton, a frequent critic of the
department, who said family members of the suspects, as well as
some witnesses, had called him to urge an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to prejudge this, but I do not understand the
necessity of shootings here,'' Sharpton said. ``This is not the
time when we are willing to take a lot of things the police say at
face value.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Residents in Starrett City, a complex of housing projects just
off the Fresh Creek Basin, said that the lot had long been a
dumping ground for stolen cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a lot of shooting, about six shots, and it woke me
up,'' said Elsie Contes, 32. ``When I went to my terrace, there
were two bodies next to a car, and it didn't look like they were
moving. Then I heard screaming, someone yelling `yo, yo' and there
was a lot of commotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ford, a 41-year-old postal worker, said he came home
shortly after the shootings to see his sister's car among those
smashed in the final chase. ``I was glad I was at work, or it could
have been my car,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and other residents, all of whom pay a fee to park in the
lot, said they hoped the incident would force their landlords to
increase security there, possibly installing locked barriers at the
entrances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is people leave stolen cars here because it is
close to the Belt Parkway, but nobody really checks on it,'' said
Louis Perez, 43. ``The only difference this time is they got
shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
