<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-SUPPORT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW THREAT IN COLLECTING CHILD SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla., Colo., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Even the staunchest critics of Gov. George
Pataki's welfare policies have praised his campaign to collect
child support from delinquent parents, most of them men, so their
families do not wind up on public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But those same people now say Pataki may be taking that campaign
too far with a proposal to deny all welfare benefits to single
parents, mostly women, when they refuse to help the state identify
and collect child support payments from delinquent parents.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty other states have a similar policy, and the Pataki
administration contends that the penalty will give the state a
powerful tool for pursuing child support payments on behalf of
single parents who, for whatever reason, have been unwilling to do
so themselves. The administration says it will provide exemptions
in certain cases, such as when a woman can prove she has been the
victim of domestic abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not intended to be punitive,'' said Robert Doar,
director of the New York State Office of Child Support Enforcement.
``We are trying to encourage compliance with child support.'' He
added: ``It is in the long-term best interest of single mothers and
their children.''
</P>
<P>
   But some advocates for the poor contend that Pataki's proposal
is misguided, noting that in many instances women do not pursue
child-support payments from a former boyfriend or husband for fear
of retaliation. To deny welfare benefits in such cases, they argue,
would ultimately hurt children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should be beating up on little kids just
because of the actions of their parents,'' said Karen Schimke,
executive director of the State Communities Aid Association, a
coalition of welfare advocacy groups that has long supported the
governor's child-support collection policies. ``We have stood with
the governor on many other things, but we think he is wrong in this
one area.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is intended to bolster the Pataki administration's
broad campaign to crack down on noncustodial parents who fail to
meet financial obligations to their children.
</P>
<P>
   The state's child-support collection efforts have been waged on
many fronts since Pataki took office in 1995. The state has
suspended the driver's licenses of delinquent parents, placed liens
on their property, located them through state labor records,
enacted new penalties for delinquency and required more women to
help caseworkers establish paternity.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the crackdown has raised child support payments in New
York to $872 million last year, from $574 million in 1994. The
additional payments have helped the state move 155,000 women and
children off the state's welfare rolls in that period. The payments
have also increased the household incomes of well over 127,000
women and children, many of whom may have wound up on welfare
without the added income, according to state officials and
advocates for the poor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pataki's aggressive campaign to collect child support is
considered particularly important for people on welfare because
they now face strict limits on how long they can receive cash
assistance from the state and federal government. But his latest
proposal has stirred such widespread concern that it will likely
face stiff opposition in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, Florida and Colorado are among the roughly 30
states that already cut off welfare benefits entirely when, for
example, a mother refuses to help the authorities track down and
collect child support from a delinquent father. Now, New York only
reduces monthly grants by 25 percent in such cases. Those grants
run about $500 for a family of three.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the governor's latest proposal contend that in many
instances women opt to lose 25 percent of their monthly grant
rather than help the state identify former husbands and boyfriends
who might retaliate against them. The critics say that eliminating
the entire grant would impose needless hardships on such families.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the critics contends that the new penalty could be
abused by cash-strapped localities seeking ways to trim their
welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration points out that the current penalty has
been used sparingly since it was adopted a year ago: Of the 312,000
single parents on the welfare rolls, only about 3,000 have been
penalized for failing to help social service officials track down
delinquent parents. The administration also says it has waived the
penalty in 600 cases involving women who have refused to cooperate
on the ground that they are victims of domestic abuse and fear
further attacks.
</P>
<P>
   To comply, the custodial parent must give the full name of the
delinquent parent, as well as other personal information about that
parent, such as a Social Security number, an employer or home
address.
</P>
<P>
   Doar, the head of the state's child-support enforcement office,
said the administration suspected that many of the single mothers
who had been penalized were probably already receiving money,
albeit surreptitiously, from their former boyfriends or husbands.
Rather than declare that money to the state and risk being taken
off the rolls, many simply choose to absorb a partial cut in their
grant, according to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Doar maintained that the full sanction would help the state
ferret out such fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
