u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MODEL-BLOCK-350&AMP;AD     03-20 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MODEL-BLOCK-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPTOWN BLOCK OPTS OUT OF INTENSIVE POLICE PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By many accounts, the New York City Police
Department's model block program has been a resounding success,
with officers and residents in nearly two dozen areas where it has
been applied noticing a sharp drop in crime.
</P>
<P>
   But when those living in a crime-ridden area of Washington
Heights heard last week that their block might be the next one
saturated by officers and then barricaded against traffic, they
took to the streets in protest.
</P>
<P>
   The strong reaction on 159th Street, between Broadway and
Amsterdam Avenue, took police officials by surprise, particularly
since the crime-fighting technique was already being used
successfully on four other nearby blocks. But on Wednesday, Police
Commissioner Howard Safir agreed not to use the tactics anywhere
residents did not want it. The organizers of the Washington Heights
protest declared victory.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition stems in part from growing tension brought out by
the fatal police shooting of Amadou Diallo and the tactics used in
the program, which can last for months and often has officers
questioning people coming onto the block.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition also reflects how the struggling neighborhood has
sought to address its problems without outside help, beginning a
cleanup of their street that goes far beyond ridding it of crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is organize the community to tackle
all of the block's problems,'' said Carlos Rodriguez, a member of a
neighborhood group, the Community League of West 159th Street. ``We
are trying to be proactive and make real changes here, which means
this will take time. But it's better than criminalizing the entire
community, which is what happens when the police close off these
blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, the department says, it has set up 21 model block
programs across the city, the first nearly two years ago at 163nd
Street between Broadway and Amsterdam. Though there has been some
grumbling on these blocks _ with neighbors' complaining that they
were harassed or merchants' saying business has been disrupted by
restraints on the flow of traffic _ the programs have drawn little
criticism.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One concern, residents say, is that the police are too quick to
view residents with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diallo situation further enhanced what we already know,
that there is a great deal of police brutality, and it has just
made us more enraged,'' said Stephanie Colley, 20, who has lived on
the block for 15 years. ``Already, they come up to you if you're
standing on the block, and harass you, asking you what you are
doing or asking for ID. The model block will only make it worse. It
will make us prisoners in our own community.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also concern that crime is merely displaced to other
blocks, although the police say that much of the illegal activity
is eradicated by the program, because many drug dealers end up in
jail and their customers are discouraged from coming back.
</P>
<P>
   While applauding the efforts of the 159th Street residents,
Deputy Inspector Garry McCarthy, commander of the local precinct,
the 33rd, takes issue with the idea that the model block program
has the effect of turning residents into suspects. And he points to
the successes that have resulted from the plan on four other blocks
in his precinct.
</P>
<P>
   Since the program was started on West 163rd Street in June 1997,
violent crime there has dropped more than 96 percent, McCarthy
said. There have been only seven crimes reported on the block in
the last year and a half, and the most serious, a domestic assault,
was proved unfounded, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear of crime doesn't exist on 163rd Street now, and when
crime does occur they are of the type you would expect in suburbia,
not violent crime,'' he said, adding that residents protesting the
program on 159th Street have misunderstood what is occurring on
model blocks elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents on 159th Street question whether the community
can clean itself up or force a drop in crime without more outside
help. These residents are not police boosters _ like their
neighbors, they complain of police harassment and worry over
well-publicized reports of brutality against members of minority
groups. But they like drug dealers even less.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cops are the lesser of two evils as far as I'm
concerned,'' said Laura McIver, 46, who grew up on the block and
returned in 1981 to buy a brownstone. Ms. McIver said the community
remains fractured, and was concerned that the latest organizing
push would not have much lasting impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place was crazy with drugs when I first left and it's
still got crime problems that would be helped by closing down the
block,'' she said. ``I want it back the way it was when I was a
kid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
