A8048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COLUMN-BEUKEBOOM-     03-20 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COLUMN-BEUKEBOOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: LaFONTAINE AND BEUKEBOOM HAVE CONCUSSIONS IN(rk) 
 By   JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Backstage at Madison Square Garden last week, two
very different hockey players discussed their very similar injuries
and their unpleasant consequences. In a large banquet room stood
Pat LaFontaine, small for a professional athlete, eloquently
thanking guests who came to honor him for a brilliant career that
prematurely ended at age 33 because of multiple concussions.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, in a smaller press room, sat Jeff Beukeboom, big
even for a hockey player, discussing the concussions that
prematurely ended his season and threaten his career at age 33.
</P>
<P>
   Even their names suggest their different styles. LaFontaine was
an elegant American-born forward, a fountain of goals and good
quotes. Beukeboom, a Canadian-born defenseman who rarely scores, is
what his onomatopoeic name suggests: a hard hitter who bangs bodies
into the boards, a taciturn man who lets his actions speak for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine is 5-foot-10-inch, 180 pounds, Beukeboom is 6-5 and
230.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't too many similarities between me and Patty other
than the concussions,'' Beukeboom said, a tight smile on his face.
``The knowledge and the circumstances that surrounded Patty really
helps my situation. Learning from his process has made this easier
for me. I know what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking to him puts things in perspective,'' Beukeboom added,
``and I know where we're at and basically what direction we're
heading in. At this point, it would be tough for me to say `Look,
I'm looking at this as a total positive thing where I'm going to
eventually get better and play next year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beukeboom said he has had at least four or five major
concussions and quite a few small ones. LaFontaine retired late
last season after his sixth major concussion. His was one of an
epidemic of head injuries that included serious ones to stars like
Paul Kariya and Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the league contends that the number of concussions
has been reduced, although the figures are not known. But lower
statistics don't heal the bruised brains of Rangers like LaFontaine
and Beukeboom. Despite improvements in headgear and mouth guards,
the physics and style of the sport suggest a growing danger.
</P>
<P>
   The modern players are bigger, faster and stronger. The size of
the rink is the same. The new style of glass in new arenas is
harder and firmer, so sturdy that players complain that hitting it
is like bumping into a brick wall. They dislike the glass the way
pro football players dislike artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   But Beukeboom and LaFontaine suffered their injuries in open
ice, not along the walls. LaFontaine's last concussion had an
unusual twist. While watching the puck, he accidentally collided
with Mike Keane, a Ranger teammate. Beukeboom's biggest concussion
in November was more traditional and troubling. It came when he was
sucker-punched from behind by Matt Johnson, a ruffian with the Los
Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Beukeboom said it bothers him that Johnson has not apologized.
The day after it happened, Johnson said it was payback for past
deeds done by Beukeboom to Kings players, some of which were
dangerous and caused injuries. All this is so much a part of
hockey's passionate culture.
</P>
<P>
   While these elite athletes may make millions of dollars, theirs
is a visceral and emotional sport that many would play for nothing.
Sometimes, it is a gut-level grudge game where men lose eyes for
eyes and teeth for teeth.
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine, who spent only one of his 15 seasons as a Ranger,
recalled his first major concussion, suffered nine years ago at the
Garden, when he was on the Islanders. It came during a playoff
series, one of those Islander-Ranger wars that got meaner by the
minute.
</P>
<P>
   A Rangers defenseman _ not Beukeboom _ flattened LaFontaine and
the fans cheered as LaFontaine lay unconscious on the ice. After he
was carried off on a stretcher and put in an ambulance, the vehicle
was attacked by hooligan Ranger fans, who rocked it and pounded on
the metal sides.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech last week, LaFontaine smiled slightly when he
recalled that night. He told a little joke about how a testimonial
dinner is like a funeral because people say good things about you.
(``If you could hear them talk at your funeral, what would you most
like to hear? Hey, he's still moving!'')
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine turned a bit wistful, mentioning that he requested
that the song ``Garden Party'' be played during a post-banquet
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   The song, recorded by Rick Nelson during a comeback attempt in
1972, is about performing at Madison Square Garden. ``A chance to
share old memories,'' the lyrics begin, optimistically. ``There was
magic in the air ... .''
</P>
<P>
   But the story turns poignant. The show doesn't go over well.
There is no happy ending. ``You can't please everyone, so you got
to please yourself,'' Nelson sang, realizing, ``It was time to
leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
