<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING OF SCHOOL OFFICIAL STARTS POLITICAL FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dismissal of a school superintendent in Queens
for her handling of a school gun incident has set the stage for a
fresh legal and political fight over the power of the New York City
schools chancellor, Rudy Crew, to impose his will on elected
community school boards, school and community officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute revolves around Celestine Miller, whom Crew fired
from her job as superintendent of District 29 on Thursday. The next
day, the district board directly challenged the chancellor by
voting to reinstate Ms. Miller.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to Crew after their vote, the board members
said they were acting according to the ``rights and duties granted
to us by the voters of southeast Queens.''
</P>
<P>
   The board hired Ms. Miller in early 1997, and so it has the
power to decide her fate, Leroy Comrie Jr., the District 29 board
president, maintained in a telephone interview Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that there's a legality in there that requires him
to have consulted us and given us the right of final determination
as to her termination,'' Comrie said.
</P>
<P>
   But the chancellor has rejected that view, based on the powers
to hire and fire district superintendents that were granted him by
a state law that took effect a few weeks after Ms. Miller's
selection in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe he has the right to dismiss any
superintendent, regardless of whom the contract was with,'' said
Chiara Coletti, the chancellor's spokeswoman. She added that Crew
``will do everything in his power under the law to sustain Mrs.
Miller's removal.''
</P>
<P>
   Comrie said the district board would pursue its challenge to the
chancellor administratively, by appealing to the central Board of
Education and, if necessary, to the courts. It has appointed an
emergency interim superintendent, Brenda McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we go from here, who knows?'' Comrie said. The board
members and Crew have staked out firm positions, he added, ``so
obviously, it's not going to be resolved between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller is the first superintendent to be fired by Crew since
1997, when the U.S. Justice Department approved the state law
giving him broad authority over New York City's 32 community school
districts, which had operated for years as largely autonomous
fiefdoms. The department reviewed the law to determine whether it
violated the rights of minority voters by diluting the power of the
elected boards.
</P>
<P>
   Since acquiring the new powers, Crew has tried to make his mark
in many districts by removing elected school board members, firing
principals and hiring the superintendents of his choice over the
objections of some school boards.
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing Ms. Miller, the chancellor cited the criticisms of
her made in a recent report by Edward Stancik, special commissioner
of investigation for the New York City school system. The report
faulted her actions last year when a loaded revolver was found in
the backpack of an 8-year-old pupil at one of the district's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said Ms. Miller did not secure the gun and did not
immediately notify police. Stancik's report also accused her of
deliberately misleading parents by saying the gun resembled a toy.
</P>
<P>
   To fire Ms. Miller on the basis of the gun incident is
``unfair,'' Comrie said, because it ignores the educational gains
made in the district during her tenure as superintendent, including
improved reading and math scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been educationally and fiscally responsible,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
