<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ARENAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARENA PLANS IN NEW JERSEY PUT SOME RESIDENTS ON EDGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Amid the cheering of city officials hungry for a
new downtown sports arena Soraida Cruz has one thing to say: ``Over
my dead body.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cruz, 34, whose house stands in the path of a proposed $223
million stadium for the Nets, has no desire to sacrifice the house
where she was born for a greater civic good. Nor do the 300 other
East Ward residents whose homes have been designated ``blighted''
by a city desperate for the 40-acre sports complex. ``Let them find
another way to improve Newark without hurting us,'' Mrs. Cruz said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar sentiments can be heard 10 miles away in Hoboken, where
the principal owner of the Devils, John McMullen, envisions a new
home for his hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen said last week that he wants to build an 18,500-seat
arena, two levels of shops and a 20-screen movie theater on a
platform above the railroad tracks, with a view of lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But McMullen's high-tech renderings and sales pitch have won few
supporters in Hoboken, a formerly down-and-out waterfront town of
30,000 people that has seen its fortunes soar in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he crazy or what?'' asked Charlie Raso, 71, a retired truck
driver who has spent his entire life in Hoboken. Like many
residents, Raso says the town is already suffering from too much of
a good thing: too many bars, too little parking, soaring real
estate prices and so many new faces that he and his wife feel like
foreigners when they walk down Washington Street. ``We need this
thing like I need a hole in my head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals face daunting competition from the New Jersey
Sports and Exposition Authority, which wants to build a $212
million replacement for the Continental Airlines arena in the
Meadowlands, which is home to the Devils, the Nets, the Giants, the
Jets and the MetroStars soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   Because all three proposals would require publicly financed
infrastructure improvements, state officials say that only one of
the stadiums will be built.
</P>
<P>
   For now the sponsors of each plan are trying to win the support
of the public and, ultimately, Gov. Christie Whitman. So when Mrs.
Cruz and a group of her neighbors held a news conference on
Thursday to announce a lawsuit against the city of Newark, Mayor
Sharpe James could not contain his fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not dignify disgruntled individuals who are against
everything and for nothing,'' the mayor said in a terse statement.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed sports, retail and entertainment development in
Newark would include two stadiums, one for the Nets and one for the
MetroStars and require the clearing of 20 blocks, city officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   That came as a surprise to people who live in that gritty
neighborhood of warehouses, vinyl-sided homes and parking lots. A
quick walk from Pennsylvania Station, the office cluster of
downtown Newark and the heavily Portuguese Ironbound section, the
neighborhood has no official name, and until now, no political or
economic clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no Beverly Hills, but it's not as run-down as they
want people to believe,'' Mrs. Cruz said. Michael Rowe, president
of the Nets, said his team has no interest in destroying any
community. ``The whole reason we want to go into Newark is to help
people, not to send them packing,'' he said. If philanthropy is
drawing the Nets to Newark, profit is behind the Devils' decision
to abandon the Meadowlands for Hoboken. McMullen has long
complained that the Continental arena has too few of the luxury
boxes that team owners covet.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed stadium in Hoboken would have 100 corporate suites,
up from 29, and include 3,000 seats in a private club overlooking
the World Trade Center. The total price tag: $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Hoboken, McMullen is hoping to attract more New
Yorkers, who would be able to reach the stadium by PATH train.
Hoboken is also a hub for New Jersey Transit trains that serve a
large swath of the state. The Meadowlands, on drained swampland in
Secaucus, has no rail links.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed arena would displace neither residents nor
businesses, but finding people who like the idea is not easy. Even
Hoboken's mayor, Anthony Russo, greeted the proposal with carefully
measured praise. ``It would cost the taxpayers very little, and
there would be all kinds of amenities, but we'll have to see how
it's going to affect our quality of life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of his biggest concerns is the proposed highway connection.
So far, $20 million in federal transportation funds have been
earmarked for it, about a fifth of the total cost, Russo said.
``Without the infrastructure, it wouldn't look as good.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the city's advocacy groups are opposed to the
stadium, even if a highway is built. With only a handful of access
roads, they say, this one-square-mile town would be quickly
overwhelmed by traffic before and after sporting events. ``As it is
you can't find parking if your life depended on it,'' said Ronald
Hines, chairman of the Coalition for a Better Waterfront, which has
fought for stricter development controls.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, city officials have approved 3,000
apartments that would increase the housing stock by 20 percent.
Those numbers frighten old-timers like Beverly Hans, who said she
moved to Hoboken in 1966 to escape the congestion of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked Hoboken when it was falling apart, when people were
ashamed to say they were from here,'' said Ms. Hans, 59, as she
served customers at the Landmark Coffee shop on Hudson Street.
``When all these new buildings fill up, it's going to be
miserable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
