<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBRUCE-GRAIN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAY SOUGHT IN PROCEEDINGS IN GRAIN ELEVATOR BLAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ Government lawyers are seeking a delay in
civil proceedings against DeBruce Grain Inc. until a parallel
criminal investigation into last year's fatal grain-elevator
explosion is concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Paul DeBruce, DuBruce founder and chief executive, said Friday
that his North Kansas City-based company will resist the delay
requested by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The June 8 grain dust explosion near Wichita, Kan., left seven
workers dead. The federal agency in December alleged three dozen
workplace-safety violations against DeBruce and proposed civil
fines totaling $1.74 million.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce has contested those allegations and is seeking an
administrative trial. In recent weeks the company has accused the
government of foot dragging in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for openness is long overdue,'' DeBruce said Friday.
``One of OSHA's stated purposes for the stay is to prevent
(DeBruce) access to information that OSHA has already assembled,
and has made public judgment and public statements upon.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the proposed fines in December, Labor Secretary
Alexis Herman said: ``It is unforgivable that DeBruce officials
would so callously disregard federal safety standards. American
workers must not become victims to indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed earlier this week, Herman's office said the
delay was essential to prevent DeBruce from ``making use of the
liberal discovery procedures applicable to a civil suit as a dodge
to avoid the restrictions on criminal discovery and thereby obtain
documents he would not otherwise be entitled to for use in his
criminal trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery is a legal procedure in which both sides must disclose
certain evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Key OSHA officials could not be reached Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Wichita, meanwhile, are continuing to
investigate the explosion for possible criminal violations. The
case was referred to U.S. Attorney Jackie Williams in Wichita in
January by regional administrators in OSHA's Kansas City office.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit filed with the government's motion for the
delay, Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan G. Metzger said the criminal
investigation should be completed within six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   In that document, Metzger said the criminal probe centers on
``alleged willful violations of the (federal workplace safety) act
which caused the death of seven employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Willful violations carry maximum civil fines of $70,000 each
plus the potential for criminal prosecution in cases of workplace
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 36 proposed violations, 26 fall into the most serious
``willful'' category. Those include at least nine instances of
inoperative grain dust collection systems.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce officials earlier this year provided /{The Kansas City
Star/} with copies of work orders, contracts and other records
indicating that the elevator's key grain dust collection systems
had been maintained just months before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, an injured worker and the families of two
who were killed sued contractor Industrial Maintenance Inc. of
Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   Their lawsuit alleges that the contractor ``failed to perform
this maintenance in a reasonably prudent manner, resulting in the
explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce officials also have raised a new theory that a halogen
lamp used by Industrial Maintenance workers the day of the
explosion might have generated enough heat to ignite volatile grain
dust that can explode with six times the force of dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Maintenance lawyers deny the company did anything to
contribute to the blast.
</P>
<P>
   In public statements, OSHA investigators have pointed to an
underground tunnel for grain conveyor belts as the likely spot
where the explosion originated.
</P>
<P>
   Investigator Vernon Grose told /{The Wichita Eagle/} last summer
that a seized bearing in that machinery caused friction and enough
heat to touch off the blast.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce officials contend that couldn't be the case because
grain was not being moved in that area at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
