<HEADER>
A8053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALTIMORE-THEATER-REA     03-20 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-THEATER-REAL-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A FAN SAVES AN ART-MOVIE HOUSE IN BALTIMORE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   (jw) 
 By CHARLES BELFOURE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Five years ago James Cusack, a fan of offbeat films,
knew little about the movie-theater business. That changed when his
nephew, John Standiford, told him that the Charles Theater, one of
the city's two first-run art movie houses, was about to close.
</P>
<P>
   Standiford, 34, was the assistant manager of the theater; his
uncle has been a building contractor for the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always gone to the Charles because I liked independent
films more than the big studio movies,'' Cusack said. ``I felt it
would be a big cultural loss for the city if the theater closed.''
But the former operator of the Charles had walked away, abandoning
its lease and leaving an intact movie theater, including projection
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack renegotiated the former tenant's lease with the owner,
Bowling Inc., and reopened the 485-seat, 10,000-square-foot theater
in 1994. Now he is about to complete a four-screen, 694-seat
expansion of the Charles, using the rest of the space in a
23,000-square-foot building that was once used to store and repair
cable cars and then trolley cars.
</P>
<P>
   By putting together a $1.5 million package to finance the
expansion, Cusack is not only giving Baltimore a new venue for
nontraditional films, but is also bringing the first sizable
commercial development project in four decades to a rundown section
of Charles Street, Baltimore's main thoroughfare. The Charles
Theater lies one block from Penn Station in a section that was once
a major transportation hub.
</P>
<P>
   The car barn was built in 1892 and used for its intended purpose
until 1939. Then the United Electric and Railways Co. sold the
property to Bowling Inc., which wanted it used for entertainment
activities. One initial tenant, at the south end of the building,
was the Times Theater, the city's only all-newsreel theater at the
time. Another tenant, at the north end, was a bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1940s a new second floor was built above the bowling
alley, as the home of the Famous Ballroom, where jazz greats like
Dizzy Gillespie and Buddy Rich played. The movie theater was
renamed the Charles in 1958, and it became an art-movie house in
the late 1970s. The rest of the space has been vacant in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Alan Shecter, the vice president of Bowling Inc.,
gave Cusack a 40-year lease for the entire building. ``I was
impressed by Cusack's motivation and drive in operating the
theater,'' said Shecter, who would not disclose the lease's terms.
But then Cusack and Standiford had to find the financing for the
expansion. They got help from Robert Embry Jr., president of the
Abell Foundation, which provides money to organizations that
promote economic growth here. The foundation agreed to guarantee a
$720,000 loan from Mercantile Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Help also came in the form of a $485,000 low-interest loan from
the State of Maryland and a $79,000 grant from the Baltimore
Development Corp. Construction started a year ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The building was put on the National Register of Historic Places
in September and is eligible for the National Park Service's
historic rehabilitation tax-credit program, which will raise
additional equity to cover any cost overruns and pay down debt
service.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the program, the developers are restoring the
original Romanesque Revival facade of the car barn. This involves
the removal of a ceramic-tile facade added in the 1950s. It
obscured three large windows with Romanesque arches.
</P>
<P>
   Multiscreen operation is the key to survival in the
movie-theater business, Cusack said, a lesson he learned soon after
he took over the Charles in 1994. Without the current expansion,
his business would have failed, he said. ``With one screen, you're
putting all your eggs in one basket to carry the business,' he
said. ``You don't have a move-over house to shift a movie.'' In a
multiscreen building, when the popularity of a movie wanes it can
be moved to a smaller screen and still produce revenue while a new
film can be brought into the larger theater.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With Alex Castro of Baltimore as the architect, the space has
been designed for four new screens with stadium seating. The new
screening rooms will have 123, 151, 173 and 247 seats. In addition
the original theater of 485 seats will be left intact and continue
in operation, but its lobby will be available as sublease space for
use as a cafe or restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance will be relocated in the northern part of the
building allowing the moviegoers to walk into a lobby 27 feet high,
with the original theater to the right and the new screening rooms
straight ahead. A box office and concession stand of glass,
concrete and recycled industrial steel designed by an artist, John
Maxwell, will greet patrons. The original brick walls will be left
exposed in the lobby. A stairway will take patrons to a curving
balcony leading to the top of the largest new screening room.
</P>
<P>
   In late April the rebuilt Charles will open as host for the
first Maryland Film Festival, which is to be an annual event
presented by the Producers Club of Maryland, based in Baltimore, an
organization that supports and raises funds for the state of
Maryland Film Office.
</P>
<P>
   It will run for four days, starting April 22, showing a mix of
new films, documentaries and restored films. After the festival the
theater will show first-run independent films as well as classic
Hollywood and foreign films, as the Charles now does. Its current
offering is ``The General,'' directed by John Boorman.
</P>
<P>
   If the Charles succeeds, there is the expectation that new
businesses will follow. ``We would like to see more bar and
restaurant potential once the Charles is up and running,'' said Jay
Brodie, president of the Baltimore Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Although the theater is the most important project in the area,
there are other evolving development efforts around Penn Station,
according to Brodie. Amtrak is considering putting a hotel in the
unused upper floors of the station as well as relocating the
Greyhound station to a new facility in an adjacent parking lot.
Three blocks to the south, the University of Baltimore is planning
a major expansion, including its first housing for students. There
have been only a few isolated attempts to renovate the deteriorated
housing to the east.
</P>
<P>
   The Charles has developed a loyal following. Though the
immediate neighborhood has had little new commercial investment,
surrounding areas are more affluent, with the Johns Hopkins
community a mile to the north, and the Maryland Institute College
of Art four blocks to the south.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of a new police kiosk now monitoring 20 new
surveillance cameras in the surrounding blocks will, planners
believe, draw many more people who were reluctant to visit an area
they perceived as unsafe. In an attempt to lessen fears about car
break-ins, there will be a reduced parking fee for patrons in lots
surrounding the movie house.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few historic elements on the interior of the car barn
is a marble plaque with the names of the people involved in the
original construction of the building in 1892. The last name listed
will bring a smile to most Charles moviegoers. The superintendent
of construction, John Waters shares the same name as the theater's
most famous patron, the director John Waters, who is enthusiastic
about the Charles' second life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Charles is important to the cultural life of this city,''
said Waters, director of the 1972 cult classic ``Pink Flamingos,''
whose latest film is ``Pecker.'' ``I know people who move out of
cities because there aren't any good movies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
