<SLUG> BC-SAFE-INTERNET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY OFFERS INTERNET SCREENING SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE SMITH  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ A 30-something man with a scruffy stubble
and a glint in his eye is cruising the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In a chat with a girl, he types: ``I'm an 11-year-old girl. My
favorite color is purple. I like to hang out at the malls. What
mall do you go to? Maybe we should meet there sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Though this man is just an actor in a commercial, the sort of
activity he portrays is real _ and especially scary for parents.
The company running the ad, Safeconnect Inc. of Lenexa, Kan., hopes
to put to rest those fears about the dark side of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Safeconnect began providing Internet connection
service across the country, but with a family twist. The company's
service points users to a family-friendly Web site and filters out
other sites that promote pornography, drug use, violence and hate.
</P>
<P>
   Safeconnect's family network, www.efamily.net, provides or links
to news, stores, cartoons, sports scores, television listings,
movie reviews and other content suitable for younger audiences. It
also will offer some type of online chat service for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really trying to target the family and people that maybe
are not real familiar with the Internet,'' said Kathleen Piper,
president of Safeconnect. ``For example, we'll have links to
multiple family vacation planning sites. It's hard for a novice ...
to figure out where to go or how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Safeconnect, available at {www.safeconnect.com,} is the latest
Internet service to enter the online family market.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Safe4Kids has been offering a similar service
since March 1998, said Grant Rogers, vice president and general
manager of Rocky Mountain Internet. The service, at
{www.safe4kids.com}, offers Internet access for $21.95 a month, a
little more than Safeconnect.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said the service had been ``steadily growing, but not
fast-growing,'' since its debut.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely recognized family Internet service was launched
in March 1996 by CompuServe, then a subsidiary of H&AMP;R Block Inc. of
Kansas City. Wow, an online service that used its own software
while offering limited access to the Internet, was criticized for
not offering enough content for the preteen crowd it focused on.
</P>
<P>
   The project was a financial disaster for Block and CompuServe.
It was abandoned in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Without the sort of filtering Safeconnect offers, concerned
parents instead can buy a ``content blocker'' program. It must be
updated frequently, and even then it doesn't block all the Web
sites a parent might want to avoid. And as children get older, they
often figure out how to turn off the blocking program.
</P>
<P>
   But with Safeconnect, Piper said, ``you don't have to worry
about the kids going around the system. That stuff doesn't even
come into your home, much less your computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Safeconnect plans to search the Web constantly, examining
patterns of words, word forms and picture scanning to predict
high-risk sites. The sites will then be reviewed individually.
While some filtering systems automatically block the word
``breast,'' for example, Safeconnect will allow information on,
say, breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   T. Scott Jenkins came up with Safeconnect after trying to
introduce his oldest daughter to the Internet. When he began
researching sites he found questionable material on some of the
most innocent searches.
</P>
<P>
   A search of ``Little Women'' can bring up such sites as ``nude
women at clubtease'' and ``best photos plus XXX erotic diaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were searching `American Girl,' a brand name for a doll,''
Jenkins said. ``I saw a lot of American girls that didn't have
clothes on. It's deceptive. They buy a lot of key words that are
wholesome. Kids type them in and get somewhere they shouldn't go.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins spent two years researching the market and getting the
support centers together. Don Peterson, founder of DeskStation
Technology Inc., served as a consultant to Safeconnect.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can override Safeconnect's filtering with special
access. And if their computer-savvy child breaks the code,
Safeconnect will send a coded message to the parents' private
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Wilson of Focus on the Family, a Colorado Springs, Colo.,
organization that strives to strengthen families, said Safeconnect
found good companies to link to its site.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done some really creative things in that realm,''
Wilson said. ``I sense that it is a new generation of Internet
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Safeconnect works with any standard browser and is nationally
available through high-speed local-access numbers in more than 267
U.S. cities. The company has 10 employees and a $4 million
advertising budget for this year. Eventually it hopes to offer the
service internationally.
</P>
<P>
   People subscribing just to Safeconnect's filtering system pay $5
a month. Unlimited access to the Internet and the use of the
filtering system costs $20 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Safeconnect also will focus on businesses that are concerned
about employees surfing the Net instead of working, and on
libraries, which have struggled with First Amendment issues when
trying to screen sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, more and more we are hearing about child being
lured through chat rooms,'' Piper said. ``With Safeconnect,
children will be safe, they can come home do their homework, and
parents will be confident that they are on the Internet they will
be safe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
