<SLUG> BC-NJ-TAKEOVER-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 FROM A TOUGH PRINCIPAL, LESSONS IN RESPONSIBILITY
</HEADLINE>
   (See related story: NJ-TAKEOVER-SCHOOL) 
(jw) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Vanessa McNeil was a freshman at West Side High
School here when the state took over the Newark schools because of
low academic achievement and corruption at the central office.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Vanessa remembered, her school in Newark's gritty
West Ward was about everything but learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It smelled in the hallways,'' she said. ``Someone drove a car
into the gym. Computers were stolen. Smoke alarms were always going
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa, who is now a senior, and her friends do not know much
about who is in charge at the central office on Cedar Street in
downtown Newark. But they see a cleaner school and improved spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a great school,'' Vanessa said.
</P>
<P>
   They credit the principal, Fernard Williams Sr., who was
appointed by Superintendent Beverly Hall two years ago to head the
school of 1,185 students. He is the fourth principal since Vanessa
was a freshman. Williams, a 54-year-old a former Marine and Newark
police officer who also graduated from West Side and was later a
teacher there, believes the details matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took charge of the school,'' Vanessa said. ``He gave us
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was appointed principal in 1997, West Side was one of
the worst schools in the city. The physical changes now are
dramatic. Inside and out, it is immaculate, and Williams is even
growing grass on the long-barren front lawn. There are changes in
attitude, too. Williams got rid of some teachers and other staff
members. He had new curriculum ideas.
</P>
<P>
   He stresses responsibility. To make sure that custodians have
examined every corner of the school, he occasionally uses a trick
he learned in the Marines: He scatters an unspecified number of
screws around the building and tells the custodians that he expects
all of the screws to be on his desk by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   When students are absent or late for school, an automated system
calls the parents that evening, and then calls them again about
6:30 the next morning to remind the students to be on time.
</P>
<P>
   The dropout rate at West Side has gone from 9.5 percent to 2.3
percent since Williams arrived at the school. Attendance is now up
to 90 percent from the low 60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers have to have high standards to make the students
competitive,'' he said. ``The students can sense when teachers are
not teaching, and then you have discipline problems. It's a growing
process.''
</P>
<P>
   But test scores have not improved as quickly as attendance. In
the statewide High School Proficiency Test, West Side 11th graders
raised their scores last year in the writing portion _ with 56.5
percent of the students passing the test, up from 42.1 percent in
1997. But the results were almost the same in math _ 29.3 percent
last year, compared with 27.7 percent _ and showed no improvement
at all in reading, which remained at 30.0 percent. The results
disappoint Williams and his students.
</P>
<P>
   But the students still feel good about what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first school I ever came to where I ever learned
anything,'' said Jerrell Smith, 18 and a senior, who is in his
fifth year of high school and says he believes he would have
dropped out had it not been for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can come to Mr. Williams anytime I need, and he talks to me
man to man,'' he said. ``A lot of us are from broken homes, and
he's like a father figure to us. I think I'd be locked up by now if
it weren't for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
