<SLUG> BC-HOG-FARMERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE ENDORSES AID PACKAGE FOR HOG FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Farmers hit by plummeting hog prices would get $250
million in federal help under legislation the Senate passed at the
urging of Sens. John Ashcroft and Kit Bond of Missouri, one of the
nation's largest hog-producing states.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate tacked the hog amendment onto an emergency
appropriations bill it sent to the House late Thursday night. It
would require House approval and the president's signature.
</P>
<P>
   Pork prices dropped about 70 percent from June through earlier
this year, Ashcroft said. Prices fell to less than 9 cents a pound,
then rebounded to about 26 to 27 cents _ but they're still low,
said Dan Cassidy, director of national legislative programs for
Missouri Farm Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to recoup some of those losses to enable
producers to remain in business until they at least can recover
their cost of production,'' Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft told the Senate Thursday night that 25 percent to 40
percent of Missouri's 5,500 hog farmers could lose their farms if
they don't get help. He said it is an economic disaster equivalent
to what a tornado or flood would cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, the feed the hogs were eating was worth more
than the hogs themselves,'' Ashcroft said. ``And not long ago,
consumers were paying more for a canned ham than the 260-pound hog
it came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Hog prices fell after supply far outpaced demand. A processing
strike in Canada flooded the U.S. market with hogs while export
markets dried up in the Far East and Europe, Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more hogs than we could process, so packers and
processors had no incentive to offer a fair price,'' Cassidy said.
``Farmers had to hold hogs longer, they were getting fatter and
they were pumping more into hogs that were worth less.''
</P>
<P>
   The appropriations bill the Senate passed Thursday would give
$150 million in new money to the Department of Agriculture for hog
farmers and would let the department spend $100 million in existing
funds. President Clinton has proposed $50 million in aid.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill passes, the Department of Agriculture would decide
how and when to distribute money to the hog farmers who apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be very attentive from a senatorial point of view to
see that the distribution is equitable and prompt,'' Ashcroft said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft and Bond said they have heard from the Farm Bureau, the
Missouri Pork Producers and many farmers about the hog price
problem. The senators were among several sponsors of the amendment
for $250 million in aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
