<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CONNECTICUT KNOWS DRILL FOR REGIONAL 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sometimes painful experience makes you conservative,
sometimes it makes you brash. Connecticut was trying the audacious
route this time, confronting the label of abject underachievers who
had never reached the Final Four of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost three regional finals in nine previous seasons,
Connecticut decided to think big Saturday as it played surprising
Gonzaga for the right to go to the Final Four. Connecticut won,
67-62.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies probably knew that a loss to Gonzaga could be the
worst jolt in their collective history of failed missions _ an
upset for the ages, truth be known _ but they were taking that
chance. They were defying the oldest sports cliche of all, the one
about playing the games one at a time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our guys in the locker room said _ and I'm not going to
name names _ that we were trying to get to the Final Four,'' said
Ricky Moore, the co-captain, who recalled how the other co-captain,
Rashamel Jones, quickly retorted that Connecticut was planning to
win the entire tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy just said: `You're right. Hit me on the back of the
head,''' Moore replied.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? People have been whacking Connecticut on the back of
the head for all of this decade, making the Huskies pay for the
terrible crime of excellence. Under Jim Calhoun, the big, hearty
coach who rescued this program in 1986-87, the Huskies had won 301
games and lost 120, a .714 percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Connecticut had been stereotyped as a disappointing
basketball school because it had not reached the Final Four while
schools like Mississippi State, Oklahoma State, Seton Hall,
Massachusetts and Minnesota managed to get there once each in the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his biggest disappointment, Calhoun has said, ``The
impression that we are not successful.'' There is the perception
that going to the Final Four is a validation of a program, quite
different from the professional football perception that the team
that loses the Super Bowl is indeed a blatant loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean, you want to go back to the old days?'' Calhoun
blusters sometimes, a not particularly veiled reference to the
previous regimes when Connecticut was pleased to play a second game
in the Big East tournament, just to get close to weekend
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday, the disappointment sat there in the record
books. Calhoun was asked if he had learned anything over the years,
and he rattled off his lessons:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let Christian Laettner into the game. Make all your foul
shots. Don't go into overtime. Don't get into a shootout with UCLA.
And by the way, don't go to Greensboro, if you get a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut fans know the drill. In the 1990 regional final in
the Meadowlands, Laettner of Duke sank a jumper in the closing
seconds in the Meadowlands to kill Connecticut (on a play revised
by coach Mike Krzyzewski in a second huddle).
</P>
<P>
   In the 1991 regional semifinal, Duke whacked Connecticut by 14.
In 1994, Donyell Marshall sleep-walked through a second-round loss
to Florida. In 1995, UCLA outran Connecticut, 102-96, in the West
Regional final. In 1996, there was a third-round loss to
Mississippi State. Last year the Huskies went to Greensboro _ a
short hop from the North Carolina campus _ and lost to the Tar
Heels by 11 in the regional final.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had three players go into the pros,'' Calhoun noted the
other day.
</P>
<P>
   The coach has figured it all out. He has all the responses. His
record is one of the best of the decade. His players also go into
pro ball. But something has been denied Jim Calhoun, and he has
brooded over the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask the question sometimes whether the Chicago Bulls would
have won six championships if they had a one-loss-and-out
tournament,'' Calhoun mused.
</P>
<P>
   What was his answer?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they'd play the A game every time out, or maybe they
wouldn't,'' Calhoun said. ``That's what makes this all the more
exciting _ great for the fans, great for the kids.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, the national tournament is more fun than the NBA
championships?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun'' is not how I'd describe it,'' Calhoun replied.
</P>
<P>
   He has won more than 7 of every 10 games at Connecticut, but
Calhoun had things to prove. He was bluntly honest about this
tournament. On Friday he said he was sure he could beat six of the
seven survivors _ ``and one I'm not so sure about,'' he said,
referring to Duke. ``You'd have to play your A game to do it, maybe
get three early fouls on some of them.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday he said, ``We're playing 40 minutes to punch our
ticket to the Final Four.'' He dared to suggest that the ticket was
for a ride long overdue, and that he would just as soon keep
riding. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
