A8058 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLOCK-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      03-20 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOCK-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUE CLOCK FETCHES $175,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA _ They're remodeling Cedar Crest, the Kansas governor's
residence, and to raise money they held a little yard sale, so to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   They did pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   What state administrators dubbed the ``old clock,'' an antique
that visitors to Cedar Crest might not have even noticed, fetched
$175,000.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this wasn't a typical yard sale. Nobody at the
Capitol recalls a transaction quite like it. Taxpayers are the
ultimate beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The object of attention: a Simon Willard lighthouse clock, made
in 1825, very rare, highly valued by collectors and donated for
Cedar Crest eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the construction project started, having the antique
around made Cedar Crest administrator Jennie Rose nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Crest isn't a museum, after all. It's a well-used
residence, the latest occupants being Gov. Bill Graves, first lady
Linda Graves and their 3-year-old daughter, Katie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want that clock broken on my watch,'' Rose said. ``It
was always a concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as the remodeling began, an idea surfaced to both
generate funds and resolve questions about the safety of the
handsome, lighthouse-shaped, glass-topped clock.
</P>
<P>
   Sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Cedar Crest, a private nonprofit group that is trying
to raise $2 million for the remodeling project, made the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a long debate,'' Rose said. ``If someone gives a
gift, you don't turn around and sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper Woodring, a former board member of Friends of Cedar
Crest, suggested the sale, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Topeka resident, Woodring had donated the clock on behalf of
his father, the late Harry Woodring, governor of Kansas from 1931
to 1933 and later secretary of war under President Franklin D.
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Woodring knew that Friends of Cedar Crest would be attempting to
raise private funds for the remodeling project and that proceeds
from the clock would aid the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his idea,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodring disagrees. ``It was not my idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodring doesn't directly criticize the sale. ``I'm not enamored
with it, but I'm not displeased,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Woodring said some potential donors may wonder in the
future about giving artifacts to the state if they think the state
may peddle the artifacts later.
</P>
<P>
   The state routinely sells surplus property such as old
furniture, computers and motor vehicles. But no one can remember
the state selling anything like an antique clock worth six figures.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at the Division of Purchases were assigned the
task.
</P>
<P>
   They advertised in national magazines of interest to antique and
art experts. Bids were sought but came in too low.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations with the highest bidder, clock expert Robert Cheney
of Brimfield, Mass., produced the $175,000 sales price.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Cheney came to Topeka and took possession of the
antique, which he reportedly bought on behalf of an unnamed
collector.
</P>
<P>
   John Stephens, curator of the Willard House and Clock Museum in
Grafton, Mass., said in a telephone interview that fewer than 200
of the lighthouse clocks were made from 1820 to 1840.
</P>
<P>
   About one a year sells, he said. But he hadn't heard of a state
government offering them on bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a new one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens said that selling through an art auction could have
brought a better price. State administrators question that.
Transporting the clock to an auction would have been expensive, as
would the sales commission, they said.
</P>
<P>
   In its final weeks with the state, the clock resided in a Topeka
bank vault for safekeeping. Cedar Crest is closed during the
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Brier, vice president of Friends of Cedar Crest, said half
the sale proceeds go to his organization and half go to state
government. All the money is destined for the Cedar Crest project,
said Brier, a former secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Legislature has appropriated $1.3 million for the
project, but that won't be enough. Proceeds from the clock sale
will ease the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Brier learned what the clock was worth only in the last year. On
previous visits to the residence, the clock made enough of an
impression for him to remember it. But, he added, ``not a $175,000
impression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
