<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Dow's dance around 10,000 will be entertaining  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's worth noting that after the Dow Jones industrial average
crossed 10,000 for the first time Tuesday, declining stocks at
day's end outnumbered gainers by a significant margin in all major
trading arenas.
</P>
<P>
   It was, therefore, a historic moment worthy of brief
celebration, but hardly a cause for optimism. Despite the solid
gains of the major indexes so far in '99, this market's leadership
seems perilously narrow.
</P>
<P>
   A recent analysis by The New York Times focused on research
showing just how rickety the overall market is. It showed 92
percent of the Nasdaq stocks and 70 percent of the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index stocks below their highs by 10 percent or more.
Meanwhile, a recent Dow Theory Forecasts analysis noted that fully
70 percent of the New York Stock Exchange stocks were trading at
least 25 percent below their 52-week highs.
</P>
<P>
   So if you've been in the right stocks, or mutual funds owning
the right stocks, you've been making money. If not, you're no doubt
wondering what all the excitement is about. This, of course, is the
way the market always works, but the imbalance between winners and
losers seems dangerously out of kilter.
</P>
<P>
   Another red flag mentioned by The Times was the Salomon Smith
Barney laggards indicator, which measures the number of stocks
underperforming the S&AMP;P 500 by 15 percent or more. Some 75 percent
now qualify as laggards, and a Salomon analyst cautioned that big
market corrections had occurred three of four times when this
indicator topped 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if 10,000 on the Dow isn't an important number. It
is probably the most symbolic number since the blue-chip indicator
first topped 1,000. It did so during intraday trading in early
1966, just as it did Tuesday, but didn't close above 1,000 until
November 1972.
</P>
<P>
   If history repeats, 10,000 could become a ceiling rather than a
floor. After the Dow held 1,000 briefly through early '73, it began
a descent to 578, where it bottomed in December 1974. It regained
1,000 for brief periods again in 1976, 1980 and 1981, but it wasn't
until December 1982 that the Dow finally transformed 1,000 from
ceiling to launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unforeseen collapse of the world's economy, which
hardly seems likely, it's not probable 10,000 will be nearly the
restraining force 1,000 was. At the 1,000 level, the world was
facing a mounting array of seemingly intractable economic problems
unsurpassed since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, 10,000 could prove a much more difficult hurdle to
get past than the other thousand milestones since a four-digit Dow
became a permanent fact of life. The pessimists say 10,000
represents for many investors a signal to trim sail. Moreover, the
longer it takes the market to secure this new high ground
permanently, the more psychologically daunting it becomes.
</P>
<P>
   The optimists say once breached, however, 10,000 will become a
strong psychological floor from which the market will soar. The
road to 11,000 or even 12,000 will be a relative cakewalk, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the Dow's entertainment value for the rest of the
year will be high even if the average has trouble deciding whether
10,000 is a floor or ceiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
