r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PHOENIX-FINAL-FOU     03-20 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PHOENIX-FINAL-FOUR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLPARK JUST WON'T CUT IT FOR FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Imagine an NCAA Final Four in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Ballpark rocking with 30-40,000 basketball fans, the
national media frenzy, the tourists and bigshots and students
flocking to town.
</P>
<P>
   March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, wait a second. Keep dreaming. There's a small matter of the
Arizona Diamondbacks, a grass ballfield, and the opening of
baseball season falling at the same time as the Final Four. Or as
one ballpark official puts it, ``logistical nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Turn your thoughts to Mesa, though, and the proposed Rio Salado
Crossing, a $1.8 billion complex that would include a retractable
roof football stadium, convention center, hotels, shops,
restaurants and a network of parks.
</P>
<P>
   The hoops dream may be more realistic there, because if the
project is approved in May, officials vow to pursue the Final Four,
which is booked through 2007.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go out and bid for that, yes,'' said Robert Brinton,
head of the Mesa Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``Until we're for
real though, there's not a lot you can talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The bid would have to be made in conjunction with Arizona State
University, which would be the host school, after the NCAA
expresses interest in having the area host the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're interested in talking to them about it,'' said
Tom Sadler, an assistant athletic director at ASU and tournament
manager for the NCAA Western Regional this weekend at America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said he has also discussed the idea with BOB officials.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials say the Phoenix area would be an ideal site for a
Final Four but share the same concerns as local officials about the
logistics at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix certainly is a wonderful destination city that would
be a terrific site for a Final Four down the road,'' said Bill
Hancock, a director of the NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's had great success with the Super Bowl and Fiesta Bowls.
The Final Four could fit right in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, who has yet to see Bank One Ballpark, said he would be
concerned about the logistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that it has a grass field and we've never had the Final
Four in a dome anyplace that has a grass field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first Final Four at baseball stadium. In
fact, next Saturday's Final Four will be played at Tropicana Field,
home of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. But Tropicana's turf is
artificial and easy to store away.
</P>
<P>
   Don't plan on it at BOB. Bob Machen, president and general
manager of Bank One Ballpark and America West Arena, said that
although Diamondbacks officials have discussed the idea of trying
to land an NCAA Final four and would like to, it isn't realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a carpet (artificial turf) down we would have
pursued it already,'' Machen said.
</P>
<P>
   Machen said because of the basketball court courtside seating
being on the baseball field, media arrangements and a host of other
issues, it would be impractical to arrange shortly before or right
at the start of baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, the championship game at the Alamodome
in San Antonio was March 30.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Day at Bank One Ballpark was the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just isn't something that could be done now,'' Machen said.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said that not only would the basketball court have to be
placed on the field, but there are a large number of courtside
premium seats, media seats, band seats and then portable bleachers
courtside on one side of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those bleachers would have to be resting on something pretty
solid, so there are some logistical concerns that would certainly
have to be addressed on the grass field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others agree that because of BOB's grass field, which will have
to be grown fresh before every season after a winter of indoor
racing, concerts and other events, the stadium is unlikely to be
sought for a Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that physically it's possible, but
it's not likely because the field is just going in,'' said Roger
Brendeckie, administrator of the Maricopa County Stadium District.
``It's just doing too much and could have an adverse effect on the
field. What's the tolerance of pain for the turf?''
</P>
<P>
   In the first season, the specially grown turf at BOB often
turned brown and had to be replaced in spots. This season, special
turf has been abandoned for a Kentucky Bluegass and some have
questioned its ability to survive an Arizona summer.
</P>
<P>
   At the proposed Mesa stadium, the grass football field would be
on rollers and could be moved outside at any time, leaving a
concrete floor that could be configured into a basketball court
suitable for the NCAA as well as other uses for the adjacent
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's Hancock said he is familiar with the proposed Mesa
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a very interesting situation to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Requirements for hosting a Final Four include a minimum of
30,000 seats, 8,000 hotel rooms and a working press room for 400
media people, with an interview room for 300.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley could meet that criteria at either BOB or a new Cards
stadium, although hotel arrangements would have to be made far in
advance because March is peak season in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said securing the rooms at high season in a Sunbelt area
can be difficult, but he said St. Petersburg, Fla., host of this
season's Final Four, handled it well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
