<HEADER>
A8063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK21-RESEND     03-20 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK21-RESEND-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As QBs sign, Jeff George waits
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ While the owners seemed mired in intertia during last
week's NFL meetings, some coaches kept the game of quarterback
musical chairs going long enough to maintain interest. Before the
meetings had adjourned, three former starters _ Scott Mitchell
(Detroit to Baltimore), Jim Harbaugh (Baltimore to San Diego) and
Glenn Foley (N.Y. Jets to Seattle) _ changed teams in trades.
</P>
<P>
   The one quarterback still scrambling for a chair, however, as
the music winds down is Jeff George. Whatever ill-will remains
toward George in Atlanta, even his critics have to concede the lack
of interest in him, particularly when players like Chris Miller,
Todd Marinovich, Andre Ware and Mark Rypien are attempting
comebacks, is inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there's nothing going on,'' George agent Leigh
Steinberg said at the meetings. ``Part of it was the timing
because, had we known the Raiders weren't going to keep him, we
would have started shopping him. But (Raiders vice president) Bruce
Allen negotiated as if we were trying to come to a deal. (Now)
we've pulled him back. Nothing will happen at least until after the
draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the coaches surveyed here agreed George has more talent
than any of the guys signed as free agents _ Rich Gannon (Oakland),
Kerry Collins (N.Y. Giants), Trent Green (St. Louis) and Doug
Pederson (Philadelphia). And certainly he carries less baggage than
Collins. But the coaches, almost to a man, cited George's losing
record in the NFL and a perception he is not close to his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   There are rumblings Jimmy Johnson is tempted to bring George to
Miami as a backup to Dan Marino. And Dennis Green, publicly
confident in Randall Cunningham but privately wary he could
backslide in Minnesota, has some interest.
</P>
<P>
   It may take an injury in camp to get George a job. That his
situation has degenerated to that is more a factor of coaching
shortsightedness than George's own shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Tuning in
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their lack of action on most issues, what most marked the
owners last week was their hypocrisy. The league will give Los
Angeles the opportunity for the 32nd franchise based primarily on
its edge in ``TV households'' (5.5 million-4.0 million) over
Houston, even though the latter is clearly more prepared for a new
team. But all the owners who recently relocated teams _ Art Modell
(Baltimore), Georgia Frontiere (St. Louis), Al Davis (Oakland), Bud
Adams (Nashville), Bill Bidwill (Arizona) and Bob Kraft (Hartford)
_ went from bigger to smaller markets. It didn't seem to matter in
those cases. San Diego owner Alex Spanos chided Adams and Kraft for
pushing the Los Angeles market so hard, but he still voted for L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   Although he's visited Chicago and New England, the most likely
landing spot for free agent linebacker Jamir Miller of Arizona is
with Tennessee. General manager Floyd Reese has been trying to work
on numbers with agent Steve Baker for three weeks, but the Titans
have only $87,000 left in the cap and will have to reshuffle some
contracts to make room. Coach Steve Fisher wants to use Miller much
like he did Lamar Lathon, to rush off the edge, a tactic that would
net the linebacker 10-12 sacks. . . . The Cowboys quietly have
reached a five-year agreement with free agent center Mark
Stepnoski. . . . Defensive end Charles Haley played so well in two
postseason appearances last year that 49ers coach Steve Mariucci
and club president Bill Walsh want him back for '99. . . . Steelers
owner Dan Rooney met with Steinberg and began earnest negotiations
on an extension for quarterback Kordell Stewart. . . . Carolina
linebacker Kevin Greene may talk himself right out of a job. New
Panthers coach George Seifert feels Greene would be perfect for the
``elephant'' pass-rush position his defense uses. But Greene told
Seifert he is still an every-down linebacker, something he really
hasn't been for six years. . . . Jets coach Bill Parcells denies he
turned down an offer of a second-round draft choice for third-year
vet linebacker James Farrior. . . . Owners quietly awarded the
Patriots $335,000 in cap relief for '99 _ the base salary for
Robert Edwards _ to compensate for the loss of the tailback to what
likely is a career-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Something for nothing
</P>
<P>
   Few owners probably know about Carlton Sheets, the king of
late-night infomercials and the guy who tells viewers how they can
buy real estate with no money down. Turns out New York businessman
Howard Milstein, the potential new owner in Washington, is the
Carlton Sheets of the NFL. Milstein had no cash of his own in his
$800 million bid for the Skins. He has three more weeks to address
concerns about his financing. His partner, Bethesda, Md.,
businessman Daniel Snyder, may split from Milstein to try to buy
the team himself.
</P>
<P>
   Film study
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants coach Jim Fassel two weeks ago dusted off an
instructional video he made with John Elway in 1982, before the
quarterback's senior season at Stanford. Fassel, the Stanford
quarterbacks coach at the time, wasn't in the mood for nostalgia.
Instead he showed the 45-minute video, which concentrates primarily
on mechanics and has no voice-over, to Collins. Despite the
protests of Fassel and general manager Ernie Accorsi, everyone
assumes Collins will beat Kent Graham for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Still the Champ
</P>
<P>
   Georgia cornerback Champ Bailey solidified his status as a top
pick in the draft at his on-campus workout last week. In front of
scouts for about 20 teams, Bailey clocked 4.28-4.31 in the 40,
depending on whose stopwatch you trust. He had a 42 1/2-inch
vertical jump and 11-foot, 3-inch broad jump, all impressive
figures. Suddenly, now the Colts, who had been locked on Southern
Cal linebacker Chris Claiborne with the fourth overall selection on
April 17, are indicating big interest in Bailey. Indy has a pair of
$4 million-a-year corners in Jeff Burris and Tyrone Poole, but
coach Jim Mora agreed at the meetings his defense needs another
player at that position.
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati coach Bruce Coslet, on the new instant replay system,
which is based on a coach's challenge: ``Oh, great, now I get to
put `referee' on my resume.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
