<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOBEL-STUDENTS21-COX     03-20 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEL-STUDENTS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientists' meeting brings Nobel winners together with students
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You could feel the intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three winners of the Nobel Prize in science were having
lunch Saturday with some Georgia high schoolers and teachers in
meeting rooms 260 and 261of the Georgia World Congress Center _ the
largest gathering ever of Nobel laureates outside Stockholm, where
the coveted award is presented annually.
</P>
<P>
   The 85 high school students were all from Georgia; the 52
science teachers were from every state in the union, Washington,
D.C., and Puerto Rico. The kids were pretty smart themselves _ at
least 16 had scored a perfect 1600 on their SATs.
</P>
<P>
   For the students, it was a stunning opportunity to chat
face-to-face with the giants of science, the very people
responsible for the great scientific discoveries that fill the
pages of their textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   What do so many super-bright people talk about while munching on
salad, chicken and chocolate dessert?
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the 'Three Little Pigs,' `` said 1998 Nobel
winner in physics Horst Stormer of Bell Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we were chatting about how we use the story to teach
physics to first graders,'' said Paul Mello, a science teacher in
Middletown, R.I., seated next to Stormer. ``We get them to look at
various types of material and see what is strongest and weakest and
what falls down down in the wind. In a way, they're learning about
some physics concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a wonderful away of teaching,'' said Stormer.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Daniel Perry, a senior at Cedar Shoals High
School in Athens, and Benjamin Watson, a senior at Hardaway High
School in Columbus, were seated on either side of Walter Kohn, the
1998 Nobel winner in chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually knew Einstein, and was friends with him,'' said
Perry. ``He was very easy to talk to, and he had a personal story
for everything we brought up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us about how we can accomplish whatever we want to do
if we put our minds to it,'' said Watson, who intends to get a
degree in communications technology and then become a U.S. Air
Force pilot.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Kohn, for the benefit of the two students, pointed
out another Nobel laureate, Hans Bethe, sitting across the room.
Bethe was the first scientist to describe the nuclear fusion
process by which the sun gets its energy. Later, he played a prime
role in the Manhattan Project that built the atomic bombs dropped
on Hiroshima and Nagasaki during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself as a bridge between these young people and the
great people of science whom I knew,'' said Kohn. ``These students
sitting here today, though, don't need any motivation from me;
they're already motivated about science.''
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon was part of the first-day activities at the meeting
of the American Physical Society in Atlanta this week. Billed as
the biggest physics meeting in history, it is attracting more than
10,000 physicists from all over the nation and the world, who will
present more than 8,000 research papers on everything from galactic
clusters to quarks, the tiniest bits of matter.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the meeting so big is that it is the 100th
anniversary of the APS, the leading society for physicists in the
United States and for many abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Meridith Owensby, a senior at Alexander High School in Douglas
County and a perfect scorer on the SAT, was nestled between Charles
Townes, whose discovery of the laser won him the Nobel Prize in
physics, and Allen Bromley, the White House science adviser during
the Bush adminstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little overwhelmed,'' said Owensby, who plans to attend
Georgia Tech and major in physics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were telling her about how physics tries to develop a
fundamental understanding of nature, and how one day she may help
achieve that,'' said Bromley. ``With a perfect SAT score, she could
have her choice of schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the luncheon, physics teacher Pat Waddell of the
Darlington School in Rome was still starry eyed. She had sat with
Georg Bednorz, who won the Nobel for helping discover
superconductivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm the most excited physics teacher you'll ever
meet,'' she said. ``This experience has been fantastic, awesome.
It's a physics teacher's dream to have this many giants in physics
assembled in one room, and have lunch with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
