<HEADER>
A8065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-EXAM-NYT &LR;      03-20 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-EXAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THIS POLICE EXAM, THE ENTIRE FORCE IS TESTED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRENTWOOD, N.Y. _ Lyndon Santiago almost didn't sign up for this
year's Suffolk County police test. He sat for the last exam in
1996, dug down for the $50 fee and got his hopes up, and then the
whole test was thrown out because of a cheating scandal.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Santiago thought long before registering again. He
has been trying to become a police officer for five years, and he
knows he would make a good one. But the fee for the test has been
raised to $100 _ the most for a civil service exam in the state,
and no small amount for a 25-year-old courier with a wife and
daughter. Most of his friends who wanted to become officers have
since given up or found jobs in other departments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he kept thinking about the pay, among the nation's
highest. Suffolk police officers earn $70,659 after five years on
the force. ``You can have a real career with that kind of money,''
Santiago said. ``Right now, I have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   So, two months from now, Santiago and thousands of would-be
officers from all over the New York area will crowd into classrooms
and gymnasiums from Huntington to the Hamptons for the test.
Hundreds of men and women are paying as much as $320 for
preparatory courses offered in New York City and on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago, who was born in Puerto Rico and lives in Central
Islip, is one of about 60 Latinos, blacks, Asian-Americans and
immigrants who began a free eight-week prep course Saturday at the
Brentwood Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   If the applicants are nervous, they are not alone. For the
Suffolk Police Department, the stakes have never been higher.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, widespread cheating defeated what police officials said
had been the department's best effort yet to comply with a
longstanding federal court order to increase the number of blacks,
Hispanics and women in its overwhelmingly white male ranks. Largely
as a result, the officials say, there still are 62 black officers _
just three more than in 1990. The 2,661-person force is still more
than 80 percent white male.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner John C. Gallagher is eager to send 100 new
recruits to the academy to replace those who have left. As many as
800 more officers will be eligible to retire next year, he said.
But if the results of this year's test prove unfair to minorities,
the Justice Department could bring the department back to court for
violating the terms of a 1986 consent degree.
</P>
<P>
   With the deadline for applications approaching on Thursday, the
number of registrants for the police test is about half what it was
at the same time in 1996. Even worse, officials said, the
percentage who are black is down considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher said the drop in minority applicants was frustrating,
but he could not explain it. ``This is a very attractive job,'' he
said. ``And we make, I think, heroic efforts to reach out,
especially to African-American candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Suffolk recruiters visit the traditionally black
colleges in the South, military bases, and hundreds of colleges
throughout the Northeast. On Friday, a recruiter was handing out
fliers in Pennsylvania Station. Recruiters have been visiting
schools and subway stations in the Bronx, Brooklyn and Queens
repeatedly in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is mystified by this year's drop in minority
applicants, however. ``It doesn't take anything more than common
sense to tell you that doubling the fee is going to
disproportionately exclude African-Americans and Latinos,'' said
Joe Morris, an organizer for Long Island Congregations,
Associations and Neighborhoods, a church-based advocacy group that
is sponsoring the Brentwood preparatory course along with the John
Jay College of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   In a much debated moved, the Suffolk Legislature raised the fee
to cover the costs of the exam, which are expected to exceed $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how helpful any of the preparatory courses will
be; instructors know little about the actual test, which has been
revised since 1996. The earlier test was aimed at addressing a
problem identified by the Justice Department in dozens of police
civil-service examinations across the country in the 1970s and
1980s: When only cognitive skills were tested _ things like memory,
spatial relations, and language ability _ minorities scored sharply
lower than whites.
</P>
<P>
   So, beginning with the 1988 test, applicants were also asked to
describe themselves, in the hopes of identifying those with the
traits needed to become successful police officers. Adding such
``biographical'' questions to the mix was supposed to reduce the
gap in scores between whites and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But those questions _ such as ``At what age did you learn to
swim?'' and ``How many of your relatives work in law enforcement?''
_ seemed irrelevant to many candidates and Suffolk officials. So
much so, in fact, that county legislators approved a resolution
blocking the use of biographical questions in the coming exam, set
for May 22. A veto from County Executive Gaffney is expected,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 cheating scandal, which resulted in the indictment of
one officer and suspensions for 38 others, prompted the department
to hire a new testing company. Rick R. Jacobs, a partner in the
Pennsylvania firm that is designing this year's test, promised that
the new exam's questions would not seem so bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our questions will look like they belong on the police test,''
he said, offering little more in the way of detail. ``They'll tap
into what they're supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   One common concern among blacks and Latinos is that, no matter
how fair the questions, the right answers will have been determined
by interviews with white Suffolk police officers. But Jacobs said
he was careful to interview a disproportionately high number of
black and Latino officers. ``We're as interested as they are in
having a diversified work force,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
