<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOG-RUN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARKING ERUPTS AT SILENT RALLY TO SAVE CITY'S LARGEST DOG RUN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With complaints of noise threatening the future of
the city's largest dog run, more than 30 dog owners and their pets
turned out at Theodore Roosevelt Park here Saturday to protest
quietly and show how well-behaved their dogs could be.
</P>
<P>
   But despite coaching from a dog behaviorist, the efforts of a
noise-reduction subcommittee and signs urging silence, barking
broke out at Teddy's Dog Run on the north side of the Museum of
Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey, a muddy sheepdog, yelped when a Labrador retriever eyed
the Nerf football clenched in his jaws. Despite frantic shushing
from owners, the dogs noisily greeted a neighbor known for
distributing snacks.
</P>
<P>
   The howling seemed only to heighten the tension between the dog
owners and the residents on 81st Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a constant barking sound which explodes at least once
an hour into snarling and yelping,'' said Jack Flam as he glared at
the dog run from his sixth-floor apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over the dog run has pitted a community board and a
block association against the dog owners, who have formed their own
group, Friends of Museum Park Dog Run. It started when the Parks
Department began a multimillion-dollar effort to restore and
landscape the museum's grounds and in the process, upgrade the dog
run.
</P>
<P>
   The run is now a 13,000 square-foot dust pit surrounded by
chicken wire. The plan calls for the run to be moved closer to the
museum wall, to be filled in with pea gravel and to be surrounded
by shrubbery to muffle sound.
</P>
<P>
   But the 81st Street Block Association said that the barking
would reverberate against the museum wall, making it even louder,
and that the dogs would muck up a cultural gem.
</P>
<P>
   The association made an alternate proposal to move the dog run
to 77th Street and Central Park West, and offered the Parks
Department $150,000 to relocate it. On Feb. 12, it submitted the
proposal to Community Board 7.
</P>
<P>
   On March 2, the community board voted to hold off on approving
the plan to upgrade the existing dog run. The dog owners countered
with a resolution to save the original run but to strictly enforce
rules against houndish behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The community board is to vote on whether to approve the Parks
Department's dog run plan on April 6, so the dogs turned out
Saturday to parade their manners. But Flam, a member of the block
association and the community board, was far from satisfied. ``We
are one block away from Central Park, the largest park in the
city,'' he said. ``Why does anyone have to come over here and bark
under our windows?''
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense to have the dog run next to the museum, said
Michael Pennachias, the sheepdog owner who is heading the group's
public relations effort. ``Dogs have been a part of natural history
for thousands of years,'' he pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
