<HEADER>
A8067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GORE-PROSPECTS-N     03-20 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GORE-PROSPECTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REINVENTING AL GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, March 21:
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has been one of the most active vice presidents in U.S.
history, a central player in an administration that continues to
get high approval ratings. Yet those same polls show that the
public is ambivalent about a Gore presidency.
</P>
<P>
   That may be unsettling to Gore, but he is hardly the first vice
president to face the problem of stepping out of the shadows.
Indeed, his problem is less formidable than that faced by George
Bush. In 1988, Bush had to offer himself as a substitute for the
American family's revered, if somewhat dotty father figure. Gore
has only to supplant the overindulged naughty brother.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Gore will have to offer more than an exaggerated rural
boyhood, a resume and an aura of entitlement if he is to win in his
own right.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Gore seems better positioned for the race than most
vice presidents. The insider books from this administration make it
clear that Gore has filled the role Clinton promised him, as one of
the president's most important advisers. One of Gore's signature
issues, the environment, is moving toward the center of the
national agenda. He is positively identified with new technology,
despite his grandiose claim about ``creating the Internet.'' As for
reinventing government, his orations put listeners into a cryogenic
trance, but they lock in the New Democrat wonk vote.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on the matter of presidential dignity, where Clinton
has managed to replace Warren G. Harding as the century's most
notable underachiever, Gore practically radiates assurance of a
dull private life. Unlike most politicians his age _ including
George W. Bush _ he saw overseas duty in the armed forces during
the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, Gore faces formidable problems. One assumes his
ability to sound as if he is talking down to slightly dull third
graders has defied the arts of Washington's finest speech coaches.
If he lacks the deficits of the bad Bill Clinton, he also lacks the
feel-your-pain skills of the good Clinton. Clinton's preternatural
empathy with whoever was in front of him gave him an enormous
advantage in the kind of campaigning that stresses staged
give-and-take with ``regular Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore cannot turn himself into a Clinton-esque campaigner. But he
has to find a way to show that he has not been permanently tainted
by the situational ethics of this administration's fund-raising.
When the presidential race really begins, the public is bound to
see a lot of Republican ads showing film clips of Gore's Buddhist
temple visit and his richly imagined account of his work there.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president would be smart to separate himself, early on,
from the Clinton campaign-finance legacy. He should assert that the
standard for his fund-raising will be something stricter than
whatever a pliant attorney general will allow. Gore needs to speak
candidly about what went wrong with the administration's
fund-raising operation in 1996 and how he will avoid Clinton's
mistakes in trading access for contributions and in taking suspect
foreign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Polls also indicate that voters do not regard Gore as a strong
leader. Somewhat surprisingly, foreign policy may provide an
opportunity for him to sketch a distinctive vision during the
campaign. Despite his worthy diplomatic successes in Northern
Ireland and the Middle East, Clinton may leave some gaps in his
international-relations legacy. He has fumbled relations with
China, has not done enough to look ahead to the next generation of
leadership in Russia and has hesitated about breaking out of the
Cold War with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it, Gore finds himself in a position to punch
up the lagging administration effort to cut the number of Russian
and U.S. nuclear weapons left over from the era of mutually assured
destruction. It is a subject Gore knows well, since as vice
president he chairs twice-a-year meetings with the Russian prime
minister. One of those meetings is scheduled to take place this
week. If Gore can get the drive toward nuclear weapons reduction
back on track, it might do a lot to impress the American people
with his leadership skills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
