<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGERS FOR THE AMERICA'S CUP ARE CLOSELY GUARDING THEIR
SECRETS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ It would seem that security at a boat yard would
not be much of a concern. But America's Cup fever has been known to
force competitors to search each other's garbage for clues on boat
design. So with the start of the next cup races less than seven
months away, no one is taking chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have curtains inside the door of the boat shed, and the
whole bit,'' Turtle Telfeyan, the general manager of Eric Goetz
Custom Sailboats in Bristol, R.I., said recently. ``We're careful
with all our staff. But we're not guarding against ourselves, the
way we had to do in 1995 when we were building boats for two
different syndicates. We're guarding against all the others.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goetz yard, of course, has something to hide. It has a
contract with the Young America syndicate to build both of the New
York Yacht Club's new 70-foot sailboats for the America's Cup
challengers' trials this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   New York's first new boat is expected to be finished in June,
and the second, which has not been started yet, is apt to take
another five months to build. Both are designed by Bruce Farr &AMP;
Associates, the race-boat firm in Annapolis, Md.
</P>
<P>
   South of Bristol, also in Rhode Island, the new cup contender
for Dennis Conner's Stars &AMP; Stripes syndicate is under
construction. It was designed by Reichel/Pugh, a naval
architectural firm in San Diego. David MacBain, a partner in the
boat-building company, has imposed similar security measures on his
waterfront site in Portsmouth.
</P>
<P>
   Workers have to slip a card into a key slot to get inside the
boat shed. Visitors are not allowed. And employees are required to
sign a document that promises they will not discuss their client's
boat design with anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have confidentiality agreements now even with non-America's
Cup boats,'' MacBain said. ``With a new keel, or any type of design
that is on the cutting edge of racing, you have to sign off on the
blueprints.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure from owners has increased in the last decade as
prices soar for hybrid yachts built with space-age materials. The
America's Cup sailboats are constructed of carbon fiber, a
composite resin material that is twice as expensive as fiberglass,
a more conventional hull material.
</P>
<P>
   The boat yards buy 300-foot rolls of carbon fiber that are
already impregnated with resin. The resin acts like glue to
sandwich a honeycomb core between two layers of carbon fiber skin.
Builders of an America's Cup yacht might go through as many as 70
of the carbon fiber rolls _ at $800 a pop _ to complete a hull.
</P>
<P>
   Once the layers of resin cloth and core are laid by hand onto a
giant mold, the whole boat is slid into a room-size oven.
Temperatures of more than 200 degrees bake the material so that it
cures into a stiff, but lightweight, hull form.
</P>
<P>
   Upside down, like a beached whale, the ungainly hull is then
rock-hard and ready for its finishing touches _ an interior, decks,
rigging and hardware. Once in the water, it is a $3 million yacht
designed to withstand the tremendous rigging loads that fully
powered sails impose on an International America's Cup Class race
boat.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 15 international challenge teams have already
designed their new boats, and a handful have started construction.
But the clock is ticking. The boats need to be shipped to Auckland,
New Zealand, for the Oct. 18 start of the Louis Vuitton Challengers
Series.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand's defense team is not under the same time
constraints. It plans no in-house trials, just testing. As the
America's Cup defender, a title the small Southern Hemisphere
community won in 1995 by defeating Conner's Stars &AMP; Stripes team,
New Zealand can build its new boat as late as it wants. The cup
match itself is scheduled to begin Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   That also means New Zealand could gain from any inside knowledge
of its opponents. ``It would do them a lot of good to see what each
challenge boat looks like,'' Telfeyan said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
