u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-BROWNFIELDS-REAL-2     03-20 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BROWNFIELDS-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: NEW JERSEY HELPS DEVELOPERS RECYCLE POLLUTED AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RACHELLE GARBARINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Todd L. Normane calls the more flexible way the state works with
developers to recycle polluted industrial sites ``more like a
handshake than a hammer.''
</P>
<P>
   For the process includes a new financial incentive _
reimbursement for up to 75 percent of the cleanup cost.
</P>
<P>
   Normane _ a lawyer at Maraziti, Falcon &AMP; Healy, a Short Hills,
N.J., firm that specializes in environmental and redevelopment law
_ is representing Arc Properties of Clifton, N.J., whose project is
the first approved for the reimbursement under the 1998 Brownfields
and Contaminated Sites Redemption Act.
</P>
<P>
   A draft of the redevelopment agreement setting the terms of the
reimbursement was completed earlier this month and the state and
the developer are expected to sign an accord by the end of the
month, Normane said.
</P>
<P>
   Arc is cleaning up the contaminants from a 30-acre site at the
intersection of Routes 1 and 287 in the south-central portion of
Edison Township in Middlesex County. At the same time, it is razing
four interconnecting industrial buildings formerly occupied by a
steel tubing manufacturer, which filed for bankruptcy in 1995, to
make way for a 285,000-square-foot shopping center called Edison
Crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the cleanup, plans for which have been approved by
the state's Department of Environmental Protection, is estimated at
$1.5 million; 75 percent of it, or $1.2 million, is expected to be
returned to Arc under the reimbursement program, said Normane.
</P>
<P>
   Eight tenants have signed on for all of the space at the
project, which will cost a total of $25 million to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Home Depot, taking 138,000 square feet; Edwards
Super Food Store, with 57,000 square feet; Worldwide Floor
Coverings, 40,000 square feet, and Office Depot, 27,500 square
feet. Completion is scheduled for early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is always great in such redevelopment projects,''
Normane said, ``but the reimbursement incentive helps to level the
playing field and add a little more reward to the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 brownfields act is the latest in a series of steps New
Jersey has taken in recent years to facilitate the reuse of the
10,000 contaminated sites in the state, down from about 20,000 in
1985, that are the legacy of its industrial past. Of the remaining
sites, about 1,130 are so-called brownfields _ which the state
defines as former commercial or industrial sites that are
underutilized or abandoned and contain known or perceived
contaminants _ that are being cleaned and redeveloped.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the reimbursement, the act provides purchasers of
tainted sites protection from private lawsuits related to past
contamination problems and carries an assurance that the state will
not sue once the site is cleaned according to its standards.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the reimbursement, developers must, among other
things, demonstrate that they were not the polluter, that their
projects are economically feasible and that they will create jobs
and fit with local, regional and state planning objectives.
</P>
<P>
   The most important condition is that the projects must generate
new tax revenue that exceeds the cost of the cleanup. The state
uses projections of eight different state taxes, from sales to use
and corporate taxes, to calculate a project's revenue. Developers
must clean the site in accordance with a plan approved by the
state's Department of Environmental Protection and enter a
redevelopment agreement with the state approved by the Commerce &AMP;
Economic Growth Commission and the state treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement specifies the amount of the reimbursement and the
frequency and duration of the payments. The latter is directly tied
to the occupancy rate of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aim is to entice developers to take a second look at
abandoned and tainted properties that are not now producing revenue
and get them back on the tax rolls,'' said Kelly A. Woods, deputy
director of the Office of Urban Programs, within New Jersey's
Commerce &AMP; Economic Growth Commission, which administers the
reimbursement program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a revenue neutral program for the state,'' said Ms.
Woods, explaining that _ rather than go into the state treasury _
the taxes collected from qualified projects go into a special
reimbursement fund and are filtered back to the project's
developer. Thus, if revenue does not come into the state from the
redevelopment project ``the developer does not receive a penny,''
she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Edison project, applications for four others are in
various stages of the review process and there have been
pre-application meetings with developers for 13 more.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The success of the first project will be key, she added, because
it will send the message that ``the program does work.''
</P>
<P>
   Arc became involved with the Edison project in 1995 when it
secured approvals from the Federal Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan to
buy the 30-acre tract. It closed the transaction last June. ``The
whole attraction to the site was its location,'' said Marc A.
Perel, executive vice president at Arc.
</P>
<P>
   He said that, along with being visible from and accessible to
two major highways, the property was close to two regional malls
and in a neighborhood of Edison that has been changing from
industrial to retail use.
</P>
<P>
   Contaminants on the site and in the groundwater include
petroleum hydrocarbons and chemical solvent left behind from
industrial users. ``Though there may be easier sites to develop,''
Perel said, ``ones of this size with this kind of location are
difficult to find.''
</P>
<P>
   The former owner _ Berger Industries, the steel-tubing
manufacturer _ had operated on the site for 14 years before it shut
down in 1993, two years before filing for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years other smaller companies also operated on part of
the site, including a fragrance manufacturer. In recent years,
sections of the 360,000-square-foot industrial complex Berger
Industries once occupied were subleased to a collection of retail
and commercial tenants. But after Arc invested two years and over
$1 million in the project Perel said it became apparent the
magnitude of the cleanup was greater than expected. The company
sought the reimbursement incentive last March soon after the state
made it available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became important to mitigate the cost overruns we didn't
anticipate, making the project much more economically feasible,''
Perel said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the cleanup plan, high levels of pollutants on portions of
the property will be removed and carted off the site. Areas with
low levels will be capped with an impervious surface.
</P>
<P>
   What helped in pursuing the reimbursement incentive, said
Normane, the lawyer, is that the Edison Crossroads redevelopment
had all its approvals in place and tenants lined up, showing the
viability of the project. In turn, he said, it will generate $4.5
million a year in sales taxes alone, which is $3 million more than
needed to cover the cost to clean the property. He added that the
property, when redeveloped, would create 800 jobs and rise in value
to $31 million from $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Smith, a legislative analyst at the Site Remediation
Program, part of the state's Department of Environmental
Protection, said Edison Crossroads ``was a perfect match'' for the
reimbursement program and a good project for the state to support
``because everyone involved stands to benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Perel said the area's demographics also supported the project,
which with its open-air design and collection of so-called big-box
retailers, will be a ``power center.'' He said some 280,000 people
with an average household income of $69,000 live within a five-mile
radius of the site.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Brunelli, who heads a retail brokerage in Old Bridge
bearing his name, said the vacancy rate in strip centers and
free-standing stores along the entire 30-mile Route 1 retail
corridor _ where Edison Crossroads is situated _ had dropped to 6.3
percent by the end of 1998 from 7.7 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is demand in the Woodbridge-Edison trade area for
another power center and for another half million square feet of
space beyond that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (The International Council of Shopping Centers in Manhattan
defines a power center as an open-air retail strip with 250,000 to
750,000 square feet of space and three or more big-box retailers.)
</P>
<P>
   Brunelli added that with today's strong economy and real estate
market developers across the state are tearing down old industrial
complexes and replacing them with new uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``But often,'' he added, ``the difference is making such
projects economically feasible or not is the cost of the cleanup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
