<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT &LR;      03-20 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 REAL ESTATE: RESTORING AN AGING BATHTUB  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a shirt gets stained and yellow you retire it
and when a carpet gets worn and shabby, you toss it out and get a
new one.
</P>
<P>
   But what do you do when the above conditions apply to an
800-pound hunk of porcelain in your bathroom?
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever try to get a bathtub into an elevator?'' said
Richard Toder, executive director of T/S Associates, a
mechanical-systems consulting company in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Toder, a licensed plumber who has waltzed more than a few tubs
out of tight corners, said that in addition to the logistical
difficulties involved in hauling a cast-iron clunker out of a house
or an apartment, replacing an existing fixture can also result in
unexpected expenses when floor or wall tiles are disturbed or
broken or when a fragile old plumbing system must be replaced and
brought up to code.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, it is becoming increasingly common for
home and apartment owners to make the best of what they already
have by restoring aging fixtures in place. With coating materials
and methods for applying them steadily improving, Toder said, there
are now several cost-effective techniques available for
refinishing, refacing, relining and generally rejuvenating
deteriorating fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your tub holds water,'' he said, ``restoration is probably
the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners can generally make at least a marginal improvement in
the appearance of their fixtures by applying epoxy-based coatings
sold in most home centers, But generally speaking, he said, the
quality of the appearance of such finishes is dependent entirely on
the skill of the amateur craftsman.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative, of course, is to hire a professional and get the
job done right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do bathtubs, wall tiles, floor tiles, sinks and even
toilets,'' said Francine Tumolo, an owner of Perma Ceram
Enterprises, a Smithtown, N.Y., company that manufactures and
distributes a ``synthetic porcelain'' reglazing product.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, she said, a bathtub can be reglazed with Perma
Ceram in three or four hours and will be dry enough to use in 12.
``To do a tub runs anywhere from $250 to $300,'' she said. ``That
comes with a five-year guarantee and a 15-year life expectancy.''
Ms. Tumolo said that her company could also reglaze ceramic-tile
tub enclosures. ``When we do tile, we spray right over the grout
lines and seal them,'' she said. ``That means no more scraping
mildew with a toothbrush.''
</P>
<P>
   John Fred, president of Perma-Glaze Remodeling in Deer Park,
N.Y., said that the finish material he uses is a polymer resin that
provides the ``look and feel of porcelain'' when it cures. In most
cases, Fred said, the first step in refinishing a bathtub or sink
is to clean the fixture thoroughly, remove any existing rust or
caulking materials, and fill any cracks or chips. Then, he said,
the surface is ``etched'' with an acid wash to make it slightly
porous, and primed with a rust-inhibiting primer.
</P>
<P>
   The top coat of Perma-Glaze is then sprayed on, Fred said, and
takes about 48 hours to fully cure. ``We can accelerate the drying
time with a heat lamp,'' he said, adding that in most cases, the
Perma-Glaze top coat can be custom-matched to any color used by
American Standard or Kohler, two large bath-fixture manufacturers.
Perma-Glaze will also refinish wall tiles, Fred said, adding that
the cost runs from $5 to $7 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Brennan, an owner of Worldwide Refinishing Systems in
Ringwood, N.J., said that her company used a urethane-based finish
originally developed for the aerospace industry. ``We always use
three coats,'' she said, adding that the finish material is sprayed
on top of a special bonding solution applied after the surface is
cleaned and etched. Ms. Brennan pointed out that since three finish
coats are used, it is possible to completely change the color of
the fixture being refinished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from hot-pink and black to all-avocado,'' she said.
``And we have matching acrylic coatings that can be used to make
any wood in the room match the fixtures.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brennan said that homeowners should make sure that their
refinishing contractor provides adequate ventilation of the
potentially dangerous fumes that may result from the refinishing
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use a filtered system that uses flexible tubing to vent
fumes from the bathroom to the outside,'' she said. She cautioned
that while mounting an exhaust fan in the bathroom window might
remove fumes, it was also more likely to draw dust particles from
other areas of the house and then deposit them in the finish coat
on the fixture.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brennan pointed out that, aside from the quality of the
refinishing material used, the most significant determinant of the
longevity of the restoration is the manner in which it is cleaned.
``You should never scrub,'' she said. ``And you should always use a
nonabrasive cleaner.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who want a more durable finish than can be obtained by
re-glazing, Ms. Brennan said, relining may be the answer. ``Our tub
liners start at around $700,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With a tub liner, the existing tub is encased in the liner.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Brakel, vice president of franchise operations for Bath
Fitter, a liner manufacturer in South Burlington, Vt., said that
her company could manufacture one-piece, quarter-inch-thick liners
that are custom-tailored to fit each customer's tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have literally hundreds of molds,'' Ms. Brakel said.
</P>
<P>
   The liners, she said, utilize existing plumbing connections and
faucets and are typically indistinguishable from stand-alone
bathtubs. To complete the custom-made appearance, Ms. Brakel said,
Bath Fitter franchisees can also install matching one-piece tub
surrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely seamless all around and from tub to ceiling,''
she said, adding that a typical tub-and-wall installation could run
anywhere from $1,500 to $1,800. And though it may take a week or
two after measurements are taken for the franchisee to install the
unit, the actual installation can usually be completed in an
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding similar installation-time claims by nearly all
re-finishers and reliners, Ms. Tumolo of Perma Ceram in Smithtown
offered one final bit of advice applicable to all homeowners
contemplating face-lifts for their bathtubs. ``Bathe before we get
there,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
