<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NH-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: IS NEW HAMPSHIRE RIPE FOR GOV. WHOSIT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an Editorial Observer on Sunday,
March 21:
</P>
<P>
   Let me summarize George Pataki's problem this way. While I was
in Manchester, N.H., for Pataki's big debut as a potential
Republican presidential candidate at a Lincoln Day dinner, I got
into an argument with a cab driver who insisted that the governor
of New York is Rudy Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's been here already,'' the driver concluded, satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pataki's big selling point is all the things he has
accomplished as governor, this is the sort of confusion that could
present a serious drawback. Still, he seemed extremely pleased by
the welcome he received in New Hampshire, where he was front-page
news in the local papers, one of which referred to him as ``the
Dennis Rodman of potential Republican candidates.'' ( Pataki is
very tall, but the point was that both men have vague career
plans.)
</P>
<P>
   This was much better treatment than Pataki gets in New York,
where journalists generally do not regard him as colorful enough to
compare with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you running?'' asked a Manchester television interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom, what I'm trying to do is make sure my party has a
positive agenda for change,'' said Pataki, in a mantra he repeated
over and over for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Of course he is running, or at least running around, and
``testing the waters,'' as the candidates like to say. Many people
may wonder why. Sure, Republican governors are all the rage this
year, but there are 31 of them, including the Big Kahuna in Texas.
Pataki does not have much name recognition, even among people as
sophisticated about Republican presidential candidates as New
Hampshire cab drivers. He has no organization, and he is infamous
in New York as a terrible public speaker. Among his own
constituents, there may be fewer people wondering whether Pataki
can win the Republican presidential nomination than people
speculating whether he has taken leave of his senses.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's quest may be improbable, but it is not crazy. If
Pataki did jump into the Republican race, he would be the only
pro-choice candidate in a field of about 12. Abortion rights are
not generally a cause that gets you very far in Republican
primaries, but a sizable minority of the Republicans in New
Hampshire are pro-choice, including the state chairman. The round
of primaries after New Hampshire's includes Pataki's home state and
California, where many Republicans believe they lost the
governorship on the abortion issue and are eager to avoid that trap
again.
</P>
<P>
   The current Republican talent pool is large but shallow. George
W. Bush is still something of an unknown quantity. Elizabeth Dole's
candidacy has sparked enormous enthusiasm for the idea of a woman
presidential candidate, but very little for the idea of Elizabeth
Dole. No one else in the pack has shown any signs of catching fire.
If Bush turns out to be less overwhelming a candidate than
everybody imagines, perhaps Pataki could get respectable showings
in a crowded field. His tax-cutting credentials are arguably even
more pristine than those of Bush, whose early unsuccessful effort
at reforming Texas' tax structure involved raising the sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, Pataki's speeches are better than the labored
productions he delivers in Albany. The governor has terrible
eyesight, which makes it hard for him to handle a teleprompter and
adds to the plodding, high-school-valedictorian quality of his
delivery. But he gives his stump speech without notes, and he
sounds more down to earth and appealing. His theme is that
Democrats have been good at pre-empting Republican themes like
fiscal discipline and individual responsibility. But only
Republicans (well, really only Republican governors) can carry
through after the election is over. The speech is laced with
constant references to the evils of big Washington bureaucracy and
``elites.'' Pataki, a Yale-educated former Manhattan lawyer, has
absolutely nothing good to say about ``elites.''
</P>
<P>
   The defining characteristic of Pataki's political career has
been his eagerness to move up _ a rare quality in New York, where
politics is about finding a safe nest and staying there forever. He
has always gotten restless quickly, and run for the next-highest
job, even if it meant taking a risk. He has now climbed so far that
the next rung is almost ridiculously far above his head. But Pataki
has been governor for more than four years now, and even though he
keeps his home elsewhere, that's a long time to spend in Albany. If
he gets into the presidential race, he will probably get mentioned
as a possible vice-presidential choice or Cabinet appointee. At
minimum the drivers in Manchester will learn that the governor of
New York is not named Rudy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
