A8076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWYER-MISSING-1STLD-     03-20 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-MISSING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM LAWYER TO MISSING MAN TO FUGITIVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for new top)   By MIKE ALLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARLBOROUGH, Conn. _ A hard rain was tailing off about noon on
March 1 when F. Mac Buckley, a burly cigar smoker who was one of
Connecticut's best-known criminal-defense lawyers, pulled out of
the driveway of his 260-year-old Colonial here in the countryside
southeast of Hartford. He grabbed his cellular phone and called his
Hartford office to say he was headed for Federal court in New
Haven, where he was due at a 2 p.m. hearing for a client charged
with selling cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The judge and other lawyers waited until 5 p.m. and then gave
up. Buckley had vanished. He is 57 and has a wife and five grown
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   At first, his family and friends said they feared he might have
been done in by a former client or by an enemy of one of the many
gang members and mobsters he had defended over the years. State
police officers in cruisers and a plane scoured the roads and woods
between Marlborough and New Haven, checking ditches and parking
lots for his 1998 teal Lincoln Navigator with a New England
Patriots sticker on the back window.
</P>
<P>
   But Buckley quickly went from missing person to wanted man.
</P>
<P>
   As clients got over the shock of his disappearance and checked
their accounts, they began accusing him of absconding with hundreds
of thousands of dollars he had held in trust for them.
</P>
<P>
   Warrants were issued charging him with forgery and embezzlement,
and this week he was declared a federal fugitive. Investigators
said they plan to seek a warrant to seize his financial records in
the next few days, and expect more charges.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have soured between investigators and Buckley's
family. A senior state official said relatives did not report him
missing for 30 hours, and even then they made the report only after
the police had heard about the disappearance from other lawyers and
went to the Buckley home to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many of those who were taken in by Buckley's gregarious
machismo say they should have seen trouble looming. The requests
for fees in advance, the secretiveness, the blithe disregard for
phone messages had all made Dennis B. Messenger wonder about
Buckley, who was representing Messenger's brother on a murder
charge.
</P>
<P>
   But then the two met for sole and lobster at the Chowder Pot IV
restaurant in Hartford, where Buckley poured out tales of his years
of freeing mobsters, moonlighting as a boxing trainer and promoter,
and dabbling in politics. He barely paused to chew as he told how
he had worked his way through college and law school, then gotten
his start as a Federal drug prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   This was the full Mac Buckley treatment _ an entrancing rap he
had honed with juries and unleashed on ESPN as a commentator during
the O.J. Simpson trial. Messenger said that Buckley went on to
boast about his estate here in Marlborough, then confided that he
loved his work so much that he would never retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't conventional, but I could see he was powerful in the
state and knew how to work the system,'' Messenger recalls
thinking. ``It obviously worked for him, and it had for quite
awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Messenger picked up the check.
</P>
<P>
   The country ``estate'' turns out to be just a house _ the
adjoining 50-acre farm was sold off four years ago, although
Buckley still sometimes gave ``Buck Hill Farm'' as his address. The
house was put in the name of Buckley's wife, Donna, in 1990, and
she is the registered owner of all three of their cars.
</P>
<P>
   The message to his law office about him heading to New Haven may
have been a diversion. Investigators say that shortly after Buckley
headed out, a signal was detected from his cellular phone _ which
was briefly switched on, although he was not making calls _ near
Albany, just off Interstate 90.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they have one other clue.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon on March 5, a man approached a caretaker
at St. Agnes Cemetery in Menands, N.Y., just outside Albany, and
asked to be directed to the grave of Buckley's father. Later, the
caretaker was shown Buckley's photo, and he said he was certain
that Buckley was the curious visitor he had helped.
</P>
<P>
   But such was Buckley's mystique that many of his neighbors and
associates refuse to believe that he disappeared intentionally. In
the courthouses and law offices of Connecticut, the tales have
grown increasingly wild: that he has joined the federal
witness-protection program, that he has enlisted in the Irish
Republican Army, that he is on a gambling spree in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, his clients are left with no lawyer and, some
of them say, no money. John T. Spellman, an owner of Marlborough
Tavern, where Buckley used booth A-2 as a satellite office for
meeting clients, is left puzzling over what the lawyer told him in
their last conversation. `` `I'm like Frank Sinatra,' '' Spellman
said Buckley said he had told his doctor, spurning advice to give
up cigars and liquor. `` `I've done it my way. I'm not afraid to
die.'''
</P>
<P>
   Friends suspect the image-conscious Buckley would be dismayed to
learn that his ``wanted'' posters identify him as Francis McKeon
Buckley, the name he was given when he was born in New Haven. He
grew up in Scarsdale, N.Y., and graduated from the College of the
Holy Cross in Worcester, Mass., in 1963 and from Georgetown
University Law Center in 1967. He often described himself as ``a
Golden Gloves boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   He clerked for a Connecticut Supreme Court justice, then learned
both sides of the legal trade as an assistant federal prosecutor
and an assistant public defender. He lost when he ran for Congress
as a Republican in 1974, then was elected the next year as a
Councilman in Newington.
</P>
<P>
   At nights and on weekends, he was a boxing trainer and promoter,
and groomed one champion, the welterweight Marlon Starling. He made
friends around inner-city gyms by paying down-and-out fighters to
spar with his boxers. He often took a carload of poor youngsters to
see out-of-town fights.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley was at home with Connecticut society, where he bought a
$3,500 box at January's inaugural ball for Gov. John G. Rowland, as
well as in Hartford's housing projects, where youngsters who knew
him from boxing called him ``Big Daddy Mac.'' (MORE)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1852EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EGYPT-BALLOON21-COX     03-20 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-BALLOON21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BALLOONISTS BREAK RECORD, HEAD FOR LANDING IN EGYPT
 &HT;    650&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ Succeeding in their quest for the first nonstop balloon
flight around the world, a Swiss psychiatrist and British pilot
headed for an early Sunday landing of their high-tech craft in the
ancient sands of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am with the angels and just completely happy,'' Bertrand
Piccard said by satellite relay shortly he and partner Brian Jones
conquered one of aviation's last great challenges. ``We are
eternally grateful to the invisible hand that has guided us through
this fantastic voyage.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a trip that matched the highest technologies of aviation
and meteorology against the vagaries of high-altitude winds and
low-level sandstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Nearing its end, it would bring a shimmering vision of
end-of-the millennium adventurism and corporate sponsorship to the
Egyptian deserts, where the first civilizations were born and where
peasants still scrape out a living herding sheep and farming.
</P>
<P>
   Piccard, 41, seemed emblematic of the spirit of the trip. He is
the son of the scientist who set a depth record for ocean descent
in his bathyscaphe submarine and the grandson of the first man to
fly a balloon into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   His partner was Jones, a 51-year-old businessman who gave up his
kitchen wares company to pursue ballooning.
</P>
<P>
   The pair completed their circumnavigation at 4:54 a.m. EST. At
that point, about 34,000 feet over the northwestern nation of
Mauritania, the Breitling Orbiter 3 balloon crossed 9 degrees 27
minutes west longitude, a line it had crossed early in the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The balloon had been afloat for 20 days. It took off March 1
from Chateau-d'Oex in the Swiss Alps, and flew southwest at first
to catch favorable winds.
</P>
<P>
   Their pear-shaped balloon, made in England, is 180 feet tall and
weighs more than nine tons. A combination of hot air and helium
filled the giant silver canopy, heated by propane burners.
</P>
<P>
   The balloon uses state-of-the-art materials _ the capsule is
made of kevlar and carbon _ but remains largely at the mercy of the
elements. It often flew at speeds over 100 mph high in the
stratosphere, where the temperature in the pressurized cabin dipped
below 45 degrees (F).
</P>
<P>
   The pilots changed altitudes throughout the trip, searching for
cooperative jet stream winds. When necessary, they descended far
enough to emerge from their foul-smelling capsule and break away
crusted ice.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the Americas, Piccard resorted to self-hypnosis to help
ease his nerves. They considered ending the flight after stalling
over the Caribbean, but caught strong winds that quickly took them
across the Atlantic to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, where the trip was monitored at a makeshift center in
the Geneva airport, flight controllers broke open champagne to
celebrate the record journey.
</P>
<P>
   Balloon recovery personnel and media flew to Egypt. The planes
are expected to quickly take the pilots to Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   With more than one day's supply of propane fuel still aboard,
the balloonists said late Saturday they would try to reach the
desert near the Nile river south of Cairo for their dawn landing.
</P>
<P>
   The landing zone shifted throughout the day. Winds near Cairo
scratched a plan to land the craft near the 4,500-year-old pyramids
of the Giza Plateau. Sandstorms, normal for this season,
complicated other landing zones.
</P>
<P>
   By concluding the trip in Egypt, the crew was in the same
country where, in 1981, Maxie Anderson and Don Ida started the
first attempt at a balloon circumnavigation. Its lasted only 48
hours. Fifteen other journeys would be launched, many by a group of
millionaire adventurers that includes British Virgin magnate
Richard Branson and American businessman Steve Fosset.
</P>
<P>
   The watch company that sponsored the trip refuses to say how
much it has spent, though this is its third attempt and costs are
certainly in the millions of dollars. Company officials vowed the
third try would be last _ succeed or fail.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Piccard's, who arrived in Cairo Saturday night to try
to meet his landing, said the trip fulfilled dreams of his and
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it is the last great adventure of the century,'' said
Jean Claude Metille, 45, a Swiss advertising executive who came to
Cairo on a private jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us in Switzerland, it is a big subject. It is the same as
the story of (American pilot Charles) Lindbergh. ...The story will
say that, in the 20th century, there was Lindbergh, (Astronaut
Neil) Armstrong and Piccard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armelle Sermier, a wife of the media coordinator for the
journey, said the landing would not be just the culmination of a
three-week trip, but a three-year struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big relief and the result of many sacrifices,'' said
Sermier, 36. Asked if it was worth the work, she answered, ``For
people who like to dream, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
