<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUMFIELD MAKES MOST OF CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ The stars and staples of teams try to
survive spring training without incident, gearing up for the
regular season with no huge worries.
</P>
<P>
   It's the fringe players who need to impress, and who can win
jobs. Outfielder Jacob Brumfield, who toiled in Triple-A Charlotte
in the Florida Marlins organization last season, is doing just
that. He's making a push to unseat the injured Trenidad Hubbard as
the Dodgers' fifth outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   While Hubbard is recovering from a thumb and shoulder injury
suffered in a March 8 outfielder collision, Brumfield is getting
playing time and showcasing his speed.
</P>
<P>
   He went 1 for 3 Saturday against the Baltimore Orioles, but
equally as impressive was Brumfield's ability to go from first to
third on a groundout to third baseman Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can play. He knows how to play,'' manager Davey Johnson
said. ``A lot of the times the question with Jacob is his health.
When he's healthy, he can still play.''
</P>
<P>
   Brumfield said the reason he spent last season in the minors was
a recurring hamstring injury, from which he tried to return too
quickly. But an offseason playing in Venezuela eased his mind in
regards to health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is dominated by numbers, and last season I didn't
have them,'' said Brumfield, who's hitting .320 since moving from
the minor-league clubhouse to the Dodgers clubhouse 10 days ago.
``Right now I'm feeling pretty confident (about making the team).
If I'm healthy, I can help anybody. Right now I feel like I'm
pretty healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek scratched: Johnson's original lineup card had Mark
Grudzielanek starting at shortstop, but that was altered before the
two-hour bus ride south from Dodgertown because Grudzielanek is
suffering from shin splints.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't appear to sit well with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know shin splints was something that could keep you
out of a game,'' Johnson said. ``Just put your (support) hose on
and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Starter Darren Dreifort had his longest
outing of the spring, not allowing a run in four innings. He
yielded three hits but was bothered by the three walks he issued.
In his past two outings, Dreifort has walked eight batters. ``The
results were better (than the last outing), but I still walked too
many,'' Dreifort said. ``I get out of whack mechanically. The guys
I'm walking, I'm just not compensating quick enough.'' . . . Warren
Newson, considered a long shot to make the club as a utility
outfielder, saw his chances diminish even further when he pulled up
lame trying to beat out a grounder in the first inning. ``I felt it
pop in the back of my (right) hamstring,'' Newson said. It could
keep him out of the lineup for more than a week, Johnson said. . .
. Right-hander Dave Mlicki, who hasn't pitched since March 13
because of stiffness near his right shoulder blade, is scheduled to
pitch in a simulated game today. Johnson said Mlicki could pitch in
the regular game, but there may not be enough innings for him to do
so since Kevin Brown is making the start against the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's recap: Baltimore scored twice in the bottom of the
eighth inning to defeat the Dodgers 3-2 at Fort Lauderdale Stadium.
The winning run scored when right fielder Scott Livingstone
misplayed Danny Clyburn's single, which allowed a run to score from
first base. Reliever Doug Bochtler allowed a hit and walked two in
one inning and took the loss. &QL; 
Today's game: Right-hander Kevin Brown returns to the mound for his
fourth outing of the spring as the Dodgers host the Montreal Expos
at 10:05 a.m. Brown is 0-0 with a 2.31 ERA and has walked one
batter in 112/3 innings. &QL; 
Radio: XTRA-AM (1150) and KAVL-AM (610). &QL; 
_ Brian Dohn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-WRAPUP21-COX     03-20 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-WRAPUP21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Degree of reform will shape IOC's future
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr. and Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Next year, when the world's 10,000 best
and brightest competitors enter the Olympic stadium in Sydney, the
IOC's nightmare will end, says Anita DeFrantz, the senior U.S.
member of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do will be criticized until the first athletes
compete in Sydney,'' DeFrantz said last week at the end of the
IOC's emergency session, intended in part to calm the critics.
``That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The sordid details of the Salt Lake City bidding scandal will
melt away, as the world remembers whatever it is about the Olympic
Games that makes them so special. The Games always offer a chance
for renewal, but never has the IOC needed the event as it does
these days.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the IOC members, usually accustomed to being fawned
over by eager representatives of bidding cities, often looked more
like organized crime bosses dodging reporters waiting on the
courthouse steps during racketeering trials. Men and women of some
note in their countries, they were reduced to explaining how they
spend the $150-a-day allowances provided them by the IOC when they
travel on committee business.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Dick Pound, the powerful IOC member from Montreal,
spent several minutes trying to justify to hostile Canadian
reporters a $44 bill he charged the bidding committee in Quebec for
alterations to a sports coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on their bid committee,'' he said solemnly. ``They
wanted my blazer to fit.''
</P>
<P>
   So, they dream of Sydney, and the chance for the universe to
realign once again, with the IOC returned to its place of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Reforms incomplete
</P>
<P>
   IOC members point with satisfaction to the accomplishments of
the emergency session and then express frustration that in the eyes
of many critics _ particularly in the United States _ it did not
seem to be enough.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented act, the IOC expelled six members because
they accepted cash, favors and other gifts from the Salt Lake City
committee bidding for the 2002 Winter Games. Four others had
resigned. The IOC also is forming an ethics commission to help
prevent a repeat of the scandal that threatened the Games. And an
as-yet-unidentified reform panel _ IOC 2000 _ is supposed to draw
up a radical redesign of a body that, except for its bank balance,
has changed little in 105 years.
</P>
<P>
   However, IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch, himself a target
of much of the world's barbs, will chair the reform body. Last
month, Samaranch was rebuffed when he attempted to put himself in
charge of an agency to oversee a worldwide effort to control
doping. Americans and Europeans thought that he lacked credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he should head the reform commission, Samaranch said
defiantly: ``I am president of the IOC. This commission must be
presided over by the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch insists the IOC has done what it said it would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We promised to clean house,'' he said. ``We did it. We
promised reforms. We did it. We promised an Olympics united. It's
done.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, however, the reform process is far from done. In the
United States, the Justice Department continues its investigation
of the Salt Lake scandal and Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes pushes for
opening Atlanta's bid records of the '96 Games.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), the Commerce Committee chairman
and one of the most formidable members of Congress, said the
changes made, while radical by IOC standards, ``fall far short of
the reforms needed to bring transparency and accountability to the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing I have witnessed provides any substantive movement in
that direction,'' said McCain, who last week issued a series of
daily rebukes about the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's harshest critic among corporate sponsors also said the
committee needed to do more. ``I didn't hear any reform yet,'' said
David D'Alessandro, president of John Hancock insurance. ``What I
heard was they are going to study reform.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the expulsions were irrelevent and then groused that
the reform effort is bogus because Samaranch will chair the reform
commission and appoint its members. ``It displays a failure to
grasp even the most basic concepts of ethics and reform,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. tone baffles IOC
</P>
<P>
   In Lausanne, some IOC members are genuinely befuddled by the
persistance of U.S. lawmakers, who won't drop the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Senegal's Keba Mbaye strode across the white marble
floors of IOC headquarters reading a copy of McCain's latest
missive and muttering to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is this McCain?'' Alex Gilady, an IOC member from Israel,
demanded of an U.S. reporter. ``What does he want?''
</P>
<P>
   A Senate hearing, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   In April, McCain will lead a hearing prompted by the Salt Lake
scandal but broadening its interest to include a inquiry into the
IOC itself. McCain and Sen. Ted Stevens (R-Alaska) have threatened
to revoke the IOC's tax-exempt status, limit the percentage of
sponsorship fees that companies can deduct from their taxes and
redirect TV rights fees to the U.S. Olympic Committee rather than
the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro says corporations would put their money elsewhere
if Congress stripped tax deductions for Games marketing.
</P>
<P>
   That worries Salt Lake organizers, who need $288 million more
from sponsors to finance its budget. Mitt Romney, the new chairman
of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, was in Lausanne seeking the
IOC's help in identifying how he can cut the committee's $1.5
billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the IOC is angry at the USOC, which threw the blame for
the Salt Lake scandal almost entirely on the international
organization even though it happened in the USOC's backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Many IOC members are saying among themselves that the committee
might just reduce its reliance on U.S. sponsors. If the Coca-Cola
Co., McDonald's or some other big sponsor leaves, IOC marketers
would respond by redoubling its effort in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that most of the longtime sponsors will leave. But
they will demand that promised reforms materialize. Ben Deutsch,
Coca-Cola spokesman, said: ``Ultimately, the success of this
meeting is going to be determined by the IOC's ability to continue
to quickly define, embrace and enforce the new reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0250 </DOCNO>
