</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOON-MILESTONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLOONISTS COMPLETE CIRCUMNAVIGATION OF GLOBE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Achieving what promoters called the last great milestone of
aviation, Bertrand Piccard and Brian Jones joined legends like the
Wright Brothers and Charles Lindbergh with Saturday's completion of
the first manned round-the-world balloon flight.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:54 a.m. EST Saturday, the two balloonists crossed the line
of longitude from which they had departed on March 1 at Chateau
D'Oex, Switzerland, officially earning them the long-sought title
of the first balloon circumnavigation of the globe, as well as a $1
million prize.
</P>
<P>
   The pair hoped to land at about dawn Sunday in Egypt, unless
their dwindling fuel supply forces them to come down earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to his ground crew in Switzerland, Piccard acknowledged
that much of the achievement was due to forces far beyond the
pilots' control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really grateful for the invisible hand that guided us
through all obstacles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Piccard, a 41-year-old Swiss psychiatrist, is the latest in a
family of explorers and record-setters. It was Auguste Piccard, his
grandfather, who in 1931 became the first human to reach the
stratosphere, the first to see the earth's curvature firsthand, and
the inventor of the pressurized cabin, which opened up the frontier
of aviation to regular passenger travel.
</P>
<P>
   And it was his father, Jacques, who in 1960 set a record that
still stands Sunday for the deepest ocean dive, taking the
bathyscaphe Trieste nearly 7 miles deep in the Pacific Ocean's
Mariana Trench.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his illustrious forebears, Piccard grew up among
astronauts as his father worked for the US National Aeronautics and
Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my childhood, I have seen a lot of adventurers, and
this gave me the wish to explore something on this beautiful
earth,'' Piccard said two years ago, just before making the first
of his three attempts at the record.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the millions of dollars spent by each team for equipment
and the support crews needed for such voyages, success hinged on a
combination of luck, politics and fortitude. At least two previous
attempts that might have had a chance at succeeding were stymied by
failure to get overflight permission from China and Libya, forcing
them to divert into less favorable wind patterns. This flight, too,
was forced to detour to honor China's requirement to stay south of
26 degrees latitude, but was still able to stay in the high-speed
jetstream needed to propel it to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   There has been an intense but friendly informal competition for
the round-the-world title since 1993, using innovative balloon
designs. While one record after another was set for distance
traveled and for time aloft, all these earlier efforts ended up
being thwarted by bad weather, technical malfunctions, or political
obstacles. But in the process, the design of high-tech versions of
the venerable Rozier balloon has progressed enormously, bringing
aviation's oldest design straight into the space age.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite navigation systems monitor the balloons' positions,
satellite communications keep them in touch with their control
centers, and satellite weather monitoring provides the guidance
essential to success _ and survival. Even the most high-tech
balloon is still at the mercy of the winds, its only means of
control being to rise or fall in order to catch the winds that seem
to be going in the most promising direction.
</P>
<P>
   It was the invention of the modern Rozier balloon that made the
feat possible, by using modern lightweight plastics for the balloon
itself and by combining the advantages of the two principal types
of balloons: helium and hot air.
</P>
<P>
   Helium's advantage is that it requires no fuel to maintain its
lifting power; its drawback is that as it expands from the sun's
heat, it threatens to tear a balloon apart and must be vented,
depleting its supply. Hot air can provide lifting power whenever it
is needed, but only by carrying huge fuel supplies to heat the air;
when the fuel runs out, the balloon comes down. But a Rozier
combines both, taking advantage of helium's lift during daylight,
and supplementing it at night with hot air.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no obvious practical benefit from this
spectacular feat, the technological advances in balloon design
engendered by the competition may well end up benefiting scientific
research. Scientists already use unpiloted high-altitude balloons
extensively to conduct some kinds of environmental monitoring and
astronomical studies that require a perch high above most of the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow balloonist Richard Branson, whose latest attempt to
circle the world ended with a landing off Hawaii last Christmas
because of bad weather ahead, immediately sent his congratulatious
to the rival team Saturday, calling it a ``magnificent
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   For the adventurers themselves, the achievement still hadn't
quite sunk in. ``We are having great difficulty realizing our
dreams have come true,'' Piccard said. ``We are with the angels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8089 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OVITZ-LBPT     03-20 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OVITZ-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVITZ KNOWS DECISION IS OUT OF HIS HANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Ovitz faithfully believes the best possible location for
a Los Angeles NFL expansion franchise is the 157-acre site in
Carson that he has been touting to the league for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   But what he or anyone else involved in the expansion issue
believes won't matter in the end. He says the NFL will decide where
the team plays and who owns it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are not anyone's to decide but the league,'' said
Ovitz, the former head of Creative Artists Agency and ex-president
of The Disney Co., Friday afternoon. ``It only matters what they
think.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to bring football back to Los Angeles, and I'm
working like crazy for Carson....But you can't force them to choose
your site. They'll make the decision, and if they tell me to play
in a sandlot, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz has been pushing his site and ownership group, which
includes Ralphs Grocery Chairman Ron Burkle, Magic Johnson and Tom
Cruise, to the league for almost a year. His primary competition
has been a renovated Los Angeles Coliseum proposal led by Kings
owner Ed Roski and billionaire Eli Broad.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the league voted 29-2 to conditionally give Los
Angeles an expansion franchise. Working with the league's expansion
committee, L.A. has a six-month window to put together a site and
ownership group that meets the league's conditions. If it can't,
the league will put its 32nd team in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion committee, co-chaired by Carolina Panthers owner
Jerry Richardson and New England Patriots owner Bob Kraft, will
tour the two sites and meet with the two ownership groups in April,
then select one of the two sites.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is whether Ovitz will be asked by the league to join
the Coliseum ownership group. Roski has an exclusive contract with
the Coliseum, and he and Broad are part of a major redevelopment
effort in downtown Los Angeles that includes the new Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan called for unity in L.A.'s NFL
bid this week. Roski has said he would make room for Ovitz, whom he
approached more than two years ago when the New Coliseum proposal
began to take shape, but he has no interest in being part of the
Carson group.
</P>
<P>
   The Carson proposal calls for the building of a retail mall and
a stadium, called The Hacienda, on a site southeast of the 405 and
110 freeway junction. The land has been unused since 1964, the last
year it was used as a landfill.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Carson has environmental approval to build a mall on
the site, and is seeking supplemental approval for the stadium
project. Glimcher Realty, a company specializing in mall
construction and ownership, has an option to buy the land, and
Herbert Glimcher is a member of the Ovitz ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-to-9 month timeline for purchase and environmental
remediation of the site is built into a timeline that would have
the stadium ready for play in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Last month NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue, Richardson and other
league officials visited Carson to view the site and meet with
members of the Ovitz group. Tagliabue said the league had no
questions about the environmental aspect of the site, and that the
Carson plan met more of the league's criteria than the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Carson project includes an investment of $180 million by the
city, in the form of $30 million in cash reserved set aside several
years ago for mall construction and a $150 million bond issue. City
officials are studying whether it can raise additional funds
through a redevelopment agency.
</P>
<P>
   The New Coliseum proposal claims to have a public investment of
more than $300 million, but only $40 million of that is fresh
money. The balance is in the form of already completed
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz said the process hasn't been as stressful as some may
think. ``In some ways, it's been easy,'' he said, ``because the
decision is out of my hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-20-99 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-EAST-NYT &LR;      03-20 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE BEATS VIRGINIA TECH, 68-52  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Pat Summitt figures her dominating Tennessee
team is good for at least two offensive explosions a game. Saturday
afternoon at the Greensboro Coliseum, it took a single burst by the
top-seeded Lady Vols to subdue Virginia Tech, 68-52, in the East
Regional semifinals of the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, sparked by a 16-0 run in the first half, improved
Tennessee's record to 31-2.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the three-time defending national champion will
face third-seeded Duke, a 76-63 winner over Old Dominion in
Saturday's first game before 13,204 fans, an East Regional record.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee and Duke, which starts three seniors, met on a neutral
court in early December, with the Lady Vols winning, 74-60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Duke has a chance,'' Bonnie Henrickson, the coach of
fourth-seeded Virginia Tech, said. ``I think their experience will
help them, quite honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the familiar, haunting strains of the song ``Rocky
Top'' and by Tennessee's superior size, depth and reputation,
Virginia Tech (28-3) matched the Lady Vols stride for stride
through the game's first 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There were eight lead changes and three ties in that span as the
Hokies repeatedly shrugged off Tennessee's defensive pressure. But
the Vols managed to stay even thanks to 11 points from Chamique
Holdsclaw, their four-time all-American, who finished with a
game-high 27 points. Then, after an inside basket by Tere Williams
put the Hokies ahead by 18-17 with 9 minutes 45 seconds left in the
half, Tennessee exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by their defense, the Vols scored 16 unanswered points,
building their lead to 33-18 on a layup by guard Semeka Randall
with 3:01 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Randall, a sophomore all-American, played despite two torn
ligaments in her left ankle, which she injured in Tennessee's
first-round game against Appalachian State. A starter all year,
Randall came off the bench Saturday to spark Tennessee's run.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as she comes in she gets a steal, a score,'' Holdsclaw
said. ``She's just instant emotions and intensity, and we need that
from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech committed 7 of its 26 turnovers in the decisive
run. Five came on consecutive possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most people don't understand is how much ground they can
cover and how fast they can cover it,'' Henrickson said of
Tennessee. ``They turn your turnover into a lay-up drill.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DUKE 76, OLD DOMINION 63 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the opening game, Duke (27-6) took the lead at the 16:40 mark
of the first half, and despite 24 turnovers kept the more physical
Lady Monarchs at bay. Second-seeded Old Dominion, from the Colonial
Athletic Association, was impatient against Duke's zone defense.
Weak shooters from the perimeter all year, the Monarchs hit only 1
of 11 3-pointers in the first half and 1 of 14 (7.1 percent) on
3-pointers for the game.
</P>
<P>
   That ineffectiveness helped the Blue Devils survive their
difficulties with Old Dominion's pressure defense, as well as foul
trouble that negated the impact of the all-American Michele Van
Gorp, Duke's 6-foot-6-inch senior center.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils weathered six ties and led, 35-31, at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Old Dominion (28-4) pulled within 38-36 with 18:36 remaining,
but the poised Blue Devils responded with an 11-2 run, capped by a
layup off a steal by Peppi Browne. That pushed Duke's advantage to
49-38 with 12:42 left, and Old Dominion never drew closer than 5
points thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, an at-large entrant from the Atlantic Coast Conference,
was led by Nicole Erickson with 24 points and 7 rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
