<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8098 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-BUSH-PRESIDENCY-C     03-20 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-BUSH-PRESIDENCY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's run for presidency met with bipartisan support
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr. and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With Republican Gov. George W. Bush moving
toward a likely race for the White House, political veterans might
expect Texas Democrats to be setting fires and roadblocks for him.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Texas, where the governor has gone to great lengths
to work with Democrats, and what there is of partisanship is
largely kept out of the legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats don't feel that we need to throw stumbling blocks in
his way,'' said Rep. Pete Gallego of Alpine, chairman of the House
Democratic Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems very focused,'' according to Rep. Patricia Gray,
D-Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be cooperative in all efforts,'' said Sen. Gonzalo
Barrientos, D-Austin, chairman of the Senate Democratic Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Texas politics is a pure lovefest. But unlike in
Congress and other state legislatures, political fights in Texas
most often erupt over spending priorities and policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a Bush-backed plan to cut taxes for owners of small
oil and gas wells passed the Legislature this month. But not before
Democrats felt certain that a children's health-care program will
cover more children than some Republicans want.
</P>
<P>
   To the amazement of non-Texans, and the likely chagrin of
Democratic presidential hopefuls, the Texas Legislature is a world
largely dominated by political realists.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Texas Legislature, there is a strong need to get
along,'' said former Democratic Land Commissioner Garry Mauro, who
challenged Bush for the governor's office last year. ``No
Democratic senator or House member is going to strongly criticize
the governor at this point because there is still the promise that
he'll sign the bills that they can get through the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   The last governor who made a serious bid for the White House
didn't catch a similar break. It's as much a testament to Bush's
bipartisan efforts as to the nonpartisan nature of Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   When then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton began running for president
in 1992, he fielded loads of criticism from both the opposition and
his own party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is the lesser of evils, we will work our butts off for
him, but we have had our differences,'' Bill Becker, then the
president of the heavily Democratic Arkansas AFL-CIO, said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Also unlike Bush, Clinton fielded pointed and public criticism
from former state government associates.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Scott Trotter was among those more than willing to speak
harshly against the governor. Trotter served as an assistant when
Clinton was Arkansas attorney general in 1977-1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became less and less of a people's champion'' after
becoming governor, Trotter said at the time, ``and more and more of
an institutional politician trying to gain business support for
certain initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush exploratory committee Mindy Tucker said Texans of both
leading parties respect that the governor has stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has been a uniter and not a divider,'' Tucker
said. ``He has worked with people of both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Political outsiders, however, expected problems for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that the Clinton-Gore team may well be on the
phone to key Texas Democratic legislators attempting to set various
and sundry bear traps during the session for him,'' University of
Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato said in January. At the
time, he was shocked to learn that Democrats here say nice things
about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know there was such a Legislature in the country,''
Sabato said. ``I never heard there was such a nonpartisan
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrientos said Democrats are focused on issues, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a job to do here right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas isn't Arkansas or Congress, added Mauro, who's helping to
raise money for Vice President Al Gore's presidential campaign.
Mauro said that in 16 years in office, eight under a Republican, he
never spoke badly about the sitting governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody understands elected officials have to do what makes
the most sense for their constituencies and their political careers
and their political goals,'' Mauro said. ``The idea that somebody
would fall on the sword and criticize George Bush to help Al Gore _
it just doesn't happen in Texas. Maybe it happens in other states,
but I've never seen it happen in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal to end social promotion is another example of
Democrats working with Republicans to achieve their goals. The bill
has cleared the Senate, but didn't get needed Democratic votes
until provisions they wanted were added to it.
</P>
<P>
   Former Clinton adviser Paul Begala said he, too, isn't surprised
that Texas Democrats aren't loudly bad-mouthing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as a fire-breathing partisan, I believe your first
obligation is to help Texas,'' said Begala, a Texan and former
Texas legislative aide. ``I think the Democrats are right to do
their best to lead their governor toward sensible and centrist
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala, a Gore supporter, said Arkansas Republicans' efforts to
derail Clinton in 1992 went nowhere. Purely partisan shots don't
work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a good thing for the system if partisan opponents
began with the premise that the other party is the opposition, not
the enemy,'' Begala said. ``Bush is a decent guy. What's wrong with
saying that? I think he is wrong on issues and doesn't have many
big ideas, and I'd rather him not be my president, but he is not a
bad human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chairman Molly Beth Malcolm added that
any Bush success comes because of help from Democrats. The Texas
Senate is narrowly controlled by Republicans 16-15. Democrats hold
the House with 78 of the 150 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for people to remember that the only
reason he has been successful is because of the Democrats that have
been willing to work on issues important to Texans rather than
making a partisan fight,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though fellow Democrats say the governor appears focused on
the Legislature, Malcolm isn't convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only 24 hours in a day, and with all those foreign
dignitaries and delegations coming to the governor's mansion, how
in the world can the man be focusing on the Legislature?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   An ever so slight bad word about Bush's availability to
lawmakers: ``Instead of seeing him in 24 hours, it takes 48 or
72,'' Rep. Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly added that once in with Bush _ something that's
happened more than once this year for the chairwoman of the House
Public Health Committee _ the governor appeared aware and
knowledgeable about the issues at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be less than human if he wasn't a little distracted,''
Gray said. But ``he seems very focused.''
</P>
<P>
   The get-along attitude could play into Bush's presidential bid _
if he makes it.
</P>
<P>
   During his State of the State address, Bush noted that Texas
lawmakers have a chance to show Congress and other states how to
operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sometimes disagree, but we do so agreeably,'' he said. ``We
know we serve Texans best when we work together in a spirit of
cooperation and respect, when we seek common ground based on Texas
values.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest tests are yet to come. Bush's centerpiece proposal
to lower property taxes and allow more money for teachers got a
late start last week after delays because of Democratic opposition.
Republicans acknowledge that they will have to work with Democrats
to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said political reality means more than getting bills
signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very concerned that we don't do anything
intentionally embarrassing,'' she said. ``It would be good for
Democrats and Republicans for there to be a Texas president.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizondo and Herman write for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
