<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8103 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     03-20 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BAD NEWS FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Pitcher Ken Hill, who is coming off elbow
surgery, wandered over to see what all the commotion was about.
</P>
<P>
   Several reporters surrounded someone, but who? Was it Mo Vaughn?
Tim Salmon? Chuck Finley?
</P>
<P>
   No, team orthopedist Dr. Lewis Yocum was holding court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bad sign, when the doctor is getting most of the
attention in the clubhouse,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the injury situation hasn't been (begin ital)that(end
ital) bad for the Angels this spring, other than the broken bone in
shortstop Gary DiSarcina's left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday it was announced that catcher Matt Walbeck,
expected to get most of the starts behind the plate, will miss the
next three to four weeks with a broken bone in his right hand. And
pitcher Jason Dickson will be out indefinitely with a torn labrum
in his right (pitching) shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson will try to treat the shoulder with therapy during the
next two weeks. But if there is no significant improvement, he'll
have to have surgery, which would sideline him at least three or
four months and possibly for the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come in in the morning and find out one guy's out for a
month and another guy's out for three months, you just want to stop
playing,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``Let 'em hit and
wait until April.''
</P>
<P>
   There were more injury problems Saturday, though not as serious.
Center fielder Jim Edmonds missed his second game in a row and will
probably miss the next two with a tight groin. Outfielder Reggie
Williams pulled a hamstring and will be out for the next couple of
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not getting used to it,'' Collins said when asked
about the yearly struggle with injuries in camp. ``You never get
used to losing key players. I'm getting pretty sick of it, I know
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yocum said Dickson had a sore shoulder, typical for spring
training, but was just starting to feel good until earlier this
week when he felt a pinching sensation. He had an MRI Friday which
revealed the tear.
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck was injured Wednesday when checking his swing in a game
at minor league camp. But he didn't have X-rays until Friday; they
revealed a non-displaced fracture of the fifth metacarpal on the
right hand (between the thumb and index finger). He was fitted with
a splint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it burn after I checked my swing, but I didn't know if
it was an old injury because I've had two broken bones in the same
hand,'' he said. ``I didn't think it was anything because I've had
to play with pain in the hand before. ... It's kind of a drag. I
was shocked when they told me it was broken. It's so close to the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels split two games with the Giants Saturday afternoon,
winning 7-3 in Scottsdale and losing 6-5 in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus continued his hot streak with two hits and two RBI in
the Angels' win. Starter Omar Olivares further solidified his hold
on the No.5 spot with five good innings _ one run, five hits, four
strikeouts, no walks.
</P>
<P>
   In the Angels' loss, the Giants scored three runs in the ninth
off losing pitcher Mike Fyhrie. Orlando Palmeiro, vying for one of
the final spots on the roster, had three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Greene made his second appearance of the spring at catcher,
going five innings in the game in Tempe. Nobody tried to steal on
Greene, so he didn't get a chance to test his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test is trying to throw somebody out at game speed,'' said
Greene, who will catch five innings again Tuesday. ``But I don't
anticipate any problems. I don't care if I throw the guy out, as
long as it doesn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Justin Baughman will likely have a second surgery
on his broken left leg next week. Baughman suffered multiple
fractures in a winter league game in Mexico on Nov. 7. The healing
process has gone slower than expected and a second surgery has been
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman has seen a number of doctors who have advised him of
the different procedures he could undergo, which could help him
return sooner, possibly before the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to expedite things just because he's a
baseball player,'' Yocum said. ``But we feel we've given it an
adequate amount of time (to heal). It's not unreasonable to
consider surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Pep Harris, another Mexican League victim (torn ligament in
right elbow), is in town for treatment. He will miss the entire
season, but is upbeat. ``The way it feels now I feel like I'll come
back better than before, he said. ... DiSarcina will have his left
forearm re-examined and X-rayed Wednesday. At that point it will be
decided if the bone has healed enough for him to shed the cast and
begin hitting and fielding. ... Jack McDowell threw Saturday for
the first time since shoulder surgery on Feb. 3. ... The Angels
travel to Phoenix today to play the A's at 12:05. Chuck Finley is
scheduled to go three innings against the A's Kevin Jarvis.
</P>
</TEXT>
