<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA FULL OF REAL-LIFE DRAMAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grading on a curve that's nearly as severe as the arc on Allen
Iverson's crossover dribble, we will render our mid-term verdict as
NBA-minus.
</P>
<P>
   Without training camp, it's just camp. But the playoffs can be
used for extra credit. With any luck, we'll all qualify for a Phi
Beta Salary Kappa key.
</P>
<P>
   However, the league's abbreviated season is not without a few
repelling stories. Instead of reflecting upon those, we present the
following real-basketball-life inspired dramas that are in the
planning stages at the NBA Entertainment Network in Secaucus, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Iverson and 76ers coach Larry ``Get Ouf Of Town'' Brown
are as chummy these days as two sportswriters in a buffet line, but
- given Larry's history - something is bound to go haywire. Follow
the trail of laughter and the tears in a doomed relationship on
``Murphy's Law Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   According to his critics, Dennis Rodman is to the Lakers' title
hopes as Y2K is to your bank account come New Year's Day. See how
Dennis conquers his personal demons by partying (because it's 1999)
in the raw and uncut ``Tattoo On The Town.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder if Michael Jordan curses other drivers on the
freeway? Does he prefer Leno or Letterman? For the answers to these
and three or four other vital inquiries, we can turn to his
sideline buddy Rashad from NBC, star of the tell-all special
``Ahmad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he now plays for the Rockets, Scottie Pippen remains
full of Bull. After being beamed aboard by Houston, Pip discovers
that Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley don't mind hogging the
ball. To see if Pippen gets a ride on the clue bus, don't miss 30
minutes of hilarious locker room banter in ``Just Shoot ... Me?''
</P>
<P>
   Our next comedy set in Minnesota features decimal-point guard
Stephon Marbury and agent David Falk concocting a caper that will
make Stephon filthy rich and return him to the Big Apple. You'll be
up to your saddlebags in laughter when Marbury only gets it as far
as New Jersey in ``Wells Fargo.'' A surefire hit? You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of New Jersey ... this is the city ... East Rutherford.
My names is Calipari ... I carry a resume. Look for me in the
upcoming NBA mystery ``Drag Nets.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you think you know about loss? You don't know anything about
loss. But you can learn. All you have to do is sit in front of a
television while NBA airs its brutal documentary ``Tales From The
Clips.''
</P>
<P>
   The price is not Wright
</P>
<P>
   It is a common perception that the Clippers are a bunch of cheap
nitwits who refuse to break out the serious scoots in order to
re-sign players.
</P>
<P>
   Not true.
</P>
<P>
   Before last weekend's contract-extension deadline for the NBA
Draft class of 1996, they made an offer to center Lorenzen Wright
that is believed to be about half of his agent's original goal of
$60 million over six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did make an offer that was substantial,'' Robert Fayne,
the agent, said, ``but we didn't feel the offer was consistent with
Lorenzen's market value.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzen is averaging about six points and eight rebounds per
game. Five big ones per season for that? Ten? You decide.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers will not confirm the contract numbers, choosing to
- for now at least - keep that issue between themselves and the
agent.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side has ruled out the possibility of coming to terms
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   More Net work
</P>
<P>
   Before Calipari was tossed overboard in Jersey, the Nets were
subjected to rigorous confidence-building gymnastics. One desperate
measure included a visit from motivational evangelist Anthony
Robbins. Robbins, it has been reported, employed the slump-killing
technique of encouraging Nets players to hit the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   Following his lead, they broke boards with their bare hands.
</P>
<P>
   In our opinion, the Nets would draw more inspiration if somebody
contracted a visit from Baskin-Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Can't get enough of Calipari? Too bad. The latest gift from the
grapevine has the former UMass coach in the catbird seat at
Michigan. But Michigan's catbird seat is occupied, right? That's
the interesting part. ... Wally ``World Tour'' Szczerbiak, Miami of
Ohio's contribution to the ``Next Larry Bird'' derby, also has been
favorably compared to Phoenix forward Tom Gugliotta. However, two
NBA scouts have told us - after violent eye rolling when Bird is
mentioned - that Szczerbiak can best be described as Kiki
Vandeweghe with muscles. Not bad company. Vandeweghe averaged more
than 20 points per game for seven consecutive seasons. ... Karl
Malone probably is thrilled that Elden Campbell was traded out of
the Western Conference by the Lakers. In Friday's Utah loss in
Charlotte, Malone missed 16 of 21 shots while attempting to fire
over the taller and bouncier Campbell. ... According to rumor,
Jerry Krause, vice president of basketball operations for the
Chicago Bulls, has cancelled his voice-mail service. Now, if you
dial Jerry's number, the system just hangs up after six rings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
