<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-SMOKING-PROGRAM-C     03-20 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SMOKING-PROGRAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida attack on anti-smoking campaign has precedents in Calif.
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Klas
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ A state health department begins an anti-tobacco
campaign with confrontational ads that blast the industry for lying
to smokers. Surveys show the program is reducing smoking. The
program director is fired.
</P>
<P>
   That scenario describes Florida last week, except it also
happened in California _ seven years ago. The addendum to the West
Coast story: The Republican governor forced the program to change
direction. The ads were toned down or dropped. The new focus was on
education. Smoking rates rose.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the anti-smoking crusade say the Florida
Legislature's attack on the year-old, anti-smoking program is
similar to the attacks sustained by tobacco control programs in
other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this stuff is nothing new,'' said Stan Glantz, a
professor of medicine at the University of California at San
Francisco, whose aggressive criticism of the industry has made him
an enemy of tobacco companies. ``With most state programs, the
better they work, the more they get to keep going. With tobacco,
the better they work, the less they get.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida lawmakers built their budgets this year with with the
bounty of the state's $13 billion settlement against the tobacco
industry _ $920 million. It was enough to pay for at least $58
million in legislators' pet projects, expand health insurance for
needy children, eliminate the waiting list for at home care for the
elderly and pay for dozens of other health programs.
</P>
<P>
   But it may not be enough to pay for the program aimed at
stopping kids from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush initially indicated he supported the tobacco
control program and asked legislators to spend $61.5 million to
continue it. But House leaders, led by House Speaker John Thrasher
who personally opposes the program, eliminated it. The Senate
supported it for $50 million, a number the agency said it could
live with.
</P>
<P>
   The idea didn't sit well with students involved in the local
youth groups financed by the program. They had been integral in the
development of the ads and were committed to it. A day after they
rallied at the state Capitol, raucously protesting the budget cuts,
the program director, Peter Mitchell, was fired.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, the agency released the results of the youth
tobacco survey, conducted by the Florida Department of Health in
collaboration with the Centers for Disease Control: Youth smoking
dropped nearly 3 percent in one year.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers astounded researchers, marketers, epidemiologists
and anti-tobacco advocates accustomed to seeing youth smoking rise
each year in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Glantz, who teaches statistics, said, ``The methods are all very
standard and off the shelf and using questions from the CDC.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the survey showed ``the most amazing reduction in youth
smoking I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that Florida has perhaps the most effective
anti-tobacco program in the world,'' beamed Ed Trapido, a professor
of epidemiology and public health at the University of Miami, who
was hired to evaluate the program.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the results also showed that the ad campaign was
working. ``In a small sample where youth were reinterviewed, almost
50 percent who had thought about smoking but hadn't, said the
reason was because of the anti-tobacco TV ads,'' Trapido said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Novelli, director of the Campaign for Tobacco Free Kids and
a consultant to the program, said the survey results have
positioned Florida as the model for the nation as other states
decide how to spend their tobacco settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand how difficult it is to change
behavior,'' Novelli said. ``Tobacco is addictive. This is like an
expansion team coming onto the field and scoring a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Florida Secretary of the Department of Health, Bob
Brooks, downplayed the results of the survey. He said he supports
the program but wants it to take a different approach _ focus more
on college students and education.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason all of this is familiar, said Glantz, who has
written a book on the California experience. It is a pattern that
has followed anti-tobacco efforts from Massachusetts and New York
to Arizona and California. In each of those states, the director of
a successful program has been fired, survey results have been
challenged and, in California, aggressive ads were taken off the
air until the American Heart Association sued to get them back on.
</P>
<P>
   Novelli believes the resistance is a culmination of ``years of
political contributions'' from cigarette manufacturers that have
``a long, chronic kind of effect on the legislative process'' and
lawmakers who don't want government involved in telling kids not to
smoke. ``They see it as big brother and nannyism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Thrasher said Friday he believes smoking is an issue of
personal responsibility, not one in which the state should be
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've raised three children and none of them smoked and they
don't smoke because they had parents who encouraged them not to
smoke and they took individual responsibility on those things,'' he
said. He added that he would prefer to spend the advertising
dollars on cancer research and education programs to encourage
personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry has clearly disliked Florida's ads. When it
negotiated the national settlement last year, it insisted a clause
be included banning the use of tobacco money to pay for ads
attacking tobacco companies, like the Florida ads did.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco litigation also exposed the techniques the industry
may use to counter Florida's efforts. Documents released in the
tobacco lawsuit brought against the industry by the state of
Minnesota, revealed that three days after California aired its
first anti-industry ads in 1990, the industry's lobbying arm
composed a memo about how to undercut the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   According to the memo produced by the Tobacco Institute, the
industry would use three primary strategies to kill the ads:
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage legislative leaders to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use ``third-party allies'' to convince the department head to
``pull or modify the current advertisements.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage the governor to intervene against the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also described how it would attempt to get the minority
community upset about the ``denigrating tones'' of the ads, get
Hispanics and black professionals to ask for money to be used
instead on health services in their communities and get the
alcoholic beverage industry concerned that the ads are headed on a
``slippery advertising slope.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of Florida's program hope they won't have to counter
that kind of attack. ``We had a two-year commitment to fund a pilot
program,'' said Ralph DeVitto of the Florida chapter of the
American Cancer Society. ``We're asking that they keep that promise
and we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
