<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-EAST-ADVANCE-COX     03-20 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Regional finals are Chaney's bane
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Fair or not, one of the primary
measuring sticks used to judge coaching greatness in college
basketball is the ability to take teams to the Final Four. That's
why John Chaney will be the emotional favorite today when Temple
takes on No. 1 Duke for the NCAA East Regional championship.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney, 67, has won 605 games in 27 years as a college coach. In
17 seasons at Temple, he has taken the Owls to 15 NCAA Tournaments,
including the current string of 10 straight. He has won six
Atlantic-10 regular season championships. He won a Division II
national championship at Cheyney State in 1978. He is the
sixth-winningest active coach in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his success, the Jacksonville, Fla., native has not
reached a Final Four. Today marks Chaney's fourth regional
championship game, and all of the three previous losses were filled
with heartache.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Temple lost to Duke on this very floor (63-53) when
All-American Mark Macon was shut down by Billy King, the Blue
Devils' defensive specialist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the Owls came back to East Rutherford and were in
position to win when North Carolina's King Rice banked home a
3-pointer to lead the Tar Heels to a 75-72 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think about that shot,'' Chaney said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 Temple led Michigan's Fab Five by 10 points in the
second half of the West Regional championship. But the Owls let the
Wolverines off the ropes and lost 77-72.
</P>
<P>
   So today, Temple's players want this one not for themselves, but
for the raspy-voiced grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give Coach the first Final Four of his life, that would be
a dream,'' guard Pepe Sanchez said. ``It would absolutely be the
best feeling in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski, who will be going for his eighth
Final Four appearance today, said it would be a mistake to judge
Chaney's career simply on whether he eventually reaches the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nature of sport that there has to be this kind of
magical moment that defines a career,'' Krzyzewski said. ``But look
at what John has done. He should be in the Hall of Fame no matter
if he ever gets to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   If Chaney never reaches the Final Four, he is content that his
consistent success, which includes 21 seasons with 20 or more wins,
will provide a suitable legacy. But would he like to go to his
first Final Four? You better believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great feeling it would be,'' Chaney said. ``It would be
like having all the peanut butter you could eat. It would be like
getting that bicycle I never had..''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski understands. He still remembers the excitement of
beating Navy in the East Regional final here in 1986 for his first
Final Four trip. He also remembers the pain of his first loss in a
regional championship game, which came to Kentucky last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven times we've gone, and I've felt the same way every
time,'' Krzyzewski said. ``And last year when we didn't go there
was an empty feeling because we weren't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
