u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HUMMER-COLUMN21-C     03-20 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUMMER-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cats' Padgett finally gets it right
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ As he measures Michigan State and today's Midwest
Regional final, which some predict will be a steel-cage,
best-two-out-of-three-falls affair, Kentucky's Scott Padgett offers
a distinctly different scouting report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the Spartans) were a wrestler, they'd be Ric Flair. They
wear you down and wear you down and then put the finishing move on
you,'' said the Wildcats senior foward. That for the benefit of
those who are more WCW than NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   One may question Padgett's taste in television. And to see him
try on a menacing glare after burying a 3-point shot against Miami
University Friday _ only to look severely constipated _ you can
doubt his ability to truly menace. ``I do some goofy things
sometimes,'' he said, explaining the face that was more comical
than intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   But for every goofball, there is hope. In Padgett you have a
player whose first instinct upon entering the sacred realm of
Kentucky basketball was to see how many breweries he could drain.
And, yet, here he is today, the Wildcats' designated driver to
another Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor, he is expressing himself with a game versatile
enough to lead Kentucky in both 3-point scoring and rebounding.
This time of year, Kentucky always seems to identify one shooter it
can count on. Now, among a core of three seniors, Padgett seems the
one chosen to be the next Jeff Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   He has led Kentucky in scoring four of its last five games,
going for 20 in the championship game of the SEC Tournament and a
season-high 29 in an overtime victory against Kansas in the second
round of the NCAAs. His two second-half 3-pointers against Miami
seemed to fuel the Wildcats' finish.
</P>
<P>
   A naturally easygoing demeanor does turn fiery on demand.
``Scott knows when it's time to joke around and when it's time for
business,'' said point guard Wayne Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Padgett) is the best player in the SEC in terms of playing
the game of basketball, doing what it takes,'' South Carolina coach
Eddie Fogler announced earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   If Michigan State comes out today playing its usual burly Big 10
kind of game, Padgett claims he will be unconcerned. ``We've played
a lot of physical teams this year and been successful. We can
adapt,'' he said. Maybe all those hours of watching pro 'rasslin on
TV finally will come to some good.
</P>
<P>
   The maturing of Scott Padgett has been most impressive in
another venue. Upon entering Kentucky, his weight training included
regular 12-ounce curls. ``I would have lost count (of his beer
consumption) real early. How do you think I got from 205 to 230 my
freshman year?'' he said. He flunked out his sophomore year, then
had to gradually work his way back into Rick Pitino's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more proud of what I've done in the classroom,'' said
Padgett, who made himself over into an honor student. ``I always
knew I could do it on the court. The classroom was something else.
When I first got to college, I thought, `Man, this is really hard.'
Of course, you can't go to class once a week and expect to do
well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm trying to get another year (of college),'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   A guy shouldn't have to leave upon finally getting it right.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
