<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIAMIOHIO21-COX     03-20 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMIOHIO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cinderella Miami looks ahead
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It was fitting that Miami's improbable NCAA
tournament run died under the Gateway Arch.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Szczerbiak was good enough to allow his team to reach the
threshold of the Final Four, but the team couldn't be carried
through by his one-man show.
</P>
<P>
   The RedHawks played three games in the tournament, and
Szczerbiak scored 90 points while hitting just over 53 percent of
his shots.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates scored 85 points and hit just under 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's 58-43 loss to Kentucky in the Midwest Regional
semifinals, Szczerbiak scored 23 points, making eight field goals.
The rest of the RedHawks had 20 points, including six field goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest game of the season, Miami sank to new lows in
field goals (14), shooting percentage (.286) and rebounds (18), and
tied the previous low for points (43).
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to do what I could to keep us in the game,''
Szczerbiak said, ``but it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-8 forward finished his senior year with 775 points,
breaking the school record of 772 set by Ron Harper in 1984-85.
Szczerbiak's career total of 1,847 is second to Harper's 2,377.
</P>
<P>
   In four years, Szczerbiak developed from a scrawny kid no one
wanted to an NBA lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think about what would have happened if I had
played for another school,'' Szczerbiak said. ``Miami has been
great to me and I'll always be grateful for what the coaches (he
was recruited by Herb Sendek, Charlie Coles' predecessor, and
played for him as a freshman) helped me develop as a player and as
a person. It's been a fun time and I'll leave with my head held
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles was obviously disappointed with his team's one-dimensional
performance against Kentucky. ``I had hoped we would play better,
but I hope this doesn't take away from what we accomplished this
season. We had a good run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was treated royally by the media during the tournament,
and Coles took part of his postgame press conference to express his
appreciation. ``We thank everyone for the attention we got. I hope
we come through this way again some day.''
</P>
<P>
   If that day comes next year, Coles will have orchestrated a
miracle that surpasses anything he accomplished this season.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak, shooting guard Damon Frierson and center John Estick
will graduate. There will be some experienced players returning,
but Coles will have no consistent scoring threats and no quality
size. Mike Ensminger, Rich Allendorf and Jay Locklier, all
sophomores who are 6-8 or taller, have a total of 162 career
points.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Coles scores a recruiting coup, his best big man may be
untested Brian Edwards, a 6-8 sophomore from Detroit who has yet to
play a game. Edwards did not meet academic requirements as a
freshman and was redshirted this year.
</P>
<P>
   And while he is out looking for new talent, Coles is sure he
won't run into UK coach Tubby Smith. When it comes to recruiting,
Kentucky and Miami are in different worlds.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had tried to sign any of the current Wildcats,
Coles rolled his eyes and shook his head. ``If I'm in the same gym
as Tubby on a recruiting trip, I'm in the wrong gym.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
