<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kentucky looks to Padgett
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ When the game is on the line for the Kentucky
Wildcats, they line up behind Scott Padgett.
</P>
<P>
   UK (28-8), the defending NCAA tournament champion, faces
Michigan State (32-4) today in the Midwest Regional finals.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Wildcats need someone to take charge, Padgett's name
heads the volunteer list.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's 92-88 overtime win over Kansas in New Orleans,
Padgett scored 22 of his career-high 29 points after intermission.
He hit a 3-pointer with 20 seconds left to send the game into OT,
then had seven of the 'Cats 13 points in the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's Regional semifinal against Miami, Padgett scored 14
of his 17 points in the second half, including eight in a 10-0 run
that put UK out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very competitive person,'' the 6-foot-9 senior said
during Saturday's press gathering at the Trans World Dome. ``I'm
not taking anything away from anyone else on our team, but in
situations like that, you need a veteran to step up. If we need a
play, it's probably going to be me (trying to make it).''
</P>
<P>
   Padgett issued a semi-apology for his behavior during the
semifinals. He hit two treys during the pivotal 10-0 run and each
time pointed at the Miami cheering section.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mainly for their fans,'' he said sheepishly. ``They
were telling, telling me I was terrible. I just do goofy things on
the court from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   Padgett had been outscored, 15-3, by Miami's Wally Sczcerbiak in
the first half and that disparity got his juices flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was embarrassed,'' he said. ``I just got two
silly fouls trying to guard him and that kept me on the bench. I
was happy that I did something to contribute because I hadn't done
much to that point.'' Padgett is a three-year starter, but his UK
career started on a downer as he flunked out of school as a
freshman. He returned to excel in the classroom and on the court.
He was on the Southeastern Conference's all-academic team as a
senior and had a 4.0 grade-point average last semester.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Michigan State is the No. 1 seed here and has won 21
straight games, many analysts favor third-seeded Kentucky because
of the experience factor.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Cats have won two of the last three NCAA tournaments and
finished second in the one they didn't win. The Spartans have made
the 64-team field seven times in the 1990s, but haven't made it to
the Final Four since Magic Johnson led the 1978-79 team to the
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think all that stuff is going to have any bearing on
what happens during (today's) game,'' Padgett said. ``Our
experience may have helped us in our preparations because we've
learned how to deal with all the media attention and focus on
getting ready for the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that isn't going to mean anything once the game starts.
Then all that's going to matter is who plays the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
