<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia women walk over Clemson
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ When asked before the Sweet 16 got under way
whether his team could switch gears from its usual high-octane
offensive push into a deliberate, half-court tempo, Georgia coach
Andy Landers didn't hesitate to answer in the affirmative.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Lady Bulldogs patiently backed up his
confidence in the second half against Clemson and rolled to a 67-54
victory in the Mideast Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia (26-6) used a punishing zone defense to keep Clemson
(26-7) to a season-low 33 percent shooting, and held its two top
scorers to only two points combined in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth time in the last five seasons and the eighth time
overall, Georgia has reached the Elite 8. The No. 3 seed Lady Dogs
meet fourth-seeded Iowa State, a 64-58 upset winner over top seed
Connecticut, in Monday's Mideast championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling, but I hope we don't forget that there's
one more game to play for us to reach our goal of getting to the
Final Four,'' said senior guard Pam Irwin-Osbolt, who had 10 points
in a clutch starting role.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, which has been averaging 82.6 points, shot 46 percent
in the second half. Kelly Miller had 22 points to lead the way, but
the story of this game was how the Lady Dogs dictated from the
defensive end of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be critical,'' Landers said. ``But their field
goal percentage has been low all season. So we said, `What the
heck, let's pack it in.'''
</P>
<P>
   As in packing in a tight 1-2-2 zone Landers drew up specifically
to limit the Lady Tigers' options on offense. Clemson forward
Natasha Anderson had 12 points to lead her team, but scored just a
deuce in the second half. And hot-shooting guard Amy Geren, who had
10 by halftime, did not score after that.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing 28-26 at halftime, Georgia stayed close over the
first seven minutes. Clemson last took the lead at 44-43, but then
were outscored 12-2 over a 6:05 spurt. Irwin-Obolt's baseline
jumper put the Lady Dogs ahead to stay at 45-44, and they led by as
many as 11 before pulling away.
</P>
<P>
   ``His game plan took away what our strength is,'' Clemson coach
Jim Davis said. ``At the same time, there seemed to be a lid over
the baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
