<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Darlington is a tough egg to crack
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Perhaps there's no other speedway on the
NASCAR circuit with more history and lore than Darlington Raceway,
which is celebrating its 50th anniversary this season.
</P>
<P>
   David Pearson won here a record 10 times, but only three of
Richard Petty's 200 career victories came at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, there's not an oval of asphalt more
loathed or despised in Winston Cup racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro golfers have a choice,'' driver Kyle Petty said. ``If
there is a tournament coming up at a course where they just don't
usually play well or a course that doesn't really suit their games,
they skip it. We don't have that luxury here.''
</P>
<P>
   In NASCAR racing, where every standings point is critical,
Darlington's 1.366-mile, egg-shaped oval demands more of drivers
than any other raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Darlington, the oldest speedway on the circuit, already has
taken its toll. In Friday's qualifying, the fourth turn claimed the
No. 18 Pontiac of Bobby Labonte, which left him with a broken right
shoulder blade in the one-car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darlington is like that old creepy house down the street when
you were a kid,'' driver Ward Burton said. ``It always looked kind
of spooky, but all of those ghost stories couldn't have been true.
The hard part was separating the true ones from the ones somebody
made up. It's the same thing trying to beat those Darlington
ghosts.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, 10th in the points standings, beat one Saturday. He
overcame the threat of five other drivers and held his 28th-place
effort in qualifying, which gives him the final pit stall on the
front straightaway. Fifteen drivers, including Dale Earnhardt and
Petty, will pit on the backstretch, leaving them a disadvantage on
yellow-flag pit stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can win the race from the 28th pit,'' Burton said. ``I'd
say it's darned near impossible from the 29th. A tenth of a second
can be the difference in being able to stop and spend some time in
that victory lane I walk past every morning. I don't know who the
winner will be Sunday, but you can pretty much narrow it down to 28
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon will start
on the pole and is looking for his sixth win in the last eight
races here. Dale Jarrett, who will start 21st, is the only driver
other than Gordon to win on the track since Sterling Marlin won the
spring race in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is all about carrying speed for 50 or 60 laps on
old tires,'' Gordon said. ``It's old Darlington. The track is very
abrasive and the tires wear out very fast. The pace slows down
tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
