<HEADER>
A8114 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WESTLEDE-COX     03-20 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WESTLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UConn finds alternatives
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ With his team's psyche rendered fragile by lofty
expectations for the future and all its well-documented failures of
the past, coach Jim Calhoun employed a sports psychologist last
fall to get inside the craniums of the Connecticut Huskies. The
shrink told the team that, to end the longest streak of Final Four
futility in the history of the NCAA tournament, it might consider
embracing some multiple personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later that analysis paid off, UConn earning its
first Final Four berth here on Saturday by transforming itself into
the basketball equivalent of Sybil. On a day when they shot 35.1
percent, connected on zero three-pointers, watched point guard
Khalid El-Amin miss all 12 of his field goal attempts and put up
the fifth lowest point total of the season, the Huskies found
enough alternatives to defeat surprisingly tough Gonzaga, 67-62,
and capture the West regional.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended a stretch of 20 straight tournament
appearances without a trip to the Final Four and allowed Calhoun,
who bitterly refers to his media detractors as ``The Horde,'' to
claim the one entry missing from an otherwise sterling resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did the things you have to dig down deep to do,'' said
former Westside High School star Ricky Moore, whose exemplary
defense against Bulldogs guards Matt Santangelo and Quentin Hall
was a major element in the victory. ``Especially with Khalid out of
the game, we struggled on the offensive end. But great teams find a
way to win even when they aren't playing great ball, and that's
what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   So suffocating was Connecticut's perimeter defense that
Santangelo and Richie Frahm, the two snipers whose three-point
marksmanship helped catapault Gonzaga to its first Elite Eight
appearance, were a combined three for 20 from the field. Frahm
played with West regional most valuable player Richard Hamilton in
his face most of the day. When he did get an open look, he usually
rushed it.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo, the Bulldogs' spiritual leader, missed the front end
of a one-on-one that would have tied the game with 1:32 left. Frahm
and Santangelo prefer to use a series of well-designed picks to run
curl cuts and occasionally a fade cut to get open looks at the
hoop. But the Huskies emphasized some hedge techniques and a few
traps to disrupt Gonzaga's offensive flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It was) terribly frustrating,'' said Frahm, who scored just
seven points. ``When I came off he pick, it seemed like Hamilton
was always in my face. Those few times he wasn't there and I had an
open look, I was so surprised that I hurried it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides their defense, it was the Huskies' outstanding board
work that paved the way for their trip to St. Petersburg next
weekend. Connecticut owned a huge 47-33 edge but more significant
was its 21 offensive boards and 42 points in the paint. Although
not a physically imposing outfit, the Huskies made up for a lack of
bulk by being very quick jumpers and finishing off every drive
strong.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who had a game-high 21 points, was able to get to the
hoop anytime he really needed to and forward Kevin Freeman bullied
his way to 15 boards, including 10 at the offensive end. ``They
were piranhas on the boards,'' said Gonzaga coach Dan Monson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
