<HEADER>
A8116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WESTNOTES21-COX     03-20 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WESTNOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    West regional notebook
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ One of the advantages Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun
had stressed all season was the presence of two point guards,
Khalid El-Amin and Ricky Moore, in the lineup. On Saturday, the
unusual pairing proved critical for the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   After picking up two fouls in the game's first four minutes,
El-Amin sat out the rest of the first half and Moore took over at
the point spot. The former standout from Westside School School in
Augusta tallied nine points in the half, dished out three assists
and had no turnovers. But it was Moore's defense against Gonzaga
guard Matt Santangelo that merited the most praise from Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best man-to-man perimeter defender I've ever
coached,'' Calhoun said. ``When Khalid came here last year, Ricky
had to decide just what kind of player he had to be in our program.
He found the way he would be most valuable to the team. He is a
special kid, one who feels obligated to the program and the
opportunity it has given him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the game's final minutes, Calhoun switched Moore onto Gonzaga
point guard Quentin Hall, whose quickness was creating problems,
and he shut him down as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rough in the diamond
</P>
<P>
   With the slick El-Amin sitting out the final 16 minutes of the
first half, Gonzaga coach Dan Monson played some 2-3 and 1-3-1
zones to try to stymie the Huskies offense and also used the much
shorter Hall (5-foot-8) on UConn star forward Richard Hamilton
(6-foot-6) in a diamond-and-one alignment. The strategy worked for
a while, but it also contributed to the Huskies' dominance in the
paint and on the boards. Hamilton was able to snake into the lane
three times for short jumpers against Hall. ``And anytime you have
to use a 'junk' defense,'' Monson said, ``you're rebounding
suffers.''
</P>
<P>
   Going inside
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 43-41 with 13:5 remaining in the game, UConn bolted to
a 12-4 run and used their quickness off the floor to do so. Jake
Voskuhl scored on a dunk after taking a pass from El-Amin, who had
penetrated into the lane. Then El-Amin was fouled on a drive and
converted one of two free throws. Kevin Freeman went strong to the
hoop to score. El-Amin, fouled on a drive, hit two free throws.
Moore was fouled on a driving layup and converted the three-point
play. Freeman finished the run with a tip-in. ``What they do is
recover quickly and go right back up again,'' Gonzaga center Jeremy
Eaton said. ``It is similar to what they can do to you defensively.
You might think you have a guy beat off the dribble or coming off a
screen, then he's back in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Notable
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga was 15-0 this year when shooting better than 45 percent
on three-pointers. The Bulldogs hit just five of 21 treys, however,
on Sunday. In its previous three NCAA victories, Gonzaga shot 56
percent on three-pointers and just 39 percent on two-point tries. .
. . The all-region team was comprised of Hamilton, Freeman and
Moore from UConn and Hall and Casey Calvary of Gonzaga. . . .
Calhoun on Gonzaga: ``They may not have a national name, but
they've got a national game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
