<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kenseth beats Cup regulars in 200
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Matt Kenseth will start his second Winston
Cup race today, but the 27-year-old driver held off several NASCAR
stars in Saturday's Diamond Hill Plywood 200 at Darlington Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, who will be the relief driver for Bobby Labonte in
today's TranSouth 400, won his fourth Busch series race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped me practicing that Cup car (Saturday) morning,''
Kenseth said, ``and Bobby taught me a few things about the grooves
here. This is a tough place to run your second Cup race, but
they've got a really good car over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth got a break when a caution flag came out during the
110th lap, when several of the leaders were making a scheduled pit
stop. That left only four cars on the lead lap, including Kenseth,
and most of the former leaders were left one lap down.
</P>
<P>
   Elton Sawyer finished second, and Phil Parsons was third. Terry
Labonte was the highest-finishing Cup regular at fourth. Four of
the top 10 finishers were Cup drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
