<DOCNO> NYT19990320.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8121 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT &LR;      03-20 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO SITUATION WORSENS AS SERBS PRESS OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., this story is now the lead item on NYT Page 1;
EXCLUSIVE-TRIBUNAL-YUGO has dropped to the bottom of the page)  
 (HLW)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As hundreds of foreign monitors left Kosovo and
President Clinton met his national security advisers to discuss the
worsening situation there, Serbian forces took advantage of the
vacuum on Saturday to press a heavy offensive against the
separatist Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton met his advisers, a senior official said it
appeared that the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, was
preparing for a major offensive.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, Gen. Wesley C. Clark, the supreme commander of NATO,
described the situation in Kosovo in much starker terms. He said in
a telephone interview on Saturday that the offensive was well under
way and that ``all sources indicate that the situation has
dramatically deteriorated on the ground in Kosovo as the verifiers
have departed.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, thousands of panicked refugees fled their homes, many
for the second time this past week. Reporters who reached the town
of Srbica said Serbian forces dressed in snow-white camouflage and
black masks were seen driving through the streets, with tanks and
troops deployed all around the town, which is in the Drenica
region, the heart of the ethnic Albanians' revolt.
</P>
<P>
   A senior NATO diplomat said Milosevic appeared to be taking
advantage of the departure on Saturday of the international
monitors, sometimes referred to as verifiers, and intensifying an
offensive aimed at crushing the forces of the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, a day after warning that the Serbs had
crossed the threshold of acceptable behavior, Clinton met with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright; Defense Secretary William
Cohen; Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff; George Tenet, the director of central intelligence; and
Sandy Berger, the national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The senior administration official who briefed reporters said
that Clinton was ``deeply concerned'' about the situation. There
were ``confirmed reports of the outbreak of violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO, the senior diplomat described about 5,000 Yugoslav
troops in the field in Kosovo and many more units pouring into the
southern Serbian province, as the 1,300 monitors of the
Organization for Security and Co-Operation in Europe were leaving.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said it appeared that Milosevic was making good
on a statement made to a number of Western officials in the last
months: That it would take him from five to seven days to ``finish
off'' the Kosovo Liberation Army if he was allowed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference on Friday, Clinton said NATO allies were
prepared to act against the Serbs. But he declined to set out a
timetable or indicate when enough was enough from Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said on Saturday that air strikes could begin as
soon as Secretary-General Janvier Solana, who has been authorized
to give the go-ahead to Clark, had consulted with all 16 allies.
</P>
<P>
   But that process could take some days. Consultation would not
begin at least until after a meeting scheduled for Sunday of the 16
NATO ambassadors at NATO headquarters in Brussels, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO diplomat said that now that the international monitors
had left, the West had to bear the consequences of Milosevic's
stepped up military activity. ``Until now the question of air
strikes has only been theoretical,'' the diplomat said. ``It's like
being on the edge of the diving board and it's another thing to
pluck up the courage to go into the water.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a senior administration official involved in
Kosovo policy said that the administration was still discussing
sending another American emissary to Milosevic in Belgrade. It was
not decided who that emissary would be, the official said. Richard
Holbrooke, who has often been sent to the Balkans as a special
envoy, was sent 10 days ago to Belgrade and came away empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to Washington on Tuesday by the Russian prime
minister, Yevgany Primakov, remained a factor in deciding the
timetable for any air strikes, the policy maker said.
</P>
<P>
   Several NATO officials expressed frustration on Saturday at the
advantage Milosevic had commanded for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's troops had made a ``horseshoe'' encirclement of
Kosovo from the north to the south, one said. Serbian troops were
well into the Drenica region, the heartland of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO officials described the history of the threats made by
the alliance but not carried out against Milsoevic since last
summer when Serbian forces embarked on a major offensive against
the ethnic Albanian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The first major threat, they recounted, was last October, after
a massacre of civilians. Then, Holbrooke was sent to Belgrade and
NATO planes were poised ready to strike until, at the 11th hour,
Milosevic agreed to a cease-fire and to certain troop withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Milosevic's forces committed another massacre
against ethnic Albanian civilians at the village of Racak. Clark
and another top NATO military officer were sent to Belgrade to tell
Milosevic to desist but, according to accounts by Clark afterward,
Milosevic remained defiant.
</P>
<P>
   Then, NATO officials recounted, Albright mounted a diplomatic
campaign to get Solana the authorization to bomb targets in Kosovo
and Serbia if Milosevic did not stop his aggression and bring his
troops back to the levels agreed in October.
</P>
<P>
   But, simultaneously, peace talks were organized in France. All
through the talks, the rationale for bombing was that Milosevic had
to be brought to the peace table. But now that the talks have
collapsed, the rationale has been changed, one NATO diplomat said,
to hitting Milosevic's troops and thus restraining their ability to
attack the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
