<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8124 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-20 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S GAME NOT SECOND-CLASS ANYMORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The First Lady was considered a second-class
athlete. Hillary Clinton grew up playing half-court basketball, an
inane exercise of temperance. ``We weren't allowed to play
full-court like the boys,'' she recently told an esteemed gathering
of women athletes at the White House, ``because we were told our
hearts were too weak.''
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady Techster was considered a second-class coach.
When Sonja Hogg attended a coaching clinic after launching the
Louisiana Tech women's program in the early 1970s, she was the only
woman in a room of 300-something participants.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana coach Bob Knight, a guest speaker not known for his
broad-mindedness, singled her out to demonstrate a defensive drill,
clearly aiming to humiliate her. Instead, Hogg walked away from the
challenge validated, with a standing ovation from the roomful of
men ringing in her ears.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now the issue isn't the acceptance of female
coaches or the stamina of female basketball players, it's the
stature of their sport. Over the past few years the women's game
has grown like a muscle on steroids. From Ames to Westwood the
players' drawing power is becoming so pronounced, some will tell
you it's strong enough to lift the game to Herculean heights.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let all the empty seats at the Sports Arena, site of this
weekend's NCAA Tournament West Regional, give you the wrong
impression. Louisiana Tech, which played intrastate rival Louisiana
State in the first semifinal, has standing-room-only crowds in its
8,000-seat arena. UCLA, which played Colorado State in the second
game, drew 9,530 for a game against rival USC in January, which is
bigger than six of the eight Clippers crowds at the Sports Arena
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Iowa State attracted 24,000 to its first two
tournament games at home and Colorado State has raised its average
attendance over the past five years from relatives and friends to
more than 4,000. Then there's the Tennessee women's team, which
averaged 17,568 fans at its home games this season, the
fifth-highest number in the nation for any program, men's or
women's.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has got the sport's guardians to thinking. Later
this year they will debate whether or not to scrap every last
home-court game in the first and second rounds of the NCAA Division
I Tournament in favor of the neutral-sites format employed to such
grand effect by the men.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the move will tell you the timing never has been
better. How much more validation does women's basketball need than
one of its own (Tennessee's Chamique Holdsclaw) beating out Heisman
Trophy winner Ricky Williams for the prestigious Sullivan Award,
given each year to the country's top amateur athlete?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way women's basketball is being perceived around the
country shows we are ready,'' said Sue Gunter, Louisiana State's
17-year coach. ``To really give the credibility to the women's game
we need to go to the neutral sites. That's going to be a sign that
our game has truly arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters, who include former UCLA great Ann Meyers
Drysdale, wonder if women's basketball isn't like the proverbial
kid sister, so hell-bent on catching up to her older brother that
she forgets to forge her own identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't financially support teams playing at eight neutral
sites like the men do,'' Meyers Drysdale said. ``It is important to
keep building fan support by having the top teams playing in their
geographic regions.''
</P>
<P>
   Home teams won all 32 games in the first week and therein lies
the rub. Among the schools that some would argue gained an unfair
competitive advantage playing in familiar surroundings was UCLA,
the No.3 seed in the West. The Bruins beat Wisconsin-Green Bay and
Kentucky at Pauley Pavilion to reach the semifinals at the Sports
Arena 10 miles down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Saturday's games at host USC's site were televised to a
cable audience. That was the good news. The bad news was they were
shoehorned between sundown and the stroke of midnight, local time.
</P>
<P>
   What price exposure?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' Gunter conceded during a press conference
on the eve of Saturday's game. ``But if we want TV exposure, we
seem to be at their mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, one of Gunter's players, Katrina Hibbert, cleared
her throat and proceeded to remind everybody in the room why
women's basketball is worth loving. The women's sound fundamentals
notwithstanding, there's the matter of their unspoiled grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter,'' Hibbert said of the late starting
times. ``I'm just happy to be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   To have a similar appreciation of where women's basketball is
headed, a refresher course on its humble beginnings is instructive.
Take the Louisiana Tech team, for example, the most storied of the
four programs in the West Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Techsters are one of only two schools (Tennessee is the
other) to have appeared in the NCAA Tournament all 18 years of its
existence. Sixteen times they have advanced at least as far as the
Sweet 16. Ten times they have reached the Final Four and they have
won three national championships _ the first two under Hogg and the
third under her one-time assistant Leon Barmore, the only other
head coach the program has had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were averaging 5,000 fans when nobody else was drawing
300,'' Hogg, now the Baylor women's coach, said from Waco. ``I
think the uniqueness of it was the drawing point, at first. But you
can only sell the uniqueness of it for so long. You have to have a
good product to keep people coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogg's father had been a left-handed pitcher and road roommate
of Stan Musial on the St. Louis Cardinals. Perhaps that had
something to do with the quality of the pitch she delivered in 1973
to Louisiana Tech president Dr. F. Jay Taylor. Upon hearing her
ideas on starting a women's basketball team, he gave her the
go-ahead and a $5,000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Money was tighter than spandex in the early years. The Lady
Techsters rode to away games on a rickety bus they affectionately
called the Blue Goose. ``We'd have to push the thing half the time
to make it start,'' Hogg said.
</P>
<P>
   They would travel to neutral sites _ New Orleans was a favorite
_ and play three teams in one day to cut down on traveling costs.
Programs everywhere were pinching their pennies. So when teams came
to rural Ruston to play Louisiana Tech, Hogg thought nothing of
lending them a university bus to use during their stay. Sometimes
she'd even take their dirty uniforms home after a game and wash
them so they'd be fresh for the next stop on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, teams travel by plane and stay at four-star hotels and
have all the free sneakers they can wear out. Agents and a few
unsavory club coaches are creeping into the picture. The
camaraderie of the early years has been replaced by a cut-throat
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Hogg watches her baby grow up and, like any guardian, frets. ``I
don't want women's basketball to get to the point where we don't
have integrity,'' she said. ``Where it's winning at all costs.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
