u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONITORING-SPIES-BOS &LR;      03-20 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONITORING-SPIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SPYING THREATENS N-PLANT MONITORING WORLDWIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The monitoring system being installed worldwide to
ensure that nuclear power plants are not used illicitly to make
nuclear weapons materials was designed with the help of a former US
intelligence officer who allegedly rigged a similar system to spy
on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure is raising fears that countries may refuse to
accept the monitoring program for fear the information will be
funneled back to the US government. And it threatens to frustrate
the efforts of the International Atomic Energy Agency to broaden
its scrutiny of weapons development projects in North Korea and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The secret involvement of US intelligence agents in the UN
effort to track down hidden Iraqi nuclear, chemical and biological
weapons became a major embarrassment for the United Nations.
Disarmament specialists said the revelations could undermine one of
the pillars of US arms control policy: a decades-long campaign to
persuade countries to open their nuclear, biological and chemical
weapons facilities to international scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major setback,'' said Spurgeon Keeny, a former US
arms control negotiator who has pressed for decades for aggressive
spot checks of the world's deadliest arms stockpiles. ``Nobody who
is really cheating is going to be willing to permit intrusive,
on-site inspections. But this gives them a built-in excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The US official is a career Air Force intelligence specialist
who led a group of Americans that built the UN remote video
surveillance system to monitor Iraqi facilities capable of
developing chemical and biological weapons, according to US and UN
officials. A senior Pentagon official, voicing concern for the
official's safety, requested that his name not be published.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf Ekeus, the former chief of the UN Special Commission
(UNSCOM) in Iraq, described the official as a ``creative''
troubleshooter who rigged an effective communications system under
highly difficult and hostile conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But the team, which included two CIA operatives, secretly
installed microwave eavesdropping devices into the system in the
mid-1990s that picked up Iraqi communications between military
bases throughout the country, the Washington Post reported.
</P>
<P>
   The March 2 report was confirmed by a US source familiar with
the operation. A senior Pentagon official declined to confirm or
deny the report.
</P>
<P>
   An UNSCOM official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
described the Air Force officer as ``a loose cannon.'' Particularly
galling, the official said, was the public disclosure on an Air
Force intelligence web site of his role in analyzing raw data from
the UN monitoring system. UNSCOM demanded that the US government
remove the information, and it was taken off the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern was that it looked like this was a US operation,''
said another UNSCOM source.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe has learned that the official has since gone to Vienna
to create a low cost, remote monitoring system for the
International Atomic Energy Agency. There is no evidence that the
new system also would pick up microwave communications between
military bases.
</P>
<P>
   In an telephone interview from his office in Vienna, the
official denied that he had spied in Iraq. He said that he was
always under the scrutiny of his Iraqi handlers. He also said that
he is not spying at his new atomic agency post.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role is clean,'' he said. ``I don't do anything that is not
approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Pellaud, the Swiss deputy director general for safeguards
at the IAEA, said he believes the American.
</P>
<P>
   He said the American communications expert came to work for him
two years ago to help establish a remote monitoring system that
will enable the agency to monitor nuclear power facilities around
the globe from the organization's Vienna headquarters through video
cameras and radio sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Pellaud and other agency officials said they recently became
aware of the report that the official had spied in Iraq. But
Pellaud said the American remains a key member of the team.
</P>
<P>
   With his help, the agency has established remote monitoring
systems at nuclear power stations in Switzerland, South Africa and
Japan. And the agency is negotiating with Iran and North Korea,
both suspected by US intelligence of having sought to develop
nuclear weapons, to install similar monitoring systems in their
nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have intensified our efforts to expand the use of remote
monitoring in nuclear facilities around the world because of the
potential for cost-saving,'' said Pellaud. ``Instead of sending
inspectors, we have the privilege to have cameras permanently
installed so we can draw a picture every hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior US officials expressed concern that charges of American
spying in Iraq may prompt countries to backtrack on their
commitments to grant future access to international inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are longstanding US efforts to halt the spread of
nuclear weapons, freeze the production of scores of chemical and
biological warfare agents from Iraq to India, and eliminate
millions of gallons of dangerous nerve agent stockpiles in the
United States, Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am worried that some of these allegations will lead to
reluctance on the part of some countries to accept intrusive
inspections,'' a senior US official said. ``I'm worried the
credibility of some organizations will be unfairly damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Butler, the executive chairman of UNSCOM, added that the
reports of espionage was likely to heighten suspicions in other
agencies that hunt for hidden weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest nightmare of any treaty partner is that one of its
members will cheat from within,'' Butler said during a recent
speech at the Council on Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   Their concerns appear to be well founded.
</P>
<P>
   Disarmament specialists and other political analysts now assume
that international inspectors from most countries, whether they are
spies or not, routinely report back to their governments on
confidential information they pick up on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain degree it's taken for granted that countries take
this information back home,'' said Eric Croddy, a chemical weapons
expert from the Monterrey Institute, a think tank specializing in
arms control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether that is a good thing or a bad thing that
our taxpayer dollars go to fund these things,'' he added. ``Many of
our spies are terrible scientists.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador John Ritch, the US representative to the IAEA, said
that he has been ``scrupulous'' in ensuring the atomic agency's
reputation for independence remains ``pristine.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in judging the IAEA, a voluntary arms control
agency, by the standards of the UN inspection operation in Iraq, is
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider what we did in Iraq was arms control,'' he
said. ``I consider it the disarmament of a defeated aggressor.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato Kiniger-Passigli, the Italian spokesman of the
Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, and the
IAEA's Pellaud said that while many of the agencies' inspectors
have been recruited from UNSCOM, they do not use the
confrontational tactics employed by UNSCOM, which included a covert
UN intelligence operation in its inspections.
</P>
<P>
   IAEA and the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical
Weapons are working with countries that are voluntarily granting
access to their nuclear and chemical facilities, the spokesmen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kiniger-Passigli said that while his organization freely accepts
offers of intelligence from its members, his organization has
imposed rigorous guidelines to ensure that inspectors don't report
sensitive information back to their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They work for us and only for us,'' he insisted, referring to
the agency's 205 international inspectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
