<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO LOOK AHEAD FOR PAC-10
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Long gone from the NCAA Tournament _ but alive and
well in the NIT _ the Pacific-10 looks to next season. For the
first time in several years, there won't be an odds-on favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one scenario, from bottom to top:
</P>
<P>
   10. Washington State. The Cougars will have a new coach, but the
same frustrating results: They're not good enough to beat the elite
teams at home, and they can't beat anyone on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Kab Kazadi and Kojo Mensah-Bonsu do not return, a relief to
public-address announcers everywhere, but Reseda's Eddie Miller and
sharpshooter Jan-Michael Thomas are back. Combined with several
decent recruits, they will help Wazu to respectability. Projected
Pac-10 record: 5-13.
</P>
<P>
   9. Washington. After coach Bob Bender bolts for Vanderbilt, the
Huskies will hire Colorado State's rising star, Ritchie McKay. He
doesn't have much to work with _ Donald Watts and Todd MacCulloch
are gone _ as Washington returns to the second-division status it
held for much of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Senque Carey and shooter Deon Luton form a solid
backcourt, but the frontcourt players (Chris Walcott, Greg Clark,
Marlon Shelton and Thalo Green) are unproven. Pac-10 record: 6-12.
</P>
<P>
   8. Arizona State. Coach Rob Evans enters the second phase of his
rebuilding job: Having lost all-conference players Bobby Lazor and
Mike Batiste, he must survive until his recruits mature.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Alton Mason and shooter Eddie House are the top
returnees. Illinois transfer Awvee Storey and incoming freshman
Donnell Knight will start. There's no proven center. Pac-10 record:
7-11.
</P>
<P>
   7. California. The good news for coach Ben Braun is
underachieving gunners Thomas Kilgore and Geno Carlisle are gone.
They will leave a less talented _ but more cohesive _ group. Watch
for forward Sean Lampley to emerge as one of the league's best.
He'll be the first option, with recruit Donte Smith and small
forward Carl Boyd in support. Pac-10 record: 7-11.
</P>
<P>
   6. Oregon State. Beware the Beavs. They're ready to dominate at
home and perhaps win a road game or two. Coach Eddie Payne has his
core intact: guards Dino Tanner and Josh Steinthal, forwards
Clifton Jones and Ramunas Petraitis, plus center Jason Heide and
6-9 recruit Brian Jackson, the best big man Payne has ever signed.
</P>
<P>
   Success may be their biggest problem: No one will take them for
granted. Pac-10 record: 8-10.
</P>
<P>
   5. USC. The Trojans showed glimpses of potential this season
against UCLA and Stanford. Inexperience was a problem, but that
shouldn't be true next season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Henry Bibby has the players to challenge for an NCAA bid:
Brandon Granville at point, Jeff Trepagnier on the wing, Sam
Clancy, Jarvis Turner, Greg Lakey and Brian Scalabrine up front.
Pac-10 record: 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   4. Oregon. Consider Oregon's charge through the NIT as the
beginning of its 1999-2000 season. With most of their top players
returning, the Ducks will be one of the Pac-10's best and a solid
NCAA Tournament team. Point guard Darius Wright returns, as do
gifted wing players Alex Scales and Freddie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   A.D. Smith is a solid power forward, but as usual, there's no
proven center. Ernie Kent's motion offense can score against
anyone, but to consistently beat the elite he'll need a junior
college big man. Pac-10 record: 11-7.
</P>
<P>
   3. UCLA. Bruins coach Steve Lavin won't have inexperience to
blame if UCLA struggles in conference play. Everyone of consequence
returns but All-American Baron Davis, who's expected to bolt for
the NBA. While he'll be a major loss, the Bruins should have enough
size, depth and talent to maintain their upper-division status.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins must shift their emphasis to a half-court attack for
two reasons: Point guard Earl Watson is not a dependable ball
handler in transition, and that style would make better use of the
big men, Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric. Now the question becomes:
Can the coaching staff teach a consistent, effective halfcourt
system? Pac-10 record: 13-5.
</P>
<P>
   1. Arizona (tie). The Wildcats lose guard Jason Terry and center
A.J. Bramlett, but everyone else returns, including Loren Woods, a
7-foot transfer from Wake Forest. Arizona also welcomes recruit
Jason Gardner, one of the nation's top point guard recruits, to
replace Terry.
</P>
<P>
   The wing and forward positions are excellent, with sophomores
Ruben Douglas, Richard Jefferson, Rick Anderson and Michael Wright.
But like UCLA this season, the Wildcats won't have many juniors and
seniors in the rotation. Pac-10 record: 14-4.
</P>
<P>
   1. Stanford (tie). Yes, the Cardinal loses four starters, but it
has enough incoming talent to avoid a rebuilding season. Mark
Madsen returns at power forward and should be the best big man in
the league. He's joined by Jarron and (if healthy) Jason Collins,
plus Mike McDonald, Ryan Mendez and Davis Moseley.
</P>
<P>
   The recruiting class is the nation's best, led by Glendora
shooting guard Casey Jacobsen, Alameda power forward Justin Davis,
and Redmond (Wash.) center Curtis Borchardt, the best incoming big
man in the league.
</P>
<P>
   After an injured-filled season, coach Mike Montgomery will have
all the depth he needs next year. Pac-10 record: 14-4. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
