<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-SHOOTINGT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-WIFE: GUNMAN CARED FOR HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Brian Ball opened fire on Tempe police officers arresting a
homeless man Friday, he was armed with more than a gun.
</P>
<P>
   He also carried a soft spot for the downtrodden and a disdain
for police, his ex-wife of six years said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just sounds like something Brian would do,'' said
Michelle Grimes, Ball's former wife, speaking from Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The gunfire critically wounded a Tempe officer _ also,
ironically, a friend of the homeless _ and caused Ball's death as
the police returned fire.
</P>
<P>
   But the seemingly senseless act made sense to Grimes. She said
Ball was a delusional, alcoholic drug abuser and gun enthusiast who
also had a fondness for the homeless that went way back.
</P>
<P>
   He was sympathetic to them, she said, because he grew up in a
poor family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be on the street himself if he didn't have friends,'' she
said. ``He spent all his money on drugs and booze.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball once brought a homeless man home to Grimes' luxury
townhouse for Thanksgiving dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called him Jesus,'' Grimes said.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes, a scuba instructor in Kailua, Hawaii, divorced Ball in
1995, ending their turbulent relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes said Ball would go through phases when he would pretend
he was a different person _ walking like rock star Jim Morrison or
shaving his head and talking like Marlon Brando.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom thought he was nice when he was sober, but I don't
remember him being nice. That's not what I think of when I think of
Brian.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball was a big talker who would get kicked out of bars for
threatening strangers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd come up to people and say, `I'm going to kill you,' and
he wouldn't even know who they were,'' Grimes said. ``He had an
evil face he would give people, like a drunk and evil thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball got violent with Grimes only once _ cocking a gun during an
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `What did you say?' and pulled back on the trigger,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Just after midnight Friday, Ball stepped out of his pickup truck
and opened fire at the arresting officers.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe police could not fathom why.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Vanlandingham, 22, the homeless man who was arrested, said
Ball likely heard him shouting that his arrest was unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably saw me protesting my arrest verbally,''
Vanlandingham said, squatting Saturday on a planter outside the
post office about a block from the shooting scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sticking up for myself, saying, `It's a public street.
How can I get arrested for standing on a public street?' '' said
Vanlandingham, who moved from Seattle to Tempe in November.
</P>
<P>
   Vanlandingham, called ``Yogi'' on the street, said Ball shot at
the officers to the side of him, guarding the scene, and he never
felt in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. John Schaper, 33, a 12-year veteran, was listed in critical
condition Saturday at Maricopa Medical Center after a two-hour
surgery to repair the damage of a bullet that fragmented in his
abdomen, according to a Tempe police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Schaper is known as a nice guy on Mill Avenue. Several ``Mill
Rats,'' the nickname given to the scruffy youngsters who panhandle
along the east side of Mill Avenue, said Schaper is sympathetic to
their plight.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Gates, 24, said he knew of at least one person Schaper took
home for a meal and a shower. Gates said Schaper didn't harass the
slackers along the avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the good ones,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaper's family couldn't be reached Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The other officer who took one of Ball's bullets, Charles
Bridges, was shot in the chest, but the shell bounced off his body
armor. The other arresting officer was Steve Smith. It was Smith
and Bridges who returned the gunfire, killing Ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised he lasted this long, really,'' Grimes said of
Ball. ``He would do such daring things.''
</P>
<P>
   She filed for a restraining order and then, months later, filed
for divorce. After Grimes moved to Hawaii, Ball sent her a letter
threatening to kill her family, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He even told me exactly how he was going to kill my mother,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   When Grimes knew Ball he worked as a maintenance man at an
apartment complex by day and haunted bars in north Phoenix and
downtown Tempe at night.
</P>
<P>
   He would often go off on benders that would last several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would just, like, wake up in the middle of the yard, or
church, or somebody's front doorstep,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes, who met Ball through a blind date, said she got married
to him because she was young and ``clingy.'' Ball, she said, was
also very handsome.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was never attracted to his personality, ever.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
