u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-LEAFS-NYT &LR;      03-20 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAFS BEAT DEVILS, 4-1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Devils have their sights on several targets with
less than a month left in the regular season. They want to finish
first in the Eastern Conference, gain the home ice advantage for
the playoffs and pocket the gate receipts that come with it, but
they also want to capture their third consecutive divisional title
and break the league record for road victories.
</P>
<P>
   Their sights were temporarily obstructed Saturday night in a 3-1
loss to the Toronto Maple Leafs at Air Canada Center. The loss,
which gave the Devils a 4-1 record on their five-game trip,
weakened their quest in every category, especially their desire to
set the record for road victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, now 38-22-8, never found a rhythm against the Maple
Leafs. They were sloppy on defense and showed little coordination
in the offensive zone. They had just two legitimate chances in the
scoreless first period, and were completely outplayed in the
second, when Toronto scored its goals.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrik Modin, who returned to action after fracturing a
collarbone Feb. 13, put the Maple Leafs on the right path with his
13th goal of the season just 55 seconds into the second period. He
beat Martin Brodeur from the slot with a shot that appeared to
bounce off one of the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who was making his 11th consecutive start, also found
himself helpless on the second goal, which Stevie Sullivan scored 5
minutes 50 seconds into the period from the bottom of the left
circle. Sullivan converted Mike Johnson's pass from the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Warriner scored the Maple Leafs' third goal with 10:58 left
in the period. It was the first time that the Devils allowed more
than two goals on this trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' Brendan Morrison scored his 12th goal of the season
at 6:49 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, the Devils fell one victory short of sweeping a
five-game trip for the first time in their history. It put the
Devils at 24-9-2 on the road and left them four victories short of
eclipsing the Montreal Canadiens' record of 27, set during the
1976-77 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have six road games left, against Florida,
Pittsburgh, Carolina, Montreal, Buffalo and Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-2 triumph over the Islanders at Nassau Coliseum on March 7
started the trip. It continued with a 3-2 victory in Pittsburgh
before the Devils went to western Canada for a 2-1 triumph in
Vancouver last Monday and a 4-1 trouncing of Edmonton on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they lost their captain, Scott Stevens, in the early
stages of the game in Vancouver, the Devils' defense has performed
effectively. Brad Bombardir stepped in as Scott Niedermayer's
partner on defense and, according to the assistant coach Jacques
Caron, played his best hockey in the game in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens strained his groin in Vancouver and returned home to
rest. He worked out lightly the last two days and will start
skating Sunday or Monday. Stevens might play Tuesday night when the
Devils return home to play the Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   In Robbie Ftorek's first season as coach, the Devils seem to be
exactly where they want to be at this stage of the season. They
seem very well tuned for the playoffs, which may encourage Lou
Lamoriello, the general manager, to avoid making any trades before
the trade deadline Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   One player the Devils were considering trading for was
Edmonton's Boris Mironov, a talented defenseman with offensive
attributes, whom the Oilers sent to Chicago Saturday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
