<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMANPILOT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'61 NASA REJECTION NEVER DAMPENED AVIATOR'S SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESCOTT, Ariz. _ Two groups of young aviators prepared
themselves for space in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Mercury 7,'' who were chosen to fly, became famous and
financially secure. Among them is John Glenn, the first American in
orbit. As a group they celebrate 40 years together April 2.
</P>
<P>
   The second group, the ``Mercury 13,'' were women pilots whose
little-publicized astronaut training was scrubbed and who now live
in relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the second group, trying hard to make ends meet,
is Irene Leverton, 72, a fixture at Prescott Airport. She earns a
small income as a flight instructor and sells the occasional
portrait of a famous aviator in the airport's small cafe, but she
lives mostly on her Social Security check.
</P>
<P>
   Although she struggles financially, money is not the driving
force in her life. Since childhood, her occupation and
preoccupation, the thing that has made it impossible for her to
stay in one place or to have a family life, is her need to fly. She
has always needed to fly.
</P>
<P>
   She gets a mystical look in her eyes when she describes flying
under the Northern Lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time you see the Aurora Borealis, when the cockpit
is dark, then you know why you are flying,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the Mercury 13, she passed 75 endurance tests,
including sleep deprivation. One painful trial included the
injection of ice water into her ears.
</P>
<P>
   But after all the tests, NASA denied the women the opportunity
to train for space, and the thought of having female astronauts was
shelved for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Leverton isn't angry about it; she's grateful for the
opportunity to show how good she was _ as good as the men.
</P>
<P>
   And she's glad that women finally made it into space. Lt. Col.
Eileen Collins will be the first female commander of a shuttle
flight this summer _ and Leverton and the other Mercury 13 hope to
be there cheering her on. Last week, NASA announced that an
all-female science mission likely will be flown soon.
</P>
<P>
   Although Leverton is applauding all those advances, she
struggles for her own flight time. The contract flights get harder
to come by as she gets ``more experienced.'' She doesn't say
``older.''
</P>
<P>
   A pilot can be on contract with a company and still not get
enough work to pay the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever comes out and says, `You're fired,' '' Leverton
said. `I've observed that men pilots can go 10 to 15 years longer
than women before this happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've got some good years left, and I plan to use
them.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't want to retire, nor can she afford to. Her
spot-flying contracts have never generated a company pension to
supplement her Social Security, and any extra money has always gone
into the thin air of her passion _ perhaps for fuel or a plane
rental.
</P>
<P>
   To keep aloft, she paints pictures of such flyers as Amelia
Earhart and Charles Lindbergh and sells them at Susie's Skyway
Restaurant at Prescott Airport. They don't sell well, but the extra
cash now and then is helpful. She has also been commissioned to do
a painting of famous woman pilots from 1911 up to today, including
Sally Ride, who became the first American woman in space in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Although flying hasn't made Leverton wealthy, it has made her
interesting. She's full of good memories, some of which are
captured in photos on the wall at Susie's. The romance of flying
leaps from the fading snapshots, one of which shows a young and
dashing Leverton, standing by one of the hundreds of planes that
have been more like home to her than any house.
</P>
<P>
   When she was a girl in Chicago, she always was threatening to
jump off the roof to fly free for a moment. Other parents were
afraid to let their kids play with Irene; she was a daredevil, not
a proper playmate.
</P>
<P>
   But her mother understood, probably because the spirit of
adventure runs deep in the DNA of some families. Her mother, who
worked as a scrubwoman, saved pennies to buy Irene a book about
flying.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Leverton joined the Civil Air Patrol and finally
got a ride into the wild blue yonder. Soon, she was flying on her
own.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In her 20s, she was a crop duster and a national speed champ
for pylon acing. Later, she was a trans-Atlantic racer.
</P>
<P>
   She was one of the most experienced women pilots in America
when, in 1961, she got the invitation to be among 25 women tested
for the rigors of space flight.
</P>
<P>
   A NASA flight would have been a thrill, but it probably wouldn't
have satisfied her need to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Flying has been her life, she says. Marriage would have
interferred, so it was ruled out. Most of the good women pilots she
once knew quit flying after marriage, so she veered away from that
altogether. When she was 45, she had a special feeling for a German
scientist she had met, but in the end, she flew away.
</P>
<P>
   She does have her friends, including Stewart Albright of
Phoenix, a flight instructor with her in the 1980s, and his wife.
They talk a couple of times a month about aviation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``She's one-of-a-kind,'' Albright said. ``She has achieved so
much, and she's still going at it. Very few women _ or men _ have
had the flying experience she's had.''
</P>
<P>
   Leverton has logged more than 25,000 hours flying anything with
a propeller.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona became her home in 1979 when she ran out of gas in her
car while driving through Phoenix and took a job to get resupplied.
She stayed.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to the Prescott area in 1988. Before that, the longest
she had lived in one place as an adult was two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to the point where I couldn't unpack,'' she said. ``The
minute I didn't get a raise or didn't get promoted, I'd leave.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Maybe she should have been pushier, Leverton concedes. But she
lost some jobs, she believes, because she was too quick to say what
she thought rather than playing along with office politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never learned what the game was,'' she said. ``I still
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mobile home in Chino Valley, north of Prescott Airport, is
home to her and her cats, P.D. and Kit Kit, and serves as a museum
of aviation. Plaques and trophies from the '50s, '60s and '70s form
the permanent collection. She has a bookcase full of books about
pioneer women fliers.
</P>
<P>
   She may have to add a video section. The History Channel last
year did a documentary on women in aviation history and included
interviews with Leverton and some of the other Mercury 13. Four of
the 13 still fly, she says, and their experience has bonded them
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The family pictures on her wall are photos of airplanes she has
flown, and she has stories for each. Her scrapbooks reveal a woman
ahead of her time: In the 1950s and '60s, when other women flyers
sported big hair and frilly outfits for ``powder puff'' air events,
she wore pants, Amelia style.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Prescott,
hearing that Leverton had never been rated to fly jets because she
couldn't afford the training time, recently invited her to fly in
their 727 simulator. She was delighted, though not exactly pleased
when invited to sit in the co-pilot's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the same as being in the pilot's seat,'' she commented
later.
</P>
<P>
   But they invited her back for additional training time. She will
go, of course. After all, it's a chance to fly.
</P>
<P>
   In Chino Valley, some of the mobile homes have old cowboys
living in them, who have lived their lives for their horses and the
freedom of the wide open spaces. It is an instinct strangely
American, and not always reserved for men.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Leverton is one of those people who needs to be moving
fast and flying far above to be happy, regardless of any earthly
consequence.
</P>
<P>
   It's deep in the DNA, she agrees. &QL; Maureen West can be reached at
444-8167 or at maureen.west(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
