<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR PRESSURE PAID OFF FOR AMWEST FLIGHT ATTENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 and DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A single figure - $80 million - was the only
salient detail to come out Saturday about the landmark contract
between America West Airlines and its flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   But it said a lot, appearing to show that the flight attendants'
perseverence - and high-profile strike threats - had paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Deanna Clarkson, spokeswoman for the America West council of the
Association of Flight Attendants, said the five-year contract for
the 2,400 attendants is valued at more than $80 million. That's a
compromise between America West's $68.7 million offer and the $85.3
million sought by the union, but is clearly closer to the flight
attendants' goal than America West's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get all that we wanted, but we got close,'' William
McGlashen, local president of the AFA, said of the deal struck in
the wee hours of Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   America West isn't commenting on the details until flight
attendants are briefed, but the airline no doubt got concessions in
exchange for bumping up the contract total. Chairman Bill Franke is
a tough negotiator and always has one eye on the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract, while difficult to negotiate, addresses the
principal concerns of both parties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One area where America West apparently prevailed is in travel
expenses, or per diem. The union demanded $1.80 per hour, matching
what pilots receive. America West has been paying the equivalent of
89 cents per hour in per diem and would only agree to increase it
to $1.30 per hour for the first 30 months, $1.50 for 30 months and
$1.75 at the end of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the deal about 3 a.m. Saturday in Washington
outside the National Mediation Board offices, McGlashen said the
company's offer to raise salaries to 90 percent of what Southwest
Airlines pays its flight attendants was the basis for the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest pay scale ranges from starting pay of $15,500 a
year to $44,000, according to the AFA. America West's scale ranges
from $12,000 to $22,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative agreement, more details of which are expected
today, rewards flight attendants for their sacrifices made to help
America West survive bankruptcy and reorganization in the early
1990s, McGlashen said. It especially boosts salaries for long-time
flight attendants, some of whom haven't had a pay increase in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,600, or 75 percent, of the carrier's flight attendants
have been with the company for between 10 and 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an improvement over our last tentative agreement,''
McGlashen said of a 1997 tentative deal of $53.5 million that was
soundly rejected by flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   AFA union members must still ratify the contract. A mail-in vote
is expected to be completed in about a month, McGlashen said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recorded message to members shortly after the settlement
was reached, the AFA said ``the upcoming days are very cruical for
our workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   It said union members will be preparing a summary of the
contract agreement to present to flight attendants. Within the next
several weeks, flight attendants will receive a copy of the
settlement at home. That will be followed by a series of road shows
by union officials after which members will vote on ratification.
No dates have been set. The process took about six weeks after the
airline's last tentative agreement in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market is likely to cheer the settlement news on
Monday, though some investors might have seen a deal coming - the
airline's stock rallied last week as the strike deadline
approached. America West's stock closed Friday at $17.63.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock gets a bump, it might be from investors betting on
renewed interest in America West from United Airlines or other
suitors. America West announced last month that it was ending
much-hyped merger talks with United and other airlines because
there were too many conditions attached and a buyout might not be
blessed by federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Maldutis, airline analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer in New
York, is in the camp that expects more bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a labor contract with the flight attendants is signed, we
fully expect UAL Corp. to make a counter offer for America West,''
he wrote in a March 9 report.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Hegeman, who chronicles the airline industry at
www.planebusiness.com and originally broke the story of United's
interest in America West, also expects an offer now that the flight
attendant troubles are behind America West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to see another offer from United Airlines for the
folks in Phoenix, as well as a possible AWA/TWA deal that may come
together as well,'' she wrote after the settlement was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Franke has said America West plans to remain independent. The
flight attendants contract, he said, ``assures that we can continue
the airline's strategic growth without interruption and our
employees can focus on providing quality customer service.''
</P>
<P>
   A big question that remains is the financial impact of the
threatened strike. Many travel agents said they had been booking
away from America West - some for months - so passengers didn't
risk getting stranded.
</P>
<P>
   America West's first quarter financial results won't be out
until mid-April. But if the impact is serious and cuts deeply into
profits, the company likely will issue a warning to Wall Street
before then so there are no surprises. AMR Corp., the parent of
American Airlines, did that last week. The Dallas company said a
sick-out by its pilots last month will shave $200 to $255 million
off earnings before taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the losses associated with the canceled
flights, customers were reluctant to book American for a period of
time after the job action,'' the company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   America West is much smaller than American - No. 9 in the
industry versus No. 2 - and its labor problems didn't result in
canceled flights. Still, the losses likely mounted.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst told Bloomberg News that America West lost millions
of dollars in advance bookings. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson can be reached at 444-8617 or at
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
