<SLUG> BC-BKW-PURDUE-NCAROLINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDUE BEATS NORTH CAROLINA, 80-59  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ZACK BURGESS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAL, Ill. _ For more than a month, Purdue has been expected
to deliver victory after victory. Their much heralded guard
combination of Ukari Figgs and Stephanie White-McCarty is
considered by many to be the best in the nation. And when it comes
to balance off the bench, they are as good as any team playing in
the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament.
</P>
<P>
   So when Purdue took the floor against North Carolina at the
Midwest Regional Saturday night, the idea of the Boilermakers being
upset became an afterthought well before the contest even started.
Purdue overwhelmed North Carolina, 80-59, to move into the final
eight Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Purdue was expected to win the game, the
Boilermakers couldn't take anything for granted. After all, North
Carolina is a former NCAA champion. And all week they had to hear
about North Carolina's athletic combination of Nikki Teasley, Juana
Brown and LaQuanda Barksdale.
</P>
<P>
   But the Boilermakers overpowered the Tar Heels with a smothering
defense and impressive offense. Purdue outrebounded, outshot and
out-hustled the Tar Heels, embarrassing them throughout the first
half, shooting 55 percent from the field in the first half. That
included 44 percent from behind the 3-point arc, while the Tar
Heels shot 33 percent from the field before the half. North
Carolina also had nine turnovers to go with its poor shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs scored a game-high 24 points while registering six
assists, and White-McCarty scored 18 points while handing out seven
assists.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs began the game with a 3-pointer from the right side and
two plays later White-McCarty hit a 3-pointer of her own. And even
though at this point it wasn't clear that the Tar Heels were about
to blown out, it became apparent a few plays later.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 minutes 59 seconds to go in the first half, North
Carolina called a timeout. It didn't help, however, as Figgs and
Michelle Duhart came out of the timeout and put on a short display
of excellent basketball to keep the Tar Heels guessing.
</P>
<P>
   There was the layup by Duhart right out of the timeout. And the
dazzling pass from Figgs back to Duhart. From there, North
Carolina's Jauna Brown struggled to make a simple layup underneath.
It was just one example of the Tar Heels' struggles.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Tar Heels tried to fight back with a 15-footer by
Jackie Higgins to cut the score to 17-10, Purdue was just too much.
By the end of the first half the Boilermakers had built a 38-22
lead. From there it was out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue Coach Carolyn Peck, who is in her second year, has guided
the Boilermakers to consecutive appearances in the final eight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
