<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROSTARS BEAT FUSION, 3-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ It wasn't Jets-Dolphins or Knicks-Heat.
But the MetroStars and Fusion Saturday night added a soccer rivalry
to the New York vs. Miami sports scene.
</P>
<P>
   In the Major League Soccer season opener for both teams, the
MetroStars won a dramatic shootout, 3-2, at Lockhart Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of the game was playoff caliber, particularly as
it tightened in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must be a Miami-New York thing,'' Fusion defender Wade Webber
said after the MetroStars' first victory in four season openers.
</P>
<P>
   They won the shootout, 2-1. Midfielder Tab Ramos started things
by scoring in the right corner. After the Fusion's Leo Cullen tied
it, Miles Joseph _ the third player up for the MetroStars _ scored
what proved to be the winner by slipping the ball just inside the
left post.
</P>
<P>
   The tension built as the final three players to shoot for Miami
_ Carlos Valderrama, Jay Heaps and Diego Serna _ all failed to
score. MetroStars goalie Mike Ammann deflected Serna's effort wide
right to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Before Serna's miss, Brian Kelly had a chance to clinch the
victory for the MetroStars, but his shot hit the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   In Bora Milutinovic's regular-season debut as MetroStars coach,
he was missing just two players who may have an impact with the
team _ midfielder Roy Myers, who is not available until April 3
because of a commitment to play in the Costa Rican Nations Cup, and
a fourth foreign player who likely won't be chosen for the first
two games.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors had practiced outdoors only once since March 12 _
on Friday _ coming into this game, but it didn't show.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars played the tight defense that is the trademark of
Milutinovic's teams, then momentarily silenced the crowd of 13,648
with a goal in the 36th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos pushed the ball up the right side, then threaded a pass to
forward Eduardo Hurtado over the middle. Hurtado paused,
flat-footed, then found the right corner, barely eluding the
outstretched arm of goalie Dusty Hudock.
</P>
<P>
   The Fusion hovered near the MetroStars' goal for much of the
remainder of the half, but headers by Valderrama and Serna missed
their target.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars received a scare near the end of the half when
Ramos was kicked in the right shin by Miami's Henry Gutierrez as
they slid into each other. Ramos lay on the field for more than a
minute before limping through the rest of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos bruised his shin, but it didn't keep him from helping the
MetroStars take a 2-0 lead. He penetrated the Miami defense, then
passed to forward Mark Chung. Chung left-footed it to Hurtado on
the right side.
</P>
<P>
   The ball never landed as Hurtado timed it for a right-footed
kick that bounced off Hudock and came to rest in the net's right
corner.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 seconds later, in the 53rd minute, the Fusion got back
into it. Valderrama slipped a pass inside to forward Roberto
Gaucho, who popped it by Ammann, the new MetroStars goalie.
</P>
<P>
   The Fusion thought it scored the game-tying goal soon after, but
a Fusion player was ruled offside when Serna put the ball in the
net.
</P>
<P>
   Ammann made a distinctive, diving stop of Gaucho's shot in the
65th minute, but the Fusion kept the pressure on. A minute later,
defender Jay Heaps scored his first MLS goal on a header to tie the
game at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars suffered a blow in the 87th minute when the
feisty defender Arley Palacios was thrown out for tackling defender
Mario Gori from behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
