<HEADER>
A8368 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-OHIO-STATE-ST.-JO     03-20 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIO-STATE-ST.-JOHN'S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHIO STATE CONTINUES TURNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The Bucks don't stop here.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's historic turnaround continued on to St. Petersburg,
Fla., last night as the Buckeyes survived a few late, anxious
moments to hold off St. John's in the South Regional championship
game, 77-74.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet and Gray will be making its first appearance in the
Final Four since 1968 _ a year that marked the end of a seven-year
span in which Ohio State appeared three times and the names of
Havlicek, Lucas and Bill Hoskett were synonymous with the best in
college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really, really hard to put into words the feeling that is
shared by all of us right now,'' said coach Jim O'Brien, whose team
was 8-22 a year ago. ``It's hard to imagine we've put ourselves in
this position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes led from the opening tip, at times by as much as 13
points. But St. John's refused to fade and the last minute was a
frantic one, as it usually is in games of this magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   So typically, the final sequence was a blur in the minds of
those closest to it.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm trailed, 76-74, when guard Erick Barkley took an
inbounds pass after Ohio State's Scoonie Penn made only one of two
free throws with 12.2 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley crossed midcourt and came off a pick at the top of the
key. But suddenly, the ball continued toward the basket without
him. And in a flash, the Buckeyes' Michael Redd had the ball and,
in effect, the game in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Fouled with only seven-tenths of a second left, Redd made one of
two free throws and Barkley's desperation full-court fling of the
rebound was way off left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost the ball, it was my fault,'' an overwhelmingly dejected
Barkley said later in the dressing room. ``It just came loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Television replays suggested Penn might have nudged him with a
forearm in the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way the game was played,'' Barkley said. ``They
didn't call it at the start and they're not going to call it at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even sure what happened,'' said Penn, who scored a
team-high 22 points and was named the region's most outstanding
player. ``I think I got a hand on the ball, then I saw it bounding
out freely.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he nudged Barkley, Penn replied, ``I don't know. Maybe
I did or maybe I didn't. I know I didn't do enough to make him lose
the ball. I didn't push him or anything like that. But it happened
so quickly, I really don't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's coach Mike Jarvis praised the Buckeyes and refused to
join the debate about the late sequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohio State played great from start to the end,'' Jarvis said.
``Unfortunately, we didn't match their intensity the whole game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great players make great plays. A great player took it away
from another great player. Even if I saw \RPenn's\S hand on Erick's
back, what good would it do?
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of hands on a lot of people's backs all
night. You have to try and make a play whether there's a hand on
your back or not. And if I saw it, I wouldn't mention it. Ohio
State deserved to win and if we'd made last basket, we'd have
deserved to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavor Postell led the Red Storm with 24. Bootsy Thornton scored
18. Barkley had 13 points and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   Penn and Redd combined for 42 points, but Ohio State also got a
boost from its front line. Center Ken Johnson had 12 points and
seven blocked shots and forward Jason Singleton scored 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrific win for us,'' O'Brien said. ``It's as good
as it gets _ for the time being.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
