<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-WEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN REACHES FIRST FINAL FOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ His burden removed and his team headed to the Final
Four, Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun lost control. He cried. He
cried for his players, he cried for his school, and he cried for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   After several trips to the brink, after crushing losses in the
Sweet 16 and Elite Eight, after missed free throws and last-second
knives and all those No.1 seeds he could not overcome, Calhoun is
headed to St. Pete.
</P>
<P>
   It sure is sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 10 years, we've had teams that made a run at the
Final Four,'' he said. ``Every one of those kids, I loved. They
never gave me an ounce of disappointment, but other teams got in
the way of moving on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for them and for this team, which wouldn't allow
anything to get in the way of St. Petersburg.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that No. 1 seed Connecticut advanced to the first
Final Four in school history with a riveting 67-62 victory Saturday
over No. 10 Gonzaga, before 18,053 at America West Arena. The
margin was closer than most expected, but for the Huskies, who play
South Regional champ Ohio State in the national semifinals,
survival was all that mattered.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy carrying the hopes of a state _ and the
burdens of previous NCAA failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since Aug. 9, there have been questions about us getting
to the Final Four,'' Connecticut point guard Khalid El-Amin said.
``We've been trying to play that down all year and just go out and
play basketball. We just have the hearts of champions. I can't tell
you how good this feels.''
</P>
<P>
   What was the difference? What separates these Huskies from
previous versions? They struggled with Gonzaga just as they
struggled with lower seeds Florida (1994) and Mississippi State
(1996). When Gonzaga dashed to a 41-37 lead early in the second
half, the memories of collapses past returned and Connecticut's
cheering section turned silent.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the difference was one man: All-American guard Richard
Hamilton, who thrived where former UConn stars Donyell Marshall and
Ray Allen had faltered.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton scored a game-high 21 points and singlehandedly forced
Gonzaga into a zone defense. During the Bulldogs' boldest charge,
early in the second half, Hamilton responded with eight consecutive
points. He gave Connecticut a 55-53 lead with six minutes left, and
he found center Jake Voskuhl for the biggest basket _ a layup with
1:02 remaining that gave the Huskies a 63-59 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hamilton played ferocious defense and held Gonzaga
sharpshooter Richie Frahm to seven points on 2 of 11 field goals.
Add his four rebounds _ UConn had a 47-33 advantage on the boards _
and Hamilton was the one equation Gonzaga could not solve during
its breathtaking postseason charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good a player as we've gone against all year,''
Gonzaga coach Dan Monson said. ``He was the reason we basically
couldn't guard them man-to-man.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 65-62 with 34 seconds remaining, the Bulldogs
uncharacteristically botched their last chances. First, Frahm
missed a leaning 15-footer, then guard Matt Santangelo heaved a
wild runner from the right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should have kicked it out,'' Santangelo said. ``I
may have made a bad decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
