<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ST.JOHN'S-OHIOSTA     03-20 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ST.JOHN'S-OHIOSTATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHIO STATE BEATS ST. JOHN'S, 77-74  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ St. John's Coach Mike Jarvis looked back at
the end to see what he was missing. Erick Barkley already knew. The
St. John's point guard pulled his white jersey up over his eyes and
weaved blindly through the celebrating Ohio State players tumbling
around him, never raising his head, inconsolable over the result.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's lost to Ohio State Saturday night, 77-74, letting a
chance to pull off a miracle victory in the final seconds of the
South Regional final and a trip to the Final Four slip away. The
magnificent run through the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament ended with uncharacteristically
absent-minded play until the final moments and the agony of a
missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to go to the Final Four,'' forward Ron Artest
said. ``We were supposed to be there. The other teams we played
were good, but we were better. Tonight, as a team, we weren't
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm had clawed from behind all night, never
rediscovering the intelligent, faultless play that had gotten it
this far. St. John's was dominated by Ohio State's guards _ Scoonie
Penn, who had 22 points and 8 assists, and Michael Redd, who had 20
points and 5 assists. It was intimidated by the shot blocking of
Buckeyes center Ken Johnson. And the St. John's players _
particularly Artest, who was completely off his game _ failed to
produce the sort of efforts on which they had come to rely. They
shot just 39.4 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't executing,'' said Artest, who had just 9 points to
go with 5 turnovers and several miserable 3-point attempts. ``We
could have easily won this game.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the closing minutes, Ohio State's shaky free-throw
shooting _ Coach Jim O'Brien had employed a sports psychologist
during the season to try to improve its 61.5 percent success rate _
gave St. John's a final chance to win. With the clock running under
12 seconds and St. John's trailing by just 2 points, it was the Red
Storm's ball and Barkley walked the ball up court, dribbling with
his left hand. As he crossed midcourt, he switched to his right
hand and began to drive diagonally to his right. Just below the
foul line, Penn put his right hand on Barkley's left hip. No foul
was called, but Barkley was turned slightly and he dribbled the
ball off his leg. It was picked up by Redd, who dribbled away in
delight as scarlet-clad fans cascaded from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no one between me and the basket,'' said Barkley,
who sobbed in the locker room afterward.
</P>
<P>
   While Barkley's rare error _ it was his only turnover of the
game _ came at the most critical moment, it was merely the last one
St. John's made. The third-seeded Red Storm was presumed to be the
quicker, more physical, more intelligent of the two teams left in
the South Regional. But the tenor of the game was set immediately,
when St. John's, for one of the few times all season, could not
find a way to compensate for its lack of height. The 6-foot-11-inch
Johnson blocked three shots in the first three minutes of the game.
He finished with seven blocks in all and, most important, kept the
Red Storm from consistently trying to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't attack him,'' Jarvis said. ``He controlled the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had 12 points, part of fourth-seeded Ohio State's
unusually balanced offensive attack. Only two Buckeyes average in
double figures for scoring, Penn and Redd. Saturday night, four
players _ Johnson and Jason Singleton were the others _ scored in
double figures. St. John's, which had excelled with the zone
defense in victories over Indiana and Maryland, played a mixture of
zone and man-to-man defense, and neither seemed to work
particularly well.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast in the scoring column was St. John's. All five
of its starters average in double figures, but only Barkley (13
points, 7 assists), Bootsy Thornton (18 points) and Lavor Postell
(24 points, a career high) performed to expectations. But the
entire team seemed lost, particularly in the first half, when the
Red Storm fell behind by as many as 11 points. The senior center
Tyrone Grant reinjured his right wrist early in the game and
finished with just 3 points. Distraught, he said he let his team
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I start out really well, the team somehow follows,'' Grant
said. ``It's very painful how it ended. I'll take all the blame for
the loss because luck hasn't been on my side. I did nothing but
hurt the team in the long run by trying to play through the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Postell seemed energized on offense. After a terrible start
in which he took several awful shots, Postell found his shooting
touch. Every time St. John's looked finished, Postell hit a
critical shot.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Storm fell behind by 10 points early in the second
half, Postell hit a 14-foot jumper. Down by 11 with 13 minutes 22
seconds to play, St. John's went to Postell again, for a layup.
When St. John's trailed by 13 with 9:08 remaining, Postell hit a
3-pointer, one of four. When it was down by 10 again, with 6:30
remaining, there was another Postell 3-pointer. It was those shots
that gave St. John's any hope as the closing minutes came.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't going out without a fight,'' Postell said. ``We
love to get up on teams and have them fight back. That's wasting
extra energy, and the whole game we were struggling to fight
back.''
</P>
<P>
   There was simply not enough fight left. St. John's had cruised
through unexpectedly easy victories over Indiana and Maryland to
get here, and, as the third-seeded team, was the clear favorite to
advance to its first Final Four since 1985. St. John's claimed it
was not surprised by how quick and physical the Buckeyes were, but
the Red Storm was stunned by its own ineptness against a team that
has enjoyed its own remarkable resurgence this season, rising from
the bottom of the Big Ten last season to the Final Four now.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Jarvis had called St. John's run an incredible
journey. Afterward, he was philosophical about what he wanted his
team to remember from this shockingly successful, and now
heartbreaking, season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a loss,'' Jarvis said. ``This was just a
temporary setback. The journey will continue because we didn't
reach our destination. I don't think we were put here to go to the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ever get there, that's great. But I don't think that's
why we're here. We were put here to learn lessons about teamwork.
And even how to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a painful lesson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
