<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-JOURNAL-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH: Y'ALL COME BACK NOW
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was just as well that the St. John's Red Storm and
Ohio State Buckeyes ended up in the South Region's championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   For alas, the highways of Tennessee might not have been safe
this weekend for Tigers and Terrapins.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours before the basketball teams from Auburn and Maryland
were eliminated from the NCAA Tournament on Thursday night, the
state's House of Representatives passed a bill legalizing the
consumption of road-killed wild animals.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the so-called ``road-kill bill'' said the measure
was formulated in response to complaints from citizens without
proper hunting licenses who harvested deer hit by motor vehicles
and wound up being charged with illegal possession by the Tennessee
Wildlife Resources Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, House Speaker Jimmy Naifeh said, it also becomes legal for
patrons to pick up a deceased raccoon that has been clocked by an
18-wheeler and donate it to his annual''Coon Supper'' without
having to pay state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Tim Burchett (R-Tenn), however, expressed concern that
the bill would only open the door for ``a bunch of Yankees coming
down here to make fun of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only a bunch of Yankees.  &LR; name:_Mike Jones
EAST: CHANEY ONE OF A KIND
</P>
<P>
   Casual sports fans likely know Temple's John Chaney for his
threatening to kill then-Massachusetts coach John Calipari a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Chaney, 67, is much more than a strutting sideline maniac.
Much more.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Florida and went to high school in Philadelphia.
In 1951, he was the city's high school player of the year. But that
was back in the days of racial quotas and Chaney wound up playing
at Bethune-Cookman. A former teammate has said that Chaney was the
best player he had seen until some guy named Michael Jordan came
along.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney has adamantly campaigned against the NCAA eligibility
guidelines that a federal judge recently struck down because they
discriminated against minorities. Chaney believes in fairness, even
though he has seen his share of injustice. He was 50 before he got
his first Division I job, at Temple in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always enjoyed being around John,'' said Duke coach Mike
Krzyzewski, whose top-seeded team face Chaney's Owls in the East
Regional final today. ``And it's obvious that he's a good coach,
too. He's an honest guy and a sincere person. There aren't many of
those.''  &LR; name:_ Wendell Barnhouse
Midwest: All-World Wally
</P>
<P>
   When Miami's remarkable ride through the Midwest Regional
finally ended Friday night, coach Charlie Coles tossed an odd
question at the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, let me ask you guys something,'' he said. ``Was Wally
\RSzczerbiak\S on the cover of /Sports Illustrated'' this week?''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Charlie. It was on newsstands all over the country. Didn't
you ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, I never have time to look for that stuff,'' Coles said.
``But when somebody told me, I thought, `Gee, I hope Kentucky
doesn't see that thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wildcats can read, too, Charlie.
</P>
<P>
   With or without magazine covers, everyone was keying on
Szczerbiak all the way. And although Miami was finally stopped by
Kentucky, the charismatic RedHawks forward _ who scored 90 points
in three games _ will remain one of the larger memories of the 1999
NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Every time he stepped on the court _ in New Orleans or St. Louis
_ crowds erupted in cheers. Kentucky players compared him to Duke's
Elton Brand and Auburn's Chris Porter. Others, noticing a certain
resemblance, called him Superman. A local columnist dismissed a
comparison with Cinderella, saying, ``Szczerbiak is
better-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over and the RedHawks were done, he said simply, ``I
will always remember Miami University, because people have been
wonderful to me, and I would not be the person I am now if I had
not gone to there. I have made lifelong friends, and I am grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We managed to do something no Miami team has ever done (reach
the Sweet 16), and we will walk away with our heads high.''
 &LR; name:_Whit Canning
West: Leave the walking to us
</P>
<P>
   Want to rent a car at Sky Harbor International Airport in
Phoenix? You'd have an easier time trying to get a ticket to the
Connecticut-Gonzaga game.
</P>
<P>
   Several high-profile events in this area, along with the usual
amount of Easterners who trek here for annual vacations, made
travel accommodations extra tough this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego resident Sharon Ross told the ``Arizona Republic''
that even though she is a preferred customer with Hertz, the
company ran out of cars for her. She said they offered her a
compact car for $159, but she would have to return it the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highway robbery,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Why are all the cars gone? There was the West Regional, The
Standard Register Ping LPGA Tournament and the Cox Communications
Air Show Spectacular. Also this week, an electrical engineers'
conference brought in 8,500 visitors, and the American Medical
Association hosted 900 doctors. Not to mention all the people who
flock here for Cactus League baseball in nearby Scottsdale and
Mesa.  &LR; name:_Kevin Lyons
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
