<HEADER>
A8374 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-CONNECTICUT-GONZA     03-20 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CONNECTICUT-GONZAGA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT ENDS FRUSTRATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ There was no Christian Laettner miracle this time, and
no national-champion-to-be UCLA standing in the way of a trip to
the Final Four. No, for Connecticut, and expectation-weary coach
Jim Calhoun, those demons were all exorcised yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Huskies made all the plays, ending the magical ride
of the nation's sweethearts, Gonzaga, in a 67-62 victory in the
West Regional final at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament most valuable player Richard Hamilton scored 21
points and Connecticut held sharpshooting Gonzaga to 5-of-21 from
the 3-point line, and just two field goals of any kind in the final
7:19.
</P>
<P>
   The elements combined to send a coach with 552 career victories
to his first Final Four after three previous regional championship
game losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last 10 years we've had a lot of great teams that
\Rcould have made\S the Final Four ... but fate, like a Christian
Laettner, or other teams, got in the way of moving on,'' said
Calhoun, in his 13th season at Connecticut and 27th season overall
as a head basketball coach. ``This win is for those teams, and for
this particular team, which wouldn't allow anything to get in the
way of us getting to St. Petersburg.'' The Huskies will play Ohio
State in the national semifinals next Saturday in the Florida.
</P>
<P>
   UConn lost a regional final to Duke in 1990 on Laettner's
game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, it was an emotional locker room for the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun dedicated the victory to former team trainer Joe McGinn,
26, who died Tuesday before the Huskies' first tournament game.
McGinn had been diagnosed with a kidney disease and died of a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a few tears in my eyes, a lot of us did,'' senior guard
Ricky Moore said. ``There were just so many emotions out there. I'm
totally exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a senior shooting guard, played 38 minutes. Most came in
the role of point guard, where he was playing because Khalid
El-Amin (0-of-12 shooting from the field) missed 15:30 of the first
half because of foul trouble. Moore scored 12 points, and held Matt
Santangelo, one of the Bulldogs' best shooters, to two points on
1-of-9 shooting, including 0-of-4 from beyond the arc.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's defensive wizardry rubbed off on his teammates, who held
Gonzaga to 35 percent shooting (20-of-57) from the floor. They made
every Gonzaga shot an adventure, Bulldogs coach Dan Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing was that even if you ran a play and a guy
was open, their quickness to recovery was tremendous,'' Monson
said. ``It seemed like every time our guys would have an open look,
there would be somebody flying at them with a hand up.''
</P>
<P>
   No one had an answer for the 6-foot-6 Hamilton, a first-team All
American. Gonzaga even tried guarding him with 5-8 point guard
Quentin Hall for much of the game. But Hamilton still wound up
shooting 9-of-16 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the feisty Bulldogs, the first No. 10 seed to reach a
regional championship game in eight years, would not go away. In
fact, Gonzaga led by as much as four, and had it tied, at 55-55
with 5:59 to go. Keeping them in the game was Hall, who drove
through the extended Huskies defense to make spectacular,
off-balance layups that accounted for many of his 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's last basket, a leaning three-pointer with 36.9 seconds to
go, brought the Bulldogs to within 63-62. But the Huskies hit their
final four free throws to end Cinderella's stay in the Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a wild ride,'' Santangelo said. ``You don't always
get to ride in the team plane and get a police escort. Stuff like
that doesn't happen to little ol' Gonzaga. None of us will ever
forget this.''  &LR; tagtop:Kevin Lyons (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:lyonsnfl &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
