<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-20 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     03-20 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 28)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ECHOES OF A NATIVE LAND: TWO CENTURIES OF A RUSSIAN VILLAGE &LR;  By
Serge Schmemann. Vintage, $15. A former Moscow bureau chief for The
New York Times visits his ancestral village, creating _ with the
help of the recollections of its long-suffering inhabitants _ a
miniature history of Russia in the 20th century. ```Echoes of a
Native Land' is that rare achievement: a Russian memoir that
subverts the conventions of the genre and tells us, in clear,
elegant and understated prose, that you can't go home again,''
Michael Ignatieff wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOWN THERE ON A VISIT &LR;  By Christopher Isherwood. University of
Minnesota, $15.95. In four tales set in Berlin, Greece, London and
California, the author of ``Berlin Stories'' explores the sexuality
and inner turmoil of four vastly different protagonists, from a
male prostitute to a German worker taken with the bohemian life.
``This excellent novel ... may be the best Christopher Isherwood
has written,'' Gerald Sykes wrote in the Book Review in 1962. ``Out
of his literary detachment, strengthened by mystical studies, has
come a deeply intelligent and quietly compelling story.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; THE MEMORIAL &LR;  ($15.95), which
tracks the falling apart of a British family after World War I.
Isherwood's ``concern is with a mood, a collective state of mind,
one which is perhaps more accurately named a state of nerves,''
Edith R. Mirrielees wrote in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FOOTNOTE: A CURIOUS HISTORY &LR;  By Anthony Grafton. Harvard
University, $14. A history professor digs up some surprising lore
as he traces the development of the footnote from ancient Greece to
Gibbon (a master of the genre) to its modern practitioners. The
result is ``a witty and characteristically erudite book,'' David
McKitterick wrote in 1997. ``The pages of `The Footnote' are
peppered with human folly.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A GENTLE MADNESS: BIBLIOPHILES, BIBLIOMANES, AND THE ETERNAL
PASSION FOR BOOKS &LR;  By Nicholas A. Basbanes. Owl/Holt, $18.95. This
explores book collecting and those driven to pursue it, and
features a sweeping Who's Who of collectors, living and dead,
visionary and loony. ```A Gentle Madness' is an impressive
achievement in its compilation of vast information, as well as
instructive and interesting,'' Philip Kopper wrote in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDURING LOVE &LR;  By Ian McEwan. Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95. A
chance encounter radically changes the lives of a married science
writer and a young man who develops an erotic religious fixation on
him. In 1998 the reviewer Sven Birkerts called this ``a vibrant and
unsettling'' novel that ``reminds us that normal behavior conceals
but does not banish unsavory truths.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RAPE OF NANKING: THE FORGOTTEN HOLOCAUST OF WORLD WAR II &LR; 
By Iris Chang. Penguin, $14.95. In 1937, Japanese troops
slaughtered hundreds of thousands of citizens in Nanking, an act of
barbarism rarely spoken of (for different reasons) in both Japan
and China. ``Iris Chang, whose own grandparents were survivors,
recounts the grisly massacre with understandable outrage,'' Orville
Schell wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BARNEY POLAN'S GAME: A NOVEL OF THE 1951 COLLEGE BASKETBALL
SCANDALS &LR;  By Charley Rosen. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13. In this
fictional account of basketball's equivalent of the 1919 Black Sox
scandal, an idealistic sports columnist bears witness to the
corruption of the sport by gamblers and players who conspired to
fix games. ``Rosen's novel is a particularly American form of
tragedy, in which the characters do not have to fall from great
heights to fall from grace,'' Allen Barra wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CITY GAME: FROM THE GARDEN TO THE PLAYGROUNDS &LR;  By Pete
Axthelm. University of Nebraska, $12. This is both a chronicle of
the New York Knicks' 1969-70 championship season and a study of the
era's playground basketball culture, focusing on asphalt legends
like Herman ``Helicopter'' Knowings and Earl Manigault. ``The book
offers absorbing insights into the most unique and gripping of all
city sports,'' Rex Lardner wrote in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAESAR: LET THE DICE FLY &LR;  By Colleen McCullough. Avon, $16.50.
The author's fifth novel in her series on the fall of the Roman
Republic features the uprising of Gaul and Caesar's crossing of the
Rubicon, among other episodes. ``Such important events ... unfold
as excitingly as if the history were not yet written,'' Allen
Lincoln wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNFINISHED JOURNEY: TWENTY YEARS LATER &LR;  By Yehudi Menuhin.
Fromm, $19. In this revamped edition of his 1976 autobiography, the
renowned violinist, who died this month at the age of 82, holds
forth on his precocious musical education (he made his debut at 7)
and his long, eventful career. ``Menuhin is ... a giant above us
all when he talks about music,'' Peggy Constantine wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPENDING: A UTOPIAN DIVERTIMENTO &LR;  By Mary Gordon. Scribner,
$13. In this modern fairy tale, a middle-aged painter adopts a
sexually dynamic futures trader as her muse, prompting a struggle
between her artistic purity and the pleasures of the flesh (and the
wallet). ``Gordon is an honest and perceptive writer,'' Hilary
Mantel wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
